{"title_page": "2010s in political history", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{See also|2020s in political history}}\n{{see also|2010s#Politics and conflicts|21st century|2019 in politics and government}}\n{{Year nav|2019}}\n{{Decadebox|201}}\n{{Year nav topic5|2020|politics and government|science|United States politics and government}}\n\n'''2010s political history''' refers to significant political and societal historical events of the 2010s, presented as a historical overview in narrative format.\n\n{{TOC limit|limit=3}}\n\n==Regional politics==\n\n===Africa===\n====Burundi====\n{{Main|Burundian unrest (2015\u201318)}}\nOn April 25, 2015, the incumbent President of [[Burundi]], [[Pierre Nkurunziza]], announced he would run for a third term in the 2015 presidential election. The announcement sparked protests by those opposed to Nkurunziza seeking a third term in office.<ref>[https://www.hrw.org/news/2015/04/27/burundi-crackdown-protesters Burundi: Crackdown on Protesters] Human Rights Watch, April 27, 2015</ref> Widespread demonstrations in the then-capital, [[Bujumbura]], lasted for over three weeks. As a result of the protests, the government also shut down the country's Internet and telephone network, closed all of the country's universities, and publicly referred to the protesters as \"terrorists\". Tens of thousands of people fled the country, hundreds of people were arrested, and several protesters and police were killed. On May 13, 2015, a coup d'etat was announced, led by Major General [[Godefroid Niyombare]], while President Nkurunziza was in [[Tanzania]] attending an emergency conference about the situation in the country. By the next day the coup collapsed and government forces reasserted control. At least 240 people were killed over the next few months, and on December 11, 87 people were killed in attacks on state targets. The violence has raised fears of a return to worsening ethnic tension between Hutus and Tutsis. Nkurunziza had led a Hutu rebel group against the then Tutsi-dominated army during the civil war that followed the killing of Hutu President Melchior Ndadaye in 1993.<ref>{{citation|title=Burundi crisis: Army says 87 killed in day of violence|date=December 12, 2015|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-35083823|website=BBC News}}</ref> Violence continued through 2017.<ref>[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/08/killed-burundi-grenade-attacks-bars-170818140040303.html Three killed in Burundi grenade attacks at bars] Al Jazeera, August 18, 2017</ref>\n\n=====Cameroon=====\n{{Main|Anglophone Crisis}}\nThe Anglophone Crisis (French: Crise anglophone), is a conflict in the [[Southern Cameroons]] region of Cameroon, part of the long-standing [[Anglophone problem]] pitting English-speakers against French-speakers; English-speakers make up about one-fifth of the population.<ref name=\"foreign\">{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/09/27/cameroon-must-make-concessions-to-end-the-anglophone-crisis-paul-biya/|title=Cameroon Must Make Concessions to End the Anglophone Crisis|date=September 27, 2019|website=Foreign Affairs}}</ref> In September 2017, separatists in the Anglophone territories of Northwest Region and Southwest Region declared the independence of [[Ambazonia]] and began fighting against the Government of Cameroon. Starting as a low-scale insurgency, the conflict spread to most parts of the Anglophone regions within a year. As of the summer of 2019, the government controls the major cities and parts of the countryside, while the separatists hold parts of the countryside and regularly appear in the major cities.\n\nThe war has killed approximately 2,000 people and forced more than half a million people to flee their homes.<ref name=\"foreign\" /> Although 2019 has seen the first known instance of dialogue between Cameroon and the separatists, as well as a major national dialogue, the war continues to escalate.<ref>[https://africanarguments.org/2019/10/29/violence-increased-cameroon-conflict-national-dialogue-anglophone/ Why has violence increased since Cameroon\u2019s National Dialogue?] R. MAXWELL BONE & AKEM KELVIN, African Arguments, October 29, 20191</ref>\n\n=====Central African Republic=====\n{{Main|Central African Republic Civil War (2012\u2013present)}}\n\n=====C\u00f4te d'Ivoire=====\n{{Main|Second Ivorian Civil War}}\n\n=====Democratic Republic of the Congo=====\n{{Main|Batwa\u2013Luba clashes|Kamwina Nsapu rebellion}}\nThe '''[[Batwa\u2013Luba clashes]]''' is a series of ongoing clashes in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC)]] between the Batwa people and the Luba people starting in 2013.<ref>[https://observers.france24.com/en/20170125-democratic-republic-congo-violent-massacres-pygmy-luba Dozens massacred, bodies mutilated in DR Congo ethnic clashes] The Observers, January 25, 2017</ref>\n\nThe '''[[Kamwina Nsapu rebellion]]''', is an ethnic conflict in the DRC. It is an ongoing rebellion instigated by the Kamwina Nsapu militia in the provinces of Kasa\u00ef-Central, Kasa\u00ef, Kasai-Oriental, Lomami, and Sankuru. The fighting began in August 2016.\n\n=====Egypt=====\n{{Main|2011 Egyptian revolution|2012\u201313 Egyptian protests}}\nThe '''Egyptian revolution of 2011''' started on 25 January 25, 2011 and spread across Egypt. Millions of protesters from a range of socio-economic and religious backgrounds demanded the overthrow of Egyptian President [[Hosni Mubarak]]. Violent clashes between security forces and protesters resulted in at least 846 people killed and over 6,000 injured. Protesters retaliated by burning over 90 police stations across the country. The protesters' grievances focused on legal and political issues, including police brutality, state-of-emergency laws, lack of political freedom, civil liberty, freedom of speech, corruption, high unemployment, food-price inflation, and low wages. The protesters' primary demands were the end of the Mubarak regime and emergency law. Strikes by labour unions added to the pressure on government officials. In February 2011 Vice President [[Omar Suleiman]] announced that had Mubarak resigned as president, turning power over to the Supreme Council of the Armed Forces (SCAF).<ref>{{citation|title=Egypt Revolution: 18 days of people power|date=January 24, 2016|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/inpictures/2016/01/egypt-revolution-160124191716737.html|website=Al Jareeza}}</ref> The military junta, headed by [[Mohamed Hussein Tantawi]], announced on February 13 that the constitution was suspended, both houses of parliament dissolved, and the military would govern until elections could be held. The [[Muslim Brotherhood in Egypt|Muslim Brotherhood]] took power in Egypt through a series of popular elections, with Egyptians electing Islamist [[Mohamed Morsi]] to the presidency in June 2012. However, the Morsi government encountered fierce opposition after his attempt to pass an Islamic-leaning constitution, and mass protests broke out against his rule in late June 2013, and on July 3, 2013, Morsi was deposed by a coup d'\u00e9tat led by the minister of defense, General [[Abdel Fattah el-Sisi]].<ref>{{citation|title=Egypt's Mohammed Morsi: A turbulent presidency cut short|date=June 17, 2019|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-18371427|website=BBC World News}}</ref> El-Sisi went on to become Egypt's president by popular election in [[2014 Egyptian presidential election|2014]].<ref>{{citation|author=Patrick Kingsley|title=Abdel Fatah al-Sisi won 96.1% of vote in Egypt presidential election, say officials|date=June 3, 2014|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jun/03/abdel-fatah-al-sisi-presidential-election-vote-egypt|website=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n=====Eritrea=====\n{{Main| Eritrean-Ethiopian border conflict|}}\n\n=====Guinea=====\n{{Main|2013 Guinea clashes}}\n\n=====Libya=====\n{{Main|Libyan Civil War (2011)|Libyan Civil War (2014\u2013present)}}\n\n=====Mali=====\n{{Main|Mali War|Tuareg rebellion (2012)}}\nThe '''Mali War''', refers to armed conflicts that started from January 2012 between the northern and southern parts of [[Mali]]. On January 16, 2012, several insurgent groups began fighting a campaign against the Malian government for independence or greater autonomy for northern Mali, an area of northern Mali they called [[Azawad]]. The [[National Movement for the Liberation of Azawad|National Movement for the Liberation of Azawad (MNLA)]], an organization fighting to make this area of Mali an independent homeland for the [[Tuareg people]], had taken control of the region by April 2012. The MNLA were initially backed by the Islamist group [[Ansar Dine]]. After the Malian military was driven from northern Mali, Ansar Dine and a number of smaller Islamist groups began imposing strict [[Sharia]] law, and the Tuareg group broke away from them. [[French Armed Forces]] and members of the [[African Union]] helped the government regain control of the area, and a peace agreement was signed in February 2015.<ref>[https://news.un.org/en/story/2015/03/493062#.VQE-cPnF9Fw Deploring ongoing violence, UN rights expert urges Malian parties to work together towards lasting peace] U.N. News, March 10, 2015 [https://www.worldpoliticsreview.com/insights/27306/how-mali-is-pursuing-justice-for-a-war-that-never-really-ended How Mali Is Pursuing Justice for a War That Never Really Ended] Anna Pujol-Mazzini, World Politics Review, January 29, 2019</ref>\n\n=====Mozambique=====\n{{Main|RENAMO insurgency (2013\u20132019)}}\nThe '''RENAMO insurgency''' was a guerrilla campaign by militants of the RENAMO party in [[Mozambique]]. The insurgency is widely considered to be an aftershock of the [[Mozambican Civil War]]; it resulted in renewed tensions between RENAMO and Mozambique's ruling FRELIMO coalition over charges of state corruption and the disputed results of 2014 general elections. A ceasefire was announced between the government and the rebels in September 2014. However, renewed tensions sparked violence in mid-2015. A peace agreement was signed on August 6, 2019.\n\n=====Nigeria=====\n{{Main|Boko Haram insurgency}}\n\n=====Republic of the Congo=====\n{{Main|Pool War}}\n\n=====Somalia=====\n{{Main|Somali Civil War (2009\u2013present)}}\n\n=====South Sudan=====\n{{Main|South Sudanese Civil War}}\nThe '''[[South Sudanese Civil War]]''' broke out in 2013 after a disputed elected and an alleged coup d\u2019etat attempt.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/10/world/africa/new-estimate-sharply-raises-death-toll-in-south-sudan.html|title=New Estimate Sharply Raises Death Toll in South Sudan|author1=Nicholas Kulish|date=January 9, 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|author2=Somini Sengupta}}</ref> An estimated 300,000 people have been killed in the fighting, and over 4 million have been displaced.<ref name=\"lumen\">{{citation|title=Africa in the 21st century|url=https://courses.lumenlearning.com/boundless-worldhistory/chapter/africa-in-the-21st-century/|website=Lumen Boundless History|accessdate=December 10, 2019}}</ref> One hundred thousand people face starvation, and nearly 5 million face severe food shortages; the government declared a [[2017 South Sudan famine|famine]] in 2017.<ref>{{citation|title=South Sudan declares famine in Unity State|date=February 20, 2017|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-39025927|website=BBC World News}}</ref> Several fruitless efforts to agree to a settlement were made in 2014. Fighting continued until a compromise peace agreement was signed in 2015,<ref>{{citation|author=Alastair Leithead|title=Will South Sudan peace deal be worth the wait?|date=August 26, 2015|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-34069032|website=BBC World News}}</ref> but fighting broke out again in [[Battle of Juba (2016)|2016]].<ref>{{citation|title=S Sudan: More than 100 dead on independence anniversary|date=July 10, 2016|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/news/2016/07/south-sudan-scores-dead-independence-anniversary-160709090438275.html|publisher=Al Jazeera}}</ref> The African Union deployed a 12,000 member peace force including soldiers from [[Ethiopia]], [[Kenya]], [[Rwanda]], [[Sudan]], and [[Uganda]], over the objections of President [[Salva Kiir]].<ref>{{citation|title=South Sudan conflict: African Union approves regional force|date=July 19, 2016|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-36833875|website=BBC World News}}</ref> However, fighting continued through 2017.<ref>{{citation|title=South Sudan needs bold alternatives, not this dumpster fire of failed interventions|date=November 15, 2017|url=http://www.thenewhumanitarian.org/opinion/2017/11/15/south-sudan-needs-bold-alternatives-not-dumpster-fire-failed-interventions|website=The New Humanitarian}}</ref>\n\n=====Sudan=====\n{{Main|War in Darfur}}\nThe '''[[War in Darfur]]''', ([[Sudan]]) began in 2003, resulting in hundreds of thousands of deaths, [[genocide]],<ref name=\"britannica\">{{cite encyclopedia|encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia Britannica|title=8 Deadliest Wars of the 21st Century|author=Michael Ray|accessdate=December 10, 2019|url=https://www.britannica.com/list/8-deadliest-wars-of-the-21st-century}}</ref> and [[ethnic cleansing]]. An [[International Criminal Court investigation in Darfur|International Criminal Court investigation]] resulted in two warrants against President [[Omar al-Bashir]] and his eventual arrest.<ref>{{citation|title=Statement to the United Nations Security Council on the Situation in Darfur, pursuant to UNSCR 1593 (2005)|date=June 19, 2019|url=https://www.icc-cpi.int/Pages/item.aspx?name=190619-stat-otp-UNSC-Darfur-Sudan|website=International Criminal Court}}</ref> The [[Darfur Peace Agreement|Doha Agreement]] was signed in 2011,<ref>{{citation|title=Under peace deal, Sudan would halt prep for Darfur Referendum|date=June 4, 2011|url=https://www.dabangasudan.org/en/all-news/article/under-peace-deal-sudan-would-halt-prep-for-darfur-referendum|website=Dabanga Sudan}}</ref> but little real progress was made a year later.<ref>{{citation|title=Sudan: Ambassador Smith \u2013 'Security Situation in Darfur Deteriorated Compared to 2011'|date=September 19, 2012|url=https://allafrica.com/stories/201209200049.html|website=All Africa}}</ref> The war continued through 2016, including with allegations that the government had used [[mustard gas]].<ref>{{citation|author=James Rothwell|title=Darfur conflict: 'Hundreds of children gassed to death since January by government in Sudan'|date=September 29, 2016|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/09/29/darfur-conflict-sudanese-government-has-gassed-hundreds-of-child/|website=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n==== Piracy ====\n{{Main|Piracy in the 21st century}}\n[[Piracy in the Gulf of Guinea]] affects a number of countries in West Africa, including [[Benin]], [[Togo]], [[C\u00f4te d\u2019Ivoire]], [[Ghana]], [[Nigeria]], and the [[Democratic Republic of Congo]] as well as the wider international community. By 2011, it had become an issue of global concern. Pirates are often part of heavily armed criminal enterprises, who employ violent methods to steal oil cargo. In 2012, the [[International Maritime Bureau]] and other agencies reported that the number of vessels attacks by West African pirates had reached a world high, with 966 seafarers attacked and five killed during the year.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/19/world/africa/west-african-piracy-exceeds-somali-attacks-report-says.html West African Piracy Exceeds Somali Attacks, Report Says] Alan Cowell, ''The New York Times'', June 18, 2013</ref>\n\n[[Piracy off the coast of Somalia]] occurs in the [[Gulf of Aden]], [[Guardafui Channel]], [[Somali Sea]], in Somali territorial waters and other areas. It was initially a threat to international fishing vessels, expanding to international shipping since the second phase of the Somali Civil War, around 2000. By December 2013, the US Office of Naval Intelligence reported that only nine vessels had been attacked during the year by the pirates, with no successful hijackings.<ref>[https://qz.com/161704/somali-piracy-was-reduced-to-zero-this-year/ Somali piracy was reduced to zero this year] David Yanofsky in Somalia, ''Quartz'', December 27, 2013</ref> In March 2017, it was reported that pirates had seized an oil tanker that had set sail from [[Djibouti]] and was headed to [[Mogadishu]]. The ship and its crew were released with no ransom given after the pirate crew learned that the ship had been hired by Somali businessmen.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/mar/16/somali-pirates-release-oil-tanker-and-crew-after-first-hijack-for-five-years Somali pirates release oil tanker and crew after first hijack for five years] The Guardian World News, March 16, 2017</ref>\n\n=====War on Terror=====\n{{Main|War on terror|ISIL insurgency in Tunisia|Insurgency in the Maghreb (2002\u2013present)|Islamist insurgency in Mozambique|Boko Haram insurgency}}\nThe most prominent terrorist groups that are creating a terror impact in Africa include [[Boko Haram]] of [[Boko Haram insurgency|Nigeria]], [[Cameroon]], [[Chad]], and [[Niger]], and [[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Al-Shabaab]] of Somalia.<ref name=\"accord\">{{citation|author=LWEENDO KAMBELA|title=Terrorism in Africa|date=June 24, 2019|url=https://www.accord.org.za/conflict-trends/terrorism-in-africa/|website=ACCORD: The African Centre for the Constructive Resolution of Disputes}}</ref>\n\n'''Boko Haram''' has carried out more than 3,416 terror events since 2009, leading to more than 36,000 fatalities. One of the better-known examples of Boko Haram's terror tactics was the [[Chibok schoolgirls kidnapping|2014 Chibok schoolgirls kidnapping]] of 276 schoolgirls in [[Borno State]], Nigeria.<ref name=\"accord\"/> Boko Haram is believed to have links to [[al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb]] dating back to at least 2010. In 2015 the group expressed its allegiance to the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]], which ISIL accepted.<ref>{{citation|title=IS welcomes Boko Haram allegiance: tape|date=March 12, 2015|url=https://news.yahoo.com/accepts-allegiance-nigeria-jihadists-boko-haram-201513146.html|website=AFP/Yahoo! News}}</ref>\n\nSomalia's '''al-Shabaab''' and its Islamic extremism can be traced back to the mid-1970s when the group began as an underground movement opposing the repressive and corrupt regime of [[Siad Barre]]. Armed conflict between al-Shabaab and the Somali army \u2013 including associated human rights violations \u2013 has resulted in slightly over 68 million human displacements.<ref name=\"accord\"/> Al-Shabaab is hostile to Sufi traditions and has often clashed with the militant Sufi group [[Ahlu Sunna Waljama'a]]. The group has also been suspected of having links with Al-Qaeda in Islamic Maghreb and Boko Haram. Among their best-known attacks are the [[Westgate shopping mall attack]] in [[Nairobi]], Kenya, in September 2013 (resulting in 71 deaths and 200 injured) and the [[14 October 2017 Mogadishu bombings]] that killed 587 and injured 316.<ref>[https://hiiraan.com/news4/2018/Mar/157047/committee_587_dead_in_oct_14_terror_attack.aspx Committee: 587 dead in Oct 14 terror attack] Hiiraan Online, March 5, 2018</ref> On September 1, 2014, a U.S. drone strike carried out as part of the broader mission killed al-Shabaab leader [[Ahmed Abdi Godane]].<ref>{{citation|author=Stefan Smith|title=Shebab's new leader a devout, ruthless hardliner|date=September 7, 2014|url=https://news.yahoo.com/shebabs-leader-devout-ruthless-hardliner-sources-105730104.html;_ylt=AwrBEiSgiwxUUkoAbqrQtDMD|website=AFP/Yahoo! News}}</ref>\n\nThe '''Insurgency in the Maghreb''' refers to Islamist militant and terrorist activity in northern Africa since 2002, including [[Algeria]], [[2007 killing of French tourists in Mauritania|Mauritania]], [[Tunisia]], [[2003 Casablanca bombings|Morocco]], [[Niger]], [[Mali War|Mali]], [[2016 Grand-Bassam shootings|Ivory Coast]], [[Brak El-Shati airbase raid|Libya]], [[Western Sahara]], and [[Burkina Faso]], as well as having ties to Boko Haram in Nigeria. The conflict followed the conclusion of the [[Algerian Civil War]] as a militant group became [[al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb|al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb (AQIM)]]. Their tactics have included bombings; shootings; and kidnappings, particularly of foreign tourists. In addition to African units, the fight against the insurgency has been led primarily by the [[Operation Serval|French Foreign Legion]], although the U.S. also has over 1,300 troops in the region. Four American soldiers were killed in the October 4, 2017 [[Tongo Tongo ambush]] in Niger.<ref>[https://abcnews.go.com/International/us-soldiers-killed-niger-outgunned-left-hunt-isis/story?id=54909240 US soldiers killed in Niger were outgunned, 'left behind' in hunt for ISIS leader] James Gordon Meek, ABC News, May 3, 2018</ref>\n\n====Arab Spring====\n{{Main|Tunisian Revolution}}\n\n====Health crisis====\nAbout 1.6&nbsp;million Africans died of malaria, tuberculosis and HIV-related illnesses in 2015.<ref name=\"renewal\">{{citation|author=TEFO PHEAGE|title=Dying from lack of medicines|date=March 2017|url=https://www.un.org/africarenewal/magazine/december-2016-march-2017/dying-lack-medicines#:~:targetText=Without%20access%20to%20medicines%2C%20Africans,World%20Health%20Organisation%20(WHO).|website=United Nations: Africa Renweal}}</ref> Poor health care, malnutrition, and [[Ebola]] are also serious problems.<ref name=lumen/>\n\nOver 25.5&nbsp;million individuals infected with '''HIV/AIDS''' in 2015 were Africans. Most of these victims are middle-income or lower, and they depend on public health sources for treatment, but many medicines are unavailable due to cost, availability, and/or other factors such as transportation.<ref name=renewal/> South Africa, Egypt, Morocco, and Tunisia have made progress in local pharmaceutical productions; Ghana, Kenya, Nigeria, and Tanzania are currently developing production capacity.<ref name=renewal/>\n\n85% to 90% of malaria victims worldwide occur in Sub-Saharan Africa.<ref name=renewal/>\n\n===Asia===\n====China====\n{{Main|Xi Jinping Core Administration}}\n[[Xi Jinping]] succeeded [[Hu Jintao]] as [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China]] and became the [[paramount leader]] of China in 15 November 2012. He immediately began an [[Anti-corruption campaign under Xi Jinping|anti-corruption campaign]], in which more than 100,000 individuals were indicted, including senior leader [[Zhou Yongkang]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/china/2015/10/22/robber-barons-beware|title=Robber barons, beware, Robber barons, beware|work=The Economist|access-date=January 11, 2020|issn=0013-0613}}</ref> There have been claims of political motives behind the campaign.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/china/2014/12/11/tiger-in-the-net|title=Tiger in the net, Tiger in the net|work=The Economist|access-date=January 11, 2020|issn=0013-0613}}</ref> In 2018, he was effectively made a [[president for life]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-43361276|title=China approves 'president for life' change|date=March 11, 2018|access-date=January 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn Xi's [[Foreign policy of Xi Jinping|foreign policy]], China became more aggressive with its actions in the [[Territorial disputes in the South China Sea|South China Sea dispute]], by building [[artificial island]]s and militarizing existing [[reef]]s, beginning in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amti.csis.org/island-tracker/china/|title=China Tracker|website=Asia Maritime Transparency Initiative|access-date=January 11, 2020}}</ref> Another key part of its foreign policy has been the [[Belt and Road Initiative]] (BRI), a strategy adopted by China involving infrastructure development and investments in countries and organizations in Asia, Europe, Africa, the Middle East, and the Americas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldbank.org/en/topic/regional-integration/brief/belt-and-road-initiative|title=Belt and Road Initiative|publisher=World Bank|access-date=March 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-05-14/china-attempts-global-dominance-with-one-belt-one/8522974</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neweurope.eu/article/panama-first-in-latin-america-to-join-chinas-belt-and-road-initiative/|title=Panama first in Latin America to join China's Belt and Road Initiative|date=December 7, 2018|website=New Europe|access-date=March 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thefinancialexpress.com.bd/economy/global/152-countries-intl-organisations-sign-belt-and-road-deals-with-china-1551686061|title=152 countries, int'l organisations sign Belt and Road deals with China|last=Express|first=The Financial|website=The Financial Express|access-date=March 10, 2019}}</ref> China has signed cooperational documents on the belt and road initiative with 126 countries and 29 international organisations,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yidaiyilu.gov.cn/info/iList.jsp?tm_id=126&cat_id=10122&info_id=77298|title=\u5df2\u540c\u4e2d\u570b\u7c3d\u8a02\u5171\u5efa\u4e00\u5e36\u4e00\u8def\u5408\u4f5c\u6587\u4ef6\u7684\u570b\u5bb6\u4e00\u89bd|publisher=\u4e2d\u570b\u4e00\u5e36\u4e00\u8def\u7db2|date=April 12, 2019|accessdate=April 24, 2019}}</ref> where various efforts then went ahead on infrastructure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eng.yidaiyilu.gov.cn/qwyw/rdxw/69500.htm|title=B&R interconnection witnesses great breakthroughs in 5-year development-Belt and Road Portal|website=eng.yidaiyilu.gov.cn|access-date=January 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the end of the decade, concerns started to grow about the future of the [[Economy of China|Chinese economy]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/17/business/china-economic-growth.html|title=China's Economic Growth Slows as Challenges Mount|last=Bradsher|first=Keith|date=October 17, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 11, 2020|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> These concerns included whether the United States and China could positively resolve their [[China\u2013United States trade war|disputes over trade]].<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-12-06/trade-war-latest-china-trump-tariffs-stocks-bonds-currency Mood Shifts in U.S.-China Trade Talks Infect Markets Far and Wide], by Liz Capo McCormick December 6, 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2019/12/06/trump-faces-complicated-calculus-on-december-tariffs-on-chinese-goods.html Trump\u2019s tricky decision: Hit Chinese goods with new tariffs or hold off?] by Kayla Tausche, December 6, 2019.</ref>\n\n=====Hong Kong=====\n{{Main|2014 Hong Kong protests|2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests]], also known as the Anti-Extradition Law Amendment Bill (Anti-ELAB) movement, is an ongoing series of demonstrations in Hong Kong triggered by the introduction of [[2019 Hong Kong extradition bill|the Fugitive Offenders amendment bill]] by the [[Government of Hong Kong|Hong Kong government]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-49317695 The Hong Kong protests explained in 100 and 500 words], bbc.com, November 28, 2019.</ref>\nIf enacted, the bill would have empowered local authorities to detain and extradite criminal fugitives who are wanted in territories with which Hong Kong does not currently have extradition agreements, including [[Taiwan]] and [[mainland China]]. This led to concerns that the bill would subject Hong Kong residents and visitors to the jursidiction and legal system of mainland China, which would undermine [[One country, two systems|the region's autonomy]] and Hong Kong people's civil liberties.As the protests progressed, the protesters laid out five key demands, which were the withdrawal of the bill, investigation into [[Allegations of Hong Kong Police Force misconduct surrounding the 2019 Hong Kong protests|alleged police brutality and misconduct]], the release of arrested protesters, a complete retraction of the official characterisation of the protests as \"riots\", and Chief Executive [[Carrie Lam]]'s resignation along with the introduction of [[universal suffrage]] for election of the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong|Legislative Council]] and the Chief Executive.<ref name=\"nbc_1061086\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/hong-kong-police-defend-shooting-protester-lawful-reasonable-n1061086|title=Hong Kong police defend shooting protester as 'lawful and reasonable'|first=Veta|last=Chan|publisher=[[NBC News]]|date=October 2, 2019|accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"nbc_1067466\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/think/opinion/chinese-mainlanders-living-hong-kong-feel-stuck-between-rock-hard-ncna1067466|title=Opinion &#124; Mainland Chinese like me are stuck between a rock and a hard place in Hong Kong|publisher=NBC News}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"nbc_1090206\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/hong-kong-turns-out-huge-numbers-vote-viewed-referendum-protests-n1090206|title=Pro-democracy candidates win big in election viewed as referendum on protests|publisher=NBC News|access-date=November 25, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"now_340955\">{{Cite news|url=https://news.now.com/home/local/player?newsId=340955|script-title=zh:\u773e\u5fd7\u885d\u5165\u653f\u7e3d\u975c\u5750\u4fc3\u64a4\u56de\u9003\u72af\u689d\u4f8b\u4fee\u8a02|language=zh|trans-title=Demosist\u014d got to HK Govt. HQ against the extradition bill amendment|work=Now.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104050116/https://news.now.com/home/local/player%3FnewsId%3D340955|archive-date=November 4, 2019 |date=March 15, 2019|url-status=live|format=video}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"now_355501\">{{cite news|url=https://news.now.com/home/local/player?newsId=355501|title=\u6709\u5927\u5f8b\u5e2b\u7a31\u8b66\u65b9\u9032\u5165\u5546\u5834\u6e05\u5834\u6216\u9055\u53cd\u8b66\u5bdf\u901a\u4f8b|publisher=[[NOW TV]]|date=July 15, 2019|accessdate=August 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190820150906/https://news.now.com/home/local/player%3FnewsId%3D355501|archive-date=August 20, 2019|url-status=live|format=video}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"npr_779399836\">{{cite web |last1=Kennedy |first1=Merrit |title=Hong Kong Police Say Protesters Are Shooting Arrows From Universities |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/11/14/779399836/hong-kong-police-say-protesters-are-shooting-arrows-from-universities |publisher=NPR |date=November 14, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"npr_780405090\">{{cite web |last1=Chappell |first1=Bill |title=Hong Kong Protesters in Tense Standoff With Police at Polytechnic University Campus |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/11/18/780405090/hong-kong-protesters-in-tense-standoff-with-police-at-polytech-university-campus |publisher=NPR |date=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"nyt_20190610_carriestandfast\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/10/world/asia/hong-kong-carrie-lam-extradition.html|title=Hong Kong Leader, Carrie Lam, Says She Won't Back Down on Extradition Bill|last=Ramzy|first=Austin|date=June 10, 2019|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=October 5, 2019|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610100501/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/10/world/asia/hong-kong-carrie-lam-extradition.html|archive-date=June 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"nyt_20190610_whatis\">{{cite news|last=Ives |first=Mike |date=June 10, 2019 |title=What Is Hong Kong's Extradition Bill? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/10/world/asia/hong-kong-extradition-bill.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|issn=0362-4331|location=Hong Kong|accessdate=July 29, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190612202157/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/10/world/asia/hong-kong-extradition-bill.html|archive-date=June 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"nyt_20190628_selfregulate\">{{cite news|last1=Lau Yiu-man|first1=Lewis|title=Hong Kong's Protesters Are Resisting China With Anarchy and Principle: The movement is leaderless but not chaotic. It self-regulates even as it constantly reinvents itself.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/28/opinion/hong-kong-protests-extradition-china.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|6=|issn=0362-4331|accessdate=July 8, 2019|date=June 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190628191107/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/28/opinion/hong-kong-protests-extradition-china.html|archive-date=June 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><!---<ref name=\"nyt_20190610_whatis\" /><ref name=\"bbc_49317695\" /><ref name=\"hkfp_20190213_trojanhorse\" /><ref name=\"hkfp_20190904_billwithdrawn\" /><ref name=\"abc_66464962\" /><ref name=\"reuters_20190524_eudiplomaticnote\" /><ref name=\"eji_20190523\" /><ref name=\"hkfp_20190522_chrispatten\" /><ref name=\"scmp_3004067\" /> --->\n\n====India====\n{{Unreferenced section|date=January 2020}}\n\nThe decade started off with the Congress led [[United Progressive Alliance]] (UPA) in power. UPA had won a majority in 2009 for a second term which was marred by corruption allegations. Taking advantage of the UPA's growing unpopularity, The [[Bhartiya Janata Party]] (BJP) led by former Gujarat Chief Minister [[Narendra Modi]] swept the polls in the 2014 general elections.\n\nRiding high on the wave of nationalism in the wake of attacks claimed by Indian authorities to have been orchestrated by Pakistan the Modi government relied heavily on anti-Pakistan rhetoric in successive elections. In 2016, a hard line Hindu monk associated with the BJP was elected chief minister of India's largest state who in turn pursued a policy of changing names of places with Muslim names to Hindu ones.\n\nThe Indian government, during this time also massively increased its defense budget and enhanced defense ties with the United States and Israel. The relationship with Israel continued to bloom as Modi became the first Indian Prime Minister to visit the Jewish state.\n\nCritics of the Modi government continued to level criticism at him for polarizing minorities, especially Muslims and changing the fabric of the Indian state by relentlessly pursuing the Hindutva ideology. In its second term in power, the BJP led National Democratic Alliance (NDA) became even more ideological in its pursuit of the Hindutva agenda. On August 5, 2019, the newly elected Indian government under a presidential order revoked Article 370 of the Indian constitution, thereby terminating the special status of Jammu and Kashmir and placed it under curfew. This move triggered widespread international condemnation and further aggravated relations with neighboring Pakistan. Later that year, the Supreme Court also delivered a verdict on the controversial Ram janam bhoomi case which called for a temple to be built on the disputed site while granting land to the Sunni Waqf Board for the establishment of a mosque elsewhere.\n\n===Middle East===\nStarting in 2010, [[Arab Spring]] led to major political upheaval across the region, leading to the violent repression of the [[Arab Winter]]. A [[Arab protests (2018\u2013present)|Second Arab Spring]] started in the later part of the decade.\n\n====Iran====\nThe [[2019 Iranian protests]] are a series of civil protests occurring in multiple cities across [[Iran]], initially from the 200% increase in fuel prices but later extended to an outcry against the [[Government of the Islamic Republic of Iran|current government in Iran]] and [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]] [[Khamenei|Ali Khamenei]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/dec/06/at-least-7000-people-reportedly-arrested-in-iran-protests-says-un At least 7,000 people reportedly arrested in Iran protests, says UN], Agence France-Presse, Fri December 6, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"auto1b\">{{Cite web|url=https://iranintl.com/%D8%A7%D9%8A%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%86/%DA%AF%D8%B3%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%B4-%D8%A7%D8%B9%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%B6%E2%80%8C%D9%87%D8%A7-%D8%A8%D9%87-%D8%A7%D9%81%D8%B2%D8%A7%DB%8C%D8%B4-%D9%82%DB%8C%D9%85%D8%AA-%D8%A8%D9%86%D8%B2%DB%8C%D9%86-%DB%8C%DA%A9-%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%B6-%D8%AF%D8%B1-%D8%B3%DB%8C%D8%B1%D8%AC%D8%A7%D9%86-%D8%A8%D8%A7-%D8%B4%D9%84%DB%8C%DA%A9-%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%85%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%86-%DA%A9%D8%B4%D8%AA%D9%87-%D8%B4%D8%AF|title=\u06af\u0633\u062a\u0631\u0634 \u0627\u0639\u062a\u0631\u0627\u0636\u200c\u0647\u0627 \u0628\u0647 \u0627\u0641\u0632\u0627\u06cc\u0634 \u0642\u06cc\u0645\u062a \u0628\u0646\u0632\u06cc\u0646: \u06cc\u06a9 \u0645\u0639\u062a\u0631\u0636 \u062f\u0631 \u0633\u06cc\u0631\u062c\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u0627 \u0634\u0644\u06cc\u06a9 \u0645\u0627\u0645\u0648\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u06a9\u0634\u062a\u0647 \u0634\u062f |date=November 15, 2019 |website=[[Iran International]] |language=fa|access-date=November 16, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":0b\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-50444429|title=Protests erupt over Iran petrol rationing|date=November 16, 2019|access-date=November 16, 2019}}</ref> The protests commenced in the evening of November 15 and within hours spread to 21 cities as videos of the protest began to circulate online.<ref>{{cite web |title=Amnesty International: Over 100 Killed in 21 Cities in Iran Protests |url=https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/iran/amnesty-international-over-100-killed-in-21-cities-in-iran-protests-1.8153333 |work=Haaretz}}</ref><ref name=\"veconomist1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/middle-east-and-africa/2019/11/17/hikes-in-the-cost-of-petrol-are-fuelling-unrest-in-iran|title=Hikes in the cost of petrol are fuelling unrest in Iran|date=November 17, 2019|work=[[The Economist]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiofarda.com/a/iran-protests-fuel-price-hike/30274328.html|title=\u0627\u0641\u0632\u0627\u06cc\u0634 \u0642\u06cc\u0645\u062a \u0628\u0646\u0632\u06cc\u0646\u061b \u0634\u0647\u0631\u0647\u0627\u06cc \u0645\u062e\u062a\u0644\u0641 \u0627\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u0635\u062d\u0646\u0647 \u0627\u0639\u062a\u0631\u0627\u0636\u0627\u062a \u0634\u062f|website=\u0631\u0627\u062f\u06cc\u0648 \u0641\u0631\u062f\u0627}}</ref> Images of the violent protests were shared on the internet with protests reaching international levels.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/19/world/middleeast/iran-protests.html|title=Iran's 'Iron Fist': Rights Group Says More Than 100 Protesters Are Dead|last=Fassihi|first=Farnaz|date=November 19, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 21, 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the protests began as peaceful gatherings, government crackdowns prompted a revolt against the entire [[Government of the Islamic Republic of Iran|Iranian government]].<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite web |last1=Fassihi |first1=Farnaz |title=Iran Declares Protests Are Over, but the Evidence Suggests Otherwise |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/21/world/middleeast/iran-protests-internet.html}}</ref>  The Iranian government employed lethal tactics in order to shut down the protests including a nationwide internet shutdown, shooting protesters dead from rooftops, helicopters, and at close range with machine gun fire.<ref name=\"With Brutal Crackdown, Iran Is Conv\">{{cite web |last1=Gladstone |first1=Rick |title=With Brutal Crackdown, Iran Is Convulsed by Worst Unrest in 40 Years |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/01/world/middleeast/iran-protests-deaths.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Swert |first1=Mia |title=Amnesty says at least 208 killed in Iran protests |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/11/amnesty-208-killed-iran-protests-191130151227593.html}}</ref> Although there is currently no conclusive casualty count current estimates suspect the government killed well over 1,000 [[Iranian peoples|Iranian]] citizens.<ref>[https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/u-s-says-iran-may-have-killed-1-000-protesters-n1096666 U.S. says Iran may have killed up to 1,000 protesters] \n</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=McKenzie |first1=Sheena |title=One of the worst crackdowns in decades is happening in Iran. Here's what we know |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/12/03/middleeast/iran-protests-violent-crackdown-information-intl/index.html |publisher=CNN}}</ref> \n \nThe government crack down prompted a violent reaction from protesters who destroyed 731 government banks including Iran's central bank, nine [[Islamic]] religious centers, tore down [[anti-American]] billboards, and posters and statues of the Supreme Leader [[Ali Khamenei]]. 50 government military bases were also attacked by protesters. This series of protests have been categorized as the most violent and severe since the rise of [[Government of the Islamic Republic of Iran|Iran's Islamic Republic]] in 1979.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2019/11/iran-more-than-100-protesters-believed-to-be-killed-as-top-officials-give-green-light-to-crush-protests/|title=Iranian security forces are using lethal force to crush protests|publisher=Amnesty International|access-date=November 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=CASCHETTA |first1=A.J. |title=Iranian protests were not about the price of gas |url=https://thehill.com/opinion/international/472359-iranian-protests-were-not-about-the-price-of-gas |website=The Hill}}</ref><ref name=\"With Brutal Crackdown, Iran Is Conv\"/>\n\nTo block the sharing of information regarding the protests and the deaths of hundreds of protesters on social media platforms, the government blocked the Internet nationwide, resulting in a near-total internet blackout of around six days.<ref>https://netblocks.org/reports/internet-disrupted-in-iran-amid-fuel-protests-in-multiple-cities-pA25L18b</ref><ref>{[https://twitter.com/netblocks/status/1198215946286055424 Internet access is being restored in #Iran after a weeklong internet shutdown amid widespread protests; real-time network data show national connectivity now up to 64% of normal levels as of shutdown hour 163 #IranProtests #Internet4Iran https://netblocks.org/reports/internet-restored-in-iran-after-protest-shutdown] |last=NetBlocks.org|date=November 23, 2019|website=@netblocks|access-date=November 24, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraph1\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/11/23/iranian-masks-spiraling-protest-death-toll-stealing-bodies-morgues/ Iranian officials 'stealing bodies' from morgues to hide true scale of government crackdown]</ref><ref name=\"albawaba1\">[https://www.albawaba.com/node/mysterious-disappearances-iran-stealing-bodies-morgues-disguise-crackdown-protesters Mysterious Disappearances: Is Iran Stealing Bodies From Morgues to Disguise Crackdown on Protesters?]</ref>\n\n====Iraq====\n{{main|2019 Iraqi protests}}\n{{see also|2010s in Iraq political history}}\n\nThe [[2019 Iraqi protests]], also nicknamed the Tishreen Revolution<ref>{{cite web|url=https://iraqakhbar.com/2084791|title=\u062b\u0648\u0631\u0629 \u062a\u0634\u0631\u064a\u0646 \u2026\u0648\u0637\u0645\u0648\u062d\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0628\u0627\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0634\u0631\u0648\u0639\u0629|language=Arabic|trans-title=The October Revolution{{nbsp}}... and the legitimate ambitions of young people|website=News of Iraq|accessdate=November 15, 2019|date=November 12, 2019}}</ref> and 2019 Iraqi Intifada, are an ongoing series of protests that consisted of [[Demonstration (political)|demonstrations]], [[marches]], [[sit-ins]] and [[civil disobedience]]. They started on 1{{nbsp}}October 2019, a date which was set by civil activists on social media, spreading over the central and southern provinces of Iraq, to protest 16 years of corruption, unemployment and inefficient public services, before they escalated into calls to overthrow the administration and to stop [[Iranian intervention in Iraq (2014\u2013present)|Iranian intervention in Iraq]]. The Iraqi government has been accused of using bullets, snipers, hot water and [[tear gas]] against protesters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/iraq-hrw-denounces-lethal-force-protesters-urges-probe-191010123643525.html|title=Iraq: HRW denounces lethal force against protesters, urges probe|publisher=Al Jazeera}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Adil Abdul-Mahdi]] announced on November 29 that he would resign.<ref name=Resignation29Nov>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/11/29/iraq-prime-minister-resign-worsening-crisis-074396|title=Iraqi prime minister to resign in wake of deadly protests|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=November 29, 2019|accessdate=November 29, 2019}}</ref> According to the [[BBC]], they call for the end of the political system which has existed since [[2003 invasion of Iraq|the US-led invasion]] ousted [[Saddam Hussein]] and has been marked by sectarian divides.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-49960677 | work=BBC News | title=Iraq protests: What's behind the anger?| date=October 7, 2019 | accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"guardiansaddam\">{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/oct/27/iraq-protests-aim-topple-regime | work=[[The Guardian]]| title='They are worse than Saddam': Iraqis take to streets to topple regime| date=October 27, 2019 | accessdate=October 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://providencemag.com/2019/11/iraq-protests/|title=An Iraq for All Iraqis?|date=November 26, 2019|website=Providence|access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref> It is the largest unrest since the Saddam Hussein government concluded.<ref name=\"larges\">{{cite news| url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/11/07/why-iraqs-protesters-are-still-in-the-streets | work=[[Foreign Policy]] | title=Iraq Protester's Step Up Their Tactics As the Government in Baghdad Scrambles to Respond | date=November 7, 2019 | accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe UN Envoy for Iraq, [[Jeanine Hennis-Plasschaert]], called for renewed efforts to restore civil balance and protections for free speech.<ref>[https://news.un.org/en/story/2019/12/1052641 Protests and civil unrest show \u2018renewed sense of patriotism\u2019 in Iraq, UN envoy tells Security Council], United Nations., December 3, 2019.</ref><ref>[https://news.un.org/en/story/2019/12/1053011 Denouncing attacks against Baghdad protesters, UN warns \u2018violence risks placing Iraq on dangerous trajectory], December 7, 2019.</ref>\n\n====Israel====\n[[Benjamin Netanyahu]] remained in the office of the [[Prime Minister of Israel|Prime Minister]] throughout the decade, becoming the longest holder of the office. Under his watch, the [[Israeli settlement|Jewish settlement movement]] has grown and gained influence, with at least 2,000 new homes built on the [[Palestinian territories]] each year, leading to a declining possibility for a [[two-state solution]] in the [[Arab\u2013Israeli conflict]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/04/08/709989737/after-a-decade-of-netanyahu-hopes-fade-for-a-palestinian-state|title=After A Decade Of Netanyahu, Hopes Fade for a Palestinian State|publisher=NPR|access-date=January 11, 2020}}</ref> In 2014, there was a [[2014 Israel\u2013Gaza conflict|war in Gaza]] over [[Hamas]] rocket firings into Israeli cities, with a final death toll of 2,100 Palestinians and 73 Israeli citizens.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-28439404|title=Gaza crisis: Toll of operations in Gaza|date=September 1, 2014|access-date=January 11, 2020}}</ref> The [[2018\u201319 Gaza border protests]] demanded a [[right of return]] for those displaced from their homes during Israel's founding.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/04/13/world/middleeast/gaza-fence-aerial.html,%20https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/04/13/world/middleeast/gaza-fence-aerial.html|title=300 Meters in Gaza: Snipers, Burning Tires and a Contested Fence \u2013 The New York Times|last=Halbfinger|first=David M.|date=May 15, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 11, 2020|last2=Abuheweila|first2=Iyad|issn=0362-4331|last3=Patel|first3=Jugal K.}}</ref> Israeli security forces responded by firing at the protesters, killing 60 in a single day.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/15/world/middleeast/israel-gaza-protests.html|title=Uneasy Calm Falls Over Gaza After Israel Kills Scores at Protests|last=Times|first=The New York|date=May 15, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 11, 2020|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn foreign policy, Israel continued the [[Iran\u2013Israel proxy conflict|proxy conflict against Iran]], with [[Israeli involvement in the Syrian Civil War]] and [[2019 Israeli airstrikes in Iraq]].\n\nIn 2019, the country entered a political crisis following two [[hung parliament]]s and corruption charges against Netanyehu.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/11/22/israel-political-crisis-deadlock-benjamin-netanyahu-indictment-corruption-election/|title=Israel's Political Crisis Deepens|last=Wilson|first=Audrey|website=Foreign Policy|access-date=January 11, 2020}}</ref> Both the [[April 2019 Israeli legislative election|April]] and [[September 2019 Israeli legislative election|September 2019 elections]] failed to produce a majority in the Knesset for either Netanyehu, or his challenger, [[Benny Gantz]], a former general. In November, Netanyehu became the first sitting Israeli leader to be criminally prosecuted, with [[Investigations involving Benjamin Netanyahu|charges of bribery, fraud and breach of trust spanning several cases]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/21/world/middleeast/netanyahu-corruption-indicted.html|title=Israel's Netanyahu Indicted on Charges of Fraud, Bribery and Breach of Trust|last=Halbfinger|first=David M.|date=November 21, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 11, 2020|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n====Syria====\n{{main|Syria Civil War}}\n{{see also|2010s in Syria political history}}\n\nThe [[2019 Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria]] is a cross-border military operation conducted by the [[Turkish Armed Forces]] (TAF) and the [[Syrian National Army]] (SNA) against the [[Syrian Democratic Forces]] (SDF) and later the [[Syrian Arab Army]] (SAA) in [[Rojava|northeastern Syria]].\n\nOn October 6, 2019, the [[Trump administration]] ordered American troops to withdraw from northeastern Syria, where the United States [[American-led intervention in the Syrian Civil War|had been supporting]] its Kurdish allies.<ref name=withdraw>{{cite news |title=Trump makes way for Turkey operation against Kurds in Syria |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-49956698?intlink_from_url=https://www.bbc.com/news/topics/cp7r8vgl2y7t/kurds&link_location=live-reporting-story |accessdate=October 10, 2019 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=October 7, 2019}}</ref> The military operation began on October 9, 2019 when the [[Turkish Air Force]] launched airstrikes on [[Syria\u2013Turkey border|border]] towns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/oct/09/turkey-launches-military-operation-in-northern-syria-erdogan|title=Turkey launches military operation in northern Syria|work=The Guardian|first=Bethan|last=McKernan|date=October 9, 2019}}</ref> The conflict resulted in the displacement of over 300,000 people and has caused the death of more than 70 civilians in Syria and 20 civilians in Turkey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bursadabugun.com/haber/teroristlerin-saldirilarinda-20-sivil-sehit-oldu-170-kisi-yaralandi-1191643.html|title=Ter\u00f6ristlerin sald\u0131r\u0131lar\u0131nda 20 sivil \u015fehit oldu, 170 ki\u015fi yaraland\u0131|website=Bursada Bug\u00fcn}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/syria/kurdish-politician-executed-by-turkish-backed-fighters-in-syria-1.7970427|title=Kurdish Politician Among Nine Civilians Executed by Turkish-backed Fighters in Syria|date=October 13, 2019|newspaper=[[Haaretz]]}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the Turkish President [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]], the operation is intended to expel the SDF\u2014viewed as a terrorist organization by Turkey due to its ties with the [[Kurdistan Workers Party]] (PKK), but considered an ally against [[ISIL]] by the [[Combined Joint Task Force \u2013 Operation Inherent Resolve|United States and its allies]]\u2014from the border region as well as to create a 30&nbsp;km-deep (20&nbsp;mi) \"safe zone\" in Northern Syria where some of the 3.6&nbsp;million [[Syrian refugees in Turkey]] would resettle.<ref name=\"aj-turkey-begins\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/turkey-begins-ground-offensive-northeastern-syria-191009212025006.html |title=Turkey begins ground offensive in northeastern Syria |date=October 9, 2019 |publisher=[[Al Jazeera]] |access-date=October 10, 2019}}</ref> As the proposed settlement zone is heavily Kurdish demographically, this intention has been criticized as an attempt to force drastic demographic change,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2019/09/turkey-syria-united-states-erdogan-plans-for-east-euphrates.html|title=Erdogan's Syria plan: Resettling the Syrian refugees or ousting Kurds from their land?|first=Cengiz|last=Candar|date=September 30, 2019|website=Al-Monitor}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/e40cb754-e456-11e9-b112-9624ec9edc59|title=Syria is witnessing a violent demographic re-engineering|website=[[Financial Times]]}}</ref><ref name=reuters_demographics>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security-turkey-refugees-graphi-idUSKBN1WN28J|title=Turkey's plan to settle refugees in northeast Syria alarms allies|date=October 8, 2019|agency=Reuters}}</ref> a criticism denied by Turkey by saying that it only intended to \"correct\" the demographics that Turkish officials stated were changed by the SDF.<ref name=reuters_demographics/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ibtimes.com/turkey-begins-military-operation-against-kurds-after-trump-pulls-troops-northern-2842727|title=Turkey Begins Military Operation Against Kurds After Trump Pulls Troops in Northern Syria|first=Wesley|last=Dockery|date=October 9, 2019|website=[[International Business Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1565401/middle-east|title=After US green light, Turkey prepares military operation in Syria|date=October 7, 2019|website=Arab News}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Syrian government]] initially criticized the Kurdish forces for the Turkish offensive, for their separatism and not reconciling with the government, while at the same time also condemning the foreign invasion in Syrian territory.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-10/11/c_138462068.htm |title=Syria blames Kurdish forces for Turkish military offensive |date=October 11, 2019|work=Xinhua Net |access-date=October 11, 2019}}</ref> However, a few days later, the SDF reached an agreement with the Syrian government, in which it would allow the [[Syrian Army]] to enter the SDF-held towns of [[Manbij]] and [[Koban\u00ee]] in an attempt to defend the towns from the Turkish offensive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2019/10/13/Syrian-army-to-enter-SDF-held-Kobani-Manbij-Monitor.html|title=Syrian army to enter SDF-held Kobani, Manbij: Monitor|publisher=Al Arabiya|access-date=October 13, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security-towns-report-idUSKBN1WS0K0|title=Report: Syrian army to enter SDF-held Kobani, Manbij|date=October 13, 2019|agency=Reuters|access-date=October 13, 2019}}</ref><ref name= \"armyinvolved\">{{Cite web|url=https://thedefensepost.com/2019/10/13/syria-government-russia-kobani-manbij-sdf/|title=Syrian government forces set to enter Kobani and Manbij after SDF deal|date=October 13, 2019|website=The Defense Post|access-date=October 13, 2019}}</ref> Shortly thereafter, Syrian state broadcaster [[SANA]] announced that Syrian Army troops had started to deploy to the country's north.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/world/mena/syrian-troops-sent-north-to-confront-turkey-over-incursion-says-state-media-1.922875|title=Syrian troops sent north to 'confront' Turkey over incursion, says state media|website=The National|access-date=October 13, 2019}}</ref> Turkey and the SNA launched an offensive to capture Manbij on the same day.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.haber.com/suriye-milli-ordusu-munbic-operasyonu-basladi-103685/|title=Suriye Milli Ordusu: M\u00fcnbi\u00e7 Operasyonu Ba\u015flad\u0131|date=October 14, 2019|website=Haber.com}}</ref>\n\nOn October 22, 2019, Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] and Turkish President [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] [[Second Northern Syria Buffer Zone|reached a deal]] to extend the ceasefire by 150 additional hours for SDF to move 30 kilometers away from the border area as well as from [[Tal Rifaat]] and [[Manbij]]. The terms of the deal also included joint Russian\u2013Turkish patrols 10 kilometers into Syria from the border except in the city of [[Qamishli]]. The new ceasefire started at 12&nbsp;pm local time on October 23.<ref name=\"auto16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/article236512698.html|title=The Latest: Pence says 5-day cease-fire in Syria has held\n|date=October 22, 2019|website=The Miami Herald}}</ref><ref name=\"auto17\">{{Cite web|url=https://thedefensepost.com/2019/10/22/russia-turkey-syria-mou/|title=FULL TEXT: Memorandum of Understanding between Turkey and Russia on northern Syria|date=October 22, 2019|website=The Defense Post}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the main combat phase did end, post ceasefire operations are still ongoing.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security-turkey/turkey-not-resuming-military-operation-in-northeast-syria-security-source-idUSKBN1XZ12M Turkey not resuming military operation in northeast Syria: security source] Reuters, November 2019</ref><ref>[http://www.milliyet.com.tr/siyaset/son-dakika-mgk-toplantisi-sonrasi-flas-baris-pinari-harekati-aciklamasi-surecek-6087904]</ref> As announced by Russia's Ministry of Defense on October 15, Russian forces have started to patrol the region along the line of contact between Turkish and Syrian forces,<ref name=ko-il-rftv>{{cite web |last1=Kottasov\u00e1 |first1=Ivana |last2=Ilyushina |first2=Mary |title=Russians fill the void left by US troops in Syria |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/10/15/middleeast/turkey-syria-russian-troops-intl/index.html |publisher=CNN |date=October 15, 2019}}</ref><ref name=wapo-ssgse/> indicating that Russia is filling the security vacuum from the sudden US withdrawal.<ref name=wapo-ssgse>{{cite web | author1= Fahim, Kareem | author2=Dadouch, Sarah | author3= Englund, Will |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/syria-says-government-soldiers-enter-manbij-after-us-troops-withdraw/2019/10/15/d494405a-eeb8-11e9-bb7e-d2026ee0c199_story.html | title=Russia patrolling between Turkish and Syrian forces after U.S. troops withdraw| date =October 15, 2019 | website=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mortazavi |first1=Negar |title=How Russia is filling the gap left by Trump's withdrawal of US troops in Syria |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/trump-syria-kurds-russia-putin-assad-a9157656.html |website=The Independent |date=October 16, 2019}}</ref><ref name=wapo-ssgse/><ref name=ol-ram>{{cite news |last1=Oliphant |first1=Roland |title=Russia assumes mantle of supreme power broker in Middle East as US retreats from Syria |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/10/15/russia-assumes-mantle-supreme-power-broker-middle-east-us-retreats/ |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=October 15, 2019}}</ref> Alexander Lavrentiev, Russia's special envoy on Syria, warned that the Turkish offensive into Syria is unacceptable and stated that Russia is seeking to prevent conflict between Turkish and Syrian troops.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sevastopulo |first1=Demetri |last2=Williams |first2=Aime |last3=Pitel |first3=Laura |last4=Foy |first4=Henry |title=US delegation to press Turkey for Syrian ceasefire |url=https://www.ft.com/content/3123143a-ef41-11e9-ad1e-4367d8281195 |website=Financial Times |date=October 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Turkish operation received mixed responses by the international community. Including condemnations<ref>{{cite news |title=India slams Turkey for its 'unilateral military offensive' in northeast Syria {{!}} India News |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/india-slams-turkey-for-its-unilateral-military-offensive-in-northeast-syria/articleshow/71520852.cms |accessdate=October 10, 2019 |work=The Times of India }}</ref> as well as support for the operation for the settlement of refugees in Northern Syria.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/539756-pm-imran-telephones-erdogan-assures-full-support-to-turkey|title=PM Imran telephones Erdogan, assures full support to Turkey|date=October 11, 2019|website=The News International}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/operation-peace-spring/turkic-council-supports-turkey-s-anti-terror-operation/1614575|title=Turkic Council supports Turkey's anti-terror operation|website=aa.com.tr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnnturk.com/turkiye/turk-konseyi-liderler-zirvesinden-ortak-baris-pinari-bildirisi|title=T\u00fcrk Konseyi Liderler Zirvesi'nden ortak 'Bar\u0131\u015f P\u0131nar\u0131' bildirisi|website=CNN T\u00fcrk}}</ref> While originally acknowledging Turkey's \"right to defend itself\", on October 15, Russia hardened its position against the operation and deployed troops.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/3123143a-ef41-11e9-ad1e-4367d8281195|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/15/world/middleeast/kurds-syria-turkey.html|title=In Syria, Russia Is Pleased to Fill an American Void|first1=Ben|last1=Hubbard|first2=Anton|last2=Troianovski|first3=Carlotta|last3=Gall|first4=Patrick|last4=Kingsley|date=October 15, 2019|work=The New York Times}}</ref> Ten European nations and Canada [[Reactions to the 2019 Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria|imposed an arms embargo on Turkey]], while the U.S. imposed sanctions on Turkish ministries and senior government officials in response to the offensive in Syria.<!---<ref name=ColumbusSanctions/>---> Likewise, Trump's sudden pullout of US forces in Syria was also criticized by journalists as a \"serious betrayal to the Kurds\" as well as a \"catastrophic blow to US credibility as an ally and Washington's standing on the world stage\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/us-betrayal-of-kurds-destroys-the-wests-credibility-for-years-to-come-11835611|title=US betrayal of Kurds destroys the West's credibility for years to come | publisher=Sky News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/trump-syria-move-delivers-blow-credibility-worldwide-191008232132422.html|title=Trump's Syria move 'delivers a blow to US credibility worldwide'| publisher=Al Jazeera}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/18/opinion/trump-kurds-syria.html|title=Trump's Gut, and the Gutting of American Credibility| website=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/meet-the-press/trump-s-decision-syria-has-already-turned-foreign-policy-disaster-n1065691|title=Trump's decision on Syria has already turned into a foreign policy disaster| publisher=NBC News}}</ref> On November 19, the Defense Department inspector general released a report finding that the American withdrawal and subsequent Turkish incursion allowed ISIL to \"reconstitute capabilities and resources within Syria and strengthen its ability to plan attacks abroad\".<ref name=\"O\u2019brien\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/11/19/trump-syria-isis-071499|title=Trump's pullout from Syria allowed ISIS to gain strength, intel agency reports|first=Connor|last=O\u2019brien|website=Politico}}</ref>\n\n=====Changes in Syria diplomatic situation=====\nAs a result of the Turkish incursion, multiple Kurdish groups that were once rivals have begun to seek greater unity. Additionally, Syrian Kurdish officials have had some positive discussions with the Assad government, and with local countries such as Saudi Arabia, UAE and Jordan.<ref name=\"al-monitor overview\">[https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2019/12/turkey-syria-gulf-ankara-kurdish-sweep-backfiring.html Turkey\u2019s Kurdish sweep backfires], Fehim Tastekin December 11, 2019, al-monitor.com</ref>\n\nOn the ground, Turkish areas of operations have been delineated by Russian mediators. Russian military officials forged agreements between Syria, Turkey and Kurds for areas to be patrolled by each side.<ref>[https://ahvalnews.com/northern-syria/russian-forces-syria-sdf-discuss-phase-two-border-security-deal Russian forces in Syria, SDF discuss phase two in border security deal], December 7, 2019.</ref> Russia handles security through its own forces deployed in some key towns.\n\nThe Assad government has forged agreements with some opposition groups to return to various local border areas.<ref name=\"al-monitor overview\"/> The Syrian Democratic Forces (SDF) reached agreement with the Assad regime for the Syrian Army to patrol several border areas. They also agreed on areas of deployment for Russian forces.<ref>[https://ahvalnews.com/northern-syria/russian-forces-syria-sdf-discuss-phase-two-border-security-deal Russian forces in Syria, SDF discuss phase two in border security deal], December 7, 2019, ahvalnews.com.</ref> The first agreement between SDF and the Assad regime occurred in October 2019, directly as a result of the Turkish incursion.<ref>[https://ahvalnews.com/operation-peace-spring/live-day-6-turkeys-syria-operation Live: Day 6 of Turkey's Syria operation],\nAhval, October 14, 2019.</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://syrianobserver.com/EN/news/53885/sdf-agrees-to-sochi-deal-for-northern-syria.html|title=SDF Agrees to Sochi Deal for Northern Syria|date=October 28, 2019|website=The Syrian Observer|access-date=October 28, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://ekurd.net/syrian-kurds-say-pulling-2019-10-28|title=Syrian Kurds say pulling out from entire length of Turkey border|date=October 28, 2019|website=Kurd Net \u2013 Ekurd.net Daily News|access-date=October 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn general positive negotiations have increased between Syria and Turkey, and between Syria and Kurdish groups.<ref>[https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2019/12/the-takeaway-december-11-2019.html The Takeaway: December 11, 2019], Andrew Parasiliti December 11, 2019.</ref>\n\nOn December 9, Russian troops entered Raqqa and began distributing humanitarian aid.<ref>[https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Russian-forces-enter-former-Islamic-State-stronghold-in-Syria-610347 Russian forces enter former Islamic State stronghold in Syria]:Russian troops in Raqqa were handing out humanitarian aid and its military doctors were offering residents medical attention. By REUTERS December 9, 2019.</ref><ref>[https://thedefensepost.com/2019/12/10/syria-russia-raqqa-us-withdraw/ Russian troops enter Syria\u2019s Raqqa, filling void of withdrawing US forces],by Jared Szuba December 10, 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Russians-in-Raqqa-two-years-after-US-helped-take-city-from-ISIS-610377 Russians near Raqqa two years after US helped take city from ISIS] By SETH J. FRANTZMAN December 9, 2019.</ref>\n\n==== Turkey ====\n[[Turkey]] spent the decade under the leadership of [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]]. Under his leadership, Turkey engaged in a [[Foreign policy of the Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan government|more active foreign policy]], including [[Turkish involvement in the Syrian Civil War|military intervention in the Syrian Civil War]].\n\nIn 2016, a [[2016 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat attempt|coup attempt]] was launched against Erdogan, which failed. This led to extensive purges within the Turkish state in an effort to remove anti-Erdogan elements, claimed by the government to be connected to the preacher [[Fethullah G\u00fclen]] and his [[G\u00fclen movement]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/13/magazine/inside-turkeys-purge.html|title=Inside Turkey's Purge|last=Hansen|first=Suzy|date=April 13, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 13, 2020|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Over 150,000 civil servants have lost their jobs as a result.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://turkeypurge.com/purge-in-numbers-2|title=Purge in Numbers new {{!}} Turkey Purge|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nErdogan has been criticized for undermining Turkish democracy,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/18/business/west-democracy-turkey-erdogan-financial-crisis.html|title=The West Hoped for Democracy in Turkey. Erdogan Had Other Ideas.|last=Goodman|first=Peter S.|date=August 18, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 13, 2020|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and for [[neo-Ottomanism]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2018/06/22/erdogan-is-making-the-ottoman-empire-great-again/|title=Erdogan Is Making the Ottoman Empire Great Again|last=Edwards|first=Michael Colborne, Maxim|website=Foreign Policy|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Yemen====\nThe [[Saudi-led intervention in Yemen]], is an intervention launched by [[Saudi Arabia]] in 2015, leading a coalition of nine countries from [[Western Asia|West Asia]] and Africa, in response to calls from the internationally recognized pro-Saudi<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.theamericanconservative.com/buchanan/with-friends-like-the-saudis/|title=With Friends Like the Saudis|first=Patrick J.|last=Buchanan|website=The American Conservative}}</ref> president of Yemen [[Abdrabbuh Mansur Hadi]] for military support after [[Houthi takeover in Yemen|he was ousted]] by the [[Houthi movement]] due to economic and political grievances, and fled to Saudi Arabia.<ref name=\"https\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/03/26/us-yemen-security-idUSKBN0ML0YC20150326|agency=[[Reuters]]|title=Yemeni leader Hadi leaves country as Saudi Arabia keeps up air strikes|date=March 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nCode-named ''Operation Decisive Storm'', the intervention is said to be in compliance with [[Use of force by states|Article 2(4)]] of the [[Charter of the United Nations|UN Charter]] by the international community;<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Nu\u00dfberger |first1=Benjamin |title=Military strikes in Yemen in 2015: intervention by invitation and self-defence in the course of Yemen's 'model transitional process' |journal=Journal on the Use of Force and International Law |date=January 5, 2017 |volume= 4, 2017 |pages=110\u2013160 |doi=10.1080/20531702.2017.1256565 }}</ref> but this has been contested by some academics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irinnews.org/analysis/2015/04/03/saudi-war-yemen-legal|title=Is the Saudi war on Yemen legal?|date=April 3, 2015|website=IRIN}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|first1=Luca|title=Weathering the Storm: Legality and Legal Implications of the Saudi-Led Military Intervention in Yemen|last1=Ferro|first2=Tom|last2=Ruys|journal=International & Comparative Law Quarterly|volume=65|issue=1|pages=61\u201398|doi=10.1017/S0020589315000536|year=2016}}</ref> The intervention initially consisted of a bombing campaign on Houthi rebels and later saw a naval [[blockade of Yemen|blockade]] and the deployment of ground forces into [[Yemen]].<ref>Gatten, Emma. [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/saudi-blockade-starves-yemen-of-vital-supplies-as-bombing-raids-continue-10509460.html Saudi blockade starves Yemen of vital supplies, as bombing raids continue]. ''[[The Independent]]''. September 19, 2016. Retrieved October 23, 2016.</ref> The Saudi-led coalition has attacked the positions of the [[Houthi]] militia, and loyalists of the former [[President of Yemen]], [[Ali Abdullah Saleh]], allegedly supported by [[Iran]] (see [[Iran\u2013Saudi Arabia proxy conflict]]).<ref name=\"CBC News\">{{cite news|url= http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/yemeni-s-abed-rabbo-mansour-hadi-arrives-in-saudi-capital-1.3010698|title=Yemeni's Abed Rabbo Mansour Hadi arrives in Saudi capital|date=March 26, 2015|access-date=March 26, 2015|publisher=[[CBC News]]}}</ref><ref name=\"https\"/>\n\n[[Fighter jet]]s and ground forces from [[Egypt]], [[Morocco]], [[Jordan]], [[Sudan]], the [[United Arab Emirates]], [[Kuwait]], [[Qatar]], [[Bahrain]], and [[Academi]] (formerly Blackwater) took part in the operation. [[Djibouti]], [[Eritrea]], and [[Somalia]] made their airspace, territorial waters, and military bases available to the coalition.<ref name=\"Ssfpstsciy\">{{cite news |title=SOMALIA: Somalia finally pledges support to Saudi-led coalition in Yemen \u2013 Raxanreeb Online |url=http://www.wargeyska.so/somalia-somalia-finally-pledges-support-to-suadi-led-coalition-in-yemen-raxanreeb-online/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20150407194428/http://www.wargeyska.so/somalia-somalia-finally-pledges-support-to-suadi-led-coalition-in-yemen-raxanreeb-online/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 7, 2015 |agency=RBC Radio |date=April 7, 2015 |access-date=April 7, 2015 }}</ref> The United States provided intelligence and logistical support, including [[aerial refueling]] and search-and-rescue for downed coalition pilots.<ref name=\"rescue\">{{cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/us-rescues-saudi-pilots-gulf-aden/story?id=29965427|publisher=[[ABC News]] |title=US Rescues 2 Saudi Pilots From Gulf of Aden|date=March 27, 2015 |first=Luis|last=Martinez |access-date=April 7, 2015}}</ref><ref name=hp-20160810>{{cite news |url=https://huffingtonpost.com/entry/barack-obama-could-end-the-killing-in-yemen-in-hours_us_57f7d5dee4b0b6a43031ba4e |title=Obama Could End The Slaughter in Yemen Within Hours |author=Akbar Shahid Ahmed |work=[[HuffPost]] |date=August 10, 2016 |accessdate=October 8, 2016}}</ref> It also accelerated the sale of weapons to coalition states<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/2015/04/07/262381/us-stepping-up-weapons-shipments.html|publisher=[[The McClatchy Company|McClatchy DC]] |first=James|last=Rosen |authorlink=James Rosen (journalist) |title=U.S. stepping up weapons shipments to aid Saudi air campaign over Yemen|date=April 7, 2015|access-date=April 7, 2015}}</ref> and continued [[List of drone strikes in Yemen|strikes against AQAP.]] The US and Britain have deployed their military personnel in the command and control centre responsible for Saudi-led air strikes on Yemen, having access to lists of targets.<ref name=\"theguardian-com_2016-01-15_BZM\">{{cite news |first=Emma |last=Graham-Harrison |title=British and US military 'in command room' for Saudi strikes on Yemen |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=January 15, 2016 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jan/15/british-us-military-in-command-room-saudi-strikes-yemen |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6eaDLp4Dq |archivedate=January 16, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"theguardian-com_2016-01-19_BHS\">{{cite news |first=Vickie |last=Hawkins |title=Bombing hospitals and schools cannot become the new normal |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=January 19, 2016 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2016/jan/19/yemen-msf-bombing-hospitals-schools-cannot-become-the-new-normal |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ehgjdWF7 |archivedate=January 21, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"publications-parliament-uk_2016-01-12_HoC\">{{cite web |title=House of Commons debate, Tuesday 12 January 2016 | publisher=publications.parliament.uk (Daily Hansard \u2013 Debate, Column 681) |date=January 12, 2016 |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201516/cmhansrd/cm160112/debtext/160112-0001.htm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ehizuhFw |archivedate=January 21, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe war has received [[International reactions to the Saudi-led intervention in Yemen (2015\u2013present)|widespread criticism]] and had a dramatic worsening effect on Yemen's humanitarian situation, that reached the level of a \"humanitarian disaster\"<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jun/05/saudi-led-naval-blockade-worsens-yemen-humanitarian-disaster |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |title=Saudi-led naval blockade leaves 20&nbsp;m Yemenis facing humanitarian disaster |date=June 5, 2015|first=Julian |last=Borger |authorlink=Julian Borger |access-date=October 31, 2015}}</ref> or \"humanitarian catastrophe\".<ref name=\"un-org_2015-07-28_DCN\">{{cite news|url=https://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=51516|title=Durable ceasefire needed as 'humanitarian catastrophe' leaves millions suffering in Yemen \u2013 UN relief chief)|date=July 28, 2015|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6aOLG7U6O|archivedate=July 29, 2015|url-status=live|publisher=UN News Centre}}</ref><ref name=\"ECHAO_2015-12-14_ECS\">{{cite web |title=European Commission steps up humanitarian aid for Yemen crisis |via=[[ReliefWeb]] |publisher=European Commission's Directorate-General for European Civil Protection and Humanitarian Aid Operations |date=December 14, 2015 |url=http://reliefweb.int/report/yemen/european-commission-steps-humanitarian-aid-yemen-crisis |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6dqN1KtTh |archivedate=December 17, 2015 |url-status=live }}; Original source: {{cite web |title=European Commission steps up humanitarian aid for Yemen crisis |url=http://ec.europa.eu/echo/news/european-commission-steps-humanitarian-aid-yemen-crisis_en |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6dqNESGuF |archivedate=December 17, 2015 |url-status=live |date=December 14, 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"BBCNews_2015-08-19_YCH\">{{cite news |title=Yemen crisis: How bad is the humanitarian situation? |work=BBC News |date=August 24, 2015 |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-34011187 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6bskayjqI |archivedate=September 28, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the conflict's status was described as a \"military stalemate for years\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Yemeni Separatists Relinquish Control of Buildings in Aden |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/17/world/middleeast/yemen-houthi-saudi-oilfield.html |accessdate=September 4, 2019 |work=The New York Times |agency=Reuters |date=August 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Trump vetoed a bipartisan bill which would have ended US support for the Saudi-led military intervention.<ref>{{cite news |last= Pilkington|first=Ed|date=April 17, 2019 |title=Dismay as Trump vetoes bill to end US support for war in Yemen|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/apr/16/trump-yemen-war-veto-military-aid|work=The Guardian |access-date=April 18, 2019}}</ref> With 53 votes instead of the 67 needed, the United States Senate failed to override the veto.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/senate-fails-to-override-trumps-veto-of-resolution-demanding-end-to-us-involvement-in-yemen/2019/05/02/4bd0a524-6cf9-11e9-8f44-e8d8bb1df986_story.html|title=Senate fails to override Trump's veto of resolution demanding end to U.S. involvement in Yemen war|last1=Demirjian|first1=Karoun|last2=Ryan|first2=Missy|date=May 2, 2019|accessdate=May 4, 2019|newspaper=The Washington Post}}</ref> The legal arguments and policies of the Obama administration were cited as justification for the veto.<ref>{{cite news |last=Olsen |first=Gunar |date=April 20, 2019 |title=Add Trump's Yemen Veto to Obama's Spotty War Legacy|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/153639/add-trumps-yemen-veto-obamas-spotty-war-legacy|work=[[The New Republic]] |access-date=April 21, 2019 }}</ref> The US Deputy Assistant Secretary of Defense [[Michael Mulroy]] stated that US support was limited to side-by-side coaching to mitigate civilian casualties and if the measure had passed it would do nothing to help the people of Yemen and may only increase civilian deaths.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.airforcemag.com/Features/Pages/2019/April%202019/DOD-Official-Ending-US-Support-for-Yemen-Fight-Would-Worsen-the-Crisis.aspx|title=Air Force Magazine}}</ref> Mulroy supported the United Nation's peace talks and he pushed the international community to come together and chart a comprehensive way ahead for Yemen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/senate-fails-to-override-trumps-veto-of-resolution-demanding-end-to-us-involvement-in-yemen/2019/05/02/4bd0a524-6cf9-11e9-8f44-e8d8bb1df986_story.html|title=Senate fails to override Trump's veto of resolution demanding end to U.S. involvement in Yemen war|website=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stamfordadvocate.com/news/article/Senate-fails-to-override-President-Trump-s-veto-13814269.php|title=Senate doesn't override Trump's veto of resolution demanding end to U.S. involvement in Yemen|first1=Karoun|last1=Demirjian|first2=Missy|last2=Ryan|first3=The Washington|last3=Post|date=May 2, 2019|website=StamfordAdvocate|accessdate=May 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehour.com/news/article/Senate-fails-to-override-President-Trump-s-veto-13814269.php|title=Senate doesn't override Trump's veto of resolution demanding end to US involvement in Yemen|first1=Karoun|last1=Demirjian|first2=Missy|last2=Ryan|first3=The Washington|last3=Post|date=May 2, 2019|website=The Hour}}</ref> Writing in ''[[The Nation]]'', [[Mohamad Bazzi]] argued that Mulroy's defence of US support as necessary to limit civilian casualties was false, and that \"Saudi leaders and their allies have ignored American entreaties to minimize civilian casualties since the war's early days\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/war-crimes-united-states-saudi-arabia-yemen/|title=Both Saudi Arabia and the United States Are Probably Guilty of War Crimes in Yemen|first=Mohamad|last=Bazzi|date=May 17, 2019|work=The Nation}}</ref>\n\n===Europe===\n====European Union====\nIn December 2019, the EU announced that banking ministers from EU member nations had failed to reach agreement over proposed banking reforms and systemic change.<ref name=\"ft.com\">[https://www.ft.com/content/5f55f7d8-1777-11ea-9ee4-11f260415385 Eurozone ministers divided over banking union negotiations].</ref><ref name=\"brecorder.com\">[https://www.brecorder.com/2019/12/06/550824/eu-ministers-fail-to-advance-eurozone-reforms/ EU  ministers fail to advance eurozone reforms], By RECORDER REPORT on December 6, 2019.</ref> The EU was concerned about high rates of debt in France, Italy and Spain.<ref name=\"euractiv.com\">[https://www.euractiv.com/section/economic-governance/news/eu-concerned-over-france-italy-and-spain-debts/ EU concerned over France, Italy and Spain debts] By Beatriz Rios | EURACTIV.com November 21, 2019.</ref>\n\n==== France ====\nThe [[2017 French presidential election]] caused a radical shift in [[Politics of France|French politics]], as the prevailing parties of [[The Republicans (France)|The Republicans]] and [[Socialist Party (France)|Socialists]] failed to make it to the second round of voting, with far-right [[Marine Le Pen]] and political newcomer [[Emmanuel Macron]] instead facing each other.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2017/5/5/15543294/french-election-macron-le-pen|title=Macron vs. Le Pen: the French presidential election, explained|last=Beauchamp|first=Zack|date=May 5, 2017|website=Vox|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> Macron ended up winning both the presidency, as well as a [[2017 French legislative election|legislative majority]] with his newfound party [[La R\u00e9publique En Marche!]] In 2018\u201319, his leadership was challenged by the [[Populism|populist]] [[Yellow vests movement]], which also rejected traditional parties.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/05/world/europe/yellow-vests-france.html|title=How France's 'Yellow Vests' Differ From Populist Movements Elsewhere|last=Nossiter|first=Adam|date=December 5, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 13, 2020|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==== Italy ====\nThe [[2013 Italian general election]] led to a major change in the country's political landscape, as the traditional center-right and center-left parties were challenged by the new [[Five Star Movement]], a populist party led by comedian [[Beppe Grillo]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Garzia|first=Diego|date=April 16, 2019|title=The Italian election of 2018 and the first populist government of Western Europe|journal=West European Politics|volume=42|issue=3|pages=670\u2013680|doi=10.1080/01402382.2018.1535381|issn=0140-2382}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[2018 Italian general election]], a coalition government was formed between the [[Lega Nord]] and [[Five Star Movement]], becoming the first fully populist government in Western Europe.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n====Russia====\nRussia re-elected [[Vladimir Putin]] as the president in [[2012 Russian presidential election]]. The election was marred by claims of fraud, contributing to the [[2011\u20132013 Russian protests]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/06/world/europe/observers-detail-flaws-in-russian-election.html|title=Observers Detail Fraud in Russian Election Won by Putin|last=Barry|first=Ellen|date=March 5, 2012|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 10, 2020|last2=Schwirtz|first2=Michael|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Under Putin, Russia engaged in a more aggressive foreign policy, with the [[Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation|2014 Annexation of Crimea]] and [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)|intervention in Ukraine]] following the [[2014 Ukrainian revolution]], the [[Russian military intervention in the Syrian Civil War|2015 intervention in the Syrian Civil War]], and [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|interference in the 2016 United States elections]].\n\n====United Kingdom====\n{{See also|Brexit negotiations|Premiership of Boris Johnson|2019 United Kingdom general election}}\nFollowing a [[hung parliament]] in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election]], the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] and [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] formed the first coalition government in the country's history since [[World War II]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/britain-politics-year-idUSLDE7492B020110510|title=TIMELINE-UK coalition government's first year in power|date=May 10, 2011|agency=Reuters|access-date=January 26, 2020}}</ref> A [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|referendum on Scottish independence]] was held on 2014, returning a negative result.\n\nAfter the Conservatives were returned to power with a majority in the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], a [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|referendum]] was called on [[Brexit|leaving the European Union]], which led to the beginning of the process of UK withdrawal from the EU.\n\nIn 2015, the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] elected as its leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]], who was considered the most left-wing leader of the party since [[Michael Foot]] (1980\u201383).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insideover.com/indepths/politics/who-is-jeremy-corbyn.html|title=Who is Jeremy Corbyn: The Most Left-Wing Leader of the Labour Party|website=InsideOver|access-date=January 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]] left the Conservatives with a minority government under [[Theresa May]].\n\nIn 2019, the Conservatives under [[Boris Johnson]] won the largest majority in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] since the [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987 election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/uk/20191214-uk-s-conservatives-win-largest-majority-since-1980s-uk-election-labour-jeremy-corbyn-week-review-brexit|title=The world this week \u2013 Blue Wave: Biggest Conservative win since 1987|date=December 14, 2019|publisher=France 24|access-date=January 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== North America ===\nFollowing pressure from the US President [[Donald Trump]], the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]] (NAFTA) was superseded by the new [[United States\u2013Mexico\u2013Canada Agreement]] (USMCA).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/27/us/politics/us-mexico-nafta-deal.html|title=Trump Reaches Revised Trade Deal With Mexico, Threatening to Leave Out Canada|last=Swanson|first=Ana|date=August 27, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 26, 2020|last2=Rogers|first2=Katie|issn=0362-4331|last3=Rappeport|first3=Alan}}</ref>\n\n====Mexico====\n[[Felipe Calderon|Felipe Calder\u00f3n Hinojosa]] became the 56th [[president of Mexico]] (and the second from the conservative [[National Action Party (Mexico)|National Action Party]]) after a [[Controversies of the 2006 Mexican general election|controversial election in 2006]]. He quickly declared a [[Mexican Drug War|War on Drugs]] that ended up costing about 200,000 lives over the next ten years.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/news/2016/dec/08/mexico-war-on-drugs-cost-achievements-us-billions Mexico's war on drugs: what has it achieved and how is the US involved?] Nina Lakhani & Erubiel Tirado. ''The Guardian'', December 8, 2016</ref> Calderon was also president during the 2007\u20132009 [[Great Recession]]. Mexico was not hit nearly as hard as the United States, and immigration to the United States greatly declined during the last few years of Calderon's presidency.<ref>[https://inequality.stanford.edu/sites/default/files/Immigration_fact_sheet.pdf Immigration and the Great Recession p. 6] Douglas S. Massey, Princeton University, Oct 2012</ref><ref>[https://www.brookings.edu/blog/up-front/2009/11/19/how-the-recessions-affecting-immigration/ How the Recession\u2019s Affecting Immigration] Audrey Singer & Jill H. Wilson, Brookings, November 19, 2009</ref> In addition to the drug war, Calderon emphasized infrastructure development, foreign investment, and health care. Mexico became the country with the eleventh-largest GDP in the world, the seventh-largest automobile manufacturer, the eighth-largest oil exporter, and a major manufacturer of electronics. Mexico signed trade agreements with 46 different countries.<ref>[https://www.thebalance.com/mexico-s-economy-facts-opportunites-challenges-3306351 Mexico's Economy Facts, Opportunities, and Challenges] Kimberly Amadeo, The Balance, November 6, 2019</ref> Calderon's drug war, which cost 47,000 lives during the last two years of his presidency (the balance), became the most important issue during the [[2012 Mexican general election]]. The election was won by the former [[Governor of the State of Mexico]] [[Enrique Pe\u00f1a Nieto]] of the [[Institutional Revolutionary Party]], the political party that had dominated Mexican politics during most of the 20th century.\n\nPe\u00f1a Nieto continued the drug war with no better success than Calderon had had. Low points were the [[2014 Iguala mass kidnapping|September 26, 2014 Ayotzinapa (Iguala) mass kidnapping]] of 43 students enrolled in a teachers\u2019 college in the southern state of Guerrero,<ref>[https://theintercept.com/2015/05/04/how-43-students-disappeared-in-mexico-part-1/ Ghosts of Iguala] Ryan Devereaux, The Intercept, May 4, 2015</ref><ref>[http://media.wix.com/ugd/3a9f6f_e1df5a84680a4a8a969bd45453da1e31.pdf Ayotzinapa Report] Interdisciplinary Group of Independent Experts (GIEI). Retrieved December 8, 2019</ref> and the 2015 prison escape of notorious drug-dealer [[Joaqu\u00edn \"El Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n]]. Pe\u00f1a Nieto was also personally wrapped up in a corruption scandal involving a US$7&nbsp;million (MXN $100&nbsp;million) house known as ''La Casa Blanca'' (\"The White House\") purchased by his showcase wife, actress [[Ang\u00e9lica Rivera]]. This was just one of many scandals that rocked his administration.<ref>{{citation|title=Estos fueron los esc\u00e1ndalos de Pe\u00f1a Nieto durante su sexenio como presidente|date=November 30, 2018|url=https://laverdadnoticias.com/mexico/Estos-fueron-los-escandalos-de-Pena-Nieto-durante-su-sexenio-como-presidente-20181130-0031.html|website=La Verdad Noticias|trans-title=These were the scandals of Pe\u00f1a Nieto during his six-year term as president|language=es}}</ref> Enrique Pe\u00f1a Nieto and Ang\u00e9lica Rivera were divorced months after he left office.<ref>{{citation|title=El divorcio de Pe\u00f1a Nieto y Ang\u00e9lica Rivera|date=February 10, 2019|url=https://www.milenio.com/opinion/alvaro-cueva/ojo-por-ojo/el-divorcio-de-pena-nieto-y-angelica-rivera|website=Milenio|trans-title=The divorce of Pe\u00f1a Nieto and Ang\u00e9lica Rivera|language=es}}</ref> Pe\u00f1a Nieto encouraged foreign investment, particularly in the automotive industry, and for the first time since President [[Lazaro Cardenas]] nationalized the [[Pemex|oil industry in 1938]], in the energy industry. He also tried to reform the country's educational system.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-21582629 Mexico's Pena Nieto enacts major education reform] BBC World News, February 26, 2013</ref> and began construction of a [[Mexico City Texcoco Airport|new airport]] for Mexico City.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mexico-airport/new-airport-plan-for-mexico-city-eyes-six-runways-sources-idUSKBN0EU1TC20140619 New airport plan for Mexico City eyes six runways: sources] Reuters World News, June 19, 2014</ref> President Pe\u00f1a was elected with by a slim plurality in 2012 with just under 39% of the vote, but by the time he left office in 2018 he had an 18% approval and a 77% disapproval rating, making him one of the least popular presidents in Mexican history.<ref>{{citation|title=#FinDeSexenio: Pe\u00f1a Nieto termina su gobierno reprobado por la mayor\u00eda|date=November 24, 2018|url=https://politica.expansion.mx/presidencia/2018/11/24/findesexenio-pena-nieto-termina-su-gobierno-reprobado-por-la-mayoria|website=Expansion Politica|trans-title=#EndofTerm: Pe\u00f1a Nieto ends his government with failing marks from the majority|language=es}}</ref>\n\n[[Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador]] (commonly called \"AMLO\") was a candidate for president for the third time in the [[2018 Mexican general election]], representing the ''[[Juntos Haremos Historia]]'' (\"Together we will make history\"), coalition. He won in a landslide victory, taking 53% of the vote. His platform called for: democratic rule of law (no more electoral fraud or vote-buying), self-determination in foreign policy, an end to corruption, decentralization of the government, agricultural revitalization, reversal of privatization of the energy sector, economic development (including increased aid for victims of the [[2017 Puebla earthquake]]), increased pensions for the elderly, a reversal of Pe\u00f1a Nieto's educational reforms, and increased public safety by ending the drug war, granting amnesty to minor drug offenders, and reorganizing the police.<ref>{{citation|website=El Universal|url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/ten-proposals-amlos-pre-campaign|title=The ten proposals of AMLOs pre-campaign|date=December 14, 2017}}</ref> Even before his inauguration in December 2018, Lopez Obrador held a referendum on canceling construction of the US$13&nbsp;billion airport in [[Mexico City Texcoco Airport|Texcoco, State of Mexico]] and instead building one at the [[Mexico City Santa Luc\u00eda Airport|Santa Lucia Air Force]] base in [[Zumpango| Zumpango, State of Mexico]]. Nearly 70% of the voters who participated voted in favor of the Santa Lucia site, although it represented only 1% of eligible voters.<ref>{{citation|website=BBC World News|url=https://www.bbc.com/mundo/noticias-america-latina-46015692 |date=October 29, 2018|title=Resultados consulta M\u00e9xico Decide: mayor\u00eda de votantes rechaza construir el nuevo aeropuerto|language=es|trans-title=Results of the Mexico Decide consultation: A majority of voters oppose construction of the new airport}}</ref> Construction of the new airport at the Santa Lucia site began in October 2019 and is scheduled to open in March 2022. Controversy over the airport has shaken investor confidence, and the economy has stagnated or entered a slight recession.<ref name=\"universal\">{{citation|website=El Universal |url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/mexico-revisiting-lopez-obradors-first-year-president|title=Mexico revisiting Lopez Obrador's first year as president}}</ref> On December 27, 2018, AMLO initiated a crackdown on fuel theft by ''[[huachicolero]]s''. This set off gasoline shortages in several states, and the [[Tlahuelilpan pipeline explosion]] of January 18, 2019, killed 137 in the state of Hidalgo.<ref>{{citation|website=Efe English edition|date=January 31, 2019|title=Death toll from Mexico pipeline explosion increase to 119|url=https://www.efe.com/efe/english/world/death-toll-from-mexico-pipeline-explosion-increase-to-119/50000262-3884711}}</ref> AMLO ended the drug war and established a [[National Guard (Mexico)|National Guard]], but violence continues to plague the nation: the government was forced to call off the arrest and extradition of [[Ovidio Guzm\u00e1n L\u00f3pez]], son of notorious drug lord \"El Chapo\" Guzman, after the city of [[Culiacan]], Sinaloa, was laid siege to by members of the [[Sinaloa Cartel]];<ref>{{citation|website=BBC World News|date=October 18, 2019 |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50092641|title=El Chapo: Mexican police free drug lord's son as Culiac\u00e1n battle erupts}}</ref> and three women and six children, all Mexican-American citizens and members of the [[LeBar\u00f3n family massacre|LeBar\u00f3n family]] were killed by presumed drug dealers in [[Sonora]] near the [[Mexico-United States border]] on November 4, 2019.<ref>[https://abc7chicago.com/5672936/ 9 members of American family, including babies, killed in Mexico] ABC7 Eyewitness News, Chicago, November 5, 2019</ref> It was reported that 2019 was the most violent year in Mexican history, with 29,574 homicides and [[femicide]]s registered during the first ten months of the year.<ref name=\"universal\" /> AMLO has run an austere government, cracking down on corruption, reducing government salaries (including his own), and selling off properties seized during drug raids as well as government vehicles, including the presidential plane.<ref name=\"universal\" /> In foreign policy, Mexican-American relations have been strained by the immigration, tariffs, and the failure of the U.S. Congress to ratify the [[United States\u2013Mexico\u2013Canada Agreement]]. President [[Donald Trump]] briefly threatened to label Mexican drug cartels ''terrorist organizations'' and even to send the U.S. military to fight them.<ref>[https://time.com/5741024/mexico-certification-cartels-terrorist-organizations/ Mexico Is Infuriated by Trump's Pledge to Designate Drug Cartels as Terrorist Organizations] ''Time'', November 28, 2019</ref> In another foreign policy move, Mexico granted former Bolivian president [[Evo Morales]] political asylum after the [[2019 Bolivian political crisis|coup d\u2019etat]] in that country.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/evo-morales-asylum-mexico-bolivia-latest-protests-a9199206.html Mexico offers former Bolivia president Evo Morales asylum] The Independent, November 12, 2019</ref> AMLO's approval rating dropped by 10% to 58.7% during the first ten months of 2019.<ref name=\"universal\" />\n\n====United States of America (USA)====\n\n==== Obama Presidency ====\n{{Main|Presidency of Barack Obama}}\nThe most important action of Obama's first 100 days was the passage of the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009|American Recovery and Reinvestment Act]] (ARRA) to address the [[Great Recession]]. After much debate, ARRA was passed by both the House and Senate on February 13, 2009. Originally intended to be a [[bipartisan]] bill, Congressional passage of the bill relied largely on Democratic votes, though three Republican Senators did vote for it.<ref name=\"grchad\">{{cite news|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Politics/2009/0214/obama-wins-his-economic-stimulus-package-but-without-the-bipartisanship-he-sought|title=USA POLITICS Obama wins his economic stimulus package, but without the bipartisanship he sought|last1=Chaddock|first1=Gail Russell|date=February 14, 2009|accessdate=February 19, 2016|work=The Christian Science Monitor}}</ref> The lack of Republican support for the bill, and the inability of Democrats to win that support, foreshadowed the gridlock and partisanship that continued throughout Obama's presidency.<ref name=\"grchad\" /><ref name=\"mgrunstim\">{{cite news|url=http://swampland.time.com/2012/08/23/the-party-of-no-new-details-on-the-gop-plot-to-obstruct-obama/|title=The Party of No: New Details on the GOP Plot to Obstruct Obama|last1=Grunwald|first1=Michael|date=August 23, 2012|accessdate=February 19, 2016|work=Time}}</ref><ref name=\"obamamemos\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2012/01/30/the-obama-memos|title=The Obama Memos|last1=Lizza|first1=Ryan|date=January 30, 2012|accessdate=February 19, 2016|work=The New Yorker}}</ref> The $787&nbsp;billion bill combined tax breaks with spending on infrastructure projects, extension of welfare benefits, and education.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2009/01/27/news/economy/stimulus_spending|title=Stimulus with interest: $1.2 trillion|last=Sahadi|first=Jeanne|date=January 27, 2009|accessdate=April 14, 2012|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2009/02/17/news/economy/obama_stimulus_meas_success/index.htm|title=Stimulus: Now for the hard part|last=Sahadi|first=Jeanne|date=February 17, 2009|accessdate=August 7, 2013|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\n=====Wall Street reform=====\n{{see also|Banking in the United States}}\nRisky practices among the major financial institutions on [[Wall Street]] were widely seen as contributing to the [[subprime mortgage crisis]], the [[financial crisis of 2007\u201308]], and the subsequent [[Great Recession]], so Obama made [[Wall Street reform]] a priority in his first term.<ref name=\"sorkin\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/15/business/15sorkin.html?ref=businessspecial4|title=A Tough Crowd on Wall Street|last1=Sorkin|first1=Andrew Ross|date=September 14, 2009|work=The New York Times|accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref> On July 21, 2010, Obama signed the [[Dodd\u2013Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act]], the largest financial regulatory overhaul since the [[New Deal]].<ref name=\"doddfrank\">{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2010/07/21/news/economy/obama_signs_wall_street_reform_bill/index.htm|title=Obama on new law: 'No more taxpayer bailouts'|last=Censky|first=Annalyn|date=July 21, 2010|accessdate=July 22, 2010|publisher=CNN}}</ref> The act increased regulation and reporting requirements on [[derivative (finance)|derivatives]] (particularly [[credit default swap]]s), and took steps to limit [[systemic risk]]s to the US economy with policies such as higher [[capital requirement]]s, the creation of the [[Orderly Liquidation Authority]] to help wind down large, failing financial institutions, and the creation of the [[Financial Stability Oversight Council]] to monitor systemic risks.<ref name=\"konczal\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/2015/7/21/9004155/dodd-frank-explainer|title=Dodd-Frank turns 5 today \u2013 it's Obama's most underappreciated achievement|last1=Konczal|first1=Mike|date=July 21, 2015|accessdate=December 14, 2015|publisher=Vox}}</ref> Dodd-Frank also established the [[Consumer Financial Protection Bureau]], which was charged with protecting consumers against abusive financial practices.<ref name=\"jcalmes15112015\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/18/us/politics/18warren.html|title=Obama Picks Warren to Set Up Consumer Bureau|last1=Calmes|first1=Jackie|date=September 17, 2010|work=The New York Times|accessdate=November 15, 2015}}</ref> On signing the bill, Obama stated that the bill would \"empower consumers and investors,\" \"bring the shadowy deals that caused the crisis to the light of day,\" and \"put a stop to taxpayer bailouts once and for all.\"<ref name=\"bdennis\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/07/21/AR2010072100512.html|title=Obama signs financial overhaul into law|last1=Dennis|first1=Brady|date=July 22, 2010|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSome liberals were disappointed that the law did not break up the country's largest banks or reinstate the [[Glass-Steagall Act]], while many conservatives criticized the bill as a government overreach that could make the country less competitive.<ref name=\"bdennis\" /> Under the bill, the Federal Reserve and other regulatory agencies were required to propose and implement several new [[rulemaking|regulatory rules]], and battles over these rules continued throughout Obama's presidency.<ref name=\"bintelligence\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/professional/blog/dodd-frank-at-five-years-several-key-rules-remain/|title=Dodd-Frank at five years: Several key rules remain|last1=Dean|first1=Nathan|date=July 21, 2015|accessdate=December 4, 2015|publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref> Obama called for further Wall Street reform after the passage of Dodd-Frank, saying that banks should have a smaller role in the economy and less incentive to make risky trades.<ref name=\"goldfarb1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2014/07/02/president-obama-sounds-ready-to-take-on-the-big-banks/|title=President Obama sounds ready to take on the big banks|last1=Goldfarb|first1=Zachary|date=July 2, 2014|accessdate=August 2, 2016|work=The Washington Post}}</ref> Obama also signed the [[Credit CARD Act of 2009]], which created new rules for credit card companies.<ref name=\"cardact\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/30884011/ns/business-personal_finance/t/obama-signs-new-rules-credit-cards-law/|title=Obama signs new rules for credit cards into law|date=May 22, 2009|accessdate=November 14, 2015|publisher=NBC|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\n=====Technology=====\nThe introduction of new [[5G wireless technology]] caused major public discussion about possible security risks and safety risks. Many experts said 5G would require new methods to insure security of data.<ref>[https://www.forbes.com/sites/gilpress/2019/12/03/141-cybersecurity-predictions-for-2020/ 141 Cybersecurity Predictions For 2020] By Gil Press.</ref> The US Congress passed legislation regarding security concerns about 5G networks.<ref>[https://fcw.com/articles/2019/11/18/house-5g-supply-chain-bills.aspx House panel moves 5G protection bills], By Mark Rockwell, November 18, 2019.</ref> The federal government prohibited the use of [[Huawei]] equipment for 5G networks due security concerns, and encouraged its allies to also do so as well. The US government imposed strict controls on US companies as to their ability to do business with Huawei, thus disrupting sales of Huawei phones overseas.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/business-50515426?intlink_from_url=https://www.bbc.com/news/topics/crdnpmp7nllt/5g&link_location=live-reporting-story Huawei: Trouble overseas but boom time in China] By Danny Vincent, BBC News, Hong Kong, November 26, 2019.</ref> Chinese vendors and the Chinese government have denied these claims.\n\nThe development of the technology has elicited various responses and concerns that 5G radiation could have adverse health effects.<ref name=\"5G item 1\">{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2019/05/22/health-concerns-5g-cellphones-cancer/|title=Health Concerns May Slow Rollout of Super-Fast 5G Mobile Networks, Analyst Warns|website=Fortune|access-date=June 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190612151157/http://fortune.com/2019/05/22/health-concerns-5g-cellphones-cancer/|archive-date=June 12, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> An editorial in the scientific magazine [[Scientific American]] emphasized that complete scientific research regarding its effects have not been conducted and that there could be health risks.<ref>Moskowitz, Joel M., ''[https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/observations/we-have-no-reason-to-believe-5g-is-safe/ We Have No Reason to Believe 5G Is Safe] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191023141403/https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/observations/we-have-no-reason-to-believe-5g-is-safe/ |date=October 23, 2019 }}'', Scientific American, October 12, 2019</ref> ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'' characterized fears that the technology could cause cancer, infertility, autism, Alzheimer's, and mysterious bird deaths as \"conspiracy theory\".<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/5g-health-risks-concerns|title=Bird-killing, cancer-causing 5G is the internet's new favourite conspiracy theory|last=Weiss|first=Sabrina|date=June 12, 2019|journal=Wired UK|access-date=June 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190619143539/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/5g-health-risks-concerns|archive-date=June 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The US FCC and nearly all other regulators claim 5G radiation will have no significant health effects.\n\nHuawei submitted a petition in the US Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit against the FCC's decision to prohibit rural U.S. network providers from using equipment from the China-based vendor due to national security concerns, asking that the recent FCC order be overturned.<ref>[https://www.sdxcentral.com/articles/news/huawei-slams-fcc-with-legal-appeal/2019/12/ Huawei Slams FCC With Legal Appeal], by Dan Meyer | Editor-in-Chief, December 5, 2019, sdxcentral.com.</ref>\n\n=====Trump Presidency=====\n[[Donald Trump]] was elected the president in 2016, losing the popular vote to [[Hillary Clinton]], but winning through the [[United States Electoral College|electoral college]].\n\nAn [[impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump]] was initiated by House Speaker [[Nancy Pelosi]] on September 24, 2019, after a [[Whistleblower protection in the United States|whistleblower]] alleged that President [[Donald Trump]] had [[abuse of power|abused the power]] of the presidency by withholding both military aid and a [[White House]] meeting as [[Trump\u2013Ukraine scandal|a means of pressuring]] newly-elected President of Ukraine [[Volodymyr Zelensky]] to publicly announce investigations which would be damaging to Trump's political rival [[Joe Biden]] in the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 election]].\n\nIn October, three full Congressional committees (Intelligence, Oversight, and Foreign Affairs) deposed witnesses including Ukraine ambassador [[William B. Taylor Jr.|Bill Taylor]],<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite news |first=Stefan |last=Becket |first2=Arden |last2=Farhi |first3=Kathryn |last3=Watson |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/bill-taylor-opening-statement-read-the-full-text-of-the-top-us-diplomats-statement-to-congress/ |title=Top diplomat tells lawmakers Ukraine aid was directly tied to investigations |date=October 23, 2019 |publisher=[[CBS News]] |url-status=live |access-date=October 24, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191108195849/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/bill-taylor-opening-statement-read-the-full-text-of-the-top-us-diplomats-statement-to-congress/ |archivedate=November 8, 2019}}</ref> [[Laura Cooper]] (the top [[Pentagon building|Pentagon]] official overseeing Ukraine-related U.S. policy),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/trump-impeachment-inquiry/laura-cooper-pentagon-official-overseeing-ukraine-testifies-impeachment-inquiry-n1070586 |title=Key Pentagon official finally testifies after Republicans storm impeachment hearing |date=October 23, 2019 |publisher=[[NBC News]]|url-status=live |first=Alex |last=Moe |first2=Rebecca |last2=Shabad |access-date=October 24, 2019}}</ref> former White House official [[Fiona Hill (presidential advisor)|Fiona Hill]],and at least six additional White House officials.<ref name=\"whistleblower\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/09/26/us/politics/whistle-blower-complaint.html |title=Document: Read the Whistle-Blower Complaint |date=September 26, 2019 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=October 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/10/12/768935251/trump-ukraine-and-the-path-to-the-impeachment-inquiry-a-timeline |title=Trump, Ukraine and the Path to the Impeachment Inquiry: A Timeline |last=Keith |first=Tamara |date=October 12, 2019 |publisher=NPR |url-status=live |access-date=October 15, 2019}}</ref> Witnesses testified that Trump wanted Zelensky to publicly announce investigations into the Bidens and Burisma<ref name=\":27\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/07/world/europe/ukraine-trump-zelensky.html|title=Ukraine's Zelensky Bowed to Trump's Demands, Until Luck Spared Him|last=Kramer|first=Andrew E.|date=November 7, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 13, 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":28\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/24/world/europe/ukraine-war-impeachment.html|title=The Cost of Trump's Aid Freeze in the Trenches of Ukraine's War|last=Kramer|first=Andrew E.|date=October 24, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 13, 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and that Ukraine was pressured to release evidence that its government had interfered in the 2016 U.S. election.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shane |first1=Scott |title=How a Fringe Theory About Ukraine Took Root in the White House |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/03/us/politics/trump-ukraine-conspiracy.html |accessdate=November 14, 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=October 3, 2019}}</ref> On October 8, in a letter from Counsel [[Pat Cipollone]] to Speaker Pelosi, the White House officially responded that it would not cooperate with the investigation due to concerns including that there had not yet been a vote of the full House and that interviews of witnesses were being conducted behind closed doors.<ref name=\"bbc Oct 9\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-49981806 |title=White House 'will not co-operate with impeachment inquiry' |date=October 9, 2019|access-date=October 9, 2019 |work=[[BBC News]]}}</ref><ref name=\"blake-aaron\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/10/09/white-houses-scathing-legally-questionable-impeachment-letter-annotated/ |title=The White House's scathing and legally dubious impeachment letter, annotated |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |date=October 9, 2019 |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=October 11, 2019|url-access=limited}}</ref> On October 17, White House acting chief of staff [[Mick Mulvaney]] said, in response to a reporter's allegation of ''[[quid pro quo]]'': \"We do that all the time with foreign policy. Get over it.\" He walked back his comments later in the day, asserting that there had been \"absolutely no ''quid pro quo''\" and that Trump had withheld military aid to Ukraine over concerns of the country's corruption.\n\nOn October 31, the House voted 232\u2013196 to establish procedures for public hearings,<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{Cite news |website=BBC News |date=October 31, 2019 |accessdate=October 31, 2019 |title=Trump impeachment: House votes to formalise inquiry |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-50246324}}</ref> which started on November 13.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/2019/10/19/bribery-is-right-there-constitution-trump-could-be-impeached-that/|title=Perspective {{!}} 'Bribery' is right there in the Constitution. Trump could be impeached for that.|last=Melber|first=Ari|website=The Washington Post|access-date=November 23, 2019}}</ref><ref name=Budryk>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/470165-schiff-trump-could-potentially-be-impeached-for-bribery|title=Schiff: Trump could be impeached for bribery|first=Zack|last=Budryk|date=November 12, 2019|website=The Hill}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Taylor |first=Jessica |date=November 12, 2019 |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/11/12/778380499/rep-adam-schiff-trumps-potentially-impeachable-offenses-include-bribery|title=Rep. Adam Schiff: Trump's Potentially Impeachable Offenses Include Bribery|publisher=NPR}}</ref> Private and public congressional testimony by twelve government witnesses in November 2019 presented a significant body of evidence indicating Trump demanded a ''quid pro quo'' of political favors in exchange for official action.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theweek.com/speedreads/879653/sondland-confirms-quid-pro-quo-points-finger-directly-trump|title=Sondland confirms 'quid pro quo,' points finger directly at Trump|date=November 20, 2019|website=The Week}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/468199-vindman-testified-he-believed-trump-demanded-quid-pro-quo-from-ukrainian-aid|title=Vindman testified he believed Trump demanded quid pro quo for Ukrainian aid: report|first=Zack|last=Budryk|date=October 30, 2019|website=The Hill}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://time.com/5720446/william-taylor-ukraine-quid-pro-quo-transcript/|title=Diplomat William Taylor Had 'Clear Understanding' of Ukraine Quid Pro Quo: Transcript|website=Time}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theweek.com/speedreads/880137/trumps-no-quid-pro-quo-defense-takes-another-hit|title=Trump's 'no quid pro quo' defense takes yet another hit|date=November 21, 2019|website=The Week}}</ref> The [[House Judiciary Committee]] hosted hearings on December 4 with more scheduled for December 9. On December 5, Pelosi announced that the House Judiciary Committee would begin drafting articles of impeachment.<ref name=charges>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/05/us/politics/pelosi-impeachment.html|title=Pelosi Says House Will Begin Drafting Impeachment Charges Against Trump|last=Fandos|first=Nicholas|date=December 5, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=December 5, 2019|last2=Stolberg|first2=Sheryl Gay|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Once these are decided on, they are expected to be presented to the Senate for [[Impeachment in the United States#Senate: Trial|a trial and vote]].\n\n===South America===\nThe [[Conservative wave]] brought many right-wing politicians to power across the continent. In [[Argentina]] the [[Peronism|Peronist]] president [[Cristina Fern\u00e1ndez de Kirchner]] was replaced by the conservative-liberal [[Mauricio Macri]] in 2015; in Brazil, [[Dilma Rousseff]]'s [[Impeachment of Dilma Rousseff|impeachment]] resulted in the rise of her Vice President [[Michel Temer]] to power in 2016; in Chile the conservative [[Sebasti\u00e1n Pi\u00f1era]] followed the socialist [[Michelle Bachelet]] in 2017; and in 2018 the far-right congressman [[Jair Bolsonaro]] became 38th President of Brazil.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dw.com/en/is-there-a-right-wing-surge-in-south-america/a-45874897|title=Is there a right-wing surge in South America?|last1=Ospina|first1=Jose|date=October 28, 2018|accessdate=December 10, 2018|agency=DW}}</ref>\n\n====Bolivia====\n{{main|2019 Bolivian protests}}\n\nStarting on October 21, 2019, protests and marches have been occurring in [[Bolivia]] in response to claims of [[electoral fraud]] in the [[2019 Bolivian general election|2019 general election]] of October 20, 2019 and, subsequently, to [[Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez]] declaring herself the acting president of Bolivia. The claims of fraud were made after the suspension of the preliminary vote count, in which incumbent [[Evo Morales]] was not leading by a large enough margin (10%) to avoid a [[Runoff (election)|runoff]], and the subsequent publication of the official count, in which Morales won by over 10%. Some international observers have expressed concern over these developments. While many of the demonstrations have been peaceful, there have been numerous acts of violence. Senior members of the [[Movement for Socialism (Bolivia)|Movement for Socialism]] (MAS) and their families were victims of attacks, including house burnings.<ref name=\"nyt201119\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/20/world/americas/bolivia-deaths-sentaka.html|title=Five Killed as Political Violence Keeps Grip on Bolivia|website=The New York Times|date=November 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/nov/11/raab-attacks-corbyn-over-support-for-ousted-bolivian-leader-evo-morales|title=Raab criticises Corbyn over support for Bolivian leader|website=The Guardian|date=November 11, 2019|access-date=November 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191113021956/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/nov/11/raab-attacks-corbyn-over-support-for-ousted-bolivian-leader-evo-morales|archive-date=November 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efe.com/efe/english/world/bolivian-governor-s-house-set-on-fire-as-anti-morales-protests-continue/50000262-4107214|title=Bolivian governor's house set on fire as anti-Morales protests continue|website=efe.com|access-date=November 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111183525/https://www.efe.com/efe/english/world/bolivian-governor-s-house-set-on-fire-as-anti-morales-protests-continue/50000262-4107214|archive-date=November 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/11/07/bolivian-mayor-beaten-dragged-through-streets/|title=Bolivian mayor beaten, dragged through streets|last=Fitz-Gibbon|first=Jorge|date=November 7, 2019|website=New York Post|access-date=November 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111183523/https://nypost.com/2019/11/07/bolivian-mayor-beaten-dragged-through-streets/|archive-date=November 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMorales denied the allegations and invited foreign governments to [[audit]] the electoral processes, promising to hold a runoff if any fraud was found. Subsequently, an audit team from the [[Organization of American States]], with access provided by Bolivian authorities, worked to verify the integrity and reliability of the results. Their preliminary report questioned the integrity of the election results and recommended another \"electoral process\".<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oas.org/documents/eng/press/Electoral-Integrity-Analysis-Bolivia2019.pdf|title=Electoral Integrity Analysis: General Elections in the Purinational State of Bolivia|date=October 20, 2019|website=OAS|url-status=live|access-date=November 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMorales announced the government would hold another election; however, the police and army demanded [[Evo Morales government resignation|Morales's resignation on November 10]], which he offered shortly thereafter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/10/world/americas/bolivia-election-evo-morales.html|title=Military Calls on President to Step Down After Election Dispute in Bolivia|first1=Anatoly|last1=Kurmanaev|first2=M\u00f3nica|last2=Machicao|first3=Ernesto|last3=Londo\u00f1o|date=November 10, 2019|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=November 10, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110192802/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/10/world/americas/bolivia-election-evo-morales.html|archive-date=November 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Following his resignation and the resignation of other senior MAS politicians, some citing fears for the safety of their families, Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez declared herself interim president and formed an [[interim government]]. Protests have continued, and several human right organizations expressed concerns over the excess use of force by the new government.<ref name=\"ft2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/8549edc6-0a72-11ea-bb52-34c8d9dc6d84|title=Bolivia's leader accused of stoking divisions after Morales' exit|website=Financial Times|date=November 19, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt201119\" />\n\n==== Brazil ====\n{{See also|2013 Brazil protests|Impeachment of Dilma Rousseff|2018 Brazilian general election}}\nPresident [[Dilma Rousseff]] was impeached and removed from office in 2016 following revelations from [[Operation Car Wash]], a corruption investigation. Former president [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva]] was also imprisoned. In 2018, far-right populist [[Jair Bolsonaro]] won the presidential election, partly owing to the fallout from the corruption scandal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2019/08/anti-corruption-crusades-paved-way-bolsonaro/596449/|title=The Dirty Problems With Operation Car Wash|last=Bevins|first=Vincent|date=August 21, 2019|website=The Atlantic|access-date=January 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Chile====\nThe [[2019 Chilean protests]] are ongoing civil protests throughout Chile in response to a raise in the [[Santiago Metro]]'s subway fare, the increased [[cost of living]], [[privatisation]] and [[Economic inequality|inequality]] prevalent in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-50119649|website=BBC News|date=October 21, 2019|title=Chile protests: Cost of living protests take deadly toll|access-date=October 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021010614/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-50119649|archive-date=October 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"aljazeera\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/chile-protests-prompted-unrest-191022160029869.html|title=Chile protests: What prompted the unrest?|author=Charis McGowan|date=October 22, 2019|publisher=Al Jazeera|access-date=October 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191026072339/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/chile-protests-prompted-unrest-191022160029869.html|archive-date=October 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/10/22/americas/chile-protests-inequality-curfew-intl-hnk/index.html|title=Chile extends curfew again as violent unrest paralyzes one of Latin America's biggest cities|publisher=CNN|author=Helen Regan|author2=Christopher Ulloa|date=October 22, 2019|access-date=October 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191025024135/https://edition.cnn.com/2019/10/22/americas/chile-protests-inequality-curfew-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=October 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Chile protests: More than one million bring Santiago to a halt|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/chile-protests-million-bring-santiago-halt-191025223542333.html|author=Naomi Larsson|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=October 26, 2019}}</ref> The protests began in Chile's capital, [[Santiago, Chile|Santiago]], as a coordinated [[fare evasion]] campaign by secondary school students which led to spontaneous{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}} takeovers of the city's main train stations and open confrontations with the [[Carabineros de Chile]] (''the national militarized police force''). On October 18, the situation escalated as organized bands of protesters began vandalizing city's infrastructure; seizing, vandalizing, and burning down many stations of the [[Santiago Metro]] network and disabling them with extensive infrastructure damage, and for a time causing the cessation the network in its entirety. All in all 81 stations have sustained major damage, incluidng 17 burned down.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bnamericas.com/es/noticias/metro-de-santiago-80-estaciones-danadas-o-destruidas-durante-protestas|title=BNamericas \u2013 Metro de Santiago: 80 estaciones da\u00f1adas o d...|website=BNamericas.com|access-date=October 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191025183130/https://www.bnamericas.com/es/noticias/metro-de-santiago-80-estaciones-danadas-o-destruidas-durante-protestas|archive-date=October 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radioagricultura.cl/nacional/2019/10/23/usuarios-reportan-nuevo-incendio-en-la-estacion-de-metro-plaza-de-maipu.html|title=Usuarios reportan nuevo incendio en la Estaci\u00f3n de Metro Plaza de Maip\u00fa|website=radioagricultura.cl|access-date=October 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191026043927/https://www.radioagricultura.cl/nacional/2019/10/23/usuarios-reportan-nuevo-incendio-en-la-estacion-de-metro-plaza-de-maipu.html|archive-date=October 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On the same day, [[President of Chile]] [[Sebasti\u00e1n Pi\u00f1era]] announced a [[state of emergency]], authorizing the deployment of [[Chilean Army]] forces across the main regions to enforce order and prevent the destruction of public property, and invoked before the courts the ''Ley de Seguridad del Estado'' (\"State Security Law\") against dozens of detainees. A [[curfew]] was declared on October 19 in the Greater Santiago area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biobiochile.cl/noticias/nacional/region-metropolitana/2019/10/19/general-iturriaga-anuncia-toque-de-queda-en-santiago-para-afrontar-graves-disturbios.shtml|title=General Iturriaga decreta toque de queda en Santiago para afrontar graves disturbios|date=October 19, 2019|website=BioBioChile \u2013 La Red de Prensa M\u00e1s Grande de Chile|access-date=October 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191019225339/https://www.biobiochile.cl/noticias/nacional/region-metropolitana/2019/10/19/general-iturriaga-anuncia-toque-de-queda-en-santiago-para-afrontar-graves-disturbios.shtml|archive-date=October 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eldesconcierto.cl/2019/10/19/decretan-inedito-toque-de-queda-en-santiago-tras-fracaso-del-gobierno-en-contener-ola-de-protestas/|title=Decretan in\u00e9dito toque de queda en Santiago tras fracaso del gobierno en contener ola de protestas|date=n.d.|website=El Desconcierto|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191020002030/https://www.eldesconcierto.cl/2019/10/19/decretan-inedito-toque-de-queda-en-santiago-tras-fracaso-del-gobierno-en-contener-ola-de-protestas/|archive-date=October 20, 2019|access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref> Protests and riots have expanded to other cities, including [[Concepci\u00f3n, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n]], [[San Antonio, Chile|San Antonio]], and [[Valpara\u00edso]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biobiochile.cl/noticias/nacional/region-de-valparaiso/2019/10/19/protestas-y-destruccion-se-registran-en-san-antonio-y-valparaiso-tras-caso-en-el-gran-santiago.shtml|title=Protestas y destrucci\u00f3n se registran en San Antonio y Valpara\u00edso tras caos en el Gran Santiago|date=October 19, 2019|website=BioBioChile \u2013 La Red de Prensa M\u00e1s Grande de Chile|access-date=October 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191019223252/https://www.biobiochile.cl/noticias/nacional/region-de-valparaiso/2019/10/19/protestas-y-destruccion-se-registran-en-san-antonio-y-valparaiso-tras-caso-en-el-gran-santiago.shtml|archive-date=October 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The state of emergency was extended to the [[Concepci\u00f3n Province, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n Province]], all [[Valpara\u00edso Region]] (except [[Easter Island]] and [[Juan Fern\u00e1ndez Archipelago]]) and the cities of [[Antofagasta]], [[Coquimbo]], [[Iquique]], [[La Serena, Chile|La Serena]], [[Rancagua]], [[Valdivia]], [[Osorno, Chile|Osorno]], and [[Puerto Montt]]. The protests have been considered the \"worst civil unrest\" having occurred in Chile since the end of [[Augusto Pinochet]]'s [[Military dictatorship of Chile (1973\u20131990)|military dictatorship]] due to the scale of damage to public infrastructure, the number of protesters, and the measures taken by the government.<ref name=\"Bloom\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmostrador.cl/dia/2019/10/19/bloomberg-santiago-despierta-en-la-devastacion/|title=Bloomberg: \"Santiago despierta en la devastaci\u00f3n\"|access-date=October 20, 2019|date=October 19, 2019|website=El Mostrador|language=es|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191020042309/https://www.elmostrador.cl/dia/2019/10/19/bloomberg-santiago-despierta-en-la-devastacion/|archive-date=October 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On October 25, over a million people took to the streets throughout Chile to protest against President Pi\u00f1era, demanding his resignation.<ref name=\"ElPais\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elpais.com.uy/mundo/personas-protestan-santiago-chile-medio-estallido-social.html|title=Al menos un mill\u00f3n de personas protestan en Santiago contra Pi\u00f1era y la desigualdad social|last=ElPais|website=Diario EL PAIS Uruguay|language=spanish|access-date=October 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191026031030/https://www.elpais.com.uy/mundo/personas-protestan-santiago-chile-medio-estallido-social.html|archive-date=October 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"nlaj2610\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/chile-protests-million-bring-santiago-halt-191025223542333.html|title=Chile protests: More than one million bring Santiago to a halt|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=October 26, 2019|author=Naoim Larsson|access-date=October 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191026165551/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/chile-protests-million-bring-santiago-halt-191025223542333.html|archive-date=October 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> As of October 26, 19 people have died, nearly 2,500 have been injured, and 2,840 have been arrested.<ref name=\"nlaj2610\" /><ref name=\"deathtoll\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/chile-news-santiago-at-least-18-dead-and-thousands-arrested-in-chile-protests-2019-10-24/|publisher=CBS News|date=October 24, 2019|title=At least 18 dead and thousands arrested in Chile protests|access-date=October 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191025191352/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/chile-news-santiago-at-least-18-dead-and-thousands-arrested-in-chile-protests-2019-10-24/|archive-date=October 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On October 28, President Pi\u00f1era changed eight ministries of [[Cabinet of Chile|his cabinet]] in response to the unrest, dismissing his Interior Minister [[Andr\u00e9s Chadwick]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/oct/28/chile-president-sebastian-pinera-replaces-cabinet-protests|title=Chile: protesters light bonfires and clash with police despite cabinet reshuffle|last=Franklin|first=Jonathan|date=October 28, 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=October 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191029011220/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/oct/28/chile-president-sebastian-pinera-replaces-cabinet-protests|archive-date=October 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc071119\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-50315106|title=Chile protests: Concerns grow over human rights abuses|website=BBC|author=Katy Watson|date=November 7, 2019}}</ref> On November 15, most{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}} of the political parties represented in the National Congress signed an agreement to call a [[2020 Chilean national referendum|national referendum]] in April 2020 regarding the creation of a new constitution.\n\n==== Colombia ====\nIn 2016, the world's longest running war<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/mar/15/colombia-end-in-sight-longest-running-conflict|title=Colombia: is the end in sight to the world's longest war?|last=Vulliamy|first=Ed|date=March 15, 2015|work=The Observer|access-date=January 21, 2020|issn=0029-7712}}</ref> was borught to an end when the [[Government of Colombia]] and the rebel group [[Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia]] signed a peace deal officially ending the [[Colombian conflict]].\n\n====Venezuela====\n{{main|2019 Venezuelan presidential crisis}}\nA crisis concerning who is the legitimate [[President of Venezuela]] has been underway since January 10, 2019, with the [[Responses to the 2019 Venezuelan presidential crisis|nation and the world divided in support]] for [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] or [[Juan Guaid\u00f3]].\n\nGuaid\u00f3 has been [[Responses to the 2019 Venezuelan presidential crisis#RecognitionMG|recognized as the acting President of Venezuela]] by 54 countries. Internationally, support has followed traditional geopolitical lines, with allies China, Cuba, Iran, Russia, Syria, and Turkey supporting Maduro; and the US, Canada, and most of Western Europe supporting Guaid\u00f3 as acting President.<ref name=\"FamiliarGeo\">{{cite news |url= https://www.apnews.com/6b7fa7cc566f486cb974362168f1d90d |title= Venezuela crisis: Familiar geopolitical sides take shape |author= Vasilyeva, Nataliya |date = January 24, 2019 | accessdate= February 25, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> As of late 2019, efforts led by Guaid\u00f3 to create a transitional government have been described as unsuccessful by various analysts and media networks, with Maduro still controlling Venezuela's state functions.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/venezuela-thousands-take-to-the-streets-of-caracas-for-rival-protests/a-51280074|title=Venezuela: Thousands take to the streets of Caracas for rival protests {{!}} DW {{!}} November 16, 2019|date=n.d.|publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]]|url-status=live|access-date=December 4, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"1d\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/11/venezuela-rival-rallies-held-guaido-calls-daily-protests-191117060107276.html|title=Venezuela: Rival rallies held as Guaido calls for daily protests|date=n.d.|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]|url-status=live|access-date=December 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/09/25/764390079/in-venezuela-juan-guaid-s-campaign-faces-new-difficulties|title=In Venezuela, Juan Guaid\u00f3's Campaign Faces New Difficulties|date=n.d.|publisher=[[NPR]]|url-status=live|access-date=December 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2019/aug/15/citgo-venezuela-fight-between-nicolas-maduro-juan-/|title=American-based Citgo targeted in fight for control of Venezuela|date=n.d.|website=[[The Washington Times]]|url-status=live|access-date=December 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/venezuela-corruption-guiado-maduro-coup-abrams-1.5191288|title=Months after failing to oust Maduro, Guaido has few cards left to play \u2013 and not long to play them|date=June 29, 2019|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|url-status=live|access-date=December 4, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"2b\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-venezuela-politics-analysis-idUSKBN1Y72BB|title='Missed his moment': opposition corruption scandal undermines Venezuela's Guaido|date=December 3, 2019|agency=[[Reuters]]|access-date=December 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-12-03/guaido-weakens-as-venezuela-legislature-probes-corruption-claim|title=Guaido Weakened as Venezuela Legislature Probes Corruption Claim|date=December 3, 2019|website=[[bloomberg.com|Bloomberg]]|url-status=live|access-date=December 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://panampost.com/orlando-avendano/2019/10/07/juan-guaidos-straitjacket/|title=Juan Guaido's Straitjacket|date=October 7, 2019|website=[[PanAm Post]]|url-status=live|access-date=December 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Global issues==\n\n===Climate change===\nIn December 2019, the [[World Meteorological Organization]] released its annual climate report revealing that climate impacts are worsening.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/04/climate/climate-change-acceleration.html Climate Change Is Accelerating, Bringing World \u2018Dangerously Close\u2019 to Irreversible Change], By Henry Fountain, December 4, 2019, ''The New York Times''.</ref> They found the global sea temperatures are rising as well as land temperatures worldwide. 2019 is the last year in a decade that is the warmest on record.<ref>[https://www.iflscience.com/environment/2019-ends-warmest-decade-on-record-state-of-the-global-climate-report-warns/ 2019 Ends Warmest Decade On Record, State Of The Global Climate Report Warns], iflscience.com</ref> The 2010s were the hottest decade in recorded history, according to NASA and the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA)]]. 2016 was the hottest year and 2019 was the second hottest.<ref>[https://www.nbcnews.com/science/environment/past-decade-was-warmest-ever-recorded-nasa-finds-n1116321?cid=sm_npd_nn_fb_ma The last decade was the warmest ever recorded, NASA and NOAA find] By Denise Chow, NBC News, January 15, 2020</ref>\n\nGlobal carbon emissions hit a record high in 2019, even though the rate of increase slowed somewhat, according to a report from [[Global Carbon Project]].<ref>[https://phys.org/news/2019-12-global-carbon-emissions-growth-high.html Global carbon emissions growth slows, but hits record high], December 3, 2019, Stanford University via phys.org.</ref>\n\n===World banking===\nConcerns increased about the [[European Debt Crisis]] as both Greece and Italy continued to have high levels of public debt. This caused concerned about stability of the Euro. In December 2019, the EU announced that banking ministers from EU member nations had failed to reach agreement over proposed banking reforms and systemic change.<ref name=\"ft.com\"/><ref name=\"brecorder.com\"/> The EU was concerned about high rates of debt in France, Italy and Spain.<ref name=\"euractiv.com\"/> Italy objected to proposed new debt bailout rules that were proposed to be added to the European Stability Mechanism.<ref>[https://www.southeusummit.com/europe/italy/italy-takes-issue-with-the-esm/ Italy Takes Issue With the ESM Proposals to reform the eurozone\u2019s bailout fund are being hotly contested in Italy amid concerns that the ESM could set the country back on rebuilding finances after the sovereign debt crisis], by Lana Guggenheim.</ref>\n\nIn the first half of 2019, global debt levels reached a record high of $250&nbsp;trillion, led by the US and China.<ref name=\"cnbc debt\">[https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/15/global-debt-surged-to-a-record-250-trillion-in-the-first-half-of-2019-led-by-the-us-and-china.html Global debt surged to a record $250 trillion in the first half of 2019, led by the US and China], November 15, 2019, Spriha Srivastava.</ref> The IMF warned about corporate debt.<ref name=\"cnbc debt\"/> The European Central Bank raised concerns as well.<ref>[http://thecorner.eu/news-europe/45-6-of-eurozones-corporate-debt-is-bbb/82875/ 45.6% Of Eurozone\u2019s Corporate Debt Is BBB], POSTED BY: THE CORNER November 23, 2019.</ref>\n\n===World trade===\n====United States-China trade dispute====\nA trade dispute between the US and China caused economic concerns worldwide. In December 2019, various US officials said a trade deal was likely before a proposed round of new tariffs took effect on December 15, 2019.<ref name=\"fox china\">[https://www.foxbusiness.com/markets/us-china-trade-deal-tariff-increase US, China trade deal expected before tariff increase: Report]. Trump's 'off the cuff' comments not a sign talks are at an impasse. Fox News Channel</ref> US tariffs had a negative effect on China's economy, which slowed to growth of 6%.<ref name=\"fox china\"/>\n\n====United States\u2013Mexico\u2013Canada Agreement====\nThe [[United States\u2013Mexico\u2013Canada Agreement]]<ref name=finaltext>{{cite web|url=https://ustr.gov/trade-agreements/free-trade-agreements/united-states-mexico-canada-agreement/agreement-between|title=Agreement between the United States of America, the United Mexican States, and Canada Text|accessdate=November 30, 2018|work=Government of the United States}}</ref> is a signed but not ratified [[free trade agreement]] between Canada, Mexico, and the United States. The Agreement is the result of a 2017\u20132018 renegotiation of the [[North American Free Trade Agreement|North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA)]] by its member states.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4500068/nafta-2018-agreement-finalized/ |title=NAFTA deal reached: Canada, U.S., Mexico reach trade agreement under new name |last1=Dangerfield |first1=Katie |work=[[Global News]] |date=August 30, 2018 |accessdate=October 1, 2018}}</ref> Negotiations \"focused largely on auto exports, steel and aluminum tariffs, and the dairy, egg, and poultry markets.\" One provision \"prevents any party from passing laws that restrict the cross-border flow of data\".<ref name=\"walrus\">{{cite news |title=Are You Afraid of Google? BlackBerry Cofounder Jim Balsillie Says You Should Be |url=https://thewalrus.ca/are-you-afraid-of-google-blackberry-cofounder-jim-balsillie-says-you-should-be/ |work=The Walrus |date=April 10, 2019}}</ref> Compared to NAFTA, USMCA increases environmental and labour regulations, and incentivizes more domestic production of cars and trucks.<ref>{{cite web|title=Labour, environment standards key to getting USMCA through: Canadian ambassador|url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/news-pmn/canada-news-pmn/canada-has-high-level-of-confidence-usmca-will-be-ratified-in-u-s-morneau|last=National Post|work=National Post|date=December 3, 2018|accessdate=May 18, 2019}}|url=</ref> The agreement also provides updated intellectual property protections, gives the United States more access to Canada's dairy market, imposes a quota for Canadian and Mexican automotive production, and increases the duty free limit for Canadians who buy U.S. goods online from $20 to $150.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.smart-biggar.ca/en/articles_detail.cfm?news_id=1463|title=USMCA v NAFTA: What's changed and what it means for IP in Canada {{!}} Smart & Biggar/Fetherstonhaugh|website=www.smart-biggar.ca|access-date=January 27, 2019}}</ref> <!--{{TOC limit|3}}-->\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Current events|Modern history|Politics}}\n\n===Overviews===\n* 21st century\n* 2010s\n* [[2019 in politics and government]]\n\n===Specific situations===\n* [[Brexit negotiations in 2019]]\n\n===Category===\n{{Category see also|2010s in politics|2010s protests|2010s by country|2010s events|21st-century elections|Category:Contemporary history by country}}\n{{Project-inline|Politics}}\u2014Wikiproject Politics\n\n===Related timelines===\n{{cat see also|2000s by country|2010s by country|2020 by country}}\n{{Div col}}\n* [[2010s]]\n* [[2010s in United Kingdom political history]]\n*[[2010s in United States political history]]\n*[[2020s in political history]]\n{{End div col}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2010s in politics| ]]\n[[Category:2010s|politics]]\n[[Category:2010s in international relations]]\n[[Category:Politics overviews by decade]]\n[[Category:2010 in politics]]\n[[Category:21st century in politics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{See also|2020s in political history}}\n{{see also|2010s#Politics and conflicts|21st century|2019 in politics and government}}\n{{Year nav|2019}}\n{{Decadebox|201}}\n{{Year nav topic5|2020|politics and government|science|United States politics and government}}\n\n'''2010s political history''' refers to significant political and societal historical events of the 2010s, presented as a historical overview in narrative format.\n\n{{TOC limit|limit=3}}\n\n==Regional politics==\n\n===Africa===\n====Burundi====\n{{Main|Burundian unrest (2015\u201318)}}\nOn April 25, 2015, the incumbent President of [[Burundi]], [[Pierre Nkurunziza]], announced he would run for a third term in the 2015 presidential election. The announcement sparked protests by those opposed to Nkurunziza seeking a third term in office.<ref>[https://www.hrw.org/news/2015/04/27/burundi-crackdown-protesters Burundi: Crackdown on Protesters] Human Rights Watch, April 27, 2015</ref> Widespread demonstrations in the then-capital, [[Bujumbura]], lasted for over three weeks. As a result of the protests, the government also shut down the country's Internet and telephone network, closed all of the country's universities, and publicly referred to the protesters as \"terrorists\". Tens of thousands of people fled the country, hundreds of people were arrested, and several protesters and police were killed. On May 13, 2015, a coup d'etat was announced, led by Major General [[Godefroid Niyombare]], while President Nkurunziza was in [[Tanzania]] attending an emergency conference about the situation in the country. By the next day the coup collapsed and government forces reasserted control. At least 240 people were killed over the next few months, and on December 11, 87 people were killed in attacks on state targets. The violence has raised fears of a return to worsening ethnic tension between Hutus and Tutsis. Nkurunziza had led a Hutu rebel group against the then Tutsi-dominated army during the civil war that followed the killing of Hutu President Melchior Ndadaye in 1993.<ref>{{citation|title=Burundi crisis: Army says 87 killed in day of violence|date=December 12, 2015|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-35083823|website=BBC News}}</ref> Violence continued through 2017.<ref>[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/08/killed-burundi-grenade-attacks-bars-170818140040303.html Three killed in Burundi grenade attacks at bars] Al Jazeera, August 18, 2017</ref>\n\n=====Cameroon=====\n{{Main|Anglophone Crisis}}\nThe Anglophone Crisis (French: Crise anglophone), is a conflict in the [[Southern Cameroons]] region of Cameroon, part of the long-standing [[Anglophone problem]] pitting English-speakers against French-speakers; English-speakers make up about one-fifth of the population.<ref name=\"foreign\">{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/09/27/cameroon-must-make-concessions-to-end-the-anglophone-crisis-paul-biya/|title=Cameroon Must Make Concessions to End the Anglophone Crisis|date=September 27, 2019|website=Foreign Affairs}}</ref> In September 2017, separatists in the Anglophone territories of Northwest Region and Southwest Region declared the independence of [[Ambazonia]] and began fighting against the Government of Cameroon. Starting as a low-scale insurgency, the conflict spread to most parts of the Anglophone regions within a year. As of the summer of 2019, the government controls the major cities and parts of the countryside, while the separatists hold parts of the countryside and regularly appear in the major cities.\n\nThe war has killed approximately 2,000 people and forced more than half a million people to flee their homes.<ref name=\"foreign\" /> Although 2019 has seen the first known instance of dialogue between Cameroon and the separatists, as well as a major national dialogue, the war continues to escalate.<ref>[https://africanarguments.org/2019/10/29/violence-increased-cameroon-conflict-national-dialogue-anglophone/ Why has violence increased since Cameroon\u2019s National Dialogue?] R. MAXWELL BONE & AKEM KELVIN, African Arguments, October 29, 20191</ref>\n\n=====Central African Republic=====\n{{Main|Central African Republic Civil War (2012\u2013present)}}\n\n=====C\u00f4te d'Ivoire=====\n{{Main|Second Ivorian Civil War}}\n\n=====Democratic Republic of the Congo=====\n{{Main|Batwa\u2013Luba clashes|Kamwina Nsapu rebellion}}\nThe '''[[Batwa\u2013Luba clashes]]''' is a series of ongoing clashes in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC)]] between the Batwa people and the Luba people starting in 2013.<ref>[https://observers.france24.com/en/20170125-democratic-republic-congo-violent-massacres-pygmy-luba Dozens massacred, bodies mutilated in DR Congo ethnic clashes] The Observers, January 25, 2017</ref>\n\nThe '''[[Kamwina Nsapu rebellion]]''', is an ethnic conflict in the DRC. It is an ongoing rebellion instigated by the Kamwina Nsapu militia in the provinces of Kasa\u00ef-Central, Kasa\u00ef, Kasai-Oriental, Lomami, and Sankuru. The fighting began in August 2016.\n\n=====Egypt=====\n{{Main|2011 Egyptian revolution|2012\u201313 Egyptian protests}}\nThe '''Egyptian revolution of 2011''' started on 25 January 25, 2011 and spread across Egypt. Millions of protesters from a range of socio-economic and religious backgrounds demanded the overthrow of Egyptian President [[Hosni Mubarak]]. Violent clashes between security forces and protesters resulted in at least 846 people killed and over 6,000 injured. Protesters retaliated by burning over 90 police stations across the country. The protesters' grievances focused on legal and political issues, including police brutality, state-of-emergency laws, lack of political freedom, civil liberty, freedom of speech, corruption, high unemployment, food-price inflation, and low wages. The protesters' primary demands were the end of the Mubarak regime and emergency law. Strikes by labour unions added to the pressure on government officials. In February 2011 Vice President [[Omar Suleiman]] announced that had Mubarak resigned as president, turning power over to the Supreme Council of the Armed Forces (SCAF).<ref>{{citation|title=Egypt Revolution: 18 days of people power|date=January 24, 2016|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/inpictures/2016/01/egypt-revolution-160124191716737.html|website=Al Jareeza}}</ref> The military junta, headed by [[Mohamed Hussein Tantawi]], announced on February 13 that the constitution was suspended, both houses of parliament dissolved, and the military would govern until elections could be held. The [[Muslim Brotherhood in Egypt|Muslim Brotherhood]] took power in Egypt through a series of popular elections, with Egyptians electing Islamist [[Mohamed Morsi]] to the presidency in June 2012. However, the Morsi government encountered fierce opposition after his attempt to pass an Islamic-leaning constitution, and mass protests broke out against his rule in late June 2013, and on July 3, 2013, Morsi was deposed by a coup d'\u00e9tat led by the minister of defense, General [[Abdel Fattah el-Sisi]].<ref>{{citation|title=Egypt's Mohammed Morsi: A turbulent presidency cut short|date=June 17, 2019|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-18371427|website=BBC World News}}</ref> El-Sisi went on to become Egypt's president by popular election in [[2014 Egyptian presidential election|2014]].<ref>{{citation|author=Patrick Kingsley|title=Abdel Fatah al-Sisi won 96.1% of vote in Egypt presidential election, say officials|date=June 3, 2014|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jun/03/abdel-fatah-al-sisi-presidential-election-vote-egypt|website=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n=====Eritrea=====\n{{Main| Eritrean-Ethiopian border conflict|}}\n\n=====Guinea=====\n{{Main|2013 Guinea clashes}}\n\n=====Libya=====\n{{Main|Libyan Civil War (2011)|Libyan Civil War (2014\u2013present)}}\n\n=====Mali=====\n{{Main|Mali War|Tuareg rebellion (2012)}}\nThe '''Mali War''', refers to armed conflicts that started from January 2012 between the northern and southern parts of [[Mali]]. On January 16, 2012, several insurgent groups began fighting a campaign against the Malian government for independence or greater autonomy for northern Mali, an area of northern Mali they called [[Azawad]]. The [[National Movement for the Liberation of Azawad|National Movement for the Liberation of Azawad (MNLA)]], an organization fighting to make this area of Mali an independent homeland for the [[Tuareg people]], had taken control of the region by April 2012. The MNLA were initially backed by the Islamist group [[Ansar Dine]]. After the Malian military was driven from northern Mali, Ansar Dine and a number of smaller Islamist groups began imposing strict [[Sharia]] law, and the Tuareg group broke away from them. [[French Armed Forces]] and members of the [[African Union]] helped the government regain control of the area, and a peace agreement was signed in February 2015.<ref>[https://news.un.org/en/story/2015/03/493062#.VQE-cPnF9Fw Deploring ongoing violence, UN rights expert urges Malian parties to work together towards lasting peace] U.N. News, March 10, 2015 [https://www.worldpoliticsreview.com/insights/27306/how-mali-is-pursuing-justice-for-a-war-that-never-really-ended How Mali Is Pursuing Justice for a War That Never Really Ended] Anna Pujol-Mazzini, World Politics Review, January 29, 2019</ref>\n\n=====Mozambique=====\n{{Main|RENAMO insurgency (2013\u20132019)}}\nThe '''RENAMO insurgency''' was a guerrilla campaign by militants of the RENAMO party in [[Mozambique]]. The insurgency is widely considered to be an aftershock of the [[Mozambican Civil War]]; it resulted in renewed tensions between RENAMO and Mozambique's ruling FRELIMO coalition over charges of state corruption and the disputed results of 2014 general elections. A ceasefire was announced between the government and the rebels in September 2014. However, renewed tensions sparked violence in mid-2015. A peace agreement was signed on August 6, 2019.\n\n=====Nigeria=====\n{{Main|Boko Haram insurgency}}\n\n=====Republic of the Congo=====\n{{Main|Pool War}}\n\n=====Somalia=====\n{{Main|Somali Civil War (2009\u2013present)}}\n\n=====South Sudan=====\n{{Main|South Sudanese Civil War}}\nThe '''[[South Sudanese Civil War]]''' broke out in 2013 after a disputed elected and an alleged coup d\u2019etat attempt.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/10/world/africa/new-estimate-sharply-raises-death-toll-in-south-sudan.html|title=New Estimate Sharply Raises Death Toll in South Sudan|author1=Nicholas Kulish|date=January 9, 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|author2=Somini Sengupta}}</ref> An estimated 300,000 people have been killed in the fighting, and over 4 million have been displaced.<ref name=\"lumen\">{{citation|title=Africa in the 21st century|url=https://courses.lumenlearning.com/boundless-worldhistory/chapter/africa-in-the-21st-century/|website=Lumen Boundless History|accessdate=December 10, 2019}}</ref> One hundred thousand people face starvation, and nearly 5 million face severe food shortages; the government declared a [[2017 South Sudan famine|famine]] in 2017.<ref>{{citation|title=South Sudan declares famine in Unity State|date=February 20, 2017|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-39025927|website=BBC World News}}</ref> Several fruitless efforts to agree to a settlement were made in 2014. Fighting continued until a compromise peace agreement was signed in 2015,<ref>{{citation|author=Alastair Leithead|title=Will South Sudan peace deal be worth the wait?|date=August 26, 2015|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-34069032|website=BBC World News}}</ref> but fighting broke out again in [[Battle of Juba (2016)|2016]].<ref>{{citation|title=S Sudan: More than 100 dead on independence anniversary|date=July 10, 2016|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/news/2016/07/south-sudan-scores-dead-independence-anniversary-160709090438275.html|publisher=Al Jazeera}}</ref> The African Union deployed a 12,000 member peace force including soldiers from [[Ethiopia]], [[Kenya]], [[Rwanda]], [[Sudan]], and [[Uganda]], over the objections of President [[Salva Kiir]].<ref>{{citation|title=South Sudan conflict: African Union approves regional force|date=July 19, 2016|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-36833875|website=BBC World News}}</ref> However, fighting continued through 2017.<ref>{{citation|title=South Sudan needs bold alternatives, not this dumpster fire of failed interventions|date=November 15, 2017|url=http://www.thenewhumanitarian.org/opinion/2017/11/15/south-sudan-needs-bold-alternatives-not-dumpster-fire-failed-interventions|website=The New Humanitarian}}</ref>\n\n=====Sudan=====\n{{Main|War in Darfur}}\nThe '''[[War in Darfur]]''', ([[Sudan]]) began in 2003, resulting in hundreds of thousands of deaths, [[genocide]],<ref name=\"britannica\">{{cite encyclopedia|encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia Britannica|title=8 Deadliest Wars of the 21st Century|author=Michael Ray|accessdate=December 10, 2019|url=https://www.britannica.com/list/8-deadliest-wars-of-the-21st-century}}</ref> and [[ethnic cleansing]]. An [[International Criminal Court investigation in Darfur|International Criminal Court investigation]] resulted in two warrants against President [[Omar al-Bashir]] and his eventual arrest.<ref>{{citation|title=Statement to the United Nations Security Council on the Situation in Darfur, pursuant to UNSCR 1593 (2005)|date=June 19, 2019|url=https://www.icc-cpi.int/Pages/item.aspx?name=190619-stat-otp-UNSC-Darfur-Sudan|website=International Criminal Court}}</ref> The [[Darfur Peace Agreement|Doha Agreement]] was signed in 2011,<ref>{{citation|title=Under peace deal, Sudan would halt prep for Darfur Referendum|date=June 4, 2011|url=https://www.dabangasudan.org/en/all-news/article/under-peace-deal-sudan-would-halt-prep-for-darfur-referendum|website=Dabanga Sudan}}</ref> but little real progress was made a year later.<ref>{{citation|title=Sudan: Ambassador Smith \u2013 'Security Situation in Darfur Deteriorated Compared to 2011'|date=September 19, 2012|url=https://allafrica.com/stories/201209200049.html|website=All Africa}}</ref> The war continued through 2016, including with allegations that the government had used [[mustard gas]].<ref>{{citation|author=James Rothwell|title=Darfur conflict: 'Hundreds of children gassed to death since January by government in Sudan'|date=September 29, 2016|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/09/29/darfur-conflict-sudanese-government-has-gassed-hundreds-of-child/|website=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n==== Piracy ====\n{{Main|Piracy in the 21st century}}\n[[Piracy in the Gulf of Guinea]] affects a number of countries in West Africa, including [[Benin]], [[Togo]], [[C\u00f4te d\u2019Ivoire]], [[Ghana]], [[Nigeria]], and the [[Democratic Republic of Congo]] as well as the wider international community. By 2011, it had become an issue of global concern. Pirates are often part of heavily armed criminal enterprises, who employ violent methods to steal oil cargo. In 2012, the [[International Maritime Bureau]] and other agencies reported that the number of vessels attacks by West African pirates had reached a world high, with 966 seafarers attacked and five killed during the year.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/19/world/africa/west-african-piracy-exceeds-somali-attacks-report-says.html West African Piracy Exceeds Somali Attacks, Report Says] Alan Cowell, ''The New York Times'', June 18, 2013</ref>\n\n[[Piracy off the coast of Somalia]] occurs in the [[Gulf of Aden]], [[Guardafui Channel]], [[Somali Sea]], in Somali territorial waters and other areas. It was initially a threat to international fishing vessels, expanding to international shipping since the second phase of the Somali Civil War, around 2000. By December 2013, the US Office of Naval Intelligence reported that only nine vessels had been attacked during the year by the pirates, with no successful hijackings.<ref>[https://qz.com/161704/somali-piracy-was-reduced-to-zero-this-year/ Somali piracy was reduced to zero this year] David Yanofsky in Somalia, ''Quartz'', December 27, 2013</ref> In March 2017, it was reported that pirates had seized an oil tanker that had set sail from [[Djibouti]] and was headed to [[Mogadishu]]. The ship and its crew were released with no ransom given after the pirate crew learned that the ship had been hired by Somali businessmen.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/mar/16/somali-pirates-release-oil-tanker-and-crew-after-first-hijack-for-five-years Somali pirates release oil tanker and crew after first hijack for five years] The Guardian World News, March 16, 2017</ref>\n\n=====War on Terror=====\n{{Main|War on terror|ISIL insurgency in Tunisia|Insurgency in the Maghreb (2002\u2013present)|Islamist insurgency in Mozambique|Boko Haram insurgency}}\nThe most prominent terrorist groups that are creating a terror impact in Africa include [[Boko Haram]] of [[Boko Haram insurgency|Nigeria]], [[Cameroon]], [[Chad]], and [[Niger]], and [[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Al-Shabaab]] of Somalia.<ref name=\"accord\">{{citation|author=LWEENDO KAMBELA|title=Terrorism in Africa|date=June 24, 2019|url=https://www.accord.org.za/conflict-trends/terrorism-in-africa/|website=ACCORD: The African Centre for the Constructive Resolution of Disputes}}</ref>\n\n'''Boko Haram''' has carried out more than 3,416 terror events since 2009, leading to more than 36,000 fatalities. One of the better-known examples of Boko Haram's terror tactics was the [[Chibok schoolgirls kidnapping|2014 Chibok schoolgirls kidnapping]] of 276 schoolgirls in [[Borno State]], Nigeria.<ref name=\"accord\"/> Boko Haram is believed to have links to [[al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb]] dating back to at least 2010. In 2015 the group expressed its allegiance to the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]], which ISIL accepted.<ref>{{citation|title=IS welcomes Boko Haram allegiance: tape|date=March 12, 2015|url=https://news.yahoo.com/accepts-allegiance-nigeria-jihadists-boko-haram-201513146.html|website=AFP/Yahoo! News}}</ref>\n\nSomalia's '''al-Shabaab''' and its Islamic extremism can be traced back to the mid-1970s when the group began as an underground movement opposing the repressive and corrupt regime of [[Siad Barre]]. Armed conflict between al-Shabaab and the Somali army \u2013 including associated human rights violations \u2013 has resulted in slightly over 68 million human displacements.<ref name=\"accord\"/> Al-Shabaab is hostile to Sufi traditions and has often clashed with the militant Sufi group [[Ahlu Sunna Waljama'a]]. The group has also been suspected of having links with Al-Qaeda in Islamic Maghreb and Boko Haram. Among their best-known attacks are the [[Westgate shopping mall attack]] in [[Nairobi]], Kenya, in September 2013 (resulting in 71 deaths and 200 injured) and the [[14 October 2017 Mogadishu bombings]] that killed 587 and injured 316.<ref>[https://hiiraan.com/news4/2018/Mar/157047/committee_587_dead_in_oct_14_terror_attack.aspx Committee: 587 dead in Oct 14 terror attack] Hiiraan Online, March 5, 2018</ref> On September 1, 2014, a U.S. drone strike carried out as part of the broader mission killed al-Shabaab leader [[Ahmed Abdi Godane]].<ref>{{citation|author=Stefan Smith|title=Shebab's new leader a devout, ruthless hardliner|date=September 7, 2014|url=https://news.yahoo.com/shebabs-leader-devout-ruthless-hardliner-sources-105730104.html;_ylt=AwrBEiSgiwxUUkoAbqrQtDMD|website=AFP/Yahoo! News}}</ref>\n\nThe '''Insurgency in the Maghreb''' refers to Islamist militant and terrorist activity in northern Africa since 2002, including [[Algeria]], [[2007 killing of French tourists in Mauritania|Mauritania]], [[Tunisia]], [[2003 Casablanca bombings|Morocco]], [[Niger]], [[Mali War|Mali]], [[2016 Grand-Bassam shootings|Ivory Coast]], [[Brak El-Shati airbase raid|Libya]], [[Western Sahara]], and [[Burkina Faso]], as well as having ties to Boko Haram in Nigeria. The conflict followed the conclusion of the [[Algerian Civil War]] as a militant group became [[al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb|al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb (AQIM)]]. Their tactics have included bombings; shootings; and kidnappings, particularly of foreign tourists. In addition to African units, the fight against the insurgency has been led primarily by the [[Operation Serval|French Foreign Legion]], although the U.S. also has over 1,300 troops in the region. Four American soldiers were killed in the October 4, 2017 [[Tongo Tongo ambush]] in Niger.<ref>[https://abcnews.go.com/International/us-soldiers-killed-niger-outgunned-left-hunt-isis/story?id=54909240 US soldiers killed in Niger were outgunned, 'left behind' in hunt for ISIS leader] James Gordon Meek, ABC News, May 3, 2018</ref>\n\n====Arab Spring====\n{{Main|Tunisian Revolution}}\n\n====Health crisis====\nAbout 1.6&nbsp;million Africans died of malaria, tuberculosis and HIV-related illnesses in 2015.<ref name=\"renewal\">{{citation|author=TEFO PHEAGE|title=Dying from lack of medicines|date=March 2017|url=https://www.un.org/africarenewal/magazine/december-2016-march-2017/dying-lack-medicines#:~:targetText=Without%20access%20to%20medicines%2C%20Africans,World%20Health%20Organisation%20(WHO).|website=United Nations: Africa Renweal}}</ref> Poor health care, malnutrition, and [[Ebola]] are also serious problems.<ref name=lumen/>\n\nOver 25.5&nbsp;million individuals infected with '''HIV/AIDS''' in 2015 were Africans. Most of these victims are middle-income or lower, and they depend on public health sources for treatment, but many medicines are unavailable due to cost, availability, and/or other factors such as transportation.<ref name=renewal/> South Africa, Egypt, Morocco, and Tunisia have made progress in local pharmaceutical productions; Ghana, Kenya, Nigeria, and Tanzania are currently developing production capacity.<ref name=renewal/>\n\n85% to 90% of malaria victims worldwide occur in Sub-Saharan Africa.<ref name=renewal/>\n\n===Asia===\n====China====\n{{Main|Xi Jinping Core Administration}}\n[[Xi Jinping]] succeeded [[Hu Jintao]] as [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China]] and became the [[paramount leader]] of China in 15 November 2012. He immediately began an [[Anti-corruption campaign under Xi Jinping|anti-corruption campaign]], in which more than 100,000 individuals were indicted, including senior leader [[Zhou Yongkang]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/china/2015/10/22/robber-barons-beware|title=Robber barons, beware, Robber barons, beware|work=The Economist|access-date=January 11, 2020|issn=0013-0613}}</ref> There have been claims of political motives behind the campaign.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/china/2014/12/11/tiger-in-the-net|title=Tiger in the net, Tiger in the net|work=The Economist|access-date=January 11, 2020|issn=0013-0613}}</ref> In 2018, he was effectively made a [[president for life]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-43361276|title=China approves 'president for life' change|date=March 11, 2018|access-date=January 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn Xi's [[Foreign policy of Xi Jinping|foreign policy]], China became more aggressive with its actions in the [[Territorial disputes in the South China Sea|South China Sea dispute]], by building [[artificial island]]s and militarizing existing [[reef]]s, beginning in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amti.csis.org/island-tracker/china/|title=China Tracker|website=Asia Maritime Transparency Initiative|access-date=January 11, 2020}}</ref> Another key part of its foreign policy has been the [[Belt and Road Initiative]] (BRI), a strategy adopted by China involving infrastructure development and investments in countries and organizations in Asia, Europe, Africa, the Middle East, and the Americas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldbank.org/en/topic/regional-integration/brief/belt-and-road-initiative|title=Belt and Road Initiative|publisher=World Bank|access-date=March 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-05-14/china-attempts-global-dominance-with-one-belt-one/8522974</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neweurope.eu/article/panama-first-in-latin-america-to-join-chinas-belt-and-road-initiative/|title=Panama first in Latin America to join China's Belt and Road Initiative|date=December 7, 2018|website=New Europe|access-date=March 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thefinancialexpress.com.bd/economy/global/152-countries-intl-organisations-sign-belt-and-road-deals-with-china-1551686061|title=152 countries, int'l organisations sign Belt and Road deals with China|last=Express|first=The Financial|website=The Financial Express|access-date=March 10, 2019}}</ref> China has signed cooperational documents on the belt and road initiative with 126 countries and 29 international organisations,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yidaiyilu.gov.cn/info/iList.jsp?tm_id=126&cat_id=10122&info_id=77298|title=\u5df2\u540c\u4e2d\u570b\u7c3d\u8a02\u5171\u5efa\u4e00\u5e36\u4e00\u8def\u5408\u4f5c\u6587\u4ef6\u7684\u570b\u5bb6\u4e00\u89bd|publisher=\u4e2d\u570b\u4e00\u5e36\u4e00\u8def\u7db2|date=April 12, 2019|accessdate=April 24, 2019}}</ref> where various efforts then went ahead on infrastructure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eng.yidaiyilu.gov.cn/qwyw/rdxw/69500.htm|title=B&R interconnection witnesses great breakthroughs in 5-year development-Belt and Road Portal|website=eng.yidaiyilu.gov.cn|access-date=January 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the end of the decade, concerns started to grow about the future of the [[Economy of China|Chinese economy]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/17/business/china-economic-growth.html|title=China's Economic Growth Slows as Challenges Mount|last=Bradsher|first=Keith|date=October 17, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 11, 2020|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> These concerns included whether the United States and China could positively resolve their [[China\u2013United States trade war|disputes over trade]].<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-12-06/trade-war-latest-china-trump-tariffs-stocks-bonds-currency Mood Shifts in U.S.-China Trade Talks Infect Markets Far and Wide], by Liz Capo McCormick December 6, 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2019/12/06/trump-faces-complicated-calculus-on-december-tariffs-on-chinese-goods.html Trump\u2019s tricky decision: Hit Chinese goods with new tariffs or hold off?] by Kayla Tausche, December 6, 2019.</ref>\n\n=====Hong Kong=====\n{{Main|2014 Hong Kong protests|2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests]], also known as the Anti-Extradition Law Amendment Bill (Anti-ELAB) movement, is an ongoing series of demonstrations in Hong Kong triggered by the introduction of [[2019 Hong Kong extradition bill|the Fugitive Offenders amendment bill]] by the [[Government of Hong Kong|Hong Kong government]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-49317695 The Hong Kong protests explained in 100 and 500 words], bbc.com, November 28, 2019.</ref>\nIf enacted, the bill would have empowered local authorities to detain and extradite criminal fugitives who are wanted in territories with which Hong Kong does not currently have extradition agreements, including [[Taiwan]] and [[mainland China]]. This led to concerns that the bill would subject Hong Kong residents and visitors to the jursidiction and legal system of mainland China, which would undermine [[One country, two systems|the region's autonomy]] and Hong Kong people's civil liberties.As the protests progressed, the protesters laid out five key demands, which were the withdrawal of the bill, investigation into [[Allegations of Hong Kong Police Force misconduct surrounding the 2019 Hong Kong protests|alleged police brutality and misconduct]], the release of arrested protesters, a complete retraction of the official characterisation of the protests as \"riots\", and Chief Executive [[Carrie Lam]]'s resignation along with the introduction of [[universal suffrage]] for election of the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong|Legislative Council]] and the Chief Executive.<ref name=\"nbc_1061086\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/hong-kong-police-defend-shooting-protester-lawful-reasonable-n1061086|title=Hong Kong police defend shooting protester as 'lawful and reasonable'|first=Veta|last=Chan|publisher=[[NBC News]]|date=October 2, 2019|accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"nbc_1067466\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/think/opinion/chinese-mainlanders-living-hong-kong-feel-stuck-between-rock-hard-ncna1067466|title=Opinion &#124; Mainland Chinese like me are stuck between a rock and a hard place in Hong Kong|publisher=NBC News}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"nbc_1090206\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/hong-kong-turns-out-huge-numbers-vote-viewed-referendum-protests-n1090206|title=Pro-democracy candidates win big in election viewed as referendum on protests|publisher=NBC News|access-date=November 25, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"now_340955\">{{Cite news|url=https://news.now.com/home/local/player?newsId=340955|script-title=zh:\u773e\u5fd7\u885d\u5165\u653f\u7e3d\u975c\u5750\u4fc3\u64a4\u56de\u9003\u72af\u689d\u4f8b\u4fee\u8a02|language=zh|trans-title=Demosist\u014d got to HK Govt. HQ against the extradition bill amendment|work=Now.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104050116/https://news.now.com/home/local/player%3FnewsId%3D340955|archive-date=November 4, 2019 |date=March 15, 2019|url-status=live|format=video}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"now_355501\">{{cite news|url=https://news.now.com/home/local/player?newsId=355501|title=\u6709\u5927\u5f8b\u5e2b\u7a31\u8b66\u65b9\u9032\u5165\u5546\u5834\u6e05\u5834\u6216\u9055\u53cd\u8b66\u5bdf\u901a\u4f8b|publisher=[[NOW TV]]|date=July 15, 2019|accessdate=August 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190820150906/https://news.now.com/home/local/player%3FnewsId%3D355501|archive-date=August 20, 2019|url-status=live|format=video}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"npr_779399836\">{{cite web |last1=Kennedy |first1=Merrit |title=Hong Kong Police Say Protesters Are Shooting Arrows From Universities |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/11/14/779399836/hong-kong-police-say-protesters-are-shooting-arrows-from-universities |publisher=NPR |date=November 14, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"npr_780405090\">{{cite web |last1=Chappell |first1=Bill |title=Hong Kong Protesters in Tense Standoff With Police at Polytechnic University Campus |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/11/18/780405090/hong-kong-protesters-in-tense-standoff-with-police-at-polytech-university-campus |publisher=NPR |date=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"nyt_20190610_carriestandfast\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/10/world/asia/hong-kong-carrie-lam-extradition.html|title=Hong Kong Leader, Carrie Lam, Says She Won't Back Down on Extradition Bill|last=Ramzy|first=Austin|date=June 10, 2019|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=October 5, 2019|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610100501/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/10/world/asia/hong-kong-carrie-lam-extradition.html|archive-date=June 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"nyt_20190610_whatis\">{{cite news|last=Ives |first=Mike |date=June 10, 2019 |title=What Is Hong Kong's Extradition Bill? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/10/world/asia/hong-kong-extradition-bill.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|issn=0362-4331|location=Hong Kong|accessdate=July 29, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190612202157/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/10/world/asia/hong-kong-extradition-bill.html|archive-date=June 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"nyt_20190628_selfregulate\">{{cite news|last1=Lau Yiu-man|first1=Lewis|title=Hong Kong's Protesters Are Resisting China With Anarchy and Principle: The movement is leaderless but not chaotic. It self-regulates even as it constantly reinvents itself.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/28/opinion/hong-kong-protests-extradition-china.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|6=|issn=0362-4331|accessdate=July 8, 2019|date=June 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190628191107/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/28/opinion/hong-kong-protests-extradition-china.html|archive-date=June 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><!---<ref name=\"nyt_20190610_whatis\" /><ref name=\"bbc_49317695\" /><ref name=\"hkfp_20190213_trojanhorse\" /><ref name=\"hkfp_20190904_billwithdrawn\" /><ref name=\"abc_66464962\" /><ref name=\"reuters_20190524_eudiplomaticnote\" /><ref name=\"eji_20190523\" /><ref name=\"hkfp_20190522_chrispatten\" /><ref name=\"scmp_3004067\" /> --->\n\n====India====\n{{Unreferenced section|date=January 2020}}\n\nThe decade started off with the Congress led [[United Progressive Alliance]] (UPA) in power. UPA had won a majority in 2009 for a second term which was marred by corruption allegations. Taking advantage of the UPA's growing unpopularity, The [[Bhartiya Janata Party]] (BJP) led by former Gujarat Chief Minister [[Narendra Modi]] swept the polls in the 2014 general elections.\n\nRiding high on the wave of nationalism in the wake of attacks claimed by Indian authorities to have been orchestrated by Pakistan the Modi government relied heavily on anti-Pakistan rhetoric in successive elections. In 2016, a hard line Hindu monk associated with the BJP was elected chief minister of India's largest state who in turn pursued a policy of changing names of places with Muslim names to Hindu ones.\n\nThe Indian government, during this time also massively increased its defense budget and enhanced defense ties with the United States and Israel. The relationship with Israel continued to bloom as Modi became the first Indian Prime Minister to visit the Jewish state.\n\nCritics of the Modi government continued to level criticism at him for polarizing minorities, especially Muslims and changing the fabric of the Indian state by relentlessly pursuing the Hindutva ideology. In its second term in power, the BJP led National Democratic Alliance (NDA) became even more ideological in its pursuit of the Hindutva agenda. On August 5, 2019, the newly elected Indian government under a presidential order revoked Article 370 of the Indian constitution, thereby terminating the special status of Jammu and Kashmir and placed it under curfew. This move triggered widespread international condemnation and further aggravated relations with neighboring Pakistan. Later that year, the Supreme Court also delivered a verdict on the controversial Ram janam bhoomi case which called for a temple to be built on the disputed site while granting land to the Sunni Waqf Board for the establishment of a mosque elsewhere.\n\n===Middle East===\nStarting in 2010, [[Arab Spring]] led to major political upheaval across the region, leading to the violent repression of the [[Arab Winter]]. A [[Arab protests (2018\u2013present)|Second Arab Spring]] started in the later part of the decade.\n\n====Iran====\nThe [[2019 Iranian protests]] are a series of civil protests occurring in multiple cities across [[Iran]], initially from the 200% increase in fuel prices but later extended to an outcry against the [[Government of the Islamic Republic of Iran|current government in Iran]] and [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]] [[Khamenei|Ali Khamenei]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/dec/06/at-least-7000-people-reportedly-arrested-in-iran-protests-says-un At least 7,000 people reportedly arrested in Iran protests, says UN], Agence France-Presse, Fri December 6, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"auto1b\">{{Cite web|url=https://iranintl.com/%D8%A7%D9%8A%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%86/%DA%AF%D8%B3%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%B4-%D8%A7%D8%B9%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%B6%E2%80%8C%D9%87%D8%A7-%D8%A8%D9%87-%D8%A7%D9%81%D8%B2%D8%A7%DB%8C%D8%B4-%D9%82%DB%8C%D9%85%D8%AA-%D8%A8%D9%86%D8%B2%DB%8C%D9%86-%DB%8C%DA%A9-%D9%85%D8%B9%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%B6-%D8%AF%D8%B1-%D8%B3%DB%8C%D8%B1%D8%AC%D8%A7%D9%86-%D8%A8%D8%A7-%D8%B4%D9%84%DB%8C%DA%A9-%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%85%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%86-%DA%A9%D8%B4%D8%AA%D9%87-%D8%B4%D8%AF|title=\u06af\u0633\u062a\u0631\u0634 \u0627\u0639\u062a\u0631\u0627\u0636\u200c\u0647\u0627 \u0628\u0647 \u0627\u0641\u0632\u0627\u06cc\u0634 \u0642\u06cc\u0645\u062a \u0628\u0646\u0632\u06cc\u0646: \u06cc\u06a9 \u0645\u0639\u062a\u0631\u0636 \u062f\u0631 \u0633\u06cc\u0631\u062c\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u0627 \u0634\u0644\u06cc\u06a9 \u0645\u0627\u0645\u0648\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u06a9\u0634\u062a\u0647 \u0634\u062f |date=November 15, 2019 |website=[[Iran International]] |language=fa|access-date=November 16, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":0b\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-50444429|title=Protests erupt over Iran petrol rationing|date=November 16, 2019|access-date=November 16, 2019}}</ref> The protests commenced in the evening of November 15 and within hours spread to 21 cities as videos of the protest began to circulate online.<ref>{{cite web |title=Amnesty International: Over 100 Killed in 21 Cities in Iran Protests |url=https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/iran/amnesty-international-over-100-killed-in-21-cities-in-iran-protests-1.8153333 |work=Haaretz}}</ref><ref name=\"veconomist1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/middle-east-and-africa/2019/11/17/hikes-in-the-cost-of-petrol-are-fuelling-unrest-in-iran|title=Hikes in the cost of petrol are fuelling unrest in Iran|date=November 17, 2019|work=[[The Economist]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiofarda.com/a/iran-protests-fuel-price-hike/30274328.html|title=\u0627\u0641\u0632\u0627\u06cc\u0634 \u0642\u06cc\u0645\u062a \u0628\u0646\u0632\u06cc\u0646\u061b \u0634\u0647\u0631\u0647\u0627\u06cc \u0645\u062e\u062a\u0644\u0641 \u0627\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u0635\u062d\u0646\u0647 \u0627\u0639\u062a\u0631\u0627\u0636\u0627\u062a \u0634\u062f|website=\u0631\u0627\u062f\u06cc\u0648 \u0641\u0631\u062f\u0627}}</ref> Images of the violent protests were shared on the internet with protests reaching international levels.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/19/world/middleeast/iran-protests.html|title=Iran's 'Iron Fist': Rights Group Says More Than 100 Protesters Are Dead|last=Fassihi|first=Farnaz|date=November 19, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 21, 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the protests began as peaceful gatherings, government crackdowns prompted a revolt against the entire [[Government of the Islamic Republic of Iran|Iranian government]].<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite web |last1=Fassihi |first1=Farnaz |title=Iran Declares Protests Are Over, but the Evidence Suggests Otherwise |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/21/world/middleeast/iran-protests-internet.html}}</ref>  The Iranian government employed lethal tactics in order to shut down the protests including a nationwide internet shutdown, shooting protesters dead from rooftops, helicopters, and at close range with machine gun fire.<ref name=\"With Brutal Crackdown, Iran Is Conv\">{{cite web |last1=Gladstone |first1=Rick |title=With Brutal Crackdown, Iran Is Convulsed by Worst Unrest in 40 Years |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/01/world/middleeast/iran-protests-deaths.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Swert |first1=Mia |title=Amnesty says at least 208 killed in Iran protests |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/11/amnesty-208-killed-iran-protests-191130151227593.html}}</ref> Although there is currently no conclusive casualty count current estimates suspect the government killed well over 1,000 [[Iranian peoples|Iranian]] citizens.<ref>[https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/u-s-says-iran-may-have-killed-1-000-protesters-n1096666 U.S. says Iran may have killed up to 1,000 protesters] \n</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=McKenzie |first1=Sheena |title=One of the worst crackdowns in decades is happening in Iran. Here's what we know |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/12/03/middleeast/iran-protests-violent-crackdown-information-intl/index.html |publisher=CNN}}</ref> \n \nThe government crack down prompted a violent reaction from protesters who destroyed 731 government banks including Iran's central bank, nine [[Islamic]] religious centers, tore down [[anti-American]] billboards, and posters and statues of the Supreme Leader [[Ali Khamenei]]. 50 government military bases were also attacked by protesters. This series of protests have been categorized as the most violent and severe since the rise of [[Government of the Islamic Republic of Iran|Iran's Islamic Republic]] in 1979.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2019/11/iran-more-than-100-protesters-believed-to-be-killed-as-top-officials-give-green-light-to-crush-protests/|title=Iranian security forces are using lethal force to crush protests|publisher=Amnesty International|access-date=November 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=CASCHETTA |first1=A.J. |title=Iranian protests were not about the price of gas |url=https://thehill.com/opinion/international/472359-iranian-protests-were-not-about-the-price-of-gas |website=The Hill}}</ref><ref name=\"With Brutal Crackdown, Iran Is Conv\"/>\n\nTo block the sharing of information regarding the protests and the deaths of hundreds of protesters on social media platforms, the government blocked the Internet nationwide, resulting in a near-total internet blackout of around six days.<ref>https://netblocks.org/reports/internet-disrupted-in-iran-amid-fuel-protests-in-multiple-cities-pA25L18b</ref><ref>{[https://twitter.com/netblocks/status/1198215946286055424 Internet access is being restored in #Iran after a weeklong internet shutdown amid widespread protests; real-time network data show national connectivity now up to 64% of normal levels as of shutdown hour 163 #IranProtests #Internet4Iran https://netblocks.org/reports/internet-restored-in-iran-after-protest-shutdown] |last=NetBlocks.org|date=November 23, 2019|website=@netblocks|access-date=November 24, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraph1\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/11/23/iranian-masks-spiraling-protest-death-toll-stealing-bodies-morgues/ Iranian officials 'stealing bodies' from morgues to hide true scale of government crackdown]</ref><ref name=\"albawaba1\">[https://www.albawaba.com/node/mysterious-disappearances-iran-stealing-bodies-morgues-disguise-crackdown-protesters Mysterious Disappearances: Is Iran Stealing Bodies From Morgues to Disguise Crackdown on Protesters?]</ref>\n\n====Iraq====\n{{main|2019 Iraqi protests}}\n{{see also|2010s in Iraq political history}}\n\nThe [[2019 Iraqi protests]], also nicknamed the Tishreen Revolution<ref>{{cite web|url=https://iraqakhbar.com/2084791|title=\u062b\u0648\u0631\u0629 \u062a\u0634\u0631\u064a\u0646 \u2026\u0648\u0637\u0645\u0648\u062d\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0628\u0627\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0634\u0631\u0648\u0639\u0629|language=Arabic|trans-title=The October Revolution{{nbsp}}... and the legitimate ambitions of young people|website=News of Iraq|accessdate=November 15, 2019|date=November 12, 2019}}</ref> and 2019 Iraqi Intifada, are an ongoing series of protests that consisted of [[Demonstration (political)|demonstrations]], [[marches]], [[sit-ins]] and [[civil disobedience]]. They started on 1{{nbsp}}October 2019, a date which was set by civil activists on social media, spreading over the central and southern provinces of Iraq, to protest 16 years of corruption, unemployment and inefficient public services, before they escalated into calls to overthrow the administration and to stop [[Iranian intervention in Iraq (2014\u2013present)|Iranian intervention in Iraq]]. The Iraqi government has been accused of using bullets, snipers, hot water and [[tear gas]] against protesters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/iraq-hrw-denounces-lethal-force-protesters-urges-probe-191010123643525.html|title=Iraq: HRW denounces lethal force against protesters, urges probe|publisher=Al Jazeera}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Adil Abdul-Mahdi]] announced on November 29 that he would resign.<ref name=Resignation29Nov>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/11/29/iraq-prime-minister-resign-worsening-crisis-074396|title=Iraqi prime minister to resign in wake of deadly protests|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=November 29, 2019|accessdate=November 29, 2019}}</ref> According to the [[BBC]], they call for the end of the political system which has existed since [[2003 invasion of Iraq|the US-led invasion]] ousted [[Saddam Hussein]] and has been marked by sectarian divides.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-49960677 | work=BBC News | title=Iraq protests: What's behind the anger?| date=October 7, 2019 | accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"guardiansaddam\">{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/oct/27/iraq-protests-aim-topple-regime | work=[[The Guardian]]| title='They are worse than Saddam': Iraqis take to streets to topple regime| date=October 27, 2019 | accessdate=October 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://providencemag.com/2019/11/iraq-protests/|title=An Iraq for All Iraqis?|date=November 26, 2019|website=Providence|access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref> It is the largest unrest since the Saddam Hussein government concluded.<ref name=\"larges\">{{cite news| url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/11/07/why-iraqs-protesters-are-still-in-the-streets | work=[[Foreign Policy]] | title=Iraq Protester's Step Up Their Tactics As the Government in Baghdad Scrambles to Respond | date=November 7, 2019 | accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe UN Envoy for Iraq, [[Jeanine Hennis-Plasschaert]], called for renewed efforts to restore civil balance and protections for free speech.<ref>[https://news.un.org/en/story/2019/12/1052641 Protests and civil unrest show \u2018renewed sense of patriotism\u2019 in Iraq, UN envoy tells Security Council], United Nations., December 3, 2019.</ref><ref>[https://news.un.org/en/story/2019/12/1053011 Denouncing attacks against Baghdad protesters, UN warns \u2018violence risks placing Iraq on dangerous trajectory], December 7, 2019.</ref>\n\n====Israel====\n[[Benjamin Netanyahu]] remained in the office of the [[Prime Minister of Israel|Prime Minister]] throughout the decade, becoming the longest holder of the office. Under his watch, the [[Israeli settlement|Jewish settlement movement]] has grown and gained influence, with at least 2,000 new homes built on the [[Palestinian territories]] each year, leading to a declining possibility for a [[two-state solution]] in the [[Arab\u2013Israeli conflict]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/04/08/709989737/after-a-decade-of-netanyahu-hopes-fade-for-a-palestinian-state|title=After A Decade Of Netanyahu, Hopes Fade for a Palestinian State|publisher=NPR|access-date=January 11, 2020}}</ref> In 2014, there was a [[2014 Israel\u2013Gaza conflict|war in Gaza]] over [[Hamas]] rocket firings into Israeli cities, with a final death toll of 2,100 Palestinians and 73 Israeli citizens.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-28439404|title=Gaza crisis: Toll of operations in Gaza|date=September 1, 2014|access-date=January 11, 2020}}</ref> The [[2018\u201319 Gaza border protests]] demanded a [[right of return]] for those displaced from their homes during Israel's founding.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/04/13/world/middleeast/gaza-fence-aerial.html,%20https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/04/13/world/middleeast/gaza-fence-aerial.html|title=300 Meters in Gaza: Snipers, Burning Tires and a Contested Fence \u2013 The New York Times|last=Halbfinger|first=David M.|date=May 15, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 11, 2020|last2=Abuheweila|first2=Iyad|issn=0362-4331|last3=Patel|first3=Jugal K.}}</ref> Israeli security forces responded by firing at the protesters, killing 60 in a single day.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/15/world/middleeast/israel-gaza-protests.html|title=Uneasy Calm Falls Over Gaza After Israel Kills Scores at Protests|last=Times|first=The New York|date=May 15, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 11, 2020|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn foreign policy, Israel continued the [[Iran\u2013Israel proxy conflict|proxy conflict against Iran]], with [[Israeli involvement in the Syrian Civil War]] and [[2019 Israeli airstrikes in Iraq]].\n\nIn 2019, the country entered a political crisis following two [[hung parliament]]s and corruption charges against Netanyehu.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/11/22/israel-political-crisis-deadlock-benjamin-netanyahu-indictment-corruption-election/|title=Israel's Political Crisis Deepens|last=Wilson|first=Audrey|website=Foreign Policy|access-date=January 11, 2020}}</ref> Both the [[April 2019 Israeli legislative election|April]] and [[September 2019 Israeli legislative election|September 2019 elections]] failed to produce a majority in the Knesset for either Netanyehu, or his challenger, [[Benny Gantz]], a former general. In November, Netanyehu became the first sitting Israeli leader to be criminally prosecuted, with [[Investigations involving Benjamin Netanyahu|charges of bribery, fraud and breach of trust spanning several cases]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/21/world/middleeast/netanyahu-corruption-indicted.html|title=Israel's Netanyahu Indicted on Charges of Fraud, Bribery and Breach of Trust|last=Halbfinger|first=David M.|date=November 21, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 11, 2020|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n====Syria====\n{{main|Syria Civil War}}\n{{see also|2010s in Syria political history}}\n\nThe [[2019 Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria]] is a cross-border military operation conducted by the [[Turkish Armed Forces]] (TAF) and the [[Syrian National Army]] (SNA) against the [[Syrian Democratic Forces]] (SDF) and later the [[Syrian Arab Army]] (SAA) in [[Rojava|northeastern Syria]].\n\nOn October 6, 2019, the [[Trump administration]] ordered American troops to withdraw from northeastern Syria, where the United States [[American-led intervention in the Syrian Civil War|had been supporting]] its Kurdish allies.<ref name=withdraw>{{cite news |title=Trump makes way for Turkey operation against Kurds in Syria |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-49956698?intlink_from_url=https://www.bbc.com/news/topics/cp7r8vgl2y7t/kurds&link_location=live-reporting-story |accessdate=October 10, 2019 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=October 7, 2019}}</ref> The military operation began on October 9, 2019 when the [[Turkish Air Force]] launched airstrikes on [[Syria\u2013Turkey border|border]] towns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/oct/09/turkey-launches-military-operation-in-northern-syria-erdogan|title=Turkey launches military operation in northern Syria|work=The Guardian|first=Bethan|last=McKernan|date=October 9, 2019}}</ref> The conflict resulted in the displacement of over 300,000 people and has caused the death of more than 70 civilians in Syria and 20 civilians in Turkey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bursadabugun.com/haber/teroristlerin-saldirilarinda-20-sivil-sehit-oldu-170-kisi-yaralandi-1191643.html|title=Ter\u00f6ristlerin sald\u0131r\u0131lar\u0131nda 20 sivil \u015fehit oldu, 170 ki\u015fi yaraland\u0131|website=Bursada Bug\u00fcn}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/syria/kurdish-politician-executed-by-turkish-backed-fighters-in-syria-1.7970427|title=Kurdish Politician Among Nine Civilians Executed by Turkish-backed Fighters in Syria|date=October 13, 2019|newspaper=[[Haaretz]]}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the Turkish President [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]], the operation is intended to expel the SDF\u2014viewed as a terrorist organization by Turkey due to its ties with the [[Kurdistan Workers Party]] (PKK), but considered an ally against [[ISIL]] by the [[Combined Joint Task Force \u2013 Operation Inherent Resolve|United States and its allies]]\u2014from the border region as well as to create a 30&nbsp;km-deep (20&nbsp;mi) \"safe zone\" in Northern Syria where some of the 3.6&nbsp;million [[Syrian refugees in Turkey]] would resettle.<ref name=\"aj-turkey-begins\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/turkey-begins-ground-offensive-northeastern-syria-191009212025006.html |title=Turkey begins ground offensive in northeastern Syria |date=October 9, 2019 |publisher=[[Al Jazeera]] |access-date=October 10, 2019}}</ref> As the proposed settlement zone is heavily Kurdish demographically, this intention has been criticized as an attempt to force drastic demographic change,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2019/09/turkey-syria-united-states-erdogan-plans-for-east-euphrates.html|title=Erdogan's Syria plan: Resettling the Syrian refugees or ousting Kurds from their land?|first=Cengiz|last=Candar|date=September 30, 2019|website=Al-Monitor}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/e40cb754-e456-11e9-b112-9624ec9edc59|title=Syria is witnessing a violent demographic re-engineering|website=[[Financial Times]]}}</ref><ref name=reuters_demographics>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security-turkey-refugees-graphi-idUSKBN1WN28J|title=Turkey's plan to settle refugees in northeast Syria alarms allies|date=October 8, 2019|agency=Reuters}}</ref> a criticism denied by Turkey by saying that it only intended to \"correct\" the demographics that Turkish officials stated were changed by the SDF.<ref name=reuters_demographics/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ibtimes.com/turkey-begins-military-operation-against-kurds-after-trump-pulls-troops-northern-2842727|title=Turkey Begins Military Operation Against Kurds After Trump Pulls Troops in Northern Syria|first=Wesley|last=Dockery|date=October 9, 2019|website=[[International Business Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1565401/middle-east|title=After US green light, Turkey prepares military operation in Syria|date=October 7, 2019|website=Arab News}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Syrian government]] initially criticized the Kurdish forces for the Turkish offensive, for their separatism and not reconciling with the government, while at the same time also condemning the foreign invasion in Syrian territory.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-10/11/c_138462068.htm |title=Syria blames Kurdish forces for Turkish military offensive |date=October 11, 2019|work=Xinhua Net |access-date=October 11, 2019}}</ref> However, a few days later, the SDF reached an agreement with the Syrian government, in which it would allow the [[Syrian Army]] to enter the SDF-held towns of [[Manbij]] and [[Koban\u00ee]] in an attempt to defend the towns from the Turkish offensive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2019/10/13/Syrian-army-to-enter-SDF-held-Kobani-Manbij-Monitor.html|title=Syrian army to enter SDF-held Kobani, Manbij: Monitor|publisher=Al Arabiya|access-date=October 13, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security-towns-report-idUSKBN1WS0K0|title=Report: Syrian army to enter SDF-held Kobani, Manbij|date=October 13, 2019|agency=Reuters|access-date=October 13, 2019}}</ref><ref name= \"armyinvolved\">{{Cite web|url=https://thedefensepost.com/2019/10/13/syria-government-russia-kobani-manbij-sdf/|title=Syrian government forces set to enter Kobani and Manbij after SDF deal|date=October 13, 2019|website=The Defense Post|access-date=October 13, 2019}}</ref> Shortly thereafter, Syrian state broadcaster [[SANA]] announced that Syrian Army troops had started to deploy to the country's north.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/world/mena/syrian-troops-sent-north-to-confront-turkey-over-incursion-says-state-media-1.922875|title=Syrian troops sent north to 'confront' Turkey over incursion, says state media|website=The National|access-date=October 13, 2019}}</ref> Turkey and the SNA launched an offensive to capture Manbij on the same day.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.haber.com/suriye-milli-ordusu-munbic-operasyonu-basladi-103685/|title=Suriye Milli Ordusu: M\u00fcnbi\u00e7 Operasyonu Ba\u015flad\u0131|date=October 14, 2019|website=Haber.com}}</ref>\n\nOn October 22, 2019, Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] and Turkish President [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] [[Second Northern Syria Buffer Zone|reached a deal]] to extend the ceasefire by 150 additional hours for SDF to move 30 kilometers away from the border area as well as from [[Tal Rifaat]] and [[Manbij]]. The terms of the deal also included joint Russian\u2013Turkish patrols 10 kilometers into Syria from the border except in the city of [[Qamishli]]. The new ceasefire started at 12&nbsp;pm local time on October 23.<ref name=\"auto16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/article236512698.html|title=The Latest: Pence says 5-day cease-fire in Syria has held\n|date=October 22, 2019|website=The Miami Herald}}</ref><ref name=\"auto17\">{{Cite web|url=https://thedefensepost.com/2019/10/22/russia-turkey-syria-mou/|title=FULL TEXT: Memorandum of Understanding between Turkey and Russia on northern Syria|date=October 22, 2019|website=The Defense Post}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the main combat phase did end, post ceasefire operations are still ongoing.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security-turkey/turkey-not-resuming-military-operation-in-northeast-syria-security-source-idUSKBN1XZ12M Turkey not resuming military operation in northeast Syria: security source] Reuters, November 2019</ref><ref>[http://www.milliyet.com.tr/siyaset/son-dakika-mgk-toplantisi-sonrasi-flas-baris-pinari-harekati-aciklamasi-surecek-6087904]</ref> As announced by Russia's Ministry of Defense on October 15, Russian forces have started to patrol the region along the line of contact between Turkish and Syrian forces,<ref name=ko-il-rftv>{{cite web |last1=Kottasov\u00e1 |first1=Ivana |last2=Ilyushina |first2=Mary |title=Russians fill the void left by US troops in Syria |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/10/15/middleeast/turkey-syria-russian-troops-intl/index.html |publisher=CNN |date=October 15, 2019}}</ref><ref name=wapo-ssgse/> indicating that Russia is filling the security vacuum from the sudden US withdrawal.<ref name=wapo-ssgse>{{cite web | author1= Fahim, Kareem | author2=Dadouch, Sarah | author3= Englund, Will |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/syria-says-government-soldiers-enter-manbij-after-us-troops-withdraw/2019/10/15/d494405a-eeb8-11e9-bb7e-d2026ee0c199_story.html | title=Russia patrolling between Turkish and Syrian forces after U.S. troops withdraw| date =October 15, 2019 | website=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mortazavi |first1=Negar |title=How Russia is filling the gap left by Trump's withdrawal of US troops in Syria |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/trump-syria-kurds-russia-putin-assad-a9157656.html |website=The Independent |date=October 16, 2019}}</ref><ref name=wapo-ssgse/><ref name=ol-ram>{{cite news |last1=Oliphant |first1=Roland |title=Russia assumes mantle of supreme power broker in Middle East as US retreats from Syria |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/10/15/russia-assumes-mantle-supreme-power-broker-middle-east-us-retreats/ |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=October 15, 2019}}</ref> Alexander Lavrentiev, Russia's special envoy on Syria, warned that the Turkish offensive into Syria is unacceptable and stated that Russia is seeking to prevent conflict between Turkish and Syrian troops.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sevastopulo |first1=Demetri |last2=Williams |first2=Aime |last3=Pitel |first3=Laura |last4=Foy |first4=Henry |title=US delegation to press Turkey for Syrian ceasefire |url=https://www.ft.com/content/3123143a-ef41-11e9-ad1e-4367d8281195 |website=Financial Times |date=October 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Turkish operation received mixed responses by the international community. Including condemnations<ref>{{cite news |title=India slams Turkey for its 'unilateral military offensive' in northeast Syria {{!}} India News |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/india-slams-turkey-for-its-unilateral-military-offensive-in-northeast-syria/articleshow/71520852.cms |accessdate=October 10, 2019 |work=The Times of India }}</ref> as well as support for the operation for the settlement of refugees in Northern Syria.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/539756-pm-imran-telephones-erdogan-assures-full-support-to-turkey|title=PM Imran telephones Erdogan, assures full support to Turkey|date=October 11, 2019|website=The News International}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/operation-peace-spring/turkic-council-supports-turkey-s-anti-terror-operation/1614575|title=Turkic Council supports Turkey's anti-terror operation|website=aa.com.tr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnnturk.com/turkiye/turk-konseyi-liderler-zirvesinden-ortak-baris-pinari-bildirisi|title=T\u00fcrk Konseyi Liderler Zirvesi'nden ortak 'Bar\u0131\u015f P\u0131nar\u0131' bildirisi|website=CNN T\u00fcrk}}</ref> While originally acknowledging Turkey's \"right to defend itself\", on October 15, Russia hardened its position against the operation and deployed troops.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/3123143a-ef41-11e9-ad1e-4367d8281195|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/15/world/middleeast/kurds-syria-turkey.html|title=In Syria, Russia Is Pleased to Fill an American Void|first1=Ben|last1=Hubbard|first2=Anton|last2=Troianovski|first3=Carlotta|last3=Gall|first4=Patrick|last4=Kingsley|date=October 15, 2019|work=The New York Times}}</ref> Ten European nations and Canada [[Reactions to the 2019 Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria|imposed an arms embargo on Turkey]], while the U.S. imposed sanctions on Turkish ministries and senior government officials in response to the offensive in Syria.<!---<ref name=ColumbusSanctions/>---> Likewise, Trump's sudden pullout of US forces in Syria was also criticized by journalists as a \"serious betrayal to the Kurds\" as well as a \"catastrophic blow to US credibility as an ally and Washington's standing on the world stage\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/us-betrayal-of-kurds-destroys-the-wests-credibility-for-years-to-come-11835611|title=US betrayal of Kurds destroys the West's credibility for years to come | publisher=Sky News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/trump-syria-move-delivers-blow-credibility-worldwide-191008232132422.html|title=Trump's Syria move 'delivers a blow to US credibility worldwide'| publisher=Al Jazeera}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/18/opinion/trump-kurds-syria.html|title=Trump's Gut, and the Gutting of American Credibility| website=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/meet-the-press/trump-s-decision-syria-has-already-turned-foreign-policy-disaster-n1065691|title=Trump's decision on Syria has already turned into a foreign policy disaster| publisher=NBC News}}</ref> On November 19, the Defense Department inspector general released a report finding that the American withdrawal and subsequent Turkish incursion allowed ISIL to \"reconstitute capabilities and resources within Syria and strengthen its ability to plan attacks abroad\".<ref name=\"O\u2019brien\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/11/19/trump-syria-isis-071499|title=Trump's pullout from Syria allowed ISIS to gain strength, intel agency reports|first=Connor|last=O\u2019brien|website=Politico}}</ref>\n\n=====Changes in Syria diplomatic situation=====\nAs a result of the Turkish incursion, multiple Kurdish groups that were once rivals have begun to seek greater unity. Additionally, Syrian Kurdish officials have had some positive discussions with the Assad government, and with local countries such as Saudi Arabia, UAE and Jordan.<ref name=\"al-monitor overview\">[https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2019/12/turkey-syria-gulf-ankara-kurdish-sweep-backfiring.html Turkey\u2019s Kurdish sweep backfires], Fehim Tastekin December 11, 2019, al-monitor.com</ref>\n\nOn the ground, Turkish areas of operations have been delineated by Russian mediators. Russian military officials forged agreements between Syria, Turkey and Kurds for areas to be patrolled by each side.<ref>[https://ahvalnews.com/northern-syria/russian-forces-syria-sdf-discuss-phase-two-border-security-deal Russian forces in Syria, SDF discuss phase two in border security deal], December 7, 2019.</ref> Russia handles security through its own forces deployed in some key towns.\n\nThe Assad government has forged agreements with some opposition groups to return to various local border areas.<ref name=\"al-monitor overview\"/> The Syrian Democratic Forces (SDF) reached agreement with the Assad regime for the Syrian Army to patrol several border areas. They also agreed on areas of deployment for Russian forces.<ref>[https://ahvalnews.com/northern-syria/russian-forces-syria-sdf-discuss-phase-two-border-security-deal Russian forces in Syria, SDF discuss phase two in border security deal], December 7, 2019, ahvalnews.com.</ref> The first agreement between SDF and the Assad regime occurred in October 2019, directly as a result of the Turkish incursion.<ref>[https://ahvalnews.com/operation-peace-spring/live-day-6-turkeys-syria-operation Live: Day 6 of Turkey's Syria operation],\nAhval, October 14, 2019.</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://syrianobserver.com/EN/news/53885/sdf-agrees-to-sochi-deal-for-northern-syria.html|title=SDF Agrees to Sochi Deal for Northern Syria|date=October 28, 2019|website=The Syrian Observer|access-date=October 28, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://ekurd.net/syrian-kurds-say-pulling-2019-10-28|title=Syrian Kurds say pulling out from entire length of Turkey border|date=October 28, 2019|website=Kurd Net \u2013 Ekurd.net Daily News|access-date=October 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn general positive negotiations have increased between Syria and Turkey, and between Syria and Kurdish groups.<ref>[https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2019/12/the-takeaway-december-11-2019.html The Takeaway: December 11, 2019], Andrew Parasiliti December 11, 2019.</ref>\n\nOn December 9, Russian troops entered Raqqa and began distributing humanitarian aid.<ref>[https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Russian-forces-enter-former-Islamic-State-stronghold-in-Syria-610347 Russian forces enter former Islamic State stronghold in Syria]:Russian troops in Raqqa were handing out humanitarian aid and its military doctors were offering residents medical attention. By REUTERS December 9, 2019.</ref><ref>[https://thedefensepost.com/2019/12/10/syria-russia-raqqa-us-withdraw/ Russian troops enter Syria\u2019s Raqqa, filling void of withdrawing US forces],by Jared Szuba December 10, 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Russians-in-Raqqa-two-years-after-US-helped-take-city-from-ISIS-610377 Russians near Raqqa two years after US helped take city from ISIS] By SETH J. FRANTZMAN December 9, 2019.</ref>\n\n==== Turkey ====\n[[Turkey]] spent the decade under the leadership of [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]]. Under his leadership, Turkey engaged in a [[Foreign policy of the Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan government|more active foreign policy]], including [[Turkish involvement in the Syrian Civil War|military intervention in the Syrian Civil War]].\n\nIn 2016, a [[2016 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat attempt|coup attempt]] was launched against Erdogan, which failed. This led to extensive purges within the Turkish state in an effort to remove anti-Erdogan elements, claimed by the government to be connected to the preacher [[Fethullah G\u00fclen]] and his [[G\u00fclen movement]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/13/magazine/inside-turkeys-purge.html|title=Inside Turkey's Purge|last=Hansen|first=Suzy|date=April 13, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 13, 2020|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Over 150,000 civil servants have lost their jobs as a result.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://turkeypurge.com/purge-in-numbers-2|title=Purge in Numbers new {{!}} Turkey Purge|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nErdogan has been criticized for undermining Turkish democracy,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/18/business/west-democracy-turkey-erdogan-financial-crisis.html|title=The West Hoped for Democracy in Turkey. Erdogan Had Other Ideas.|last=Goodman|first=Peter S.|date=August 18, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 13, 2020|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and for [[neo-Ottomanism]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2018/06/22/erdogan-is-making-the-ottoman-empire-great-again/|title=Erdogan Is Making the Ottoman Empire Great Again|last=Edwards|first=Michael Colborne, Maxim|website=Foreign Policy|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Yemen====\nThe [[Saudi-led intervention in Yemen]], is an intervention launched by [[Saudi Arabia]] in 2015, leading a coalition of nine countries from [[Western Asia|West Asia]] and Africa, in response to calls from the internationally recognized pro-Saudi<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.theamericanconservative.com/buchanan/with-friends-like-the-saudis/|title=With Friends Like the Saudis|first=Patrick J.|last=Buchanan|website=The American Conservative}}</ref> president of Yemen [[Abdrabbuh Mansur Hadi]] for military support after [[Houthi takeover in Yemen|he was ousted]] by the [[Houthi movement]] due to economic and political grievances, and fled to Saudi Arabia.<ref name=\"https\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/03/26/us-yemen-security-idUSKBN0ML0YC20150326|agency=[[Reuters]]|title=Yemeni leader Hadi leaves country as Saudi Arabia keeps up air strikes|date=March 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nCode-named ''Operation Decisive Storm'', the intervention is said to be in compliance with [[Use of force by states|Article 2(4)]] of the [[Charter of the United Nations|UN Charter]] by the international community;<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Nu\u00dfberger |first1=Benjamin |title=Military strikes in Yemen in 2015: intervention by invitation and self-defence in the course of Yemen's 'model transitional process' |journal=Journal on the Use of Force and International Law |date=January 5, 2017 |volume= 4, 2017 |pages=110\u2013160 |doi=10.1080/20531702.2017.1256565 }}</ref> but this has been contested by some academics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irinnews.org/analysis/2015/04/03/saudi-war-yemen-legal|title=Is the Saudi war on Yemen legal?|date=April 3, 2015|website=IRIN}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|first1=Luca|title=Weathering the Storm: Legality and Legal Implications of the Saudi-Led Military Intervention in Yemen|last1=Ferro|first2=Tom|last2=Ruys|journal=International & Comparative Law Quarterly|volume=65|issue=1|pages=61\u201398|doi=10.1017/S0020589315000536|year=2016}}</ref> The intervention initially consisted of a bombing campaign on Houthi rebels and later saw a naval [[blockade of Yemen|blockade]] and the deployment of ground forces into [[Yemen]].<ref>Gatten, Emma. [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/saudi-blockade-starves-yemen-of-vital-supplies-as-bombing-raids-continue-10509460.html Saudi blockade starves Yemen of vital supplies, as bombing raids continue]. ''[[The Independent]]''. September 19, 2016. Retrieved October 23, 2016.</ref> The Saudi-led coalition has attacked the positions of the [[Houthi]] militia, and loyalists of the former [[President of Yemen]], [[Ali Abdullah Saleh]], allegedly supported by [[Iran]] (see [[Iran\u2013Saudi Arabia proxy conflict]]).<ref name=\"CBC News\">{{cite news|url= http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/yemeni-s-abed-rabbo-mansour-hadi-arrives-in-saudi-capital-1.3010698|title=Yemeni's Abed Rabbo Mansour Hadi arrives in Saudi capital|date=March 26, 2015|access-date=March 26, 2015|publisher=[[CBC News]]}}</ref><ref name=\"https\"/>\n\n[[Fighter jet]]s and ground forces from [[Egypt]], [[Morocco]], [[Jordan]], [[Sudan]], the [[United Arab Emirates]], [[Kuwait]], [[Qatar]], [[Bahrain]], and [[Academi]] (formerly Blackwater) took part in the operation. [[Djibouti]], [[Eritrea]], and [[Somalia]] made their airspace, territorial waters, and military bases available to the coalition.<ref name=\"Ssfpstsciy\">{{cite news |title=SOMALIA: Somalia finally pledges support to Saudi-led coalition in Yemen \u2013 Raxanreeb Online |url=http://www.wargeyska.so/somalia-somalia-finally-pledges-support-to-suadi-led-coalition-in-yemen-raxanreeb-online/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20150407194428/http://www.wargeyska.so/somalia-somalia-finally-pledges-support-to-suadi-led-coalition-in-yemen-raxanreeb-online/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 7, 2015 |agency=RBC Radio |date=April 7, 2015 |access-date=April 7, 2015 }}</ref> The United States provided intelligence and logistical support, including [[aerial refueling]] and search-and-rescue for downed coalition pilots.<ref name=\"rescue\">{{cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/us-rescues-saudi-pilots-gulf-aden/story?id=29965427|publisher=[[ABC News]] |title=US Rescues 2 Saudi Pilots From Gulf of Aden|date=March 27, 2015 |first=Luis|last=Martinez |access-date=April 7, 2015}}</ref><ref name=hp-20160810>{{cite news |url=https://huffingtonpost.com/entry/barack-obama-could-end-the-killing-in-yemen-in-hours_us_57f7d5dee4b0b6a43031ba4e |title=Obama Could End The Slaughter in Yemen Within Hours |author=Akbar Shahid Ahmed |work=[[HuffPost]] |date=August 10, 2016 |accessdate=October 8, 2016}}</ref> It also accelerated the sale of weapons to coalition states<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/2015/04/07/262381/us-stepping-up-weapons-shipments.html|publisher=[[The McClatchy Company|McClatchy DC]] |first=James|last=Rosen |authorlink=James Rosen (journalist) |title=U.S. stepping up weapons shipments to aid Saudi air campaign over Yemen|date=April 7, 2015|access-date=April 7, 2015}}</ref> and continued [[List of drone strikes in Yemen|strikes against AQAP.]] The US and Britain have deployed their military personnel in the command and control centre responsible for Saudi-led air strikes on Yemen, having access to lists of targets.<ref name=\"theguardian-com_2016-01-15_BZM\">{{cite news |first=Emma |last=Graham-Harrison |title=British and US military 'in command room' for Saudi strikes on Yemen |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=January 15, 2016 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jan/15/british-us-military-in-command-room-saudi-strikes-yemen |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6eaDLp4Dq |archivedate=January 16, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"theguardian-com_2016-01-19_BHS\">{{cite news |first=Vickie |last=Hawkins |title=Bombing hospitals and schools cannot become the new normal |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=January 19, 2016 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2016/jan/19/yemen-msf-bombing-hospitals-schools-cannot-become-the-new-normal |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ehgjdWF7 |archivedate=January 21, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"publications-parliament-uk_2016-01-12_HoC\">{{cite web |title=House of Commons debate, Tuesday 12 January 2016 | publisher=publications.parliament.uk (Daily Hansard \u2013 Debate, Column 681) |date=January 12, 2016 |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201516/cmhansrd/cm160112/debtext/160112-0001.htm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ehizuhFw |archivedate=January 21, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe war has received [[International reactions to the Saudi-led intervention in Yemen (2015\u2013present)|widespread criticism]] and had a dramatic worsening effect on Yemen's humanitarian situation, that reached the level of a \"humanitarian disaster\"<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jun/05/saudi-led-naval-blockade-worsens-yemen-humanitarian-disaster |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |title=Saudi-led naval blockade leaves 20&nbsp;m Yemenis facing humanitarian disaster |date=June 5, 2015|first=Julian |last=Borger |authorlink=Julian Borger |access-date=October 31, 2015}}</ref> or \"humanitarian catastrophe\".<ref name=\"un-org_2015-07-28_DCN\">{{cite news|url=https://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=51516|title=Durable ceasefire needed as 'humanitarian catastrophe' leaves millions suffering in Yemen \u2013 UN relief chief)|date=July 28, 2015|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6aOLG7U6O|archivedate=July 29, 2015|url-status=live|publisher=UN News Centre}}</ref><ref name=\"ECHAO_2015-12-14_ECS\">{{cite web |title=European Commission steps up humanitarian aid for Yemen crisis |via=[[ReliefWeb]] |publisher=European Commission's Directorate-General for European Civil Protection and Humanitarian Aid Operations |date=December 14, 2015 |url=http://reliefweb.int/report/yemen/european-commission-steps-humanitarian-aid-yemen-crisis |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6dqN1KtTh |archivedate=December 17, 2015 |url-status=live }}; Original source: {{cite web |title=European Commission steps up humanitarian aid for Yemen crisis |url=http://ec.europa.eu/echo/news/european-commission-steps-humanitarian-aid-yemen-crisis_en |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6dqNESGuF |archivedate=December 17, 2015 |url-status=live |date=December 14, 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"BBCNews_2015-08-19_YCH\">{{cite news |title=Yemen crisis: How bad is the humanitarian situation? |work=BBC News |date=August 24, 2015 |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-34011187 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6bskayjqI |archivedate=September 28, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the conflict's status was described as a \"military stalemate for years\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Yemeni Separatists Relinquish Control of Buildings in Aden |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/17/world/middleeast/yemen-houthi-saudi-oilfield.html |accessdate=September 4, 2019 |work=The New York Times |agency=Reuters |date=August 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Trump vetoed a bipartisan bill which would have ended US support for the Saudi-led military intervention.<ref>{{cite news |last= Pilkington|first=Ed|date=April 17, 2019 |title=Dismay as Trump vetoes bill to end US support for war in Yemen|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/apr/16/trump-yemen-war-veto-military-aid|work=The Guardian |access-date=April 18, 2019}}</ref> With 53 votes instead of the 67 needed, the United States Senate failed to override the veto.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/senate-fails-to-override-trumps-veto-of-resolution-demanding-end-to-us-involvement-in-yemen/2019/05/02/4bd0a524-6cf9-11e9-8f44-e8d8bb1df986_story.html|title=Senate fails to override Trump's veto of resolution demanding end to U.S. involvement in Yemen war|last1=Demirjian|first1=Karoun|last2=Ryan|first2=Missy|date=May 2, 2019|accessdate=May 4, 2019|newspaper=The Washington Post}}</ref> The legal arguments and policies of the Obama administration were cited as justification for the veto.<ref>{{cite news |last=Olsen |first=Gunar |date=April 20, 2019 |title=Add Trump's Yemen Veto to Obama's Spotty War Legacy|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/153639/add-trumps-yemen-veto-obamas-spotty-war-legacy|work=[[The New Republic]] |access-date=April 21, 2019 }}</ref> The US Deputy Assistant Secretary of Defense [[Michael Mulroy]] stated that US support was limited to side-by-side coaching to mitigate civilian casualties and if the measure had passed it would do nothing to help the people of Yemen and may only increase civilian deaths.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.airforcemag.com/Features/Pages/2019/April%202019/DOD-Official-Ending-US-Support-for-Yemen-Fight-Would-Worsen-the-Crisis.aspx|title=Air Force Magazine}}</ref> Mulroy supported the United Nation's peace talks and he pushed the international community to come together and chart a comprehensive way ahead for Yemen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/senate-fails-to-override-trumps-veto-of-resolution-demanding-end-to-us-involvement-in-yemen/2019/05/02/4bd0a524-6cf9-11e9-8f44-e8d8bb1df986_story.html|title=Senate fails to override Trump's veto of resolution demanding end to U.S. involvement in Yemen war|website=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stamfordadvocate.com/news/article/Senate-fails-to-override-President-Trump-s-veto-13814269.php|title=Senate doesn't override Trump's veto of resolution demanding end to U.S. involvement in Yemen|first1=Karoun|last1=Demirjian|first2=Missy|last2=Ryan|first3=The Washington|last3=Post|date=May 2, 2019|website=StamfordAdvocate|accessdate=May 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehour.com/news/article/Senate-fails-to-override-President-Trump-s-veto-13814269.php|title=Senate doesn't override Trump's veto of resolution demanding end to US involvement in Yemen|first1=Karoun|last1=Demirjian|first2=Missy|last2=Ryan|first3=The Washington|last3=Post|date=May 2, 2019|website=The Hour}}</ref> Writing in ''[[The Nation]]'', [[Mohamad Bazzi]] argued that Mulroy's defence of US support as necessary to limit civilian casualties was false, and that \"Saudi leaders and their allies have ignored American entreaties to minimize civilian casualties since the war's early days\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/war-crimes-united-states-saudi-arabia-yemen/|title=Both Saudi Arabia and the United States Are Probably Guilty of War Crimes in Yemen|first=Mohamad|last=Bazzi|date=May 17, 2019|work=The Nation}}</ref>\n\n===Europe===\n====European Union====\nIn December 2019, the EU announced that banking ministers from EU member nations had failed to reach agreement over proposed banking reforms and systemic change.<ref name=\"ft.com\">[https://www.ft.com/content/5f55f7d8-1777-11ea-9ee4-11f260415385 Eurozone ministers divided over banking union negotiations].</ref><ref name=\"brecorder.com\">[https://www.brecorder.com/2019/12/06/550824/eu-ministers-fail-to-advance-eurozone-reforms/ EU  ministers fail to advance eurozone reforms], By RECORDER REPORT on December 6, 2019.</ref> The EU was concerned about high rates of debt in France, Italy and Spain.<ref name=\"euractiv.com\">[https://www.euractiv.com/section/economic-governance/news/eu-concerned-over-france-italy-and-spain-debts/ EU concerned over France, Italy and Spain debts] By Beatriz Rios | EURACTIV.com November 21, 2019.</ref>\n\n==== France ====\nThe [[2017 French presidential election]] caused a radical shift in [[Politics of France|French politics]], as the prevailing parties of [[The Republicans (France)|The Republicans]] and [[Socialist Party (France)|Socialists]] failed to make it to the second round of voting, with far-right [[Marine Le Pen]] and political newcomer [[Emmanuel Macron]] instead facing each other.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2017/5/5/15543294/french-election-macron-le-pen|title=Macron vs. Le Pen: the French presidential election, explained|last=Beauchamp|first=Zack|date=May 5, 2017|website=Vox|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> Macron ended up winning both the presidency, as well as a [[2017 French legislative election|legislative majority]] with his newfound party [[La R\u00e9publique En Marche!]] In 2018\u201319, his leadership was challenged by the [[Populism|populist]] [[Yellow vests movement]], which also rejected traditional parties.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/05/world/europe/yellow-vests-france.html|title=How France's 'Yellow Vests' Differ From Populist Movements Elsewhere|last=Nossiter|first=Adam|date=December 5, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 13, 2020|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==== Italy ====\nThe [[2013 Italian general election]] led to a major change in the country's political landscape, as the traditional center-right and center-left parties were challenged by the new [[Five Star Movement]], a populist party led by comedian [[Beppe Grillo]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Garzia|first=Diego|date=April 16, 2019|title=The Italian election of 2018 and the first populist government of Western Europe|journal=West European Politics|volume=42|issue=3|pages=670\u2013680|doi=10.1080/01402382.2018.1535381|issn=0140-2382}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[2018 Italian general election]], a coalition government was formed between the [[Lega Nord]] and [[Five Star Movement]], becoming the first fully populist government in Western Europe.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n====Russia====\nRussia re-elected [[Vladimir Putin]] as the president in [[2012 Russian presidential election]]. The election was marred by claims of fraud, contributing to the [[2011\u20132013 Russian protests]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/06/world/europe/observers-detail-flaws-in-russian-election.html|title=Observers Detail Fraud in Russian Election Won by Putin|last=Barry|first=Ellen|date=March 5, 2012|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 10, 2020|last2=Schwirtz|first2=Michael|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Under Putin, Russia engaged in a more aggressive foreign policy, with the [[Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation|2014 Annexation of Crimea]] and [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)|intervention in Ukraine]] following the [[2014 Ukrainian revolution]], the [[Russian military intervention in the Syrian Civil War|2015 intervention in the Syrian Civil War]], and [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|interference in the 2016 United States elections]].\n\n====United Kingdom====\n{{See also|Brexit negotiations|Premiership of Boris Johnson|2019 United Kingdom general election}}\nFollowing a [[hung parliament]] in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election]], the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] and [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] formed the first coalition government in the country's history since [[World War II]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/britain-politics-year-idUSLDE7492B020110510|title=TIMELINE-UK coalition government's first year in power|date=May 10, 2011|agency=Reuters|access-date=January 26, 2020}}</ref> A [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|referendum on Scottish independence]] was held on 2014, returning a negative result.\n\nAfter the Conservatives were returned to power with a majority in the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], a [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|referendum]] was called on [[Brexit|leaving the European Union]], which led to the beginning of the process of UK withdrawal from the EU.\n\nIn 2015, the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] elected as its leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]], who was considered the most left-wing leader of the party since [[Michael Foot]] (1980\u201383).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insideover.com/indepths/politics/who-is-jeremy-corbyn.html|title=Who is Jeremy Corbyn: The Most Left-Wing Leader of the Labour Party|website=InsideOver|access-date=January 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]] left the Conservatives with a minority government under [[Theresa May]].\n\nIn 2019, the Conservatives under [[Boris Johnson]] won the largest majority in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] since the [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987 election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/uk/20191214-uk-s-conservatives-win-largest-majority-since-1980s-uk-election-labour-jeremy-corbyn-week-review-brexit|title=The world this week \u2013 Blue Wave: Biggest Conservative win since 1987|date=December 14, 2019|publisher=France 24|access-date=January 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== North America ===\nFollowing pressure from the US President [[Donald Trump]], the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]] (NAFTA) was superseded by the new [[United States\u2013Mexico\u2013Canada Agreement]] (USMCA).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/27/us/politics/us-mexico-nafta-deal.html|title=Trump Reaches Revised Trade Deal With Mexico, Threatening to Leave Out Canada|last=Swanson|first=Ana|date=August 27, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 26, 2020|last2=Rogers|first2=Katie|issn=0362-4331|last3=Rappeport|first3=Alan}}</ref>\n\n====Mexico====\n[[Felipe Calderon|Felipe Calder\u00f3n Hinojosa]] became the 56th [[president of Mexico]] (and the second from the conservative [[National Action Party (Mexico)|National Action Party]]) after a [[Controversies of the 2006 Mexican general election|controversial election in 2006]]. He quickly declared a [[Mexican Drug War|War on Drugs]] that ended up costing about 200,000 lives over the next ten years.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/news/2016/dec/08/mexico-war-on-drugs-cost-achievements-us-billions Mexico's war on drugs: what has it achieved and how is the US involved?] Nina Lakhani & Erubiel Tirado. ''The Guardian'', December 8, 2016</ref> Calderon was also president during the 2007\u20132009 [[Great Recession]]. Mexico was not hit nearly as hard as the United States, and immigration to the United States greatly declined during the last few years of Calderon's presidency.<ref>[https://inequality.stanford.edu/sites/default/files/Immigration_fact_sheet.pdf Immigration and the Great Recession p. 6] Douglas S. Massey, Princeton University, Oct 2012</ref><ref>[https://www.brookings.edu/blog/up-front/2009/11/19/how-the-recessions-affecting-immigration/ How the Recession\u2019s Affecting Immigration] Audrey Singer & Jill H. Wilson, Brookings, November 19, 2009</ref> In addition to the drug war, Calderon emphasized infrastructure development, foreign investment, and health care. Mexico became the country with the eleventh-largest GDP in the world, the seventh-largest automobile manufacturer, the eighth-largest oil exporter, and a major manufacturer of electronics. Mexico signed trade agreements with 46 different countries.<ref>[https://www.thebalance.com/mexico-s-economy-facts-opportunites-challenges-3306351 Mexico's Economy Facts, Opportunities, and Challenges] Kimberly Amadeo, The Balance, November 6, 2019</ref> Calderon's drug war, which cost 47,000 lives during the last two years of his presidency (the balance), became the most important issue during the [[2012 Mexican general election]]. The election was won by the former [[Governor of the State of Mexico]] [[Enrique Pe\u00f1a Nieto]] of the [[Institutional Revolutionary Party]], the political party that had dominated Mexican politics during most of the 20th century.\n\nPe\u00f1a Nieto continued the drug war with no better success than Calderon had had. Low points were the [[2014 Iguala mass kidnapping|September 26, 2014 Ayotzinapa (Iguala) mass kidnapping]] of 43 students enrolled in a teachers\u2019 college in the southern state of Guerrero,<ref>[https://theintercept.com/2015/05/04/how-43-students-disappeared-in-mexico-part-1/ Ghosts of Iguala] Ryan Devereaux, The Intercept, May 4, 2015</ref><ref>[http://media.wix.com/ugd/3a9f6f_e1df5a84680a4a8a969bd45453da1e31.pdf Ayotzinapa Report] Interdisciplinary Group of Independent Experts (GIEI). Retrieved December 8, 2019</ref> and the 2015 prison escape of notorious drug-dealer [[Joaqu\u00edn \"El Chapo\" Guzm\u00e1n]]. Pe\u00f1a Nieto was also personally wrapped up in a corruption scandal involving a US$7&nbsp;million (MXN $100&nbsp;million) house known as ''La Casa Blanca'' (\"The White House\") purchased by his showcase wife, actress [[Ang\u00e9lica Rivera]]. This was just one of many scandals that rocked his administration.<ref>{{citation|title=Estos fueron los esc\u00e1ndalos de Pe\u00f1a Nieto durante su sexenio como presidente|date=November 30, 2018|url=https://laverdadnoticias.com/mexico/Estos-fueron-los-escandalos-de-Pena-Nieto-durante-su-sexenio-como-presidente-20181130-0031.html|website=La Verdad Noticias|trans-title=These were the scandals of Pe\u00f1a Nieto during his six-year term as president|language=es}}</ref> Enrique Pe\u00f1a Nieto and Ang\u00e9lica Rivera were divorced months after he left office.<ref>{{citation|title=El divorcio de Pe\u00f1a Nieto y Ang\u00e9lica Rivera|date=February 10, 2019|url=https://www.milenio.com/opinion/alvaro-cueva/ojo-por-ojo/el-divorcio-de-pena-nieto-y-angelica-rivera|website=Milenio|trans-title=The divorce of Pe\u00f1a Nieto and Ang\u00e9lica Rivera|language=es}}</ref> Pe\u00f1a Nieto encouraged foreign investment, particularly in the automotive industry, and for the first time since President [[Lazaro Cardenas]] nationalized the [[Pemex|oil industry in 1938]], in the energy industry. He also tried to reform the country's educational system.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-21582629 Mexico's Pena Nieto enacts major education reform] BBC World News, February 26, 2013</ref> and began construction of a [[Mexico City Texcoco Airport|new airport]] for Mexico City.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mexico-airport/new-airport-plan-for-mexico-city-eyes-six-runways-sources-idUSKBN0EU1TC20140619 New airport plan for Mexico City eyes six runways: sources] Reuters World News, June 19, 2014</ref> President Pe\u00f1a was elected with by a slim plurality in 2012 with just under 39% of the vote, but by the time he left office in 2018 he had an 18% approval and a 77% disapproval rating, making him one of the least popular presidents in Mexican history.<ref>{{citation|title=#FinDeSexenio: Pe\u00f1a Nieto termina su gobierno reprobado por la mayor\u00eda|date=November 24, 2018|url=https://politica.expansion.mx/presidencia/2018/11/24/findesexenio-pena-nieto-termina-su-gobierno-reprobado-por-la-mayoria|website=Expansion Politica|trans-title=#EndofTerm: Pe\u00f1a Nieto ends his government with failing marks from the majority|language=es}}</ref>\n\n[[Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador]] (commonly called \"AMLO\") was a candidate for president for the third time in the [[2018 Mexican general election]], representing the ''[[Juntos Haremos Historia]]'' (\"Together we will make history\"), coalition. He won in a landslide victory, taking 53% of the vote. His platform called for: democratic rule of law (no more electoral fraud or vote-buying), self-determination in foreign policy, an end to corruption, decentralization of the government, agricultural revitalization, reversal of privatization of the energy sector, economic development (including increased aid for victims of the [[2017 Puebla earthquake]]), increased pensions for the elderly, a reversal of Pe\u00f1a Nieto's educational reforms, and increased public safety by ending the drug war, granting amnesty to minor drug offenders, and reorganizing the police.<ref>{{citation|website=El Universal|url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/ten-proposals-amlos-pre-campaign|title=The ten proposals of AMLOs pre-campaign|date=December 14, 2017}}</ref> Even before his inauguration in December 2018, Lopez Obrador held a referendum on canceling construction of the US$13&nbsp;billion airport in [[Mexico City Texcoco Airport|Texcoco, State of Mexico]] and instead building one at the [[Mexico City Santa Luc\u00eda Airport|Santa Lucia Air Force]] base in [[Zumpango| Zumpango, State of Mexico]]. Nearly 70% of the voters who participated voted in favor of the Santa Lucia site, although it represented only 1% of eligible voters.<ref>{{citation|website=BBC World News|url=https://www.bbc.com/mundo/noticias-america-latina-46015692 |date=October 29, 2018|title=Resultados consulta M\u00e9xico Decide: mayor\u00eda de votantes rechaza construir el nuevo aeropuerto|language=es|trans-title=Results of the Mexico Decide consultation: A majority of voters oppose construction of the new airport}}</ref> Construction of the new airport at the Santa Lucia site began in October 2019 and is scheduled to open in March 2022. Controversy over the airport has shaken investor confidence, and the economy has stagnated or entered a slight recession.<ref name=\"universal\">{{citation|website=El Universal |url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/mexico-revisiting-lopez-obradors-first-year-president|title=Mexico revisiting Lopez Obrador's first year as president}}</ref> On December 27, 2018, AMLO initiated a crackdown on fuel theft by ''[[huachicolero]]s''. This set off gasoline shortages in several states, and the [[Tlahuelilpan pipeline explosion]] of January 18, 2019, killed 137 in the state of Hidalgo.<ref>{{citation|website=Efe English edition|date=January 31, 2019|title=Death toll from Mexico pipeline explosion increase to 119|url=https://www.efe.com/efe/english/world/death-toll-from-mexico-pipeline-explosion-increase-to-119/50000262-3884711}}</ref> AMLO ended the drug war and established a [[National Guard (Mexico)|National Guard]], but violence continues to plague the nation: the government was forced to call off the arrest and extradition of [[Ovidio Guzm\u00e1n L\u00f3pez]], son of notorious drug lord \"El Chapo\" Guzman, after the city of [[Culiacan]], Sinaloa, was laid siege to by members of the [[Sinaloa Cartel]];<ref>{{citation|website=BBC World News|date=October 18, 2019 |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50092641|title=El Chapo: Mexican police free drug lord's son as Culiac\u00e1n battle erupts}}</ref> and three women and six children, all Mexican-American citizens and members of the [[LeBar\u00f3n family massacre|LeBar\u00f3n family]] were killed by presumed drug dealers in [[Sonora]] near the [[Mexico-United States border]] on November 4, 2019.<ref>[https://abc7chicago.com/5672936/ 9 members of American family, including babies, killed in Mexico] ABC7 Eyewitness News, Chicago, November 5, 2019</ref> It was reported that 2019 was the most violent year in Mexican history, with 29,574 homicides and [[femicide]]s registered during the first ten months of the year.<ref name=\"universal\" /> AMLO has run an austere government, cracking down on corruption, reducing government salaries (including his own), and selling off properties seized during drug raids as well as government vehicles, including the presidential plane.<ref name=\"universal\" /> In foreign policy, Mexican-American relations have been strained by the immigration, tariffs, and the failure of the U.S. Congress to ratify the [[United States\u2013Mexico\u2013Canada Agreement]]. President [[Donald Trump]] briefly threatened to label Mexican drug cartels ''terrorist organizations'' and even to send the U.S. military to fight them.<ref>[https://time.com/5741024/mexico-certification-cartels-terrorist-organizations/ Mexico Is Infuriated by Trump's Pledge to Designate Drug Cartels as Terrorist Organizations] ''Time'', November 28, 2019</ref> In another foreign policy move, Mexico granted former Bolivian president [[Evo Morales]] political asylum after the [[2019 Bolivian political crisis|coup d\u2019etat]] in that country.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/evo-morales-asylum-mexico-bolivia-latest-protests-a9199206.html Mexico offers former Bolivia president Evo Morales asylum] The Independent, November 12, 2019</ref> AMLO's approval rating dropped by 10% to 58.7% during the first ten months of 2019.<ref name=\"universal\" />\n\n====United States of America (USA)====\n\n==== Obama Presidency ====\n{{Main|Presidency of Barack Obama}}\nThe most important action of Obama's first 100 days was the passage of the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009|American Recovery and Reinvestment Act]] (ARRA) to address the [[Great Recession]]. After much debate, ARRA was passed by both the House and Senate on February 13, 2009. Originally intended to be a [[bipartisan]] bill, Congressional passage of the bill relied largely on Democratic votes, though three Republican Senators did vote for it.<ref name=\"grchad\">{{cite news|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Politics/2009/0214/obama-wins-his-economic-stimulus-package-but-without-the-bipartisanship-he-sought|title=USA POLITICS Obama wins his economic stimulus package, but without the bipartisanship he sought|last1=Chaddock|first1=Gail Russell|date=February 14, 2009|accessdate=February 19, 2016|work=The Christian Science Monitor}}</ref> The lack of Republican support for the bill, and the inability of Democrats to win that support, foreshadowed the gridlock and partisanship that continued throughout Obama's presidency.<ref name=\"grchad\" /><ref name=\"mgrunstim\">{{cite news|url=http://swampland.time.com/2012/08/23/the-party-of-no-new-details-on-the-gop-plot-to-obstruct-obama/|title=The Party of No: New Details on the GOP Plot to Obstruct Obama|last1=Grunwald|first1=Michael|date=August 23, 2012|accessdate=February 19, 2016|work=Time}}</ref><ref name=\"obamamemos\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2012/01/30/the-obama-memos|title=The Obama Memos|last1=Lizza|first1=Ryan|date=January 30, 2012|accessdate=February 19, 2016|work=The New Yorker}}</ref> The $787&nbsp;billion bill combined tax breaks with spending on infrastructure projects, extension of welfare benefits, and education.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2009/01/27/news/economy/stimulus_spending|title=Stimulus with interest: $1.2 trillion|last=Sahadi|first=Jeanne|date=January 27, 2009|accessdate=April 14, 2012|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2009/02/17/news/economy/obama_stimulus_meas_success/index.htm|title=Stimulus: Now for the hard part|last=Sahadi|first=Jeanne|date=February 17, 2009|accessdate=August 7, 2013|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\n=====Wall Street reform=====\n{{see also|Banking in the United States}}\nRisky practices among the major financial institutions on [[Wall Street]] were widely seen as contributing to the [[subprime mortgage crisis]], the [[financial crisis of 2007\u201308]], and the subsequent [[Great Recession]], so Obama made [[Wall Street reform]] a priority in his first term.<ref name=\"sorkin\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/15/business/15sorkin.html?ref=businessspecial4|title=A Tough Crowd on Wall Street|last1=Sorkin|first1=Andrew Ross|date=September 14, 2009|work=The New York Times|accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref> On July 21, 2010, Obama signed the [[Dodd\u2013Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act]], the largest financial regulatory overhaul since the [[New Deal]].<ref name=\"doddfrank\">{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2010/07/21/news/economy/obama_signs_wall_street_reform_bill/index.htm|title=Obama on new law: 'No more taxpayer bailouts'|last=Censky|first=Annalyn|date=July 21, 2010|accessdate=July 22, 2010|publisher=CNN}}</ref> The act increased regulation and reporting requirements on [[derivative (finance)|derivatives]] (particularly [[credit default swap]]s), and took steps to limit [[systemic risk]]s to the US economy with policies such as higher [[capital requirement]]s, the creation of the [[Orderly Liquidation Authority]] to help wind down large, failing financial institutions, and the creation of the [[Financial Stability Oversight Council]] to monitor systemic risks.<ref name=\"konczal\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/2015/7/21/9004155/dodd-frank-explainer|title=Dodd-Frank turns 5 today \u2013 it's Obama's most underappreciated achievement|last1=Konczal|first1=Mike|date=July 21, 2015|accessdate=December 14, 2015|publisher=Vox}}</ref> Dodd-Frank also established the [[Consumer Financial Protection Bureau]], which was charged with protecting consumers against abusive financial practices.<ref name=\"jcalmes15112015\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/18/us/politics/18warren.html|title=Obama Picks Warren to Set Up Consumer Bureau|last1=Calmes|first1=Jackie|date=September 17, 2010|work=The New York Times|accessdate=November 15, 2015}}</ref> On signing the bill, Obama stated that the bill would \"empower consumers and investors,\" \"bring the shadowy deals that caused the crisis to the light of day,\" and \"put a stop to taxpayer bailouts once and for all.\"<ref name=\"bdennis\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/07/21/AR2010072100512.html|title=Obama signs financial overhaul into law|last1=Dennis|first1=Brady|date=July 22, 2010|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSome liberals were disappointed that the law did not break up the country's largest banks or reinstate the [[Glass-Steagall Act]], while many conservatives criticized the bill as a government overreach that could make the country less competitive.<ref name=\"bdennis\" /> Under the bill, the Federal Reserve and other regulatory agencies were required to propose and implement several new [[rulemaking|regulatory rules]], and battles over these rules continued throughout Obama's presidency.<ref name=\"bintelligence\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/professional/blog/dodd-frank-at-five-years-several-key-rules-remain/|title=Dodd-Frank at five years: Several key rules remain|last1=Dean|first1=Nathan|date=July 21, 2015|accessdate=December 4, 2015|publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref> Obama called for further Wall Street reform after the passage of Dodd-Frank, saying that banks should have a smaller role in the economy and less incentive to make risky trades.<ref name=\"goldfarb1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2014/07/02/president-obama-sounds-ready-to-take-on-the-big-banks/|title=President Obama sounds ready to take on the big banks|last1=Goldfarb|first1=Zachary|date=July 2, 2014|accessdate=August 2, 2016|work=The Washington Post}}</ref> Obama also signed the [[Credit CARD Act of 2009]], which created new rules for credit card companies.<ref name=\"cardact\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/30884011/ns/business-personal_finance/t/obama-signs-new-rules-credit-cards-law/|title=Obama signs new rules for credit cards into law|date=May 22, 2009|accessdate=November 14, 2015|publisher=NBC|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\n=====Technology=====\nThe introduction of new [[5G wireless technology]] caused major public discussion about possible security risks and safety risks. Many experts said 5G would require new methods to insure security of data.<ref>[https://www.forbes.com/sites/gilpress/2019/12/03/141-cybersecurity-predictions-for-2020/ 141 Cybersecurity Predictions For 2020] By Gil Press.</ref> The US Congress passed legislation regarding security concerns about 5G networks.<ref>[https://fcw.com/articles/2019/11/18/house-5g-supply-chain-bills.aspx House panel moves 5G protection bills], By Mark Rockwell, November 18, 2019.</ref> The federal government prohibited the use of [[Huawei]] equipment for 5G networks due security concerns, and encouraged its allies to also do so as well. The US government imposed strict controls on US companies as to their ability to do business with Huawei, thus disrupting sales of Huawei phones overseas.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/business-50515426?intlink_from_url=https://www.bbc.com/news/topics/crdnpmp7nllt/5g&link_location=live-reporting-story Huawei: Trouble overseas but boom time in China] By Danny Vincent, BBC News, Hong Kong, November 26, 2019.</ref> Chinese vendors and the Chinese government have denied these claims.\n\nThe development of the technology has elicited various responses and concerns that 5G radiation could have adverse health effects.<ref name=\"5G item 1\">{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2019/05/22/health-concerns-5g-cellphones-cancer/|title=Health Concerns May Slow Rollout of Super-Fast 5G Mobile Networks, Analyst Warns|website=Fortune|access-date=June 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190612151157/http://fortune.com/2019/05/22/health-concerns-5g-cellphones-cancer/|archive-date=June 12, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> An editorial in the scientific magazine [[Scientific American]] emphasized that complete scientific research regarding its effects have not been conducted and that there could be health risks.<ref>Moskowitz, Joel M., ''[https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/observations/we-have-no-reason-to-believe-5g-is-safe/ We Have No Reason to Believe 5G Is Safe] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191023141403/https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/observations/we-have-no-reason-to-believe-5g-is-safe/ |date=October 23, 2019 }}'', Scientific American, October 12, 2019</ref> ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'' characterized fears that the technology could cause cancer, infertility, autism, Alzheimer's, and mysterious bird deaths as \"conspiracy theory\".<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/5g-health-risks-concerns|title=Bird-killing, cancer-causing 5G is the internet's new favourite conspiracy theory|last=Weiss|first=Sabrina|date=June 12, 2019|journal=Wired UK|access-date=June 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190619143539/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/5g-health-risks-concerns|archive-date=June 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The US FCC and nearly all other regulators claim 5G radiation will have no significant health effects.\n\nHuawei submitted a petition in the US Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit against the FCC's decision to prohibit rural U.S. network providers from using equipment from the China-based vendor due to national security concerns, asking that the recent FCC order be overturned.<ref>[https://www.sdxcentral.com/articles/news/huawei-slams-fcc-with-legal-appeal/2019/12/ Huawei Slams FCC With Legal Appeal], by Dan Meyer | Editor-in-Chief, December 5, 2019, sdxcentral.com.</ref>\n\n=====Trump Presidency=====\n[[Donald Trump]] was elected the president in 2016, losing the popular vote to [[Hillary Clinton]], but winning through the [[United States Electoral College|electoral college]].\n\nAn [[impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump]] was initiated by House Speaker [[Nancy Pelosi]] on September 24, 2019, after a [[Whistleblower protection in the United States|whistleblower]] alleged that President [[Donald Trump]] had [[abuse of power|abused the power]] of the presidency by withholding both military aid and a [[White House]] meeting as [[Trump\u2013Ukraine scandal|a means of pressuring]] newly-elected President of Ukraine [[Volodymyr Zelensky]] to publicly announce investigations which would be damaging to Trump's political rival [[Joe Biden]] in the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 election]].\n\nIn October, three full Congressional committees (Intelligence, Oversight, and Foreign Affairs) deposed witnesses including Ukraine ambassador [[William B. Taylor Jr.|Bill Taylor]],<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite news |first=Stefan |last=Becket |first2=Arden |last2=Farhi |first3=Kathryn |last3=Watson |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/bill-taylor-opening-statement-read-the-full-text-of-the-top-us-diplomats-statement-to-congress/ |title=Top diplomat tells lawmakers Ukraine aid was directly tied to investigations |date=October 23, 2019 |publisher=[[CBS News]] |url-status=live |access-date=October 24, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191108195849/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/bill-taylor-opening-statement-read-the-full-text-of-the-top-us-diplomats-statement-to-congress/ |archivedate=November 8, 2019}}</ref> [[Laura Cooper]] (the top [[Pentagon building|Pentagon]] official overseeing Ukraine-related U.S. policy),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/trump-impeachment-inquiry/laura-cooper-pentagon-official-overseeing-ukraine-testifies-impeachment-inquiry-n1070586 |title=Key Pentagon official finally testifies after Republicans storm impeachment hearing |date=October 23, 2019 |publisher=[[NBC News]]|url-status=live |first=Alex |last=Moe |first2=Rebecca |last2=Shabad |access-date=October 24, 2019}}</ref> former White House official [[Fiona Hill (presidential advisor)|Fiona Hill]],and at least six additional White House officials.<ref name=\"whistleblower\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/09/26/us/politics/whistle-blower-complaint.html |title=Document: Read the Whistle-Blower Complaint |date=September 26, 2019 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=October 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/10/12/768935251/trump-ukraine-and-the-path-to-the-impeachment-inquiry-a-timeline |title=Trump, Ukraine and the Path to the Impeachment Inquiry: A Timeline |last=Keith |first=Tamara |date=October 12, 2019 |publisher=NPR |url-status=live |access-date=October 15, 2019}}</ref> Witnesses testified that Trump wanted Zelensky to publicly announce investigations into the Bidens and Burisma<ref name=\":27\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/07/world/europe/ukraine-trump-zelensky.html|title=Ukraine's Zelensky Bowed to Trump's Demands, Until Luck Spared Him|last=Kramer|first=Andrew E.|date=November 7, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 13, 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":28\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/24/world/europe/ukraine-war-impeachment.html|title=The Cost of Trump's Aid Freeze in the Trenches of Ukraine's War|last=Kramer|first=Andrew E.|date=October 24, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 13, 2019|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and that Ukraine was pressured to release evidence that its government had interfered in the 2016 U.S. election.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shane |first1=Scott |title=How a Fringe Theory About Ukraine Took Root in the White House |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/03/us/politics/trump-ukraine-conspiracy.html |accessdate=November 14, 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=October 3, 2019}}</ref> On October 8, in a letter from Counsel [[Pat Cipollone]] to Speaker Pelosi, the White House officially responded that it would not cooperate with the investigation due to concerns including that there had not yet been a vote of the full House and that interviews of witnesses were being conducted behind closed doors.<ref name=\"bbc Oct 9\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-49981806 |title=White House 'will not co-operate with impeachment inquiry' |date=October 9, 2019|access-date=October 9, 2019 |work=[[BBC News]]}}</ref><ref name=\"blake-aaron\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/10/09/white-houses-scathing-legally-questionable-impeachment-letter-annotated/ |title=The White House's scathing and legally dubious impeachment letter, annotated |last1=Blake |first1=Aaron |date=October 9, 2019 |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=October 11, 2019|url-access=limited}}</ref> On October 17, White House acting chief of staff [[Mick Mulvaney]] said, in response to a reporter's allegation of ''[[quid pro quo]]'': \"We do that all the time with foreign policy. Get over it.\" He walked back his comments later in the day, asserting that there had been \"absolutely no ''quid pro quo''\" and that Trump had withheld military aid to Ukraine over concerns of the country's corruption.\n\nOn October 31, the House voted 232\u2013196 to establish procedures for public hearings,<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{Cite news |website=BBC News |date=October 31, 2019 |accessdate=October 31, 2019 |title=Trump impeachment: House votes to formalise inquiry |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-50246324}}</ref> which started on November 13.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/2019/10/19/bribery-is-right-there-constitution-trump-could-be-impeached-that/|title=Perspective {{!}} 'Bribery' is right there in the Constitution. Trump could be impeached for that.|last=Melber|first=Ari|website=The Washington Post|access-date=November 23, 2019}}</ref><ref name=Budryk>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/470165-schiff-trump-could-potentially-be-impeached-for-bribery|title=Schiff: Trump could be impeached for bribery|first=Zack|last=Budryk|date=November 12, 2019|website=The Hill}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Taylor |first=Jessica |date=November 12, 2019 |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/11/12/778380499/rep-adam-schiff-trumps-potentially-impeachable-offenses-include-bribery|title=Rep. Adam Schiff: Trump's Potentially Impeachable Offenses Include Bribery|publisher=NPR}}</ref> Private and public congressional testimony by twelve government witnesses in November 2019 presented a significant body of evidence indicating Trump demanded a ''quid pro quo'' of political favors in exchange for official action.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theweek.com/speedreads/879653/sondland-confirms-quid-pro-quo-points-finger-directly-trump|title=Sondland confirms 'quid pro quo,' points finger directly at Trump|date=November 20, 2019|website=The Week}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/468199-vindman-testified-he-believed-trump-demanded-quid-pro-quo-from-ukrainian-aid|title=Vindman testified he believed Trump demanded quid pro quo for Ukrainian aid: report|first=Zack|last=Budryk|date=October 30, 2019|website=The Hill}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://time.com/5720446/william-taylor-ukraine-quid-pro-quo-transcript/|title=Diplomat William Taylor Had 'Clear Understanding' of Ukraine Quid Pro Quo: Transcript|website=Time}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theweek.com/speedreads/880137/trumps-no-quid-pro-quo-defense-takes-another-hit|title=Trump's 'no quid pro quo' defense takes yet another hit|date=November 21, 2019|website=The Week}}</ref> The [[House Judiciary Committee]] hosted hearings on December 4 with more scheduled for December 9. On December 5, Pelosi announced that the House Judiciary Committee would begin drafting articles of impeachment.<ref name=charges>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/05/us/politics/pelosi-impeachment.html|title=Pelosi Says House Will Begin Drafting Impeachment Charges Against Trump|last=Fandos|first=Nicholas|date=December 5, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=December 5, 2019|last2=Stolberg|first2=Sheryl Gay|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Once these are decided on, they are expected to be presented to the Senate for [[Impeachment in the United States#Senate: Trial|a trial and vote]].\n\n===South America===\nThe [[Conservative wave]] brought many right-wing politicians to power across the continent. In [[Argentina]] the [[Peronism|Peronist]] president [[Cristina Fern\u00e1ndez de Kirchner]] was replaced by the conservative-liberal [[Mauricio Macri]] in 2015; in Brazil, [[Dilma Rousseff]]'s [[Impeachment of Dilma Rousseff|impeachment]] resulted in the rise of her Vice President [[Michel Temer]] to power in 2016; in Chile the conservative [[Sebasti\u00e1n Pi\u00f1era]] followed the socialist [[Michelle Bachelet]] in 2017; and in 2018 the far-right congressman [[Jair Bolsonaro]] became 38th President of Brazil.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dw.com/en/is-there-a-right-wing-surge-in-south-america/a-45874897|title=Is there a right-wing surge in South America?|last1=Ospina|first1=Jose|date=October 28, 2018|accessdate=December 10, 2018|agency=DW}}</ref>\n\n====Bolivia====\n{{main|2019 Bolivian protests}}\n\nStarting on October 21, 2019, protests and marches have been occurring in [[Bolivia]] in response to claims of [[electoral fraud]] in the [[2019 Bolivian general election|2019 general election]] of October 20, 2019 and, subsequently, to [[Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez]] declaring herself the acting president of Bolivia. The claims of fraud were made after the suspension of the preliminary vote count, in which incumbent [[Evo Morales]] was not leading by a large enough margin (10%) to avoid a [[Runoff (election)|runoff]], and the subsequent publication of the official count, in which Morales won by over 10%. Some international observers have expressed concern over these developments. While many of the demonstrations have been peaceful, there have been numerous acts of violence. Senior members of the [[Movement for Socialism (Bolivia)|Movement for Socialism]] (MAS) and their families were victims of attacks, including house burnings.<ref name=\"nyt201119\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/20/world/americas/bolivia-deaths-sentaka.html|title=Five Killed as Political Violence Keeps Grip on Bolivia|website=The New York Times|date=November 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/nov/11/raab-attacks-corbyn-over-support-for-ousted-bolivian-leader-evo-morales|title=Raab criticises Corbyn over support for Bolivian leader|website=The Guardian|date=November 11, 2019|access-date=November 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191113021956/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/nov/11/raab-attacks-corbyn-over-support-for-ousted-bolivian-leader-evo-morales|archive-date=November 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efe.com/efe/english/world/bolivian-governor-s-house-set-on-fire-as-anti-morales-protests-continue/50000262-4107214|title=Bolivian governor's house set on fire as anti-Morales protests continue|website=efe.com|access-date=November 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111183525/https://www.efe.com/efe/english/world/bolivian-governor-s-house-set-on-fire-as-anti-morales-protests-continue/50000262-4107214|archive-date=November 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/11/07/bolivian-mayor-beaten-dragged-through-streets/|title=Bolivian mayor beaten, dragged through streets|last=Fitz-Gibbon|first=Jorge|date=November 7, 2019|website=New York Post|access-date=November 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111183523/https://nypost.com/2019/11/07/bolivian-mayor-beaten-dragged-through-streets/|archive-date=November 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMorales denied the allegations and invited foreign governments to [[audit]] the electoral processes, promising to hold a runoff if any fraud was found. Subsequently, an audit team from the [[Organization of American States]], with access provided by Bolivian authorities, worked to verify the integrity and reliability of the results. Their preliminary report questioned the integrity of the election results and recommended another \"electoral process\".<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oas.org/documents/eng/press/Electoral-Integrity-Analysis-Bolivia2019.pdf|title=Electoral Integrity Analysis: General Elections in the Purinational State of Bolivia|date=October 20, 2019|website=OAS|url-status=live|access-date=November 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMorales announced the government would hold another election; however, the police and army demanded [[Evo Morales government resignation|Morales's resignation on November 10]], which he offered shortly thereafter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/10/world/americas/bolivia-election-evo-morales.html|title=Military Calls on President to Step Down After Election Dispute in Bolivia|first1=Anatoly|last1=Kurmanaev|first2=M\u00f3nica|last2=Machicao|first3=Ernesto|last3=Londo\u00f1o|date=November 10, 2019|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=November 10, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110192802/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/10/world/americas/bolivia-election-evo-morales.html|archive-date=November 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Following his resignation and the resignation of other senior MAS politicians, some citing fears for the safety of their families, Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez declared herself interim president and formed an [[interim government]]. Protests have continued, and several human right organizations expressed concerns over the excess use of force by the new government.<ref name=\"ft2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/8549edc6-0a72-11ea-bb52-34c8d9dc6d84|title=Bolivia's leader accused of stoking divisions after Morales' exit|website=Financial Times|date=November 19, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt201119\" />\n\n==== Brazil ====\n{{See also|2013 Brazil protests|Impeachment of Dilma Rousseff|2018 Brazilian general election}}\nPresident [[Dilma Rousseff]] was impeached and removed from office in 2016 following revelations from [[Operation Car Wash]], a corruption investigation. Former president [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva]] was also imprisoned. In 2018, far-right populist [[Jair Bolsonaro]] won the presidential election, partly owing to the fallout from the corruption scandal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2019/08/anti-corruption-crusades-paved-way-bolsonaro/596449/|title=The Dirty Problems With Operation Car Wash|last=Bevins|first=Vincent|date=August 21, 2019|website=The Atlantic|access-date=January 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Chile====\nThe [[2019 Chilean protests]] are ongoing civil protests throughout Chile in response to a raise in the [[Santiago Metro]]'s subway fare, the increased [[cost of living]], [[privatisation]] and [[Economic inequality|inequality]] prevalent in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-50119649|website=BBC News|date=October 21, 2019|title=Chile protests: Cost of living protests take deadly toll|access-date=October 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021010614/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-50119649|archive-date=October 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"aljazeera\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/chile-protests-prompted-unrest-191022160029869.html|title=Chile protests: What prompted the unrest?|author=Charis McGowan|date=October 22, 2019|publisher=Al Jazeera|access-date=October 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191026072339/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/chile-protests-prompted-unrest-191022160029869.html|archive-date=October 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/10/22/americas/chile-protests-inequality-curfew-intl-hnk/index.html|title=Chile extends curfew again as violent unrest paralyzes one of Latin America's biggest cities|publisher=CNN|author=Helen Regan|author2=Christopher Ulloa|date=October 22, 2019|access-date=October 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191025024135/https://edition.cnn.com/2019/10/22/americas/chile-protests-inequality-curfew-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=October 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Chile protests: More than one million bring Santiago to a halt|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/chile-protests-million-bring-santiago-halt-191025223542333.html|author=Naomi Larsson|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=October 26, 2019}}</ref> The protests began in Chile's capital, [[Santiago, Chile|Santiago]], as a coordinated [[fare evasion]] campaign by secondary school students which led to spontaneous{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}} takeovers of the city's main train stations and open confrontations with the [[Carabineros de Chile]] (''the national militarized police force''). On October 18, the situation escalated as organized bands of protesters began vandalizing city's infrastructure; seizing, vandalizing, and burning down many stations of the [[Santiago Metro]] network and disabling them with extensive infrastructure damage, and for a time causing the cessation the network in its entirety. All in all 81 stations have sustained major damage, incluidng 17 burned down.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bnamericas.com/es/noticias/metro-de-santiago-80-estaciones-danadas-o-destruidas-durante-protestas|title=BNamericas \u2013 Metro de Santiago: 80 estaciones da\u00f1adas o d...|website=BNamericas.com|access-date=October 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191025183130/https://www.bnamericas.com/es/noticias/metro-de-santiago-80-estaciones-danadas-o-destruidas-durante-protestas|archive-date=October 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radioagricultura.cl/nacional/2019/10/23/usuarios-reportan-nuevo-incendio-en-la-estacion-de-metro-plaza-de-maipu.html|title=Usuarios reportan nuevo incendio en la Estaci\u00f3n de Metro Plaza de Maip\u00fa|website=radioagricultura.cl|access-date=October 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191026043927/https://www.radioagricultura.cl/nacional/2019/10/23/usuarios-reportan-nuevo-incendio-en-la-estacion-de-metro-plaza-de-maipu.html|archive-date=October 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On the same day, [[President of Chile]] [[Sebasti\u00e1n Pi\u00f1era]] announced a [[state of emergency]], authorizing the deployment of [[Chilean Army]] forces across the main regions to enforce order and prevent the destruction of public property, and invoked before the courts the ''Ley de Seguridad del Estado'' (\"State Security Law\") against dozens of detainees. A [[curfew]] was declared on October 19 in the Greater Santiago area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biobiochile.cl/noticias/nacional/region-metropolitana/2019/10/19/general-iturriaga-anuncia-toque-de-queda-en-santiago-para-afrontar-graves-disturbios.shtml|title=General Iturriaga decreta toque de queda en Santiago para afrontar graves disturbios|date=October 19, 2019|website=BioBioChile \u2013 La Red de Prensa M\u00e1s Grande de Chile|access-date=October 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191019225339/https://www.biobiochile.cl/noticias/nacional/region-metropolitana/2019/10/19/general-iturriaga-anuncia-toque-de-queda-en-santiago-para-afrontar-graves-disturbios.shtml|archive-date=October 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eldesconcierto.cl/2019/10/19/decretan-inedito-toque-de-queda-en-santiago-tras-fracaso-del-gobierno-en-contener-ola-de-protestas/|title=Decretan in\u00e9dito toque de queda en Santiago tras fracaso del gobierno en contener ola de protestas|date=n.d.|website=El Desconcierto|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191020002030/https://www.eldesconcierto.cl/2019/10/19/decretan-inedito-toque-de-queda-en-santiago-tras-fracaso-del-gobierno-en-contener-ola-de-protestas/|archive-date=October 20, 2019|access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref> Protests and riots have expanded to other cities, including [[Concepci\u00f3n, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n]], [[San Antonio, Chile|San Antonio]], and [[Valpara\u00edso]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biobiochile.cl/noticias/nacional/region-de-valparaiso/2019/10/19/protestas-y-destruccion-se-registran-en-san-antonio-y-valparaiso-tras-caso-en-el-gran-santiago.shtml|title=Protestas y destrucci\u00f3n se registran en San Antonio y Valpara\u00edso tras caos en el Gran Santiago|date=October 19, 2019|website=BioBioChile \u2013 La Red de Prensa M\u00e1s Grande de Chile|access-date=October 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191019223252/https://www.biobiochile.cl/noticias/nacional/region-de-valparaiso/2019/10/19/protestas-y-destruccion-se-registran-en-san-antonio-y-valparaiso-tras-caso-en-el-gran-santiago.shtml|archive-date=October 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The state of emergency was extended to the [[Concepci\u00f3n Province, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n Province]], all [[Valpara\u00edso Region]] (except [[Easter Island]] and [[Juan Fern\u00e1ndez Archipelago]]) and the cities of [[Antofagasta]], [[Coquimbo]], [[Iquique]], [[La Serena, Chile|La Serena]], [[Rancagua]], [[Valdivia]], [[Osorno, Chile|Osorno]], and [[Puerto Montt]]. The protests have been considered the \"worst civil unrest\" having occurred in Chile since the end of [[Augusto Pinochet]]'s [[Military dictatorship of Chile (1973\u20131990)|military dictatorship]] due to the scale of damage to public infrastructure, the number of protesters, and the measures taken by the government.<ref name=\"Bloom\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmostrador.cl/dia/2019/10/19/bloomberg-santiago-despierta-en-la-devastacion/|title=Bloomberg: \"Santiago despierta en la devastaci\u00f3n\"|access-date=October 20, 2019|date=October 19, 2019|website=El Mostrador|language=es|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191020042309/https://www.elmostrador.cl/dia/2019/10/19/bloomberg-santiago-despierta-en-la-devastacion/|archive-date=October 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On October 25, over a million people took to the streets throughout Chile to protest against President Pi\u00f1era, demanding his resignation.<ref name=\"ElPais\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.elpais.com.uy/mundo/personas-protestan-santiago-chile-medio-estallido-social.html|title=Al menos un mill\u00f3n de personas protestan en Santiago contra Pi\u00f1era y la desigualdad social|last=ElPais|website=Diario EL PAIS Uruguay|language=spanish|access-date=October 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191026031030/https://www.elpais.com.uy/mundo/personas-protestan-santiago-chile-medio-estallido-social.html|archive-date=October 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"nlaj2610\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/chile-protests-million-bring-santiago-halt-191025223542333.html|title=Chile protests: More than one million bring Santiago to a halt|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=October 26, 2019|author=Naoim Larsson|access-date=October 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191026165551/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/chile-protests-million-bring-santiago-halt-191025223542333.html|archive-date=October 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> As of October 26, 19 people have died, nearly 2,500 have been injured, and 2,840 have been arrested.<ref name=\"nlaj2610\" /><ref name=\"deathtoll\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/chile-news-santiago-at-least-18-dead-and-thousands-arrested-in-chile-protests-2019-10-24/|publisher=CBS News|date=October 24, 2019|title=At least 18 dead and thousands arrested in Chile protests|access-date=October 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191025191352/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/chile-news-santiago-at-least-18-dead-and-thousands-arrested-in-chile-protests-2019-10-24/|archive-date=October 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On October 28, President Pi\u00f1era changed eight ministries of [[Cabinet of Chile|his cabinet]] in response to the unrest, dismissing his Interior Minister [[Andr\u00e9s Chadwick]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/oct/28/chile-president-sebastian-pinera-replaces-cabinet-protests|title=Chile: protesters light bonfires and clash with police despite cabinet reshuffle|last=Franklin|first=Jonathan|date=October 28, 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=October 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191029011220/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/oct/28/chile-president-sebastian-pinera-replaces-cabinet-protests|archive-date=October 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc071119\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-50315106|title=Chile protests: Concerns grow over human rights abuses|website=BBC|author=Katy Watson|date=November 7, 2019}}</ref> On November 15, most{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}} of the political parties represented in the National Congress signed an agreement to call a [[2020 Chilean national referendum|national referendum]] in April 2020 regarding the creation of a new constitution.\n\n==== Colombia ====\nIn 2016, the world's longest running war<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/mar/15/colombia-end-in-sight-longest-running-conflict|title=Colombia: is the end in sight to the world's longest war?|last=Vulliamy|first=Ed|date=March 15, 2015|work=The Observer|access-date=January 21, 2020|issn=0029-7712}}</ref> was borught to an end when the [[Government of Colombia]] and the rebel group [[Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia]] signed a peace deal officially ending the [[Colombian conflict]].\n\n====Venezuela====\n{{main|2019 Venezuelan presidential crisis}}\nA crisis concerning who is the legitimate [[President of Venezuela]] has been underway since January 10, 2019, with the [[Responses to the 2019 Venezuelan presidential crisis|nation and the world divided in support]] for [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] or [[Juan Guaid\u00f3]].\n\nGuaid\u00f3 has been [[Responses to the 2019 Venezuelan presidential crisis#RecognitionMG|recognized as the acting President of Venezuela]] by 54 countries. Internationally, support has followed traditional geopolitical lines, with allies China, Cuba, Iran, Russia, Syria, and Turkey supporting Maduro; and the US, Canada, and most of Western Europe supporting Guaid\u00f3 as acting President.<ref name=\"FamiliarGeo\">{{cite news |url= https://www.apnews.com/6b7fa7cc566f486cb974362168f1d90d |title= Venezuela crisis: Familiar geopolitical sides take shape |author= Vasilyeva, Nataliya |date = January 24, 2019 | accessdate= February 25, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> As of late 2019, efforts led by Guaid\u00f3 to create a transitional government have been described as unsuccessful by various analysts and media networks, with Maduro still controlling Venezuela's state functions.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/venezuela-thousands-take-to-the-streets-of-caracas-for-rival-protests/a-51280074|title=Venezuela: Thousands take to the streets of Caracas for rival protests {{!}} DW {{!}} November 16, 2019|date=n.d.|publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]]|url-status=live|access-date=December 4, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"1d\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/11/venezuela-rival-rallies-held-guaido-calls-daily-protests-191117060107276.html|title=Venezuela: Rival rallies held as Guaido calls for daily protests|date=n.d.|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]|url-status=live|access-date=December 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/09/25/764390079/in-venezuela-juan-guaid-s-campaign-faces-new-difficulties|title=In Venezuela, Juan Guaid\u00f3's Campaign Faces New Difficulties|date=n.d.|publisher=[[NPR]]|url-status=live|access-date=December 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2019/aug/15/citgo-venezuela-fight-between-nicolas-maduro-juan-/|title=American-based Citgo targeted in fight for control of Venezuela|date=n.d.|website=[[The Washington Times]]|url-status=live|access-date=December 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/venezuela-corruption-guiado-maduro-coup-abrams-1.5191288|title=Months after failing to oust Maduro, Guaido has few cards left to play \u2013 and not long to play them|date=June 29, 2019|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|url-status=live|access-date=December 4, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"2b\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-venezuela-politics-analysis-idUSKBN1Y72BB|title='Missed his moment': opposition corruption scandal undermines Venezuela's Guaido|date=December 3, 2019|agency=[[Reuters]]|access-date=December 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-12-03/guaido-weakens-as-venezuela-legislature-probes-corruption-claim|title=Guaido Weakened as Venezuela Legislature Probes Corruption Claim|date=December 3, 2019|website=[[bloomberg.com|Bloomberg]]|url-status=live|access-date=December 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://panampost.com/orlando-avendano/2019/10/07/juan-guaidos-straitjacket/|title=Juan Guaido's Straitjacket|date=October 7, 2019|website=[[PanAm Post]]|url-status=live|access-date=December 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Global issues==\n\n===Climate change===\nIn December 2019, the [[World Meteorological Organization]] released its annual climate report revealing that climate impacts are worsening.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/04/climate/climate-change-acceleration.html Climate Change Is Accelerating, Bringing World \u2018Dangerously Close\u2019 to Irreversible Change], By Henry Fountain, December 4, 2019, ''The New York Times''.</ref> They found the global sea temperatures are rising as well as land temperatures worldwide. 2019 is the last year in a decade that is the warmest on record.<ref>[https://www.iflscience.com/environment/2019-ends-warmest-decade-on-record-state-of-the-global-climate-report-warns/ 2019 Ends Warmest Decade On Record, State Of The Global Climate Report Warns], iflscience.com</ref> The 2010s were the hottest decade in recorded history, according to NASA and the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA)]]. 2016 was the hottest year and 2019 was the second hottest.<ref>[https://www.nbcnews.com/science/environment/past-decade-was-warmest-ever-recorded-nasa-finds-n1116321?cid=sm_npd_nn_fb_ma The last decade was the warmest ever recorded, NASA and NOAA find] By Denise Chow, NBC News, January 15, 2020</ref>\n\nGlobal carbon emissions hit a record high in 2019, even though the rate of increase slowed somewhat, according to a report from [[Global Carbon Project]].<ref>[https://phys.org/news/2019-12-global-carbon-emissions-growth-high.html Global carbon emissions growth slows, but hits record high], December 3, 2019, Stanford University via phys.org.</ref>\n\n===World banking===\nConcerns increased about the [[European Debt Crisis]] as both Greece and Italy continued to have high levels of public debt. This caused concerned about stability of the Euro. In December 2019, the EU announced that banking ministers from EU member nations had failed to reach agreement over proposed banking reforms and systemic change.<ref name=\"ft.com\"/><ref name=\"brecorder.com\"/> The EU was concerned about high rates of debt in France, Italy and Spain.<ref name=\"euractiv.com\"/> Italy objected to proposed new debt bailout rules that were proposed to be added to the European Stability Mechanism.<ref>[https://www.southeusummit.com/europe/italy/italy-takes-issue-with-the-esm/ Italy Takes Issue With the ESM Proposals to reform the eurozone\u2019s bailout fund are being hotly contested in Italy amid concerns that the ESM could set the country back on rebuilding finances after the sovereign debt crisis], by Lana Guggenheim.</ref>\n\nIn the first half of 2019, global debt levels reached a record high of $250&nbsp;trillion, led by the US and China.<ref name=\"cnbc debt\">[https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/15/global-debt-surged-to-a-record-250-trillion-in-the-first-half-of-2019-led-by-the-us-and-china.html Global debt surged to a record $250 trillion in the first half of 2019, led by the US and China], November 15, 2019, Spriha Srivastava.</ref> The IMF warned about corporate debt.<ref name=\"cnbc debt\"/> The European Central Bank raised concerns as well.<ref>[http://thecorner.eu/news-europe/45-6-of-eurozones-corporate-debt-is-bbb/82875/ 45.6% Of Eurozone\u2019s Corporate Debt Is BBB], POSTED BY: THE CORNER November 23, 2019.</ref>\n\n===World trade===\n====United States-China trade dispute====\nA trade dispute between the US and China caused economic concerns worldwide. In December 2019, various US officials said a trade deal was likely before a proposed round of new tariffs took effect on December 15, 2019.<ref name=\"fox china\">[https://www.foxbusiness.com/markets/us-china-trade-deal-tariff-increase US, China trade deal expected before tariff increase: Report]. Trump's 'off the cuff' comments not a sign talks are at an impasse. Fox News Channel</ref> US tariffs had a negative effect on China's economy, which slowed to growth of 6%.<ref name=\"fox china\"/>\n\n====United States\u2013Mexico\u2013Canada Agreement====\nThe [[United States\u2013Mexico\u2013Canada Agreement]]<ref name=finaltext>{{cite web|url=https://ustr.gov/trade-agreements/free-trade-agreements/united-states-mexico-canada-agreement/agreement-between|title=Agreement between the United States of America, the United Mexican States, and Canada Text|accessdate=November 30, 2018|work=Government of the United States}}</ref> is a signed but not ratified [[free trade agreement]] between Canada, Mexico, and the United States. The Agreement is the result of a 2017\u20132018 renegotiation of the [[North American Free Trade Agreement|North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA)]] by its member states.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4500068/nafta-2018-agreement-finalized/ |title=NAFTA deal reached: Canada, U.S., Mexico reach trade agreement under new name |last1=Dangerfield |first1=Katie |work=[[Global News]] |date=August 30, 2018 |accessdate=October 1, 2018}}</ref> Negotiations \"focused largely on auto exports, steel and aluminum tariffs, and the dairy, egg, and poultry markets.\" One provision \"prevents any party from passing laws that restrict the cross-border flow of data\".<ref name=\"walrus\">{{cite news |title=Are You Afraid of Google? BlackBerry Cofounder Jim Balsillie Says You Should Be |url=https://thewalrus.ca/are-you-afraid-of-google-blackberry-cofounder-jim-balsillie-says-you-should-be/ |work=The Walrus |date=April 10, 2019}}</ref> Compared to NAFTA, USMCA increases environmental and labour regulations, and incentivizes more domestic production of cars and trucks.<ref>{{cite web|title=Labour, environment standards key to getting USMCA through: Canadian ambassador|url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/news-pmn/canada-news-pmn/canada-has-high-level-of-confidence-usmca-will-be-ratified-in-u-s-morneau|last=National Post|work=National Post|date=December 3, 2018|accessdate=May 18, 2019}}|url=</ref> The agreement also provides updated intellectual property protections, gives the United States more access to Canada's dairy market, imposes a quota for Canadian and Mexican automotive production, and increases the duty free limit for Canadians who buy U.S. goods online from $20 to $150.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.smart-biggar.ca/en/articles_detail.cfm?news_id=1463|title=USMCA v NAFTA: What's changed and what it means for IP in Canada {{!}} Smart & Biggar/Fetherstonhaugh|website=www.smart-biggar.ca|access-date=January 27, 2019}}</ref> <!--{{TOC limit|3}}-->\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Current events|Modern history|Politics}}\n\n===Overviews===\n* 21st century\n* 2010s\n* [[2019 in politics and government]]\n\n===Specific situations===\n* [[Brexit negotiations in 2019]]\n\n===Category===\n{{Category see also|2010s in politics|2010s protests|2010s by country|2010s events|21st-century elections|Category:Contemporary history by country}}\n{{Project-inline|Politics}}\u2014Wikiproject Politics\n\n===Related timelines===\n{{cat see also|2000s by country|2010s by country|2020 by country}}\n{{Div col}}\n* [[2010s]]\n* [[2010s in United Kingdom political history]]\n*[[2010s in United States political history]]\n*[[2020s in political history]]\n{{End div col}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2010s in politics| ]]\n[[Category:2010s|politics]]\n[[Category:2010s in international relations]]\n[[Category:Politics overviews by decade]]\n[[Category:21st century in politics]]\n", "name_user": "Fayenatic london", "label": "safe", "comment": "Copying fromCategory:Politics overviews by decadetoCategory:2010 in politicsusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2010s_in_political_history"}
{"title_page": "2010s in Syria political history", "text_new": "'''2010s in Syria political history''' refers to events during the 2010s in political history of [[Syria]]. \n\n{{Year nav topic5|2019|Syria}}\n\n==General history==\n\n==History by government ministry==\n\n==History of conflict (Early to mid-2010s)==\n{{main|Syrian Civil War}}\n\n===Syrian Civil War===\nThe [[Syrian Civil War]] is an ongoing multi-sided [[civil war]] in Syria fought between the [[Ba'ath Party (Syrian-dominated faction)|Ba'athist]] [[Syrian Arab Republic]] led by Syrian President [[Bashar al-Assad]], along with domestic and foreign allies, and various domestic and foreign forces opposing both the Syrian government and each other in varying combinations.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/05/syria-civil-war-explained-160505084119966.html |title=Syria's civil war explained from the beginning |publisher=Al Jazeera |access-date=29 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170430014912/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/05/syria-civil-war-explained-160505084119966.html |archive-date=30 April 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> The war is currently the second [[Casualties of the Syrian Civil War|deadliest of the 21st century]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/list/8-deadliest-wars-of-the-21st-century|title=8 Deadliest Wars of the 21st Century|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2019-07-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190526191400/https://www.britannica.com/list/8-deadliest-wars-of-the-21st-century|archive-date=26 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe unrest in Syria, part of a wider wave of the 2011 [[Arab Spring]] protests, grew out of discontent with the Syrian government and escalated to an armed conflict after [[Civil uprising phase of the Syrian Civil War|protests calling for Assad's removal]] were violently suppressed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-26116868 |title=Syria: The story of the conflict |date=11 March 2016 |work=BBC News |access-date=21 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622052951/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-26116868 |archive-date=22 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/26/world/middleeast/26syria.html|title=Syrian Troops Open Fire on Protestors in Several Cities|date=25 March 2011|work=The New York Times|access-date=23 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621011638/https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/26/world/middleeast/26syria.html|archive-date=21 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The war, which began on 15 March 2011 with major unrest in [[Damascus]] and [[Aleppo]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-12749674|title=Mid-East unrest: Syrian protests in Damascus and Aleppo|last=|first=|date=2011-03-15|newspaper=BBC News|access-date=2013-03-15|work=|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180721134738/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-12749674|archive-date=21 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> is being fought by several factions: the [[Syrian Armed Forces]] and its international allies, a loose alliance of mostly [[Sunni]] [[Syrian Opposition|opposition]] rebel groups (including the [[Free Syrian Army]]), [[Salafi jihadist]] groups (including [[al-Nusra Front]]), the mixed Kurdish-Arab [[Syrian Democratic Forces]] (SDF), and the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL), with a number of [[Foreign involvement in the Syrian Civil War|countries in the region and beyond being either directly involved]] or providing support to one or another faction (Iran, Russia, Turkey, the United States, as well as others).\n\nIran, Russia, and [[Hezbollah]] support the Syrian Arab Republic and the Syrian Armed Forces militarily, with Russia conducting [[Russian military intervention in the Syrian Civil War|airstrikes and other military operations]] since September 2015. The [[Combined Joint Task Force \u2013 Operation Inherent Resolve|U.S.-led international coalition]], established in 2014 with the declared purpose of countering ISIL, has [[American-led intervention in the Syrian Civil War|conducted airstrikes]] primarily against ISIL as well as some [[List of United States attacks on the Syrian government during the Syrian Civil War|against government and pro-government targets]]. They have also deployed special forces and artillery units to engage ISIL on the ground. Since 2015, the U.S. has supported the [[Democratic Federation of Northern Syria]] and its armed wing, the SDF, materially, financially, and logistically. Turkey has been [[Turkish occupation of northern Syria|directly involved in operations]] against the Syrian government since August 2016, not only participating in airstrikes against ISIL alongside the U.S.-led coalition, but also actively supporting the [[Syrian opposition]] and [[Turkish occupation of northern Syria|occupying large swaths of northwestern Syria]] while engaging in significant ground combat with ISIL, the SDF, and the Syrian government. Between 2011 and 2017, fighting from the Syrian Civil War [[Spillover of the Syrian Civil War|spilled over]] into [[Lebanon]] as opponents and supporters of the Syrian government traveled to Lebanon to fight and attack each other on Lebanese soil, with ISIL and Al-Nusra also engaging the Lebanese Army. Furthermore, while officially neutral, [[Israel]] has [[Israeli\u2013Syrian ceasefire line incidents during the Syrian Civil War|conducted airstrikes]] against Hezbollah and Iranian forces, whose presence in southwestern Syria it views as a threat.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-syria/u-s-russian-ceasefire-takes-effect-in-southwest-syria-idUSKBN19U08D|title=U.S.-Russian ceasefire deal holding in southwest Syria|date=9 July 2017|work=Reuters|access-date=2017-11-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921113246/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-syria/u-s-russian-ceasefire-takes-effect-in-southwest-syria-idUSKBN19U08D|archive-date=21 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nInternational organizations have criticized virtually all sides involved, including the Ba'athist Syrian government, ISIL, opposition rebel groups, Russia,<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/sep/25/russia-accused-war-crimes-syria-un-security-council-aleppo|title=Russia accused of war crimes in Syria at UN security council session|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=18 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401192517/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/sep/25/russia-accused-war-crimes-syria-un-security-council-aleppo|archive-date=1 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and the U.S.-led coalition<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/06/05/middleeast/us-led-coalition-raqqa-war-crimes-intl/index.html |title=US-led strikes on Raqqa may amount to war crimes, Amnesty says |first1=Angela |last1=Dewan |first2=Hillary |last2=McGann |date=5 June 2018 |publisher=CNN |access-date=5 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180605205903/https://www.cnn.com/2018/06/05/middleeast/us-led-coalition-raqqa-war-crimes-intl/index.html |archive-date=5 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> of severe human rights violations and [[List of massacres during the Syrian Civil War|massacres]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/15/world/middleeast/syria-bashar-al-assad-evidence.html |title=As Atrocities Mount in Syria, Justice Seems Out of Reach |first1=Anne Barnard, Ben |last1=Hubbard |first2=Ian |last2=Fisher |date=15 April 2017 |work=The New York Times |access-date=18 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517192038/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/15/world/middleeast/syria-bashar-al-assad-evidence.html |archive-date=17 May 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> The conflict has caused a major [[Refugees of the Syrian Civil War|refugee crisis]]. Over the course of the war, a number of peace initiatives have been launched, including the [[Geneva peace talks on Syria (2017)|March 2017 Geneva peace talks on Syria]] led by the [[United Nations]], but fighting continues.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Lundgren |first=Magnus |year=2016 |title=Mediation in Syria: Initiatives, strategies, and obstacles, 2011\u20132016 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/303312425_Mediation_in_Syria_Initiatives_strategies_and_obstacles_2011-2016 |journal=Contemporary Security Policy |volume=37 |pages=283\u2013298 |access-date=20 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202000757/https://www.researchgate.net/publication/303312425_Mediation_in_Syria_Initiatives_strategies_and_obstacles_2011-2016 |archive-date=2 February 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==History of conflict (Late 2010s to present)==\n===Turkish offensive, 2019===\n\n{{main|2019 Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria}}\n\nThe 2019 Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria, code-named by Turkey as Operation Peace Spring ({{lang-tr|Bar\u0131\u015f P\u0131nar\u0131 Harek\u00e2t\u0131}}), is a cross-border military operation conducted by the [[Turkish Armed Forces]] (TAF) and the [[Syrian National Army]] (SNA) against the [[Syrian Democratic Forces]] (SDF) and later the [[Syrian Arab Army]] (SAA) in [[Rojava|northeastern Syria]].\n\nOn 6 October 2019, the [[Trump administration]] ordered American troops to withdraw from northeastern Syria, where the United States [[American-led intervention in the Syrian Civil War|had been supporting]] its Kurdish allies.<ref name=withdraw>{{cite news |title=Trump makes way for Turkey operation against Kurds in Syria |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-49956698?intlink_from_url=https://www.bbc.com/news/topics/cp7r8vgl2y7t/kurds&link_location=live-reporting-story |accessdate=10 October 2019 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=7 October 2019}}</ref> The military operation began on 9 October 2019 when the [[Turkish Air Force]] launched airstrikes on [[Syria\u2013Turkey border|border]] towns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/oct/09/turkey-launches-military-operation-in-northern-syria-erdogan|title=Turkey launches military operation in northern Syria|work=The Guardian|first=Bethan|last=McKernan|date=9 October 2019}}</ref> The conflict resulted in the displacement of over 300,000 people and has caused the death of more than 70 civilians in Syria and 20 civilians in Turkey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bursadabugun.com/haber/teroristlerin-saldirilarinda-20-sivil-sehit-oldu-170-kisi-yaralandi-1191643.html|title=Ter\u00f6ristlerin sald\u0131r\u0131lar\u0131nda 20 sivil \u015fehit oldu, 170 ki\u015fi yaraland\u0131|website=Bursada Bug\u00fcn}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/syria/kurdish-politician-executed-by-turkish-backed-fighters-in-syria-1.7970427|title=Kurdish Politician Among Nine Civilians Executed by Turkish-backed Fighters in Syria|date=13 October 2019|newspaper=[[Haaretz]]}}</ref> Human rights violations have also been reported. [[Amnesty International]] stated that it had gathered evidence of [[war crimes]] and other violations committed by Turkish and Turkey-backed Syrian forces who are said to \"have displayed a shameful disregard for civilian life, carrying out serious violations and war crimes, including summary killings and unlawful attacks that have killed and injured civilians\".\n\nAccording to the Turkish President [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]], the operation is intended to expel the SDF\u2014viewed as a terrorist organization by Turkey due to its ties with the [[Kurdistan Workers Party]] (PKK), but considered an ally against [[ISIL]] by the [[Combined Joint Task Force \u2013 Operation Inherent Resolve|United States and its allies]]\u2014from the border region as well as to create a 30&nbsp;km-deep (20&nbsp;mi) \"safe zone\" in Northern Syria where some of the 3.6 million [[Syrian refugees in Turkey]] would resettle.<ref name=\"aj-turkey-begins\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/turkey-begins-ground-offensive-northeastern-syria-191009212025006.html |title=Turkey begins ground offensive in northeastern Syria |date=9 October 2019 |work=[[Al Jazeera]] |access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref> As the proposed settlement zone is heavily Kurdish demographically, this intention has been criticized as an attempt to force drastic demographic change,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2019/09/turkey-syria-united-states-erdogan-plans-for-east-euphrates.html|title=Erdogan's Syria plan: Resettling the Syrian refugees or ousting Kurds from their land?|first=Cengiz|last=Candar|date=30 September 2019|website=Al-Monitor}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/e40cb754-e456-11e9-b112-9624ec9edc59|title=Syria is witnessing a violent demographic re-engineering|website=[[Financial Times]]}}</ref><ref name=reuters_demographics>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security-turkey-refugees-graphi-idUSKBN1WN28J|title=Turkey's plan to settle refugees in northeast Syria alarms allies|date=8 October 2019|via=reuters.com|newspaper=Reuters}}</ref> a criticism denied by Turkey by saying that it only intended to \"correct\" the demographics that Turkish officials stated were changed by the SDF.<ref name=reuters_demographics/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ibtimes.com/turkey-begins-military-operation-against-kurds-after-trump-pulls-troops-northern-2842727|title=Turkey Begins Military Operation Against Kurds After Trump Pulls Troops In Northern Syria|first=Wesley|last=Dockery|date=9 October 2019|website=[[International Business Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1565401/middle-east|title=After US green light, Turkey prepares military operation in Syria|date=7 October 2019|website=Arab News}}</ref>\n\nThe Turkish operation received mixed responses by the international community. Including condemnations<ref>{{cite news |title=India slams Turkey for its 'unilateral military offensive' in northeast Syria {{!}} India News \u2013 Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/india-slams-turkey-for-its-unilateral-military-offensive-in-northeast-syria/articleshow/71520852.cms |accessdate=10 October 2019 |work=The Times of India |language=en}}</ref> as well as support for the operation for the settlement of refugees in Northern Syria.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/539756-pm-imran-telephones-erdogan-assures-full-support-to-turkey|title=PM Imran telephones Erdogan, assures full support to Turkey|date=11 October 2019|website=The News International}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/operation-peace-spring/turkic-council-supports-turkey-s-anti-terror-operation/1614575|title=Turkic Council supports Turkey's anti-terror operation|website=aa.com.tr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnnturk.com/turkiye/turk-konseyi-liderler-zirvesinden-ortak-baris-pinari-bildirisi|title=T\u00fcrk Konseyi Liderler Zirvesi'nden ortak 'Bar\u0131\u015f P\u0131nar\u0131' bildirisi|website=CNN T\u00fcrk}}</ref> While originally acknowledging Turkey's \"right to defend itself\", on 15 October, Russia hardened its position against the operation and deployed troops.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/3123143a-ef41-11e9-ad1e-4367d8281195|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/15/world/middleeast/kurds-syria-turkey.html|title=In Syria, Russia Is Pleased to Fill an American Void|first1=Ben|last1=Hubbard|first2=Anton|last2=Troianovski|first3=Carlotta|last3=Gall|first4=Patrick|last4=Kingsley|date=15 October 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> Ten European nations and Canada [[Reactions to the 2019 Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria|imposed an arms embargo on Turkey]], while the U.S. imposed sanctions on Turkish ministries and senior government officials in response to the offensive in Syria.<ref name=ColumbusSanctions>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-50050264|title=Turkey-Syria offensive: US sanctions Turkish ministries|date=15 October 2019|agency=BBC}}</ref> Likewise, Trump's sudden pullout of US forces in Syria was also criticized by journalists as a \"serious betrayal to the Kurds\" as well as a \"catastrophic blow to US credibility as an ally and Washington's standing on the world stage\", one journalist stating that \"this is one of the worst US foreign policy disasters since the [[Iraq War]]\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/us-betrayal-of-kurds-destroys-the-wests-credibility-for-years-to-come-11835611|title=US betrayal of Kurds destroys the West's credibility for years to come | website=Sky News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/trump-syria-move-delivers-blow-credibility-worldwide-191008232132422.html|title=Trump's Syria move 'delivers a blow to US credibility worldwide'| website=Al Jazeera}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/18/opinion/trump-kurds-syria.html|title=Trump's Gut, and the Gutting of American Credibility| website=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/meet-the-press/trump-s-decision-syria-has-already-turned-foreign-policy-disaster-n1065691|title=Trump's decision on Syria has already turned into a foreign policy disaster| website=NBC News}}</ref> On November 19, the Defense Department inspector general released a report finding that the American withdrawal and subsequent Turkish incursion allowed ISIL to \"reconstitute capabilities and resources within Syria and strengthen its ability to plan attacks abroad\".<ref name=\"O\u2019brien\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/11/19/trump-syria-isis-071499|title=Trump's pullout from Syria allowed ISIS to gain strength, intel agency reports|first=Connor|last=O\u2019brien|website=POLITICO}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Syrian government]] initially criticized the Kurdish forces for the Turkish offensive, for their separatism and not reconciling with the government, while at the same time also condemning the foreign invasion in Syrian territory.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-10/11/c_138462068.htm |title=Syria blames Kurdish forces for Turkish military offensive |date=11 October 2019|work=Xinhua Net |access-date=11 October 2019}}</ref> However, a few days later, the SDF reached an agreement with the Syrian government, in which it would allow the [[Syrian Army]] to enter the SDF-held towns of [[Manbij]] and [[Koban\u00ee]] in an attempt to defend the towns from the Turkish offensive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2019/10/13/Syrian-army-to-enter-SDF-held-Kobani-Manbij-Monitor.html|title=Syrian army to enter SDF-held Kobani, Manbij: Monitor|website=english.alarabiya.net|language=en|access-date=13 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security-towns-report-idUSKBN1WS0K0|title=Report: Syrian army to enter SDF-held Kobani, Manbij|date=13 October 2019|work=Reuters|access-date=13 October 2019|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"armyinvolved\">{{Cite web|url=https://thedefensepost.com/2019/10/13/syria-government-russia-kobani-manbij-sdf/|title=Syrian government forces set to enter Kobani and Manbij after SDF deal|date=13 October 2019|website=The Defense Post|language=en-US|access-date=13 October 2019}}</ref> Shortly thereafter, Syrian state broadcaster [[SANA]] announced that Syrian Army troops had started to deploy to the country's north.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/world/mena/syrian-troops-sent-north-to-confront-turkey-over-incursion-says-state-media-1.922875|title=Syrian troops sent north to 'confront' Turkey over incursion, says state media|website=The National|language=en|access-date=13 October 2019}}</ref> Turkey and the SNA launched an offensive to capture Manbij on the same day.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.haber.com/suriye-milli-ordusu-munbic-operasyonu-basladi-103685/|title=Suriye Milli Ordusu: M\u00fcnbi\u00e7 Operasyonu Ba\u015flad\u0131|date=14 October 2019|website=Haber.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 October 2019, U.S. Vice President [[Mike Pence]] announced that the U.S. and Turkey agreed on a deal in which Turkey will agree to a ceasefire in Syria for 5 days in return for a complete withdrawal by the SDF from a safe zone south of the Syria-Turkey border.<ref name=\":1c\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/us-and-turkey-reach-agreement-temporarily-suspend-military-operation-syria|title=US and Turkey reach agreement to suspend military operation in Syria|website=Middle East Eye|date=17 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":2c\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-50091305|title=Turkey to suspend Syria offensive, US says|website=BBC|date=17 October 2019}}</ref> On 22 October 2019, Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] and Turkish President [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] [[Second Northern Syria Buffer Zone|reached a deal]] to extend the ceasefire by 150 additional hours for SDF to move 30 kilometers away from the border area as well as from [[Tal Rifaat]] and [[Manbij]]. The terms of the deal also included joint Russian\u2013Turkish patrols 10 kilometers into Syria from the border except in the city of [[Qamishli]]. The new ceasefire started at 12pm local time on 23 October.<ref name=\"auto16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/article236512698.html|title=The Latest: Pence says 5-day cease-fire in Syria has held\n|date=22 October 2019|website=Miami Herald}}</ref><ref name=\"auto17\">{{Cite web|url=https://thedefensepost.com/2019/10/22/russia-turkey-syria-mou/|title=FULL TEXT: Memorandum of Understanding between Turkey and Russia on northern Syria|date=22 October 2019|website=The Defense Post}}</ref>\n\n==Changes to conflict due to Turkish incursion of October 2019==\n=== Changes in the local areas ===\nIn October 2019, in response to the Turkish offensive, Russia arranged for negotiations between the Syrian government in Damascus and the Kurdish-led forces.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Foy |first1=Henry |title=Russia calls Turkey's invasion of north Syria 'unacceptable' |url=https://www.ft.com/content/3123143a-ef41-11e9-ad1e-4367d8281195 |website=Financial Times}}</ref><ref name=ko-il-rftv/> [[Mazloum Abdi]], the Syrian Kurdish commander-in-chief, announced that they are ready to partner with [[Vladimir Putin]] (Russia) and [[Bashar al-Assad]] (Syria), stating that \"We know that we would have to make painful compromises with Moscow and Bashar al-Assad if we go down the road of working with them. But if we have to choose between compromises and the genocide of our people, we will surely choose life for our people.\"<ref name=\"abma-if-we\"/> The details of the agreement is unknown, but there are reports that suggest that the SDF will be incorporated into the [[Syrian Armed Forces]] and that northeastern Syria will come under direct rule of the Syrian government in Damascus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sanchez |first1=Raf |title=Assad troops enter north-east Syria after Russia-backed deal with Kurds |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/10/14/assad-troops-enter-northeast-syria-russia-backed-deal-kurds/ |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=14 October 2019}}</ref> According to Syrian Kurdish officials, the deal allows Syrian government forces to take over security in some border areas, but their own administration would maintain control of local institutions.<ref name=wapo-ssgse/>\n\nThe prospects for Kurdish autonomy in the region is severely diminished, because the Kurds were exposed to the Turkish-led offensive by the US withdrawal and the Russia-backed Syrian government forces under Assad\u2014whose commonality is enmity towards Turkey and Sunni rebel militias\u2014regained their foothold in northeast Syria after the Kurds had to seek their help.<ref name=\"dvcopt\">{{cite web |last1=Dominic Evans |first1=Dominic |last2=Coskun |first2=Orhan |last3=Perry |first3=Tom |title=Power shift: Who gains in the battle for Syria's northeast? |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security-turkey-usa-power-analy/power-shift-who-gains-in-the-battle-for-syrias-northeast-idUSKBN1WU2K8 |website=Reuters |date=16 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Seligman |first1=Lara |title=How the Iran Hawks Botched Trump's Syria Withdrawal |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/10/30/iran-hawks-botched-trump-syria-policy-james-jeffrey-turkey/ |website=Foreign Policy |date=30 October 2019}}</ref> In regards to the United States and the situation, Mazloum Abdi stated that \"We are disappointed and frustrated by the current crisis. Our people are under attack, and their safety is our paramount concern. Two questions remain: How can we best protect our people? And is the United States still our ally?\"<ref name=\"abma-if-we\">{{cite web |last1=Abdi |first1=Mazloum |title=If We Have to Choose Between Compromise and Genocide, We Will Choose Our People |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/10/13/kurds-assad-syria-russia-putin-turkey-genocide/ |website=Foreign Policy |date=13 October 2019}}</ref> A deep sense of betrayal by their once American allies has come to be felt among the Syrian Kurdish populace.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Evans |first1=Margaret |title=Turkey 'outsourcing war crimes' to armed groups, Amnesty says after Kurdish politician's murder |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/syria-turkey-1.5328109 |website=CBC |date=20 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Perry |first1=Tom |last2=Francis |first2=Ellen |title=For Syrian Kurds, a leader's killing deepens sense of U.S. betrayal |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security-kurds-future/for-syrian-kurds-a-leaders-killing-deepens-sense-of-us-betrayal-idUSKBN1X11HZ |website=Reuters |language=en |date=22 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hubbard |first1=Ben |last2=Kirkpatrick |first2=David D. |title=Kurds' Sense of Betrayal Compounded by Empowerment of Unsavory Rivals |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/18/world/middleeast/kurds-sense-of-betrayal-compounded-by-empowerment-of-unsavory-rivals.html |website=The New York Times |date=18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs announced by Russia's Ministry of Defense on 15 October, Russian forces have started to patrol the region along the line of contact between Turkish and Syrian forces,<ref name=ko-il-rftv>{{cite web |last1=Kottasov\u00e1 |first1=Ivana |last2=Ilyushina |first2=Mary |title=Russians fill the void left by US troops in Syria |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/10/15/middleeast/turkey-syria-russian-troops-intl/index.html |website=CNN |date=15 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=wapo-ssgse/> indicating that Russia is filling the security vacuum from the sudden US withdrawal.<ref name=wapo-ssgse>{{cite web | author1= Fahim, Kareem | author2=Dadouch, Sarah | author3= Englund, Will |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/syria-says-government-soldiers-enter-manbij-after-us-troops-withdraw/2019/10/15/d494405a-eeb8-11e9-bb7e-d2026ee0c199_story.html | title=Russia patrolling between Turkish and Syrian forces after U.S. troops withdraw| date =15 October 2019 | website=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mortazavi |first1=Negar |title=How Russia is filling the gap left by Trump's withdrawal of US troops in Syria |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/trump-syria-kurds-russia-putin-assad-a9157656.html |website=The Independent |date=16 October 2019}}</ref> Video footage shows Russian soldiers and journalists touring a base that the US left behind.<ref name=wapo-ssgse/><ref name=ol-ram>{{cite news |last1=Oliphant |first1=Roland |title=Russia assumes mantle of supreme power broker in Middle East as US retreats from Syria |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/10/15/russia-assumes-mantle-supreme-power-broker-middle-east-us-retreats/ |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=15 October 2019}}</ref> Alexander Lavrentiev, Russia's special envoy on Syria, warned that the Turkish offensive into Syria is unacceptable and stated that Russia is seeking to prevent conflict between Turkish and Syrian troops.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sevastopulo |first1=Demetri |last2=Williams |first2=Aime |last3=Pitel |first3=Laura |last4=Foy |first4=Henry |title=US delegation to press Turkey for Syrian ceasefire |url=https://www.ft.com/content/3123143a-ef41-11e9-ad1e-4367d8281195 |website=Financial Times |date=16 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn response to a speech by Assad, the Syrian Democratic Council said it was ready to have positive discussions with the Assad government. They said their focus would shift to stopping the Turkish invasion.<ref> [https://www.rudaw.net/english/middleeast/syria/021120192 Syrian Democratic Council : We are ready to start negotiating with Damascus], 02-11-2019, Lawk Ghafuri, rudaw.net. </ref>\n\n===International reactions to Turkish incursion of October 2019===\nSeveral US lawmakers have criticized the abandonment of their Kurdish allies, remarking that it undermines US credibility as an ally while benefiting Russia, Iran, and the Syrian regime of Assad.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Olorunnipa |first1=Toluse |last2=Kim |first2=Seung Min |title=Republicans deliver rare rebuke of Trump, slamming his Syria withdrawal decision |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/mcconnell-joins-other-republicans-in-rebuking-trumps-syria-withdrawal/2019/10/07/aef0d11e-e914-11e9-9306-47cb0324fd44_story.html |website=Washington Post |date=8 October 2019}}</ref> Meanwhile, several commentators in Moscow have stated that the situation is not in the immediate Russian interests, as the Turkish intervention in Syria clashes with Russia's backing of the Syrian government in the region, but it may provide opportunities for Russia as mediator as the US withdraws from Syria.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sherwin |first1=Emily |title=Turkey offensive in Syria forces Russia into a balancing act |url=https://www.dw.com/en/turkey-offensive-in-syria-forces-russia-into-a-balancing-act/a-50828950 |website=Deutsche Welle |date=14 October 2019 }}</ref> Commentators have remarked that, since the US withdrawal, Russia has cemented its status as the key power broker in the Middle East.<ref name=ol-ram/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Rosenberg |first1=Steve |title=Putin: From pariah to Middle East power broker |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-50068498 |website=BBC |date=17 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Pitarakis |first1=Lefteris |last2=Mroue |first2=Bassem |title=Russia Seeks to Cement its Role as a Power Broker in Syria |url=https://time.com/5701729/russia-troops-syria-turkey-conflict/ |website=Time |language=en |date=16 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nDue to the situation in Syria, there are signs of a schism between Turkey and other [[NATO]] members, in which NATO is seen as effectively \"powerless\" to manage the situation and the Turkish government is aware that NATO does not hold much leverage.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stolton |first1=Samuel |title=Turkey's relationship with NATO tested over Syria operation |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/turkey-relationship-nato-tested-syria-operation-191013190857028.html |website=Aljazeera | date=14 October 2019}}</ref> Furthermore, US President Trump, as well as US military and diplomatic officials, has cited the NATO membership of Turkey as a key reason that the United States can not be involved in the conflict between the Turkish and Syrian Kurdish forces.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wolfgang |first1=Ben |last2=Glenn |first2=Mike |title=Turkey's NATO status complicates U.S. response to Erdogan's Syria incursion |url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2019/oct/16/turkey-nato-status-complicates-response-erdogan-sy/ |website=The Washington Times |date=16 October 2019}}</ref> Meanwhile, due to Turkey's strategic position between Europe and the Middle East, the NATO alliance members are in a situation where they have limited themselves to relatively muted criticism.<ref>{{cite web |title=Esper chides NATO ally Turkey for \"heading in the wrong direction\" with Russia in Syria |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/turkey-syria-wrong-direction-russia-mark-esper-says-us-nato-ally-donald-trump-lauds-ceasefire-2019-10-24/ |website=CBS News |date=24 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe U.S. is reviewing the potential withdrawal of its [[Nuclear weapons of the United States|nuclear weapons]] from [[Incirlik airbase]] under NATO's [[nuclear sharing]] as a result of the Turkish offensive per [[The New York Times|NYT]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/amid-rising-tensions-us-said-considering-plan-to-remove-nukes-from-turkish-base/|title=US said considering plan to remove nukes from Turkish base near Syrian border|first=T. O. I.|last=staff|website=timesofisrael.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/u-s-turkey-tensions-fears-future-nuclear-weapons-syria-donald-trump-erdogan-1465331|title=U.S.-Turkey tensions raise fears over future of nuclear weapons near Syria|first=David|last=Brennan|date=15 October 2019|website=Newsweek}}</ref> Republican senator Lindsay Graham<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2019/10/turkey-and-nato-troubled-relationship/599890/|title=Why is Turkey in NATO Anyway?|agency=The Atlantic}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/lindsey-graham-warns-turkey-nato-suspension-sanctions-if-kurds-attacked-2019-10|title=Lindsey Graham says Congress will call for Turkey to be suspended from NATO and hit it with sanctions if it attacks Kurds|agency=Business Insider|date=7 October 2019}}</ref> and Democratic representative [[Eric Swalwell]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/465847-democratic-lawmaker-expelling-turkey-from-nato-should-be-on-the-table|title=Democratic lawmaker: Expelling Turkey from NATO 'should be on the table'|agency=The Hill|date=15 October 2019}}</ref> have called for possibly suspending Turkey's membership in NATO.\n===Agreement to Northern Buffer Zone===\n{{main|Second Northern Syria Buffer Zone}} \n\nRussia and Turkey made an agreement via the [[Sochi Agreement of 2019]] to set up a [[Second Northern Syria Buffer Zone]]. Syrian President Assad expressed full support for the deal, as various terms of the agreement also applied to the Syrian government.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-50152235|title=Russia deploys troops to Turkey-Syria border|date=2019-10-23|access-date=2019-10-24|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref> [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/oct/22/turkey-and-russia-agree-deal-over-buffer-zone-in-northern-syria Turkey and Russia agree on deal over buffer zone in northern Syria]. Erdo\u011fan hails agreement with Putin in which Kurdish fighters will be moved from border area. guardian.com. </ref> \n\nThe agreement reportedly included the following terms:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/turkeys-erdogan-meets-with-putin-in-russia-to-discuss-syrian-operation/2019/10/22/764abcea-f43f-11e9-b2d2-1f37c9d82dbb_story.html|title=Russia and Turkey reach deal to push Kurdish forces out of zone in northern Syria|last=Fahim|first=Kareem|last2=DeYoung|date=|website=Washington Post|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/german-defense-minister-proposes-security-zone-for-syria/2019/10/22/19af90b8-f49f-11e9-b2d2-1f37c9d82dbb_story.html|title=Russia, Turkey seal power in northeast Syria with new accord|last=Fraser|first=Suzan|last2=AP|first2=Vladimir Isachenkov {{!}}|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-50152235|title=Russia deploys troops to Turkey-Syria border|date=2019-10-23|access-date=2019-10-24|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/russia-syria-map-troops-deal-turkey-1467252|title=Russia shows off new Syria map, sends troops to border after its deal with Turkey|last=EDT|first=Tom O'Connor On 10/23/19 at 11:49 AM|date=2019-10-23|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ragipsoylu/status/1186692319703130119|title=LATEST \u2014 Here is the complete text of Turkish, Russian agreement on Northern Syria, that pushed YPG 30km from Turkish, Syria borderpic.twitter.com/jwiOurbfa3|last=Soylu|first=Rag\u0131p|date=2019-10-22|website=@ragipsoylu|language=en|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref><ref>[https://lobelog.com/the-sochi-agreement-and-its-implications/ The Sochi Agreement And Its Implications] OCTOBER 25, 2019.</ref>\n\n* A buffer zone would be established in Northern Syria. The zone would be around '''{{Convert|30|km|mi|abbr=}}''' deep,{{Efn|Starting from the [[Syrian-Turkish border]] and going south into Syria|name=|group=}} stretching from [[Euphrates River]] to [[Tall Abyad]] and from [[Ras al-Ayn]] to the Iraq-Syria border, but excluding the town of [[Qamishli]], the Kurds' ''de facto'' capital.{{Efn|See the \"External links\" section in the article [[Second Northern Syria Buffer Zone]], for a link to an article containing an explanatory map of the buffer zone.|name=|group=}}\n* The buffer zone would be controlled jointly by the [[Syrian Army]] and [[Russian Military Police]].\n* All [[YPG]] forces, which constitute the majority of the SDF, must withdraw from the buffer zone entirely, along with their weapons, within 150 hours from the announcement of the deal. Their withdrawal would be overseen by Russian Military Police and the Syrian Border Guards, which would enter the zone at noon on 23 October.\n* The YPG would also withdraw from the cities of [[Manbij]] and [[Tell Rifaat]].{{Efn|Both of these cities are further to the south and not covered by the depth of the buffer zone, but are nonetheless explicitly mentioned in the agreement.|name=|group=}}\n* Following the YPG withdrawal, joint Russian-Turkish ground patrols would be held in the buffer zone area, but only within '''{{Convert|10|km|mi|abbr=}}''' from the border and not including Qamishli.{{Efn|No joint patrols will be held in the remaining part of the buffer zone.|name=|group=}}{{Efn|Later, the Turkish President announced that the patrols would only be held to a depth of 7km, as opposed to 10. No reason was given for this change.|name=|group=}}\n* Turkey would retain sole control of the areas it had captured during its offensive between the towns of [[Tell Abyad]] and [[Ras al-Ayn]].\n* The [[Syrian Government]] would construct and man 15 border posts on the [[Turkish-Syrian border]].\n* The parties would launch a joint effort to resettle [[Syrian refugee]]s in a \"safe and voluntary manner\". \n* The parties would agree to \"preserve the political unity and territorial integrity of Syria\" as well as protect the \"national security of Turkey\".\n* The parties would agree to reaffirm the importance of the [[Adana Agreement]]. Russia will facilitate the implementation of the Adana Agreement.\n===Reactions===\nVarious parties reacted to this new agreement, as follows. \n\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of United Nations.svg}} [[United Nations]] - On 1 November 2019 the UN Secretary-General met with President Erdogan of Turkey to discuss Turkey's proposal to relocate a large number of Syrian Refugees in Turkey to the Safe Zone. Mr. Guterres informed the Turkish President that the UNHCR will immediately form a team to study the proposal and engage in discussions with Turkish authorities, in line with its mandate.<ref name=\"un.org\">https://www.un.org/sg/en/content/sg/readout/2019-11-01/readout-of-the-secretary-general%E2%80%99s-meeting-he-mr-recep-tayyip-erdogan-president-of-turkey</ref><ref>https://news.un.org/en/story/2019/11/1050451</ref> The Secretary-General greenlighted the proposal but told the Turkish President that the relocations should be \"voluntary, safe and dignified\".<ref name=\"un.org\"/>\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Syrian Democratic Forces.svg}} [[Syrian Democratic Forces]] - The SDF stated that they consider themselves as \"Syrian and a part of Syria\", adding that they will agree to work with the Syrian Government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/10/23/772557773/kurdish-reaction-to-turkey-russia-deal-to-patrol-northern-syria|title=Kurdish Reaction To Turkey-Russia Deal To Patrol Northern Syria|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref> The SDF officially announced their support for the deal on October 27.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://syrianobserver.com/EN/news/53885/sdf-agrees-to-sochi-deal-for-northern-syria.html|title=SDF Agrees to Sochi Deal for Northern Syria|date=2019-10-28|website=The Syrian Observer|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://ekurd.net/syrian-kurds-say-pulling-2019-10-28|title=Syrian Kurds say pulling out from entire length of Turkey border|last=Staff|first=Editorial|date=2019-10-28|website=Kurd Net - Ekurd.net Daily News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Syria}} - Syrian President [[Bashar al-Assad]] thanked the Russian President for his role in the negotiation of the deal and expressed his full support for it. At the same time, he raised concerns about Turkish interference in Syrian affairs and dubbed Turkish President Erdogan a \"thief\".<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/turkey-russia-agree-clear-kurdish-fighters-control-syria-turkey-border-n1070141|title=Turkey, Russia agree to clear Kurdish fighters and control the Syria-Turkey border|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref>\n*{{Flag|Turkey}} - Turkish President [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] threatened to forcefully \"clear terrorists\" from the Syrian-Turkish border should the deal fail. He further reiterated his threat to let the Syrian refugees residing in Turkey at that point to freely emigrate into Europe, if Turkey does not receive \"support\" in its plan for the relocation of 1 to 2 million refugees within the buffer zone in what the Turkish President dubbed the \"first stage\" of their return.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/middle-east/erdogan-says-will-clear-terrorists-syria-border-if-sochi-deal-fails|title=Erdogan Says Will 'Clear Terrorists' From Syria Border if Sochi Deal Fails|website=Voice of America|language=en|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Iran}} - Iran's foreign ministry called the agreement \"a positive step\" and stated that it \"backed any move to restore stability in the region\".<ref name=\":2\" />\n* {{Flag|United States}} - US President [[Donald Trump]] praised the deal that he viewed as allowing \"someone else [to] fight over this long bloodstained land\", following which he ordered the lifting of the sanctions that he had placed on Turkey nine days prior as a reaction to the start of Turkey's offensive.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-50157439|title=Trump lifts sanctions on Turkey over Syria assault|date=2019-10-23|access-date=2019-10-24|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n*{{Flag|Germany}} - German Chancellor [[Angela Merkel]] proposed that the buffer zone be enforced through an international force. Turkish Foreign Minister [[Mevl\u00fct \u00c7avu\u015fo\u011flu]] rejected the plan, dubbing it \"unrealistic\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/turkey-rejects-german-security-zone-plan-unrealistic-191026141506342.html|title=Turkey rejects German security zone plan as 'unrealistic'|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2019-10-27}}</ref>\n\n==General operational developments, December 2019 to present==\n{{updated|12-11-2019}} ''updated''\n\nAs a result of the Turkish incursion, multiple Kurdish groups that were once rivals have begun to seek greater unity. Additionally, Syrian Kurdish officials have had some positive discussions with the Assad government, and with local countries such as Saudi Arabia, UAE and Jordan.<ref name=\"al-monitor overview\"> [https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2019/12/turkey-syria-gulf-ankara-kurdish-sweep-backfiring.html Turkey\u2019s Kurdish sweep backfires], Fehim Tastekin December 11, 2019, al-monitor.com</ref>\n\nOn the ground, Turkish areas of operations have been delineated by Russian mediators. Russian military officials forged agreements between Syria, Turkey and Kurds for areas to be patrolled by each side.<ref> [https://ahvalnews.com/northern-syria/russian-forces-syria-sdf-discuss-phase-two-border-security-deal Russian forces in Syria, SDF discuss phase two in border security deal], Dec 07 2019. </ref> Russia handles security through its own forces deployed in some key towns. \n\nThe Assad government has forged agreements with some opposition groups to return to various local border areas.<ref name=\"al-monitor overview\"/> The Syrian Democratic Forces (SDF) reached agreement with the Assad regime for the Syrian Army to patrol several border areas. They also agreed on areas of deployment for Russian forces.<ref> [https://ahvalnews.com/northern-syria/russian-forces-syria-sdf-discuss-phase-two-border-security-deal Russian forces in Syria, SDF discuss phase two in border security deal], Dec 07 2019, ahvalnews.com. </ref> The first agreement between SDF and the Assad regime occurred in October 2019, directly as a result of the Turkish incursion.<ref> [https://ahvalnews.com/operation-peace-spring/live-day-6-turkeys-syria-operation Live: Day 6 of Turkey's Syria operation],\nAhval, Oct 14 2019. </ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://syrianobserver.com/EN/news/53885/sdf-agrees-to-sochi-deal-for-northern-syria.html|title=SDF Agrees to Sochi Deal for Northern Syria|date=2019-10-28|website=The Syrian Observer|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://ekurd.net/syrian-kurds-say-pulling-2019-10-28|title=Syrian Kurds say pulling out from entire length of Turkey border|last=Staff|first=Editorial|date=2019-10-28|website=Kurd Net - Ekurd.net Daily News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref>\n\nIn general positive negotiations have increased between Syria and Turkey, and between Syria and Kurdish groups.<ref> [https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2019/12/the-takeaway-december-11-2019.html The Takeaway: December 11, 2019], Andrew Parasiliti December 11, 2019. </ref>\n\nOn December 9, Russian troops entered Raqqa and began distributing humanitarian aid.<ref> [https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Russian-forces-enter-former-Islamic-State-stronghold-in-Syria-610347 Russian forces enter former Islamic State stronghold in Syria]:Russian troops in Raqqa were handing out humanitarian aid and its military doctors were offering residents medical attention. By REUTERS DECEMBER 9, 2019. </ref><ref> [https://thedefensepost.com/2019/12/10/syria-russia-raqqa-us-withdraw/ Russian troops enter Syria\u2019s Raqqa, filling void of withdrawing US forces], by Jared Szuba DECEMBER 10, 2019. </ref><ref> [https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Russians-in-Raqqa-two-years-after-US-helped-take-city-from-ISIS-610377 Russians near Raqqa two years after US helped take city from ISIS] By SETH J. FRANTZMAN DECEMBER 9, 2019. </ref>\n\nRussia and Syria escalated their attacks against rebel forces in [[Idlib]].<ref> [https://www.voanews.com/extremism-watch/russian-syrian-regime-forces-step-attacks-rebel-stronghold-idlib Russian, Syrian Regime Forces Step Up Attacks on Rebel Stronghold Idlib], By Sirwan Kajjo, December 08, 2019 </ref>\n\n===Refugees status===\nNumerous refugees remain in local refugee camps. Conditions there are reported to be severe, especially with winter approaching.<ref name=\"washokani\"> [https://anfenglishmobile.com/rojava-syria/winter-threatens-the-idps-in-the-washokani-camp-39991 Winter threatens the IDPs in the Washokani Camp].For the displaced people in northern and eastern Syria, winter is a torture: many set up for those seeking shelter have already collapsed due to rain and wind. Almost all international aid organisations are watching the misery. ANF HESEK\u00ca  Tuesday, 10 Dec 2019. </ref>\n\n4,000 people are housed at the Washokani Camp. No organizations are assisting them other than the Kurdish Red Cross. Numerous camp residents have called for assistance from international groups.<ref> [https://anfenglishmobile.com/rojava-syria/over-3500-refugees-accommodated-in-the-washokani-camp-39924 Over 3500 refugees accommodated in the Washokani camp]. The Washokani camp, set up by the autonomous administration of North-East Syria near Hesek\u00ea, now hosts 3566 people who have fled the Turkish occupation troops in Ser\u00eakaniy\u00ea. ANF HESEK\u00ca  Saturday, 7 Dec 2019. </ref><ref> [https://anfenglishmobile.com/rojava-syria/no-help-for-people-displaced-by-the-turkish-invasion-39771 No help for people displaced by the Turkish invasion]. More than 2,500 people now live in the northern Syrian camp Washokani who had to flee due to the Turkish occupation war. No help has arrived from international organisations yet. ANF HESEKE Sunday, 1 Dec 2019. </ref> \n\nRefugees in Northeast Syria report they have received no help from international aid organizations.<ref> [https://anfenglishmobile.com/rojava-syria/ignorance-of-aid-organisations-exacerbates-the-situation-of-idps-39283 Ignorance of aid organisations exacerbates the situation of IDPs] Hundreds of thousands have fled home due to the attacks of the AKP regime and its gangs on Northern Syria. The living conditions of the refugees are being exacerbated by the ignorance of international aid organisations. ANF HESEKE Wednesday, 13 Nov 2019. </ref>\n\n===Syrian and Kurdish actions===\nSome reports stated that Bashar Assad was favorable towards Russia's efforts to restore calm and to stabilize the situation in Syria.<ref> [https://frontline.thehindu.com/world-affairs/article30025808.ece Syria: Russian helping hand], by JOHN CHERIAN, December 06, 2019. </ref>\n\nMeanwhile various Kurdish faction that were historical rivals began to meet in order to work together more. Their stated reason was to stand together against Russia and Turkey more strongly if needed.<ref> [https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2019/12/sdf-woo-syria-kurd-rivals-turkey-assault.html SDF woos Syrian Kurdish rivals in wake of Turkish assault], Amberin Zaman December 4, 2019. </ref><ref name=\"what now\"> [https://www.rudaw.net/english/middleeast/syria/09122019 2 months of Operation Peace Spring: what now?] Karwan Faidhi Dri, Dec 10, 2019. </ref> The Russian government has informed the Kurdish factions that they should reconcile and come up with a unified set of demands to clarify to Russia.<ref> [https://www.rudaw.net/english/middleeast/syria/10122019 Russia wants Syrian Kurds to unify, clarify their demands of Moscow: Kurdish opposition] Karwan Faidhi Dri, Dec 10, 2019. </ref> Various Kurdish factions blamed each other and their council for lack of progress.<ref> [https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2019/12/kurds-syria-pyd-national-council-russia-syrian-regime.html Syria\u2019s Kurdish parties do not see eye to eye], Shivan Ibrahim December 9, 2019. </ref>\n\nMustafa Bali, head of the Syrian Democratic Forces (SDF) said there were some agreements on the ground with the Syrian government, for Syrian forces to be deployed along the border.<ref> [https://www.rudaw.net/english/interview/09122019 Mustafa Bali: Turkey continues to violate ceasefire deals, targets Kurds], Dec 9, 2019. </ref> \n\nThe national Syrian government sent representatives to northeast Syria to meet with local groups there in order to address their concerns and to emphasize unity and combined effort to address problems.<ref> [https://www.hawarnews.com/en/haber/faisal-azouz-our-goal-is-to-know-regions-project-we-do-not-wish-to-see-any-disagreement-h13091.html Faisal Azouz: Our goal is to know region's project, we do not wish to see any disagreement]. The coordinator of the National Dialogue Follow-up Committee of the Arab Socialist Baath Party, Faisal, indicated that they are looking for ways to find a formula for compatibility between the Autonomous Administration project and Article 107 of the Syrian constitution related to local administrations. 08 Dec 2019, Sun - 13:54 2019-12-08T13:54:00 QAMISHLO_ SHINDA AKRAM \u2013 AKRAM BARAKAT. </ref>A meeting occurred in Qamishli city, in northeast Syria, that included Syrian national officials, and delegates from Kurdish, Arab, and Syrian figures and forces.<ref> [https://aawsat.com/english/home/article/2027786/northeast-syria-between-autonomous-local-administrations Northeast Syria Between Autonomous, Local Administrations], Monday, 9 December, 2019. </ref> Kurdish delegates emphasized their desire to help to protect Syria as a whole. They expressed willingness to have positive discussions with the Assad government.<ref> [https://www.kurdistan24.net/en/news/e0a4a994-9c19-4560-af63-eeddc1c0aac2 Syrian delegation explores dialogue between Kurds and Damascus, following US withdrawal] by Wladimir van Wilgenburg, December 10, 2019. </ref> \n\nLuqman Ehm\u00ea, spokesman for the North East Syria Autonomous Administration, said that his organization was ready for positive discussions with the Syrian regime.<ref> [https://anfenglish.com/rojava-syria/ehme-we-are-ready-for-dialogue-with-damascus-39977 Ehm\u00ea: We are ready for dialogue with Damascus]  ANF RAQQA Tuesday, 10 Dec 2019, 09:33.\n\"We are ready for dialogue with the Damascus government for a lasting solution to the Syrian crisis,\" said Luqman Ehm\u00ea, spokesman for the North East Syria Autonomous Administration in a press release. </ref>\n\nSDF General Commander Mazlum Abdi has met with local leaders of the Wise Committee, which is composed of leaders of local communities and local family groupings. This meeting emphasized the importance on national unity, and the need to stand against Turkish invaders.<ref> [https://anfenglishmobile.com/rojava-syria/sdf-general-commander-abdi-met-wise-leaders-40002 SDF General Commander Abdi met Wise leaders]. SDF General Commander Mazlum Abdi met with the Committee of Wise people in North and East Syria. At the meeting, developments in the region were discussed. NF NEWS DESK Wednesday, 11 Dec 2019. </ref>\n\nSDF Commander Mazlum Abdi called on the US and Russia to help stop Turkey from displacing entire communities and ethnic groups from the areas that it controls.<ref> [https://www.kurdistan24.net/en/news/b622efd0-c175-4602-aa3c-a118cd8ee09e Syrian Kurdish leader calls on US, Russia to prevent ethnic cleansing by Turkey], Wladimir van Wilgenburg Wladimir van Wilgenburg | December 11, 2019. </ref>\n\n===Turkish actions===\nErdogan stated that Turkey was ready to resettle the Syrian refugees in the northern area that Turkey had invaded, and that Turkey would pay for it if necessary.<ref> [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security-turkey/erdogan-says-turkey-aims-to-settle-1-million-refugees-in-syria-offensive-area-idUSKBN1YD27R Erdogan says Turkey aims to settle 1 million refugees in Syria offensive area], reuters, December 9, 2019. </ref> On December 9, 2019, various local accounts indicated that Turkey was moving Syrian refugees into its zone of operations in Northern Syria for the first time.<ref> [https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/12/09/turkey-resettling-refugees-northeastern-syria/ Turkey Begins Resettling Refugees in Northeastern Syria: Continued reports of atrocities by Turkish-backed forces raise concerns about ethnic cleansing]. BY LARA SELIGMAN | DECEMBER 9, 2019. </ref> Erdogan said that Turkey was working to settle one million people in the cities of Tal Abyad and Ras Al-Ain in northern Syria.<ref> [https://www.shafaaq.com/en/world/erdogan-announces-start-working-to-house-one-million-people-in-northern-syria/ Erdogan announces start working to house one million people in northern Syria], December 9, 2019. </ref>This has led to fears of population change<ref>https://www.newyorker.com/news/q-and-a/americas-ally-in-syria-warns-of-ethnic-cleansing-by-turkey</ref>\n\nRussia said it would pledge to remove Turkish forces from a key highway in northern Syria, and replace them with Russian forces to maintain stability.<ref> [https://www.rudaw.net/english/middleeast/syria/051220193 Russia has pledged to remove Turkish forces from strategic highway], 05-12-2019 by Karwan Faidhi Dri. </ref> Meanwhile, Turkey began to appoint local mayors and governors in several northern Syrian towns.<ref> [https://www.rudaw.net/english/middleeast/syria/06122019 Turkey appoints mayors in recently invaded northern Syrian towns], 06-12-2019, Karwan Faidhi Dri. </ref> They have also appointed about 4,000 police officers and other local officials, and are providing some basic local services for citizens.<ref> [https://ahvalnews.com/turkey-syria/turkey-appoint-4000-police-officers-syria Turkey to appoint 4,000 police officers to Syria], Dec 07 2019. </ref> \n\nIt was reported that the Russian and Turkish armies had made a deal whereby electricity would be supplied to Tal Abyad by Russia's allies, the Kurdish-led Syrian Democratic Forces (SDF) who support Assad; while water would be supplied by the Alouk water station that is controlled by Turkish forces.<ref> [https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20191209-russia-and-turkey-armies-strike-deal-to-swap-water-for-electricity/ Russia and Turkey armies strike deal to swap water for electricity], December 9, 2019, middleeastmonitor.com </ref> This deal was mainly facilitated by Russian military officials.<ref> [https://www.kurdistan24.net/en/news/860c5e68-1e9e-4bb5-a014-6a3505d90ad4 Russians appear to broker deal with Turkey in electricity for water swap in Syria], Wladimir van Wilgenburg Wladimir van Wilgenburg |December 09-2019. </ref>\n\nIt appeared that Turkey was withdrawing all of its forces away from the al-Shirkark silos, which hold important supplies of wheat, this seemed to be a result of Russian mediation.<ref> [https://www.hawarnews.com/en/haber/what-is-happening-in-al-shirkark-silos-in-ain-issa-district-h13119.html What is happening in al-Shirkark silos in Ain Issa district?]\nThe Turkish occupation army withdrew from al-Shirkrak silo, according it seems agreement with Russia, while yesterday, the Russian forces headed with the Syrian regime to remove mines in the silos' vicinity, we have no precise information about the forces which will be stationed in the silos. 10 Dec 2019, Tue - 14:38 2019-12-10T14:38:00 AIN ISSA \u2013 SHARVIN MUSTAFA. hawarnews.com</ref> However, some reports said they later returned to re-occupy that area.<ref> [https://anfenglishmobile.com/rojava-syria/turkish-forces-re-occupy-the-wheat-silo-it-retreated-from-39989 Turkish forces re-occupy the wheat silo they retreated from.] AIN ISSA Tuesday, 10 Dec 2019. </ref>\n\nRussian and Turkish forces are continuing their joint patrols.<ref name=\"what now\"> [https://www.rudaw.net/english/middleeast/syria/09122019 2 months of Operation Peace Spring: what now?] Karwan Faidhi Dri, Dec 10, 2019. </ref> Questions remained about how much control Turkey has over its proxies, such as the Free Syrian Army.<ref> [https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/11/23/life-on-the-front-lines-in-northern-syria/ Life on the Front Lines in Northern Syria]; With echoes of shelling from Turkish-allied forces nearby, families sheltering in abandoned villages wonder when they can go home. BY JADE SACKER, NOVEMBER 23, 2019. </ref>\n\n==Diplomatic developments, December 2019 to present==\nAt a panel discussion on the conflict in December 2019, several experts said the conflict was slowly moving towards resolution. One expert said that the \"Astana\" diplomatic process, involving Turkey, Russia, and Iran, was having some positive results. Experts also said that Bashar Assad had made progress in restoring rule by local councils in areas affected by the conflict.<ref> [https://cyprus-mail.com/2019/12/08/syria-the-most-complex-conflict-of-our-time/ Syria: the most complex conflict of our time], By Elias Hazou, December 8, 2019 </ref>\n===Diplomacy with NATO member nations===\nAt the NATO summit in London in December 2019, President Emmanuel Macron of France highlighted major differences with Turkey over the definition of terrorism, and said there was little chance this aspect of the conflict could be resolved positively.<ref> [https://www.express.co.uk/news/world/1214065/emmanuel-macron-news-turkey-syria-terrorism-definition Macron and Turkey clash over terrorism after Syria conflict 'No consensus possible!'] By ROMINA MCGUINNESS,  Dec 6, 2019. </ref> Macron criticized Turkey strongly for fighting against groups who had been allied with France and the West in fighting terrorism.<ref name=\"euobserver nato\"> [https://euobserver.com/foreign/146810 Macron spars with US and Turkey over Nato], By NIKOLAJ NIELSEN BRUSSELS, 4. DEC, euobserver.com. </ref> \n\nNumerous issues in resolving the conflict emerged at the NATO summit in London. Turkey proposed a safe zone where Syrian refugees could be relocated, but this idea did not receive support from all parties.<ref name=\"euobserver nato\"/> One professed \"exclusive\" press report claimed that prior to the NATO Summit, there was a meeting at 10 Downing Street of the leaders of France, the UK, Germany and Turkey. One key point that emerged that the Western countries insisted that refugees could only be relocated voluntarily.<ref> [https://www.dailysabah.com/columns/yahya_bostan/2019/12/09/exclusive-details-of-erdogans-meeting-with-johnson-merkel-and-macron Exclusive details of Erdo\u011fan's meeting with Johnson, Merkel and Macron], by Yahya Bostan, dailysabah.com </ref> Meanwhile, there were concerns in NATO about Turkey's growing closeness with Russia.<ref> [https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2019/12/turkey-united-states-russia-is-erdogan-trojan-horse-in-nato.html Erdogan in NATO: Russia\u2019s \u2018Trojan horse\u2019?], by Cengiz Candar December 9, 2019.</ref>\n\nErdogan claimed that a four-way summit on Syria was scheduled to occur in Turkey in February 2020, to include Turkey, Germany, the UK and France.<ref> [http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/a-four-way-summit-on-syria-will-be-in-turkey-149498 A four-way summit on Syria will be in Turkey], NewsTurkey December 05 2019. </ref>\n\n===Diplomacy with nations outside NATO===\nAt a meeting in Damascus, Russian and Syrian officials clearly stated their support for Syria regaining control over all of its territory.<ref> [https://aawsat.com/english/home/article/2018801/putin%E2%80%99s-envoy-tells-assad-russia-supports-%E2%80%98recapturing-all-syrian-territories%E2%80%99 Putin\u2019s Envoy Tells Assad Russia Supports \u2018Recapturing All Syrian Territories\u2019], Tuesday, 3 December, 2019. </ref><ref> [https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2019/12/intel-russia-change-course-syria.html Intel: How Russia is changing course in Syria], Maxim A. Suchkov December 3, 2019. </ref><ref> [https://www.mid.ru/en/foreign_policy/news/-/asset_publisher/cKNonkJE02Bw/content/id/3928776 Press release on Russian officials\u2019 meeting with President of Syria Bashar al-Assad], 02-12-2019. </ref> The United Arab Emirates also expressed official support for Assad.<ref> [https://www.newsweek.com/uae-officially-backs-syria-assad-win-1475341 UAE OFFICIALLY BACKS SYRIA'S ASSAD TO WIN WAR], BY TOM O'CONNOR ON 12/3/19. </ref>\n\nA new round of meetings for the Astana summit process took place in the Kazakh capital Nur Sultan. The meeting includes Russia, Syria, Turkey and Iran.<ref> [https://www.hawarnews.com/en/haber/astana-round-begins-with-a-meeting-between-the-meeting-sponsors-h13118.html Astana round begins with a meeting between the meeting sponsors]\nThe 14th round of the Astana meetings began in the Kazakh capital Nur Sultan on Tuesday morning with a series of meetings of the meeting sponsors (Russia, Turkey and Iran). 10 Dec 2019, Tue - 14:07 2019-12-10T14:07:00 NEWS DESK </ref> At this meeting Russia, stated that the \"safe zone\" established by Turkey should not be expanded, as this would not accomplish anything positive for the region.<ref> [https://www.rudaw.net/english/world/10122019 Astana talks: Expanding Syria \u2018safe zone\u2019 will \u2018do nothing good\u2019, says Russian envoy], 18 hours ago, Karwan Faidhi Dri, rudaw.net. </ref>\n\nThe Astana process was created by Turkey, Iran and Russia in order to find a lasting solution to the conflict. they have examined a process to reform the constitution of Syria via the newly-formed Syrian Constitutional Committee.<ref name=\"Astana Sabah\"> [https://www.dailysabah.com/syrian-crisis/2019/12/10/regime-continues-to-violate-sochi-deal-amid-diplomatic-efforts-for-political-solution-in-syria Regime continues to violate Sochi deal amid diplomatic efforts for political solution in Syria] DAILY SABAH, ISTANBUL Published Dec. 10, 2019.</ref> The parties reported that they reached some important understandings at this meeting, including affirming a commitment to work together to respect Syrian territorial integrity.<ref> [https://www.inform.kz/en/14th-round-led-to-significant-results-mfa-about-the-astana-process-on-syria_a3593712 14th round led to significant results, MFA about the Astana process on Syria], 11 December 2019, inform.kz, kazinform news agency. </ref>\n\n==Syrian Constitutional Committee==\n{{main|Syrian Constitutional Committee}}\n\nOn November 20, 2019, a new [[Syrian Constitutional Committee]] began operating in order to discuss a new settlement and to draft a new constitution for Syria.<ref name=\"Astana Sabah\"> [https://www.dailysabah.com/syrian-crisis/2019/12/10/regime-continues-to-violate-sochi-deal-amid-diplomatic-efforts-for-political-solution-in-syria Regime continues to violate Sochi deal amid diplomatic efforts for political solution in Syria] DAILY SABAH, ISTANBUL Published Dec. 10, 2019.</ref>  This committee comprises about 150 members. It includes representatives of the Syrian regime, opposition groups, and countries serving as guarantors of the process such as e.g. Russia. However, this committee has faced strong opposition from the Assad regime. 50 of the committee members represent the regime, and 50 members represent the opposition. The committee began its work in November 2019 in Geneva, under UN auspices. However, the Assad regime delegation left on the second day of the process.<ref name=\"Astana Sabah\"/> \n\nAt a summit in October 2018, envoys from Russia, Turkey, France and Germany issued a joint statement affirming the need to respect territorial integrity of Syria as a whole. This forms one basis for their role as \"guarantor nations.\"<ref name=\"Astana Sabah\"/> \n\nThe second round of talks occurred around November 25th, but was not successful due to opposition from the Assad regime.<ref name=\"Astana Sabah\"/>  At the Astana Process meeting in December 2019, a UN official stated that in order for the third round of talks to proceed, co-chairs from the Assad regime and the opposition need to agree on an agenda.<ref name=\"Astana Sabah\"/> \n\nThe committee has two co-chairs, Ahmad Kuzbari representing the Assad regime, and Hadi Albahra from the opposition. It is unclear if the third round of talks will proceed on a firm schedule, until the Assad regime provides its assent to participate.<ref name=\"Astana Sabah\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[NATO]]\n* [[Arab League]]\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links|wikt=no|commons=Category:Syrian Civil War|b=no|n=Category:Syrian Civil War|q=no|s=no|v=no|voy=no|display=the Syrian Civil War}}\n'''Interviews'''\n* [https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20161205135549/http://nation.foxnews.com/2013/09/18/fox-news-exclusive-interview-syrian-president-bashar-al-assad Fox News exclusive interview with Syrian President Bashar Al-Assad] [[Fox News]], 18 September 2013\n* [http://www.presidentassad.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&id=307&Itemid=468 Interview with Bashar Assad: 'In the End, a Lie Is a Lie'] [[Der Spiegel]], 7 October 2013\n* [http://www.spiegel.de/international/world/spiegel-interview-with-syrian-president-bashar-assad-a-926456.html President Bashar al-Assad's interview with Agence France Presse AFP 20-01-2014] 20 January 2014\n* A discussion of the [http://www.monitor.upeace.org/innerpg.cfm?id_article=1017 causes of the civil war] at the ''[[United Nations University for Peace]]''.\n* [http://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2013/12/al-qaeda-leader-syria-speaks-al-jazeera-20131218155917935989.html First ever broadcast interview with Jabhat al Nusra founder Abu Mohammed al-Joulani]\n'''Supranational government bodies'''\n* [http://www.fao.org/emergencies/crisis/syria/en/ FAO \u2013 Syria crisis]\n'''Human rights bodies'''\n* [http://www.icrc.org/eng/where-we-work/middle-east/syria/index.jsp The ICRC in Syria], [[International Committee of the Red Cross]]\n'''Media'''\n* [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-17258397 Syria's war] at ''[[BBC News]]''\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/special/world/syrian-uprising-one-year-of-bloodshed/index.html Syrian uprising: A year in turmoil] at ''[[The Washington Post]]''\n* [http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/syria-pulse Syria Pulse] collected news and commentary at ''[[Al Monitor]]''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160320165721/https://now.mmedia.me/lb/en/Now-Syria/latest_syria_developments Latest Syria developments] at ''[[NOW Lebanon]]''\n* {{Guardian topic|2=Syria}}\n* [http://topics.nytimes.com/top/news/international/countriesandterritories/syria/index.html Syria] collected news and commentary at ''[[The New York Times]]''\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/syria/ Syria news, all the latest and breaking Syria news] at ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''\n* [http://www.aljazeera.com/topics/country/syria.html Syria] collected coverage at ''[[Al Jazeera English]]''\n* [http://www.intelligenceonline.com/search/search.aspx?keywords=Syria Syria] collected news at ''[[Intelligence Online]]''\n* [https://syriancivilwarmap.com/ Interactive Map of the Syrian Civil War]\n* [https://www.newsdeeply.com/syria Syria Deeply] at [[News Deeply]]\n* [http://omniatlas.com/maps/europe/20151007/ Maps of Europe and Syrian Civil War (omniatlas.com)]\n\n{{Syrian Civil War}}\n{{Syria topics}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list1 = \n{{Ongoing military conflicts}}\n{{Arab Spring}}\n{{Middle East conflicts}}\n{{Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant}}\n{{Post-Cold War Asian conflicts}}\n{{Iran\u2013Saudi Arabia relations}}\n{{Arab-Israeli conflict}}\n{{Russia\u2013United States relations}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Syrian Civil War}}\n{{Kurdish\u2013Turkish conflict (1978\u2013present)}}\n{{Portal bar|Asia|Kurdistan|Turkey|War}}\n\n[[Category:2010s in Syria]]\n[[Category:Politics overviews by decade]]\n[[Category:2010 in politics]]\n", "text_old": "'''2010s in Syria political history''' refers to events during the 2010s in political history of [[Syria]]. \n\n{{Year nav topic5|2019|Syria}}\n\n==General history==\n\n==History by government ministry==\n\n==History of conflict (Early to mid-2010s)==\n{{main|Syrian Civil War}}\n\n===Syrian Civil War===\nThe [[Syrian Civil War]] is an ongoing multi-sided [[civil war]] in Syria fought between the [[Ba'ath Party (Syrian-dominated faction)|Ba'athist]] [[Syrian Arab Republic]] led by Syrian President [[Bashar al-Assad]], along with domestic and foreign allies, and various domestic and foreign forces opposing both the Syrian government and each other in varying combinations.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/05/syria-civil-war-explained-160505084119966.html |title=Syria's civil war explained from the beginning |publisher=Al Jazeera |access-date=29 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170430014912/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/05/syria-civil-war-explained-160505084119966.html |archive-date=30 April 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> The war is currently the second [[Casualties of the Syrian Civil War|deadliest of the 21st century]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/list/8-deadliest-wars-of-the-21st-century|title=8 Deadliest Wars of the 21st Century|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2019-07-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190526191400/https://www.britannica.com/list/8-deadliest-wars-of-the-21st-century|archive-date=26 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe unrest in Syria, part of a wider wave of the 2011 [[Arab Spring]] protests, grew out of discontent with the Syrian government and escalated to an armed conflict after [[Civil uprising phase of the Syrian Civil War|protests calling for Assad's removal]] were violently suppressed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-26116868 |title=Syria: The story of the conflict |date=11 March 2016 |work=BBC News |access-date=21 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622052951/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-26116868 |archive-date=22 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/26/world/middleeast/26syria.html|title=Syrian Troops Open Fire on Protestors in Several Cities|date=25 March 2011|work=The New York Times|access-date=23 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621011638/https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/26/world/middleeast/26syria.html|archive-date=21 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The war, which began on 15 March 2011 with major unrest in [[Damascus]] and [[Aleppo]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-12749674|title=Mid-East unrest: Syrian protests in Damascus and Aleppo|last=|first=|date=2011-03-15|newspaper=BBC News|access-date=2013-03-15|work=|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180721134738/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-12749674|archive-date=21 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> is being fought by several factions: the [[Syrian Armed Forces]] and its international allies, a loose alliance of mostly [[Sunni]] [[Syrian Opposition|opposition]] rebel groups (including the [[Free Syrian Army]]), [[Salafi jihadist]] groups (including [[al-Nusra Front]]), the mixed Kurdish-Arab [[Syrian Democratic Forces]] (SDF), and the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL), with a number of [[Foreign involvement in the Syrian Civil War|countries in the region and beyond being either directly involved]] or providing support to one or another faction (Iran, Russia, Turkey, the United States, as well as others).\n\nIran, Russia, and [[Hezbollah]] support the Syrian Arab Republic and the Syrian Armed Forces militarily, with Russia conducting [[Russian military intervention in the Syrian Civil War|airstrikes and other military operations]] since September 2015. The [[Combined Joint Task Force \u2013 Operation Inherent Resolve|U.S.-led international coalition]], established in 2014 with the declared purpose of countering ISIL, has [[American-led intervention in the Syrian Civil War|conducted airstrikes]] primarily against ISIL as well as some [[List of United States attacks on the Syrian government during the Syrian Civil War|against government and pro-government targets]]. They have also deployed special forces and artillery units to engage ISIL on the ground. Since 2015, the U.S. has supported the [[Democratic Federation of Northern Syria]] and its armed wing, the SDF, materially, financially, and logistically. Turkey has been [[Turkish occupation of northern Syria|directly involved in operations]] against the Syrian government since August 2016, not only participating in airstrikes against ISIL alongside the U.S.-led coalition, but also actively supporting the [[Syrian opposition]] and [[Turkish occupation of northern Syria|occupying large swaths of northwestern Syria]] while engaging in significant ground combat with ISIL, the SDF, and the Syrian government. Between 2011 and 2017, fighting from the Syrian Civil War [[Spillover of the Syrian Civil War|spilled over]] into [[Lebanon]] as opponents and supporters of the Syrian government traveled to Lebanon to fight and attack each other on Lebanese soil, with ISIL and Al-Nusra also engaging the Lebanese Army. Furthermore, while officially neutral, [[Israel]] has [[Israeli\u2013Syrian ceasefire line incidents during the Syrian Civil War|conducted airstrikes]] against Hezbollah and Iranian forces, whose presence in southwestern Syria it views as a threat.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-syria/u-s-russian-ceasefire-takes-effect-in-southwest-syria-idUSKBN19U08D|title=U.S.-Russian ceasefire deal holding in southwest Syria|date=9 July 2017|work=Reuters|access-date=2017-11-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921113246/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-syria/u-s-russian-ceasefire-takes-effect-in-southwest-syria-idUSKBN19U08D|archive-date=21 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nInternational organizations have criticized virtually all sides involved, including the Ba'athist Syrian government, ISIL, opposition rebel groups, Russia,<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/sep/25/russia-accused-war-crimes-syria-un-security-council-aleppo|title=Russia accused of war crimes in Syria at UN security council session|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=18 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401192517/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/sep/25/russia-accused-war-crimes-syria-un-security-council-aleppo|archive-date=1 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and the U.S.-led coalition<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/06/05/middleeast/us-led-coalition-raqqa-war-crimes-intl/index.html |title=US-led strikes on Raqqa may amount to war crimes, Amnesty says |first1=Angela |last1=Dewan |first2=Hillary |last2=McGann |date=5 June 2018 |publisher=CNN |access-date=5 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180605205903/https://www.cnn.com/2018/06/05/middleeast/us-led-coalition-raqqa-war-crimes-intl/index.html |archive-date=5 June 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> of severe human rights violations and [[List of massacres during the Syrian Civil War|massacres]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/15/world/middleeast/syria-bashar-al-assad-evidence.html |title=As Atrocities Mount in Syria, Justice Seems Out of Reach |first1=Anne Barnard, Ben |last1=Hubbard |first2=Ian |last2=Fisher |date=15 April 2017 |work=The New York Times |access-date=18 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517192038/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/15/world/middleeast/syria-bashar-al-assad-evidence.html |archive-date=17 May 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> The conflict has caused a major [[Refugees of the Syrian Civil War|refugee crisis]]. Over the course of the war, a number of peace initiatives have been launched, including the [[Geneva peace talks on Syria (2017)|March 2017 Geneva peace talks on Syria]] led by the [[United Nations]], but fighting continues.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Lundgren |first=Magnus |year=2016 |title=Mediation in Syria: Initiatives, strategies, and obstacles, 2011\u20132016 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/303312425_Mediation_in_Syria_Initiatives_strategies_and_obstacles_2011-2016 |journal=Contemporary Security Policy |volume=37 |pages=283\u2013298 |access-date=20 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202000757/https://www.researchgate.net/publication/303312425_Mediation_in_Syria_Initiatives_strategies_and_obstacles_2011-2016 |archive-date=2 February 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==History of conflict (Late 2010s to present)==\n===Turkish offensive, 2019===\n\n{{main|2019 Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria}}\n\nThe 2019 Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria, code-named by Turkey as Operation Peace Spring ({{lang-tr|Bar\u0131\u015f P\u0131nar\u0131 Harek\u00e2t\u0131}}), is a cross-border military operation conducted by the [[Turkish Armed Forces]] (TAF) and the [[Syrian National Army]] (SNA) against the [[Syrian Democratic Forces]] (SDF) and later the [[Syrian Arab Army]] (SAA) in [[Rojava|northeastern Syria]].\n\nOn 6 October 2019, the [[Trump administration]] ordered American troops to withdraw from northeastern Syria, where the United States [[American-led intervention in the Syrian Civil War|had been supporting]] its Kurdish allies.<ref name=withdraw>{{cite news |title=Trump makes way for Turkey operation against Kurds in Syria |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-49956698?intlink_from_url=https://www.bbc.com/news/topics/cp7r8vgl2y7t/kurds&link_location=live-reporting-story |accessdate=10 October 2019 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=7 October 2019}}</ref> The military operation began on 9 October 2019 when the [[Turkish Air Force]] launched airstrikes on [[Syria\u2013Turkey border|border]] towns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/oct/09/turkey-launches-military-operation-in-northern-syria-erdogan|title=Turkey launches military operation in northern Syria|work=The Guardian|first=Bethan|last=McKernan|date=9 October 2019}}</ref> The conflict resulted in the displacement of over 300,000 people and has caused the death of more than 70 civilians in Syria and 20 civilians in Turkey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bursadabugun.com/haber/teroristlerin-saldirilarinda-20-sivil-sehit-oldu-170-kisi-yaralandi-1191643.html|title=Ter\u00f6ristlerin sald\u0131r\u0131lar\u0131nda 20 sivil \u015fehit oldu, 170 ki\u015fi yaraland\u0131|website=Bursada Bug\u00fcn}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/syria/kurdish-politician-executed-by-turkish-backed-fighters-in-syria-1.7970427|title=Kurdish Politician Among Nine Civilians Executed by Turkish-backed Fighters in Syria|date=13 October 2019|newspaper=[[Haaretz]]}}</ref> Human rights violations have also been reported. [[Amnesty International]] stated that it had gathered evidence of [[war crimes]] and other violations committed by Turkish and Turkey-backed Syrian forces who are said to \"have displayed a shameful disregard for civilian life, carrying out serious violations and war crimes, including summary killings and unlawful attacks that have killed and injured civilians\".\n\nAccording to the Turkish President [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]], the operation is intended to expel the SDF\u2014viewed as a terrorist organization by Turkey due to its ties with the [[Kurdistan Workers Party]] (PKK), but considered an ally against [[ISIL]] by the [[Combined Joint Task Force \u2013 Operation Inherent Resolve|United States and its allies]]\u2014from the border region as well as to create a 30&nbsp;km-deep (20&nbsp;mi) \"safe zone\" in Northern Syria where some of the 3.6 million [[Syrian refugees in Turkey]] would resettle.<ref name=\"aj-turkey-begins\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/turkey-begins-ground-offensive-northeastern-syria-191009212025006.html |title=Turkey begins ground offensive in northeastern Syria |date=9 October 2019 |work=[[Al Jazeera]] |access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref> As the proposed settlement zone is heavily Kurdish demographically, this intention has been criticized as an attempt to force drastic demographic change,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2019/09/turkey-syria-united-states-erdogan-plans-for-east-euphrates.html|title=Erdogan's Syria plan: Resettling the Syrian refugees or ousting Kurds from their land?|first=Cengiz|last=Candar|date=30 September 2019|website=Al-Monitor}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/e40cb754-e456-11e9-b112-9624ec9edc59|title=Syria is witnessing a violent demographic re-engineering|website=[[Financial Times]]}}</ref><ref name=reuters_demographics>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security-turkey-refugees-graphi-idUSKBN1WN28J|title=Turkey's plan to settle refugees in northeast Syria alarms allies|date=8 October 2019|via=reuters.com|newspaper=Reuters}}</ref> a criticism denied by Turkey by saying that it only intended to \"correct\" the demographics that Turkish officials stated were changed by the SDF.<ref name=reuters_demographics/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ibtimes.com/turkey-begins-military-operation-against-kurds-after-trump-pulls-troops-northern-2842727|title=Turkey Begins Military Operation Against Kurds After Trump Pulls Troops In Northern Syria|first=Wesley|last=Dockery|date=9 October 2019|website=[[International Business Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arabnews.com/node/1565401/middle-east|title=After US green light, Turkey prepares military operation in Syria|date=7 October 2019|website=Arab News}}</ref>\n\nThe Turkish operation received mixed responses by the international community. Including condemnations<ref>{{cite news |title=India slams Turkey for its 'unilateral military offensive' in northeast Syria {{!}} India News \u2013 Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/india-slams-turkey-for-its-unilateral-military-offensive-in-northeast-syria/articleshow/71520852.cms |accessdate=10 October 2019 |work=The Times of India |language=en}}</ref> as well as support for the operation for the settlement of refugees in Northern Syria.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/539756-pm-imran-telephones-erdogan-assures-full-support-to-turkey|title=PM Imran telephones Erdogan, assures full support to Turkey|date=11 October 2019|website=The News International}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/operation-peace-spring/turkic-council-supports-turkey-s-anti-terror-operation/1614575|title=Turkic Council supports Turkey's anti-terror operation|website=aa.com.tr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnnturk.com/turkiye/turk-konseyi-liderler-zirvesinden-ortak-baris-pinari-bildirisi|title=T\u00fcrk Konseyi Liderler Zirvesi'nden ortak 'Bar\u0131\u015f P\u0131nar\u0131' bildirisi|website=CNN T\u00fcrk}}</ref> While originally acknowledging Turkey's \"right to defend itself\", on 15 October, Russia hardened its position against the operation and deployed troops.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/3123143a-ef41-11e9-ad1e-4367d8281195|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/15/world/middleeast/kurds-syria-turkey.html|title=In Syria, Russia Is Pleased to Fill an American Void|first1=Ben|last1=Hubbard|first2=Anton|last2=Troianovski|first3=Carlotta|last3=Gall|first4=Patrick|last4=Kingsley|date=15 October 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> Ten European nations and Canada [[Reactions to the 2019 Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria|imposed an arms embargo on Turkey]], while the U.S. imposed sanctions on Turkish ministries and senior government officials in response to the offensive in Syria.<ref name=ColumbusSanctions>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-50050264|title=Turkey-Syria offensive: US sanctions Turkish ministries|date=15 October 2019|agency=BBC}}</ref> Likewise, Trump's sudden pullout of US forces in Syria was also criticized by journalists as a \"serious betrayal to the Kurds\" as well as a \"catastrophic blow to US credibility as an ally and Washington's standing on the world stage\", one journalist stating that \"this is one of the worst US foreign policy disasters since the [[Iraq War]]\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/us-betrayal-of-kurds-destroys-the-wests-credibility-for-years-to-come-11835611|title=US betrayal of Kurds destroys the West's credibility for years to come | website=Sky News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/trump-syria-move-delivers-blow-credibility-worldwide-191008232132422.html|title=Trump's Syria move 'delivers a blow to US credibility worldwide'| website=Al Jazeera}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/18/opinion/trump-kurds-syria.html|title=Trump's Gut, and the Gutting of American Credibility| website=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/meet-the-press/trump-s-decision-syria-has-already-turned-foreign-policy-disaster-n1065691|title=Trump's decision on Syria has already turned into a foreign policy disaster| website=NBC News}}</ref> On November 19, the Defense Department inspector general released a report finding that the American withdrawal and subsequent Turkish incursion allowed ISIL to \"reconstitute capabilities and resources within Syria and strengthen its ability to plan attacks abroad\".<ref name=\"O\u2019brien\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/11/19/trump-syria-isis-071499|title=Trump's pullout from Syria allowed ISIS to gain strength, intel agency reports|first=Connor|last=O\u2019brien|website=POLITICO}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Syrian government]] initially criticized the Kurdish forces for the Turkish offensive, for their separatism and not reconciling with the government, while at the same time also condemning the foreign invasion in Syrian territory.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-10/11/c_138462068.htm |title=Syria blames Kurdish forces for Turkish military offensive |date=11 October 2019|work=Xinhua Net |access-date=11 October 2019}}</ref> However, a few days later, the SDF reached an agreement with the Syrian government, in which it would allow the [[Syrian Army]] to enter the SDF-held towns of [[Manbij]] and [[Koban\u00ee]] in an attempt to defend the towns from the Turkish offensive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2019/10/13/Syrian-army-to-enter-SDF-held-Kobani-Manbij-Monitor.html|title=Syrian army to enter SDF-held Kobani, Manbij: Monitor|website=english.alarabiya.net|language=en|access-date=13 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security-towns-report-idUSKBN1WS0K0|title=Report: Syrian army to enter SDF-held Kobani, Manbij|date=13 October 2019|work=Reuters|access-date=13 October 2019|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"armyinvolved\">{{Cite web|url=https://thedefensepost.com/2019/10/13/syria-government-russia-kobani-manbij-sdf/|title=Syrian government forces set to enter Kobani and Manbij after SDF deal|date=13 October 2019|website=The Defense Post|language=en-US|access-date=13 October 2019}}</ref> Shortly thereafter, Syrian state broadcaster [[SANA]] announced that Syrian Army troops had started to deploy to the country's north.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/world/mena/syrian-troops-sent-north-to-confront-turkey-over-incursion-says-state-media-1.922875|title=Syrian troops sent north to 'confront' Turkey over incursion, says state media|website=The National|language=en|access-date=13 October 2019}}</ref> Turkey and the SNA launched an offensive to capture Manbij on the same day.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.haber.com/suriye-milli-ordusu-munbic-operasyonu-basladi-103685/|title=Suriye Milli Ordusu: M\u00fcnbi\u00e7 Operasyonu Ba\u015flad\u0131|date=14 October 2019|website=Haber.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 October 2019, U.S. Vice President [[Mike Pence]] announced that the U.S. and Turkey agreed on a deal in which Turkey will agree to a ceasefire in Syria for 5 days in return for a complete withdrawal by the SDF from a safe zone south of the Syria-Turkey border.<ref name=\":1c\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/us-and-turkey-reach-agreement-temporarily-suspend-military-operation-syria|title=US and Turkey reach agreement to suspend military operation in Syria|website=Middle East Eye|date=17 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":2c\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-50091305|title=Turkey to suspend Syria offensive, US says|website=BBC|date=17 October 2019}}</ref> On 22 October 2019, Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] and Turkish President [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] [[Second Northern Syria Buffer Zone|reached a deal]] to extend the ceasefire by 150 additional hours for SDF to move 30 kilometers away from the border area as well as from [[Tal Rifaat]] and [[Manbij]]. The terms of the deal also included joint Russian\u2013Turkish patrols 10 kilometers into Syria from the border except in the city of [[Qamishli]]. The new ceasefire started at 12pm local time on 23 October.<ref name=\"auto16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/article236512698.html|title=The Latest: Pence says 5-day cease-fire in Syria has held\n|date=22 October 2019|website=Miami Herald}}</ref><ref name=\"auto17\">{{Cite web|url=https://thedefensepost.com/2019/10/22/russia-turkey-syria-mou/|title=FULL TEXT: Memorandum of Understanding between Turkey and Russia on northern Syria|date=22 October 2019|website=The Defense Post}}</ref>\n\n==Changes to conflict due to Turkish incursion of October 2019==\n=== Changes in the local areas ===\nIn October 2019, in response to the Turkish offensive, Russia arranged for negotiations between the Syrian government in Damascus and the Kurdish-led forces.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Foy |first1=Henry |title=Russia calls Turkey's invasion of north Syria 'unacceptable' |url=https://www.ft.com/content/3123143a-ef41-11e9-ad1e-4367d8281195 |website=Financial Times}}</ref><ref name=ko-il-rftv/> [[Mazloum Abdi]], the Syrian Kurdish commander-in-chief, announced that they are ready to partner with [[Vladimir Putin]] (Russia) and [[Bashar al-Assad]] (Syria), stating that \"We know that we would have to make painful compromises with Moscow and Bashar al-Assad if we go down the road of working with them. But if we have to choose between compromises and the genocide of our people, we will surely choose life for our people.\"<ref name=\"abma-if-we\"/> The details of the agreement is unknown, but there are reports that suggest that the SDF will be incorporated into the [[Syrian Armed Forces]] and that northeastern Syria will come under direct rule of the Syrian government in Damascus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sanchez |first1=Raf |title=Assad troops enter north-east Syria after Russia-backed deal with Kurds |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/10/14/assad-troops-enter-northeast-syria-russia-backed-deal-kurds/ |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=14 October 2019}}</ref> According to Syrian Kurdish officials, the deal allows Syrian government forces to take over security in some border areas, but their own administration would maintain control of local institutions.<ref name=wapo-ssgse/>\n\nThe prospects for Kurdish autonomy in the region is severely diminished, because the Kurds were exposed to the Turkish-led offensive by the US withdrawal and the Russia-backed Syrian government forces under Assad\u2014whose commonality is enmity towards Turkey and Sunni rebel militias\u2014regained their foothold in northeast Syria after the Kurds had to seek their help.<ref name=\"dvcopt\">{{cite web |last1=Dominic Evans |first1=Dominic |last2=Coskun |first2=Orhan |last3=Perry |first3=Tom |title=Power shift: Who gains in the battle for Syria's northeast? |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security-turkey-usa-power-analy/power-shift-who-gains-in-the-battle-for-syrias-northeast-idUSKBN1WU2K8 |website=Reuters |date=16 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Seligman |first1=Lara |title=How the Iran Hawks Botched Trump's Syria Withdrawal |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/10/30/iran-hawks-botched-trump-syria-policy-james-jeffrey-turkey/ |website=Foreign Policy |date=30 October 2019}}</ref> In regards to the United States and the situation, Mazloum Abdi stated that \"We are disappointed and frustrated by the current crisis. Our people are under attack, and their safety is our paramount concern. Two questions remain: How can we best protect our people? And is the United States still our ally?\"<ref name=\"abma-if-we\">{{cite web |last1=Abdi |first1=Mazloum |title=If We Have to Choose Between Compromise and Genocide, We Will Choose Our People |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/10/13/kurds-assad-syria-russia-putin-turkey-genocide/ |website=Foreign Policy |date=13 October 2019}}</ref> A deep sense of betrayal by their once American allies has come to be felt among the Syrian Kurdish populace.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Evans |first1=Margaret |title=Turkey 'outsourcing war crimes' to armed groups, Amnesty says after Kurdish politician's murder |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/syria-turkey-1.5328109 |website=CBC |date=20 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Perry |first1=Tom |last2=Francis |first2=Ellen |title=For Syrian Kurds, a leader's killing deepens sense of U.S. betrayal |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security-kurds-future/for-syrian-kurds-a-leaders-killing-deepens-sense-of-us-betrayal-idUSKBN1X11HZ |website=Reuters |language=en |date=22 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hubbard |first1=Ben |last2=Kirkpatrick |first2=David D. |title=Kurds' Sense of Betrayal Compounded by Empowerment of Unsavory Rivals |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/18/world/middleeast/kurds-sense-of-betrayal-compounded-by-empowerment-of-unsavory-rivals.html |website=The New York Times |date=18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs announced by Russia's Ministry of Defense on 15 October, Russian forces have started to patrol the region along the line of contact between Turkish and Syrian forces,<ref name=ko-il-rftv>{{cite web |last1=Kottasov\u00e1 |first1=Ivana |last2=Ilyushina |first2=Mary |title=Russians fill the void left by US troops in Syria |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/10/15/middleeast/turkey-syria-russian-troops-intl/index.html |website=CNN |date=15 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=wapo-ssgse/> indicating that Russia is filling the security vacuum from the sudden US withdrawal.<ref name=wapo-ssgse>{{cite web | author1= Fahim, Kareem | author2=Dadouch, Sarah | author3= Englund, Will |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/syria-says-government-soldiers-enter-manbij-after-us-troops-withdraw/2019/10/15/d494405a-eeb8-11e9-bb7e-d2026ee0c199_story.html | title=Russia patrolling between Turkish and Syrian forces after U.S. troops withdraw| date =15 October 2019 | website=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mortazavi |first1=Negar |title=How Russia is filling the gap left by Trump's withdrawal of US troops in Syria |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/trump-syria-kurds-russia-putin-assad-a9157656.html |website=The Independent |date=16 October 2019}}</ref> Video footage shows Russian soldiers and journalists touring a base that the US left behind.<ref name=wapo-ssgse/><ref name=ol-ram>{{cite news |last1=Oliphant |first1=Roland |title=Russia assumes mantle of supreme power broker in Middle East as US retreats from Syria |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/10/15/russia-assumes-mantle-supreme-power-broker-middle-east-us-retreats/ |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=15 October 2019}}</ref> Alexander Lavrentiev, Russia's special envoy on Syria, warned that the Turkish offensive into Syria is unacceptable and stated that Russia is seeking to prevent conflict between Turkish and Syrian troops.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sevastopulo |first1=Demetri |last2=Williams |first2=Aime |last3=Pitel |first3=Laura |last4=Foy |first4=Henry |title=US delegation to press Turkey for Syrian ceasefire |url=https://www.ft.com/content/3123143a-ef41-11e9-ad1e-4367d8281195 |website=Financial Times |date=16 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn response to a speech by Assad, the Syrian Democratic Council said it was ready to have positive discussions with the Assad government. They said their focus would shift to stopping the Turkish invasion.<ref> [https://www.rudaw.net/english/middleeast/syria/021120192 Syrian Democratic Council : We are ready to start negotiating with Damascus], 02-11-2019, Lawk Ghafuri, rudaw.net. </ref>\n\n===International reactions to Turkish incursion of October 2019===\nSeveral US lawmakers have criticized the abandonment of their Kurdish allies, remarking that it undermines US credibility as an ally while benefiting Russia, Iran, and the Syrian regime of Assad.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Olorunnipa |first1=Toluse |last2=Kim |first2=Seung Min |title=Republicans deliver rare rebuke of Trump, slamming his Syria withdrawal decision |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/mcconnell-joins-other-republicans-in-rebuking-trumps-syria-withdrawal/2019/10/07/aef0d11e-e914-11e9-9306-47cb0324fd44_story.html |website=Washington Post |date=8 October 2019}}</ref> Meanwhile, several commentators in Moscow have stated that the situation is not in the immediate Russian interests, as the Turkish intervention in Syria clashes with Russia's backing of the Syrian government in the region, but it may provide opportunities for Russia as mediator as the US withdraws from Syria.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sherwin |first1=Emily |title=Turkey offensive in Syria forces Russia into a balancing act |url=https://www.dw.com/en/turkey-offensive-in-syria-forces-russia-into-a-balancing-act/a-50828950 |website=Deutsche Welle |date=14 October 2019 }}</ref> Commentators have remarked that, since the US withdrawal, Russia has cemented its status as the key power broker in the Middle East.<ref name=ol-ram/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Rosenberg |first1=Steve |title=Putin: From pariah to Middle East power broker |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-50068498 |website=BBC |date=17 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Pitarakis |first1=Lefteris |last2=Mroue |first2=Bassem |title=Russia Seeks to Cement its Role as a Power Broker in Syria |url=https://time.com/5701729/russia-troops-syria-turkey-conflict/ |website=Time |language=en |date=16 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nDue to the situation in Syria, there are signs of a schism between Turkey and other [[NATO]] members, in which NATO is seen as effectively \"powerless\" to manage the situation and the Turkish government is aware that NATO does not hold much leverage.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stolton |first1=Samuel |title=Turkey's relationship with NATO tested over Syria operation |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/turkey-relationship-nato-tested-syria-operation-191013190857028.html |website=Aljazeera | date=14 October 2019}}</ref> Furthermore, US President Trump, as well as US military and diplomatic officials, has cited the NATO membership of Turkey as a key reason that the United States can not be involved in the conflict between the Turkish and Syrian Kurdish forces.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wolfgang |first1=Ben |last2=Glenn |first2=Mike |title=Turkey's NATO status complicates U.S. response to Erdogan's Syria incursion |url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2019/oct/16/turkey-nato-status-complicates-response-erdogan-sy/ |website=The Washington Times |date=16 October 2019}}</ref> Meanwhile, due to Turkey's strategic position between Europe and the Middle East, the NATO alliance members are in a situation where they have limited themselves to relatively muted criticism.<ref>{{cite web |title=Esper chides NATO ally Turkey for \"heading in the wrong direction\" with Russia in Syria |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/turkey-syria-wrong-direction-russia-mark-esper-says-us-nato-ally-donald-trump-lauds-ceasefire-2019-10-24/ |website=CBS News |date=24 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe U.S. is reviewing the potential withdrawal of its [[Nuclear weapons of the United States|nuclear weapons]] from [[Incirlik airbase]] under NATO's [[nuclear sharing]] as a result of the Turkish offensive per [[The New York Times|NYT]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/amid-rising-tensions-us-said-considering-plan-to-remove-nukes-from-turkish-base/|title=US said considering plan to remove nukes from Turkish base near Syrian border|first=T. O. I.|last=staff|website=timesofisrael.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/u-s-turkey-tensions-fears-future-nuclear-weapons-syria-donald-trump-erdogan-1465331|title=U.S.-Turkey tensions raise fears over future of nuclear weapons near Syria|first=David|last=Brennan|date=15 October 2019|website=Newsweek}}</ref> Republican senator Lindsay Graham<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2019/10/turkey-and-nato-troubled-relationship/599890/|title=Why is Turkey in NATO Anyway?|agency=The Atlantic}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/lindsey-graham-warns-turkey-nato-suspension-sanctions-if-kurds-attacked-2019-10|title=Lindsey Graham says Congress will call for Turkey to be suspended from NATO and hit it with sanctions if it attacks Kurds|agency=Business Insider|date=7 October 2019}}</ref> and Democratic representative [[Eric Swalwell]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/465847-democratic-lawmaker-expelling-turkey-from-nato-should-be-on-the-table|title=Democratic lawmaker: Expelling Turkey from NATO 'should be on the table'|agency=The Hill|date=15 October 2019}}</ref> have called for possibly suspending Turkey's membership in NATO.\n===Agreement to Northern Buffer Zone===\n{{main|Second Northern Syria Buffer Zone}} \n\nRussia and Turkey made an agreement via the [[Sochi Agreement of 2019]] to set up a [[Second Northern Syria Buffer Zone]]. Syrian President Assad expressed full support for the deal, as various terms of the agreement also applied to the Syrian government.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-50152235|title=Russia deploys troops to Turkey-Syria border|date=2019-10-23|access-date=2019-10-24|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref> [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/oct/22/turkey-and-russia-agree-deal-over-buffer-zone-in-northern-syria Turkey and Russia agree on deal over buffer zone in northern Syria]. Erdo\u011fan hails agreement with Putin in which Kurdish fighters will be moved from border area. guardian.com. </ref> \n\nThe agreement reportedly included the following terms:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/turkeys-erdogan-meets-with-putin-in-russia-to-discuss-syrian-operation/2019/10/22/764abcea-f43f-11e9-b2d2-1f37c9d82dbb_story.html|title=Russia and Turkey reach deal to push Kurdish forces out of zone in northern Syria|last=Fahim|first=Kareem|last2=DeYoung|date=|website=Washington Post|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/german-defense-minister-proposes-security-zone-for-syria/2019/10/22/19af90b8-f49f-11e9-b2d2-1f37c9d82dbb_story.html|title=Russia, Turkey seal power in northeast Syria with new accord|last=Fraser|first=Suzan|last2=AP|first2=Vladimir Isachenkov {{!}}|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-50152235|title=Russia deploys troops to Turkey-Syria border|date=2019-10-23|access-date=2019-10-24|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/russia-syria-map-troops-deal-turkey-1467252|title=Russia shows off new Syria map, sends troops to border after its deal with Turkey|last=EDT|first=Tom O'Connor On 10/23/19 at 11:49 AM|date=2019-10-23|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ragipsoylu/status/1186692319703130119|title=LATEST \u2014 Here is the complete text of Turkish, Russian agreement on Northern Syria, that pushed YPG 30km from Turkish, Syria borderpic.twitter.com/jwiOurbfa3|last=Soylu|first=Rag\u0131p|date=2019-10-22|website=@ragipsoylu|language=en|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref><ref>[https://lobelog.com/the-sochi-agreement-and-its-implications/ The Sochi Agreement And Its Implications] OCTOBER 25, 2019.</ref>\n\n* A buffer zone would be established in Northern Syria. The zone would be around '''{{Convert|30|km|mi|abbr=}}''' deep,{{Efn|Starting from the [[Syrian-Turkish border]] and going south into Syria|name=|group=}} stretching from [[Euphrates River]] to [[Tall Abyad]] and from [[Ras al-Ayn]] to the Iraq-Syria border, but excluding the town of [[Qamishli]], the Kurds' ''de facto'' capital.{{Efn|See the \"External links\" section in the article [[Second Northern Syria Buffer Zone]], for a link to an article containing an explanatory map of the buffer zone.|name=|group=}}\n* The buffer zone would be controlled jointly by the [[Syrian Army]] and [[Russian Military Police]].\n* All [[YPG]] forces, which constitute the majority of the SDF, must withdraw from the buffer zone entirely, along with their weapons, within 150 hours from the announcement of the deal. Their withdrawal would be overseen by Russian Military Police and the Syrian Border Guards, which would enter the zone at noon on 23 October.\n* The YPG would also withdraw from the cities of [[Manbij]] and [[Tell Rifaat]].{{Efn|Both of these cities are further to the south and not covered by the depth of the buffer zone, but are nonetheless explicitly mentioned in the agreement.|name=|group=}}\n* Following the YPG withdrawal, joint Russian-Turkish ground patrols would be held in the buffer zone area, but only within '''{{Convert|10|km|mi|abbr=}}''' from the border and not including Qamishli.{{Efn|No joint patrols will be held in the remaining part of the buffer zone.|name=|group=}}{{Efn|Later, the Turkish President announced that the patrols would only be held to a depth of 7km, as opposed to 10. No reason was given for this change.|name=|group=}}\n* Turkey would retain sole control of the areas it had captured during its offensive between the towns of [[Tell Abyad]] and [[Ras al-Ayn]].\n* The [[Syrian Government]] would construct and man 15 border posts on the [[Turkish-Syrian border]].\n* The parties would launch a joint effort to resettle [[Syrian refugee]]s in a \"safe and voluntary manner\". \n* The parties would agree to \"preserve the political unity and territorial integrity of Syria\" as well as protect the \"national security of Turkey\".\n* The parties would agree to reaffirm the importance of the [[Adana Agreement]]. Russia will facilitate the implementation of the Adana Agreement.\n===Reactions===\nVarious parties reacted to this new agreement, as follows. \n\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of United Nations.svg}} [[United Nations]] - On 1 November 2019 the UN Secretary-General met with President Erdogan of Turkey to discuss Turkey's proposal to relocate a large number of Syrian Refugees in Turkey to the Safe Zone. Mr. Guterres informed the Turkish President that the UNHCR will immediately form a team to study the proposal and engage in discussions with Turkish authorities, in line with its mandate.<ref name=\"un.org\">https://www.un.org/sg/en/content/sg/readout/2019-11-01/readout-of-the-secretary-general%E2%80%99s-meeting-he-mr-recep-tayyip-erdogan-president-of-turkey</ref><ref>https://news.un.org/en/story/2019/11/1050451</ref> The Secretary-General greenlighted the proposal but told the Turkish President that the relocations should be \"voluntary, safe and dignified\".<ref name=\"un.org\"/>\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Syrian Democratic Forces.svg}} [[Syrian Democratic Forces]] - The SDF stated that they consider themselves as \"Syrian and a part of Syria\", adding that they will agree to work with the Syrian Government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/10/23/772557773/kurdish-reaction-to-turkey-russia-deal-to-patrol-northern-syria|title=Kurdish Reaction To Turkey-Russia Deal To Patrol Northern Syria|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref> The SDF officially announced their support for the deal on October 27.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://syrianobserver.com/EN/news/53885/sdf-agrees-to-sochi-deal-for-northern-syria.html|title=SDF Agrees to Sochi Deal for Northern Syria|date=2019-10-28|website=The Syrian Observer|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://ekurd.net/syrian-kurds-say-pulling-2019-10-28|title=Syrian Kurds say pulling out from entire length of Turkey border|last=Staff|first=Editorial|date=2019-10-28|website=Kurd Net - Ekurd.net Daily News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Syria}} - Syrian President [[Bashar al-Assad]] thanked the Russian President for his role in the negotiation of the deal and expressed his full support for it. At the same time, he raised concerns about Turkish interference in Syrian affairs and dubbed Turkish President Erdogan a \"thief\".<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/turkey-russia-agree-clear-kurdish-fighters-control-syria-turkey-border-n1070141|title=Turkey, Russia agree to clear Kurdish fighters and control the Syria-Turkey border|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref>\n*{{Flag|Turkey}} - Turkish President [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] threatened to forcefully \"clear terrorists\" from the Syrian-Turkish border should the deal fail. He further reiterated his threat to let the Syrian refugees residing in Turkey at that point to freely emigrate into Europe, if Turkey does not receive \"support\" in its plan for the relocation of 1 to 2 million refugees within the buffer zone in what the Turkish President dubbed the \"first stage\" of their return.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/middle-east/erdogan-says-will-clear-terrorists-syria-border-if-sochi-deal-fails|title=Erdogan Says Will 'Clear Terrorists' From Syria Border if Sochi Deal Fails|website=Voice of America|language=en|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Iran}} - Iran's foreign ministry called the agreement \"a positive step\" and stated that it \"backed any move to restore stability in the region\".<ref name=\":2\" />\n* {{Flag|United States}} - US President [[Donald Trump]] praised the deal that he viewed as allowing \"someone else [to] fight over this long bloodstained land\", following which he ordered the lifting of the sanctions that he had placed on Turkey nine days prior as a reaction to the start of Turkey's offensive.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-50157439|title=Trump lifts sanctions on Turkey over Syria assault|date=2019-10-23|access-date=2019-10-24|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n*{{Flag|Germany}} - German Chancellor [[Angela Merkel]] proposed that the buffer zone be enforced through an international force. Turkish Foreign Minister [[Mevl\u00fct \u00c7avu\u015fo\u011flu]] rejected the plan, dubbing it \"unrealistic\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/turkey-rejects-german-security-zone-plan-unrealistic-191026141506342.html|title=Turkey rejects German security zone plan as 'unrealistic'|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2019-10-27}}</ref>\n\n==General operational developments, December 2019 to present==\n{{updated|12-11-2019}} ''updated''\n\nAs a result of the Turkish incursion, multiple Kurdish groups that were once rivals have begun to seek greater unity. Additionally, Syrian Kurdish officials have had some positive discussions with the Assad government, and with local countries such as Saudi Arabia, UAE and Jordan.<ref name=\"al-monitor overview\"> [https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2019/12/turkey-syria-gulf-ankara-kurdish-sweep-backfiring.html Turkey\u2019s Kurdish sweep backfires], Fehim Tastekin December 11, 2019, al-monitor.com</ref>\n\nOn the ground, Turkish areas of operations have been delineated by Russian mediators. Russian military officials forged agreements between Syria, Turkey and Kurds for areas to be patrolled by each side.<ref> [https://ahvalnews.com/northern-syria/russian-forces-syria-sdf-discuss-phase-two-border-security-deal Russian forces in Syria, SDF discuss phase two in border security deal], Dec 07 2019. </ref> Russia handles security through its own forces deployed in some key towns. \n\nThe Assad government has forged agreements with some opposition groups to return to various local border areas.<ref name=\"al-monitor overview\"/> The Syrian Democratic Forces (SDF) reached agreement with the Assad regime for the Syrian Army to patrol several border areas. They also agreed on areas of deployment for Russian forces.<ref> [https://ahvalnews.com/northern-syria/russian-forces-syria-sdf-discuss-phase-two-border-security-deal Russian forces in Syria, SDF discuss phase two in border security deal], Dec 07 2019, ahvalnews.com. </ref> The first agreement between SDF and the Assad regime occurred in October 2019, directly as a result of the Turkish incursion.<ref> [https://ahvalnews.com/operation-peace-spring/live-day-6-turkeys-syria-operation Live: Day 6 of Turkey's Syria operation],\nAhval, Oct 14 2019. </ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://syrianobserver.com/EN/news/53885/sdf-agrees-to-sochi-deal-for-northern-syria.html|title=SDF Agrees to Sochi Deal for Northern Syria|date=2019-10-28|website=The Syrian Observer|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://ekurd.net/syrian-kurds-say-pulling-2019-10-28|title=Syrian Kurds say pulling out from entire length of Turkey border|last=Staff|first=Editorial|date=2019-10-28|website=Kurd Net - Ekurd.net Daily News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref>\n\nIn general positive negotiations have increased between Syria and Turkey, and between Syria and Kurdish groups.<ref> [https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2019/12/the-takeaway-december-11-2019.html The Takeaway: December 11, 2019], Andrew Parasiliti December 11, 2019. </ref>\n\nOn December 9, Russian troops entered Raqqa and began distributing humanitarian aid.<ref> [https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Russian-forces-enter-former-Islamic-State-stronghold-in-Syria-610347 Russian forces enter former Islamic State stronghold in Syria]:Russian troops in Raqqa were handing out humanitarian aid and its military doctors were offering residents medical attention. By REUTERS DECEMBER 9, 2019. </ref><ref> [https://thedefensepost.com/2019/12/10/syria-russia-raqqa-us-withdraw/ Russian troops enter Syria\u2019s Raqqa, filling void of withdrawing US forces], by Jared Szuba DECEMBER 10, 2019. </ref><ref> [https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Russians-in-Raqqa-two-years-after-US-helped-take-city-from-ISIS-610377 Russians near Raqqa two years after US helped take city from ISIS] By SETH J. FRANTZMAN DECEMBER 9, 2019. </ref>\n\nRussia and Syria escalated their attacks against rebel forces in [[Idlib]].<ref> [https://www.voanews.com/extremism-watch/russian-syrian-regime-forces-step-attacks-rebel-stronghold-idlib Russian, Syrian Regime Forces Step Up Attacks on Rebel Stronghold Idlib], By Sirwan Kajjo, December 08, 2019 </ref>\n\n===Refugees status===\nNumerous refugees remain in local refugee camps. Conditions there are reported to be severe, especially with winter approaching.<ref name=\"washokani\"> [https://anfenglishmobile.com/rojava-syria/winter-threatens-the-idps-in-the-washokani-camp-39991 Winter threatens the IDPs in the Washokani Camp].For the displaced people in northern and eastern Syria, winter is a torture: many set up for those seeking shelter have already collapsed due to rain and wind. Almost all international aid organisations are watching the misery. ANF HESEK\u00ca  Tuesday, 10 Dec 2019. </ref>\n\n4,000 people are housed at the Washokani Camp. No organizations are assisting them other than the Kurdish Red Cross. Numerous camp residents have called for assistance from international groups.<ref> [https://anfenglishmobile.com/rojava-syria/over-3500-refugees-accommodated-in-the-washokani-camp-39924 Over 3500 refugees accommodated in the Washokani camp]. The Washokani camp, set up by the autonomous administration of North-East Syria near Hesek\u00ea, now hosts 3566 people who have fled the Turkish occupation troops in Ser\u00eakaniy\u00ea. ANF HESEK\u00ca  Saturday, 7 Dec 2019. </ref><ref> [https://anfenglishmobile.com/rojava-syria/no-help-for-people-displaced-by-the-turkish-invasion-39771 No help for people displaced by the Turkish invasion]. More than 2,500 people now live in the northern Syrian camp Washokani who had to flee due to the Turkish occupation war. No help has arrived from international organisations yet. ANF HESEKE Sunday, 1 Dec 2019. </ref> \n\nRefugees in Northeast Syria report they have received no help from international aid organizations.<ref> [https://anfenglishmobile.com/rojava-syria/ignorance-of-aid-organisations-exacerbates-the-situation-of-idps-39283 Ignorance of aid organisations exacerbates the situation of IDPs] Hundreds of thousands have fled home due to the attacks of the AKP regime and its gangs on Northern Syria. The living conditions of the refugees are being exacerbated by the ignorance of international aid organisations. ANF HESEKE Wednesday, 13 Nov 2019. </ref>\n\n===Syrian and Kurdish actions===\nSome reports stated that Bashar Assad was favorable towards Russia's efforts to restore calm and to stabilize the situation in Syria.<ref> [https://frontline.thehindu.com/world-affairs/article30025808.ece Syria: Russian helping hand], by JOHN CHERIAN, December 06, 2019. </ref>\n\nMeanwhile various Kurdish faction that were historical rivals began to meet in order to work together more. Their stated reason was to stand together against Russia and Turkey more strongly if needed.<ref> [https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2019/12/sdf-woo-syria-kurd-rivals-turkey-assault.html SDF woos Syrian Kurdish rivals in wake of Turkish assault], Amberin Zaman December 4, 2019. </ref><ref name=\"what now\"> [https://www.rudaw.net/english/middleeast/syria/09122019 2 months of Operation Peace Spring: what now?] Karwan Faidhi Dri, Dec 10, 2019. </ref> The Russian government has informed the Kurdish factions that they should reconcile and come up with a unified set of demands to clarify to Russia.<ref> [https://www.rudaw.net/english/middleeast/syria/10122019 Russia wants Syrian Kurds to unify, clarify their demands of Moscow: Kurdish opposition] Karwan Faidhi Dri, Dec 10, 2019. </ref> Various Kurdish factions blamed each other and their council for lack of progress.<ref> [https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2019/12/kurds-syria-pyd-national-council-russia-syrian-regime.html Syria\u2019s Kurdish parties do not see eye to eye], Shivan Ibrahim December 9, 2019. </ref>\n\nMustafa Bali, head of the Syrian Democratic Forces (SDF) said there were some agreements on the ground with the Syrian government, for Syrian forces to be deployed along the border.<ref> [https://www.rudaw.net/english/interview/09122019 Mustafa Bali: Turkey continues to violate ceasefire deals, targets Kurds], Dec 9, 2019. </ref> \n\nThe national Syrian government sent representatives to northeast Syria to meet with local groups there in order to address their concerns and to emphasize unity and combined effort to address problems.<ref> [https://www.hawarnews.com/en/haber/faisal-azouz-our-goal-is-to-know-regions-project-we-do-not-wish-to-see-any-disagreement-h13091.html Faisal Azouz: Our goal is to know region's project, we do not wish to see any disagreement]. The coordinator of the National Dialogue Follow-up Committee of the Arab Socialist Baath Party, Faisal, indicated that they are looking for ways to find a formula for compatibility between the Autonomous Administration project and Article 107 of the Syrian constitution related to local administrations. 08 Dec 2019, Sun - 13:54 2019-12-08T13:54:00 QAMISHLO_ SHINDA AKRAM \u2013 AKRAM BARAKAT. </ref>A meeting occurred in Qamishli city, in northeast Syria, that included Syrian national officials, and delegates from Kurdish, Arab, and Syrian figures and forces.<ref> [https://aawsat.com/english/home/article/2027786/northeast-syria-between-autonomous-local-administrations Northeast Syria Between Autonomous, Local Administrations], Monday, 9 December, 2019. </ref> Kurdish delegates emphasized their desire to help to protect Syria as a whole. They expressed willingness to have positive discussions with the Assad government.<ref> [https://www.kurdistan24.net/en/news/e0a4a994-9c19-4560-af63-eeddc1c0aac2 Syrian delegation explores dialogue between Kurds and Damascus, following US withdrawal] by Wladimir van Wilgenburg, December 10, 2019. </ref> \n\nLuqman Ehm\u00ea, spokesman for the North East Syria Autonomous Administration, said that his organization was ready for positive discussions with the Syrian regime.<ref> [https://anfenglish.com/rojava-syria/ehme-we-are-ready-for-dialogue-with-damascus-39977 Ehm\u00ea: We are ready for dialogue with Damascus]  ANF RAQQA Tuesday, 10 Dec 2019, 09:33.\n\"We are ready for dialogue with the Damascus government for a lasting solution to the Syrian crisis,\" said Luqman Ehm\u00ea, spokesman for the North East Syria Autonomous Administration in a press release. </ref>\n\nSDF General Commander Mazlum Abdi has met with local leaders of the Wise Committee, which is composed of leaders of local communities and local family groupings. This meeting emphasized the importance on national unity, and the need to stand against Turkish invaders.<ref> [https://anfenglishmobile.com/rojava-syria/sdf-general-commander-abdi-met-wise-leaders-40002 SDF General Commander Abdi met Wise leaders]. SDF General Commander Mazlum Abdi met with the Committee of Wise people in North and East Syria. At the meeting, developments in the region were discussed. NF NEWS DESK Wednesday, 11 Dec 2019. </ref>\n\nSDF Commander Mazlum Abdi called on the US and Russia to help stop Turkey from displacing entire communities and ethnic groups from the areas that it controls.<ref> [https://www.kurdistan24.net/en/news/b622efd0-c175-4602-aa3c-a118cd8ee09e Syrian Kurdish leader calls on US, Russia to prevent ethnic cleansing by Turkey], Wladimir van Wilgenburg Wladimir van Wilgenburg | December 11, 2019. </ref>\n\n===Turkish actions===\nErdogan stated that Turkey was ready to resettle the Syrian refugees in the northern area that Turkey had invaded, and that Turkey would pay for it if necessary.<ref> [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-security-turkey/erdogan-says-turkey-aims-to-settle-1-million-refugees-in-syria-offensive-area-idUSKBN1YD27R Erdogan says Turkey aims to settle 1 million refugees in Syria offensive area], reuters, December 9, 2019. </ref> On December 9, 2019, various local accounts indicated that Turkey was moving Syrian refugees into its zone of operations in Northern Syria for the first time.<ref> [https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/12/09/turkey-resettling-refugees-northeastern-syria/ Turkey Begins Resettling Refugees in Northeastern Syria: Continued reports of atrocities by Turkish-backed forces raise concerns about ethnic cleansing]. BY LARA SELIGMAN | DECEMBER 9, 2019. </ref> Erdogan said that Turkey was working to settle one million people in the cities of Tal Abyad and Ras Al-Ain in northern Syria.<ref> [https://www.shafaaq.com/en/world/erdogan-announces-start-working-to-house-one-million-people-in-northern-syria/ Erdogan announces start working to house one million people in northern Syria], December 9, 2019. </ref>This has led to fears of population change<ref>https://www.newyorker.com/news/q-and-a/americas-ally-in-syria-warns-of-ethnic-cleansing-by-turkey</ref>\n\nRussia said it would pledge to remove Turkish forces from a key highway in northern Syria, and replace them with Russian forces to maintain stability.<ref> [https://www.rudaw.net/english/middleeast/syria/051220193 Russia has pledged to remove Turkish forces from strategic highway], 05-12-2019 by Karwan Faidhi Dri. </ref> Meanwhile, Turkey began to appoint local mayors and governors in several northern Syrian towns.<ref> [https://www.rudaw.net/english/middleeast/syria/06122019 Turkey appoints mayors in recently invaded northern Syrian towns], 06-12-2019, Karwan Faidhi Dri. </ref> They have also appointed about 4,000 police officers and other local officials, and are providing some basic local services for citizens.<ref> [https://ahvalnews.com/turkey-syria/turkey-appoint-4000-police-officers-syria Turkey to appoint 4,000 police officers to Syria], Dec 07 2019. </ref> \n\nIt was reported that the Russian and Turkish armies had made a deal whereby electricity would be supplied to Tal Abyad by Russia's allies, the Kurdish-led Syrian Democratic Forces (SDF) who support Assad; while water would be supplied by the Alouk water station that is controlled by Turkish forces.<ref> [https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20191209-russia-and-turkey-armies-strike-deal-to-swap-water-for-electricity/ Russia and Turkey armies strike deal to swap water for electricity], December 9, 2019, middleeastmonitor.com </ref> This deal was mainly facilitated by Russian military officials.<ref> [https://www.kurdistan24.net/en/news/860c5e68-1e9e-4bb5-a014-6a3505d90ad4 Russians appear to broker deal with Turkey in electricity for water swap in Syria], Wladimir van Wilgenburg Wladimir van Wilgenburg |December 09-2019. </ref>\n\nIt appeared that Turkey was withdrawing all of its forces away from the al-Shirkark silos, which hold important supplies of wheat, this seemed to be a result of Russian mediation.<ref> [https://www.hawarnews.com/en/haber/what-is-happening-in-al-shirkark-silos-in-ain-issa-district-h13119.html What is happening in al-Shirkark silos in Ain Issa district?]\nThe Turkish occupation army withdrew from al-Shirkrak silo, according it seems agreement with Russia, while yesterday, the Russian forces headed with the Syrian regime to remove mines in the silos' vicinity, we have no precise information about the forces which will be stationed in the silos. 10 Dec 2019, Tue - 14:38 2019-12-10T14:38:00 AIN ISSA \u2013 SHARVIN MUSTAFA. hawarnews.com</ref> However, some reports said they later returned to re-occupy that area.<ref> [https://anfenglishmobile.com/rojava-syria/turkish-forces-re-occupy-the-wheat-silo-it-retreated-from-39989 Turkish forces re-occupy the wheat silo they retreated from.] AIN ISSA Tuesday, 10 Dec 2019. </ref>\n\nRussian and Turkish forces are continuing their joint patrols.<ref name=\"what now\"> [https://www.rudaw.net/english/middleeast/syria/09122019 2 months of Operation Peace Spring: what now?] Karwan Faidhi Dri, Dec 10, 2019. </ref> Questions remained about how much control Turkey has over its proxies, such as the Free Syrian Army.<ref> [https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/11/23/life-on-the-front-lines-in-northern-syria/ Life on the Front Lines in Northern Syria]; With echoes of shelling from Turkish-allied forces nearby, families sheltering in abandoned villages wonder when they can go home. BY JADE SACKER, NOVEMBER 23, 2019. </ref>\n\n==Diplomatic developments, December 2019 to present==\nAt a panel discussion on the conflict in December 2019, several experts said the conflict was slowly moving towards resolution. One expert said that the \"Astana\" diplomatic process, involving Turkey, Russia, and Iran, was having some positive results. Experts also said that Bashar Assad had made progress in restoring rule by local councils in areas affected by the conflict.<ref> [https://cyprus-mail.com/2019/12/08/syria-the-most-complex-conflict-of-our-time/ Syria: the most complex conflict of our time], By Elias Hazou, December 8, 2019 </ref>\n===Diplomacy with NATO member nations===\nAt the NATO summit in London in December 2019, President Emmanuel Macron of France highlighted major differences with Turkey over the definition of terrorism, and said there was little chance this aspect of the conflict could be resolved positively.<ref> [https://www.express.co.uk/news/world/1214065/emmanuel-macron-news-turkey-syria-terrorism-definition Macron and Turkey clash over terrorism after Syria conflict 'No consensus possible!'] By ROMINA MCGUINNESS,  Dec 6, 2019. </ref> Macron criticized Turkey strongly for fighting against groups who had been allied with France and the West in fighting terrorism.<ref name=\"euobserver nato\"> [https://euobserver.com/foreign/146810 Macron spars with US and Turkey over Nato], By NIKOLAJ NIELSEN BRUSSELS, 4. DEC, euobserver.com. </ref> \n\nNumerous issues in resolving the conflict emerged at the NATO summit in London. Turkey proposed a safe zone where Syrian refugees could be relocated, but this idea did not receive support from all parties.<ref name=\"euobserver nato\"/> One professed \"exclusive\" press report claimed that prior to the NATO Summit, there was a meeting at 10 Downing Street of the leaders of France, the UK, Germany and Turkey. One key point that emerged that the Western countries insisted that refugees could only be relocated voluntarily.<ref> [https://www.dailysabah.com/columns/yahya_bostan/2019/12/09/exclusive-details-of-erdogans-meeting-with-johnson-merkel-and-macron Exclusive details of Erdo\u011fan's meeting with Johnson, Merkel and Macron], by Yahya Bostan, dailysabah.com </ref> Meanwhile, there were concerns in NATO about Turkey's growing closeness with Russia.<ref> [https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2019/12/turkey-united-states-russia-is-erdogan-trojan-horse-in-nato.html Erdogan in NATO: Russia\u2019s \u2018Trojan horse\u2019?], by Cengiz Candar December 9, 2019.</ref>\n\nErdogan claimed that a four-way summit on Syria was scheduled to occur in Turkey in February 2020, to include Turkey, Germany, the UK and France.<ref> [http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/a-four-way-summit-on-syria-will-be-in-turkey-149498 A four-way summit on Syria will be in Turkey], NewsTurkey December 05 2019. </ref>\n\n===Diplomacy with nations outside NATO===\nAt a meeting in Damascus, Russian and Syrian officials clearly stated their support for Syria regaining control over all of its territory.<ref> [https://aawsat.com/english/home/article/2018801/putin%E2%80%99s-envoy-tells-assad-russia-supports-%E2%80%98recapturing-all-syrian-territories%E2%80%99 Putin\u2019s Envoy Tells Assad Russia Supports \u2018Recapturing All Syrian Territories\u2019], Tuesday, 3 December, 2019. </ref><ref> [https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2019/12/intel-russia-change-course-syria.html Intel: How Russia is changing course in Syria], Maxim A. Suchkov December 3, 2019. </ref><ref> [https://www.mid.ru/en/foreign_policy/news/-/asset_publisher/cKNonkJE02Bw/content/id/3928776 Press release on Russian officials\u2019 meeting with President of Syria Bashar al-Assad], 02-12-2019. </ref> The United Arab Emirates also expressed official support for Assad.<ref> [https://www.newsweek.com/uae-officially-backs-syria-assad-win-1475341 UAE OFFICIALLY BACKS SYRIA'S ASSAD TO WIN WAR], BY TOM O'CONNOR ON 12/3/19. </ref>\n\nA new round of meetings for the Astana summit process took place in the Kazakh capital Nur Sultan. The meeting includes Russia, Syria, Turkey and Iran.<ref> [https://www.hawarnews.com/en/haber/astana-round-begins-with-a-meeting-between-the-meeting-sponsors-h13118.html Astana round begins with a meeting between the meeting sponsors]\nThe 14th round of the Astana meetings began in the Kazakh capital Nur Sultan on Tuesday morning with a series of meetings of the meeting sponsors (Russia, Turkey and Iran). 10 Dec 2019, Tue - 14:07 2019-12-10T14:07:00 NEWS DESK </ref> At this meeting Russia, stated that the \"safe zone\" established by Turkey should not be expanded, as this would not accomplish anything positive for the region.<ref> [https://www.rudaw.net/english/world/10122019 Astana talks: Expanding Syria \u2018safe zone\u2019 will \u2018do nothing good\u2019, says Russian envoy], 18 hours ago, Karwan Faidhi Dri, rudaw.net. </ref>\n\nThe Astana process was created by Turkey, Iran and Russia in order to find a lasting solution to the conflict. they have examined a process to reform the constitution of Syria via the newly-formed Syrian Constitutional Committee.<ref name=\"Astana Sabah\"> [https://www.dailysabah.com/syrian-crisis/2019/12/10/regime-continues-to-violate-sochi-deal-amid-diplomatic-efforts-for-political-solution-in-syria Regime continues to violate Sochi deal amid diplomatic efforts for political solution in Syria] DAILY SABAH, ISTANBUL Published Dec. 10, 2019.</ref> The parties reported that they reached some important understandings at this meeting, including affirming a commitment to work together to respect Syrian territorial integrity.<ref> [https://www.inform.kz/en/14th-round-led-to-significant-results-mfa-about-the-astana-process-on-syria_a3593712 14th round led to significant results, MFA about the Astana process on Syria], 11 December 2019, inform.kz, kazinform news agency. </ref>\n\n==Syrian Constitutional Committee==\n{{main|Syrian Constitutional Committee}}\n\nOn November 20, 2019, a new [[Syrian Constitutional Committee]] began operating in order to discuss a new settlement and to draft a new constitution for Syria.<ref name=\"Astana Sabah\"> [https://www.dailysabah.com/syrian-crisis/2019/12/10/regime-continues-to-violate-sochi-deal-amid-diplomatic-efforts-for-political-solution-in-syria Regime continues to violate Sochi deal amid diplomatic efforts for political solution in Syria] DAILY SABAH, ISTANBUL Published Dec. 10, 2019.</ref>  This committee comprises about 150 members. It includes representatives of the Syrian regime, opposition groups, and countries serving as guarantors of the process such as e.g. Russia. However, this committee has faced strong opposition from the Assad regime. 50 of the committee members represent the regime, and 50 members represent the opposition. The committee began its work in November 2019 in Geneva, under UN auspices. However, the Assad regime delegation left on the second day of the process.<ref name=\"Astana Sabah\"/> \n\nAt a summit in October 2018, envoys from Russia, Turkey, France and Germany issued a joint statement affirming the need to respect territorial integrity of Syria as a whole. This forms one basis for their role as \"guarantor nations.\"<ref name=\"Astana Sabah\"/> \n\nThe second round of talks occurred around November 25th, but was not successful due to opposition from the Assad regime.<ref name=\"Astana Sabah\"/>  At the Astana Process meeting in December 2019, a UN official stated that in order for the third round of talks to proceed, co-chairs from the Assad regime and the opposition need to agree on an agenda.<ref name=\"Astana Sabah\"/> \n\nThe committee has two co-chairs, Ahmad Kuzbari representing the Assad regime, and Hadi Albahra from the opposition. It is unclear if the third round of talks will proceed on a firm schedule, until the Assad regime provides its assent to participate.<ref name=\"Astana Sabah\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[NATO]]\n* [[Arab League]]\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links|wikt=no|commons=Category:Syrian Civil War|b=no|n=Category:Syrian Civil War|q=no|s=no|v=no|voy=no|display=the Syrian Civil War}}\n'''Interviews'''\n* [https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20161205135549/http://nation.foxnews.com/2013/09/18/fox-news-exclusive-interview-syrian-president-bashar-al-assad Fox News exclusive interview with Syrian President Bashar Al-Assad] [[Fox News]], 18 September 2013\n* [http://www.presidentassad.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&id=307&Itemid=468 Interview with Bashar Assad: 'In the End, a Lie Is a Lie'] [[Der Spiegel]], 7 October 2013\n* [http://www.spiegel.de/international/world/spiegel-interview-with-syrian-president-bashar-assad-a-926456.html President Bashar al-Assad's interview with Agence France Presse AFP 20-01-2014] 20 January 2014\n* A discussion of the [http://www.monitor.upeace.org/innerpg.cfm?id_article=1017 causes of the civil war] at the ''[[United Nations University for Peace]]''.\n* [http://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2013/12/al-qaeda-leader-syria-speaks-al-jazeera-20131218155917935989.html First ever broadcast interview with Jabhat al Nusra founder Abu Mohammed al-Joulani]\n'''Supranational government bodies'''\n* [http://www.fao.org/emergencies/crisis/syria/en/ FAO \u2013 Syria crisis]\n'''Human rights bodies'''\n* [http://www.icrc.org/eng/where-we-work/middle-east/syria/index.jsp The ICRC in Syria], [[International Committee of the Red Cross]]\n'''Media'''\n* [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-17258397 Syria's war] at ''[[BBC News]]''\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/special/world/syrian-uprising-one-year-of-bloodshed/index.html Syrian uprising: A year in turmoil] at ''[[The Washington Post]]''\n* [http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/syria-pulse Syria Pulse] collected news and commentary at ''[[Al Monitor]]''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160320165721/https://now.mmedia.me/lb/en/Now-Syria/latest_syria_developments Latest Syria developments] at ''[[NOW Lebanon]]''\n* {{Guardian topic|2=Syria}}\n* [http://topics.nytimes.com/top/news/international/countriesandterritories/syria/index.html Syria] collected news and commentary at ''[[The New York Times]]''\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/syria/ Syria news, all the latest and breaking Syria news] at ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''\n* [http://www.aljazeera.com/topics/country/syria.html Syria] collected coverage at ''[[Al Jazeera English]]''\n* [http://www.intelligenceonline.com/search/search.aspx?keywords=Syria Syria] collected news at ''[[Intelligence Online]]''\n* [https://syriancivilwarmap.com/ Interactive Map of the Syrian Civil War]\n* [https://www.newsdeeply.com/syria Syria Deeply] at [[News Deeply]]\n* [http://omniatlas.com/maps/europe/20151007/ Maps of Europe and Syrian Civil War (omniatlas.com)]\n\n{{Syrian Civil War}}\n{{Syria topics}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list1 = \n{{Ongoing military conflicts}}\n{{Arab Spring}}\n{{Middle East conflicts}}\n{{Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant}}\n{{Post-Cold War Asian conflicts}}\n{{Iran\u2013Saudi Arabia relations}}\n{{Arab-Israeli conflict}}\n{{Russia\u2013United States relations}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Syrian Civil War}}\n{{Kurdish\u2013Turkish conflict (1978\u2013present)}}\n{{Portal bar|Asia|Kurdistan|Turkey|War}}\n\n[[Category:2010s in Syria]]\n[[Category:Politics overviews by decade]]\n", "name_user": "Fayenatic london", "label": "safe", "comment": "Copying fromCategory:Politics overviews by decadetoCategory:2010 in politicsusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2010s_in_Syria_political_history"}
{"title_page": "2010s in United Kingdom political history", "text_new": "{{see also|2020s in United Kingdom political history|2010s in political history}}\n\n{{see also|2010s#Politics and conflicts|21st century|2019 in politics and government}}\n{{Decadebox|201}}\n{{Year nav topic5|2019|the United Kingdom|politics and government|science|United Kingdom politics and government}}\n\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n\n'''2010s political history''' refers to significant political and societal historical events in the [[United Kingdom]] in the 2010s, presented as a historical overview in narrative format. \n\nThere were four Prime Ministers ([[Gordon Brown|Brown]], [[David Cameron|Cameron]], [[Theresa May|May]], [[Boris Johnson|Johnson]]), four general elections ([[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]], [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]], [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]], [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]), the same number of referendums ([[2011 Welsh devolution referendum|Further Welsh devolution]], [[2011 United Kingdom Alternative Vote referendum|voting reform]], [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|Scottish independence]], [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|Brexit]]) and three parties ([[Labour party (UK)|Labour]], [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]], [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] as a junior coalition partner) had been in government during this time. The decade began with the last months of an unpopular [[Brown ministry|Labour government]] that had been in power for 13 years and was grappling a [[Financial crisis of 2007-08|global financial crisis]], and a [[2010 United Kingdom general election|general election]] that resulted in the first [[hung parliament]] in 36 years, and ended with a [[Brexit]] deadlock that was resolved with a [[2019 United Kingdom general election|general election]] that produced the biggest Conservative majority since [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]].\n\n==History by Premiership ==\n\n===Premiership of Gordon Brown ===\n{{main|Premiership of Gordon Brown}}\n\n==== 2010 general election ====\n{{Main|2010 United Kingdom general election}}\nAt the beginning of the decade the [[United Kingdom|UK]] was governed by the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], which had been in power since its landslide victory in the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 UK general election]] before winning comfortable majorities in the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]] and [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]] general elections. The prime minister was [[Gordon Brown]], who had been in office since 2007. On 6 April 2010, Brown visited [[Buckingham Palace]] to seek [[Elizabeth II|the Queen]]'s permission to dissolve Parliament on 12 April, initiating a general election on 6 May.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/election_2010/8603591.stm|title=Brown triggers May election race|date=2010-04-06|access-date=2019-12-09|language=en-GB}}</ref> Notable events in that campaign included the UK's first televised debates between the leaders of the main parties. In these debates the prime minister was widely considered to have been outperformed by his opponents [[David Cameron]] of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] and [[Nick Clegg]] of the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/election_2010/8621119.stm|title=Leaders clash in historic debate|date=2010-04-15|access-date=2019-12-09|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/election-2010/7696467/General-Election-2010-the-great-debate-election.html|title=General Election 2010: the great debate election|date=2010-05-08|access-date=2019-12-09|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nAt the election, Labour lost 91 seats in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]], but the Conservatives failed to achieve an overall majority, resulting in the first [[hung parliament]] since [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|1974]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/election_2010/8667071.stm|title=First hung parliament for decades|date=2010-05-07|access-date=2019-12-09|language=en-GB}}</ref> Brown remained temporarily as Prime Minister, while the Liberal Democrats and Conservatives entered into talks aimed at forming a [[coalition government]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/may/07/hung-parliament-david-cameron-momentum|title=Hung parliament: David Cameron has momentum, but Brown still has power|last=Travis|first=Alan|date=2010-05-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-09|last2=editor|first2=home affairs|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/election_2010/8669508.stm|title=Lib Dems back Clegg on Tory talks|date=2010-05-08|access-date=2019-12-09|language=en-GB}}</ref> There were also talks between the Liberal Democrats and Labour.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/may/10/labour-liberal-democrats-conservative-coalition|title=Labour prepares to pounce if Liberal Democrat-Conservative coalition talks fail|last=Wintour|first=Patrick|date=2010-05-10|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-09|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> On 10 May, Brown announced his intention to resign as leader of the Labour Party and instructed the party to initiate the election of a new leader. Brown's continued presence as Prime Minister was seen an obstacle to the negotiation of a Labour-Liberal Democrat deal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/election_2010/8672859.stm|title=Brown to quit as Labour leader|date=2010-05-10|access-date=2019-12-09|language=en-GB}}</ref> In a telephone conversation with his predecessor [[Tony Blair]], Blair suggested to Brown that the election had shown that British voters had lost faith in both him and the Labour Party and that the United Kingdom would not accept him continuing as Prime Minister. He concluded that he would not be able to form a government, and announced his resignation as Prime Minister.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/election_2010/8675913.stm|title=Brown resigns as prime minister|date=2010-05-11|access-date=2019-12-09|language=en-GB}}</ref> He also resigned as leader of the Labour Party with immediate effect. Brown was succeeded as Prime Minister by David Cameron, whose party had formed a coalition with the Liberal Democrats, while [[Harriet Harman]] became acting leader of the Labour Party.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/election_2010/8675265.stm|title=Cameron is new UK prime minister|date=2010-05-12|access-date=2019-12-09|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/election_2010/8676333.stm|title=Harman made acting Labour leader|date=2010-05-11|access-date=2019-12-09|language=en-GB}}</ref> The latter until [[Ed Miliband]]'s victory in the [[2010 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|2010 labour leadership contest]] a few months later.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-11412031|title=Ed Miliband is new Labour leader|date=2010-09-25|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-17|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n\n\n=== Premiership of David Cameron ===\n{{main|Premiership of David Cameron}}\n\n==== Appointment ====\nThe [[premiership of David Cameron]] began on 11 May 2010 when [[David Cameron|Cameron]] accepted [[Elizabeth II|the Queen]]'s invitation to form a government, after the resignation of Cameron's predecessor as [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]], [[Gordon Brown]]. While serving as Prime Minister, Cameron also served as [[First Lord of the Treasury]], [[Minister for the Civil Service]] and [[Leader of the Conservative Party (UK)|Leader of the Conservative Party]]. He headed a [[#First term (2010\u201315)|coalition government]] between the Conservatives and the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]. He immediately appointed [[Nick Clegg]], the leader of the Liberal Democrats, as [[Deputy Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Deputy Prime Minister]]. Between them, the Conservatives and Liberal Democrats controlled 363 seats in the House of Commons, with a majority of 76 seats.<ref>{{cite news |author=Lyall, Sarah |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/13/world/europe/13britain.html|title= Britain's Improbable New Leaders Promise Big Changes |newspaper=The New York Times |date=25 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n==== Policies ====\nThroughout his time in office, Cameron's government attempted to reduce the large deficit in government finances through [[austerity]] measures. Internationally, his government [[Operation Ellamy|intervened militarily]] in the [[Libyan Civil War (2011)|Libyan Civil War]] and later authorised the bombing of the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]]; domestically, his government oversaw the [[2011 United Kingdom Alternative Vote referendum|referendum on voting reform]] and the [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|Scottish independence referendum]], both of which confirmed Cameron's favoured outcome (a \"No\" in each case).\n\n==== 2015 general election ====\n{{Main|2015 United Kingdom general election}}\nThe [[2015 United Kingdom general election]] was held on Thursday, 7 May 2015 to elect [[List of MPs elected in the 2015 United Kingdom general election|650 members]] to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]]. After the 2015 general election, Cameron was re-elected as Prime Minister, but this time at the head of a [[#Second term (2015\u201316)|Conservative majority government]] with a parliamentary majority of 12 seats.<ref>{{cite web|title=Election 2015&nbsp;\u2013 Results|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election/2015/results|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref> Forming the first [[Second Cameron Ministry|Conservative majority government]] since 1992, [[David Cameron]] became the first Prime Minister since [[1900 United Kingdom general election|1900]] to continue in office immediately after a term of at least four years with a larger popular vote share, and the only Prime Minister other than [[Margaret Thatcher]] to continue in office immediately after a term of at least four years with a greater number of seats. The [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], led by [[Ed Miliband]], saw a small increase in its share of the vote to 30.4%, but incurred a net loss of seats to return 232 MPs. This was its lowest seat tally since the [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987 general election]]. Senior Labour [[Official Opposition Shadow Cabinet (United Kingdom)|Shadow Cabinet]] members, notably [[Ed Balls]], [[Douglas Alexander]], and [[Scottish Labour Party|Scottish Labour]] leader [[Jim Murphy]], were defeated.\n\nThe [[Scottish National Party]], enjoying a surge in support since the [[2014 Scottish independence referendum]], recorded a number of huge swings of over 30% (including a record-breaking swing of 39.3% achieved in [[Glasgow North East (UK Parliament constituency)|Glasgow North East]]) from Labour, as it won 56 of the 59 Scottish seats to become the third-largest party in the Commons. The Liberal Democrats, led by outgoing Deputy Prime Minister [[Nick Clegg]], had their worst result since their formation in 1988, holding just eight out of their previous 57 seats, with Cabinet ministers [[Vince Cable]], [[Ed Davey]] and [[Danny Alexander]] losing their seats. [[UK Independence Party|UKIP]] came third in terms of votes with 12.6%, but only won [[Clacton (UK Parliament constituency)|one seat]], with party leader [[Nigel Farage]] failing to win the seat of [[South Thanet (UK Parliament constituency)|South Thanet]]. The [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] won its highest-ever share of the vote with 3.8%, and retained the [[Brighton Pavilion (UK Parliament constituency)|Brighton Pavilion]] seat with an increased majority, though did not win any additional seats.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/generalelection/a-victorious-caroline-lucas-has-perfectly-summed-up-how-negative-our-politics-is-10235534.html|title=A victorious Caroline Lucas perfectly has just summed up how negative our politics is|date=2015-05-08|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref> Labour's Miliband (as national leader) and Murphy (as Scottish leader) both resigned, as did Clegg. Farage said that his resignation was rejected by his party, and he remained in post.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2015/05/exclusive-nigel-farage-never-resigned-from-ukip-in-stitch-up/|title=Exclusive: Nigel Farage \u2018never resigned\u2019 from Ukip in \u2018stitch up\u2019|date=2015-05-15|website=Coffee House|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n\n==== EU referendum and end of premiership ====\n{{Main|2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum}}\nImmediately after the vote by the British electorate to leave the [[European Union]] on [[#Referendum on the European Union|23 June 2016]], Cameron announced in a televised speech outside [[10 Downing Street]] that he intended to step down as Prime Minister following the Conservative Party conference in the autumn of that year. Cameron, who had campaigned in favour of the UK remaining in a reformed EU, said that he had informed the Queen of his decision before going to the public. He remarked that \"fresh leadership\" needed to come in to deliver Brexit.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36615028|title=Brexit: David Cameron to quit after UK votes to leave EU|publisher=BBC News|date=24 June 2016|accessdate=24 June 2016}}</ref> He officially resigned as Prime Minister on 13 July 2016, following the unopposed victory of [[Theresa May]] in the [[2016 Conservative Party leadership election|Conservative Party leadership election]] on 11 July.\n\n===Premiership of Theresa May===\n{{main|Premiership of Theresa May}}\n\n==== Party election ====\n{{Main|2016 Conservative Party leadership election}}\nIn [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|a referendum held on 23 June 2016]], the UK voted to [[United Kingdom withdrawal from the European Union|withdraw from the European Union]], with a result of 52% for withdrawal and 48% for remaining within the union. [[David Cameron]], who as Prime Minister had campaigned to remain within the European Union, announced on 24 June 2016, immediately following the announcement of the referendum results, that he would resign from his post.<ref name=\"BBC11JUL\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36768148 | title=Theresa May to succeed Cameron as UK PM on Wednesday | publisher=BBC News | date=11 July 2016 | accessdate=11 July 2016}}</ref> Following the first stages of a [[2016 Conservative Party leadership election|Conservative Party leadership election]], Home Secretary [[Theresa May]]'s only remaining competitor, [[Andrea Leadsom]], withdrew from the race on 11 July 2016. Following this announcement, Cameron said that he would step down from his post on 13 July.<ref name=\"BBC11JUL\" /> Cameron formally tendered his resignation to [[Queen Elizabeth II]] on that day, who subsequently appointed Theresa May as his successor.<ref name=\"BBC16J\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36778350 | title=David Cameron says being PM 'the greatest honour' in final Downing Street speech | publisher=BBC News | date=13 July 2016 | accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"GD13JUL\">{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/13/theresa-may-becomes-britains-prime-minister | title=Theresa May becomes Britain's prime minister | work=The Guardian | date=13 July 2016 | accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== 2017 general election ====\n{{Main|2017 United Kingdom general election}}\nUnder the [[Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011]] an election had not been due until May 2020, but a call by Prime Minister [[Theresa May]] for a [[snap election]] was ratified by the necessary two-thirds vote in a 522\u201313 vote in the House of Commons on 19 April 2017. May said that she hoped to secure a larger majority to \"strengthen [her] hand\" in the forthcoming [[Brexit]] negotiations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2017/may/02/europe-landslide-victory-theresa-may-brexit|title=Strengthen our hand in Europe? No, a landslide for May would weaken it {{!}} Ian Birrell|last=Birrell|first=Ian|date=2017-05-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-19|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n[[Opinion polling for the 2017 United Kingdom general election|Opinion polls]] had consistently shown strong leads for the Conservatives over Labour. From a 21-point lead, the Conservatives' lead began to diminish in the final weeks of the campaign. In a surprising result, the Conservative Party made a net loss of 13 seats despite winning 42.4% of the vote (its highest share of the vote since [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]), whereas Labour made a net gain of 30 seats with 40.0% (its highest vote share since [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]] and the first time the party had gained seats since [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]). This was the closest result between the two major parties since [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|February 1974]] and their highest combined vote share since [[1970 United Kingdom general election|1970]]. The [[Scottish National Party]] (SNP) and the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]], the third- and fourth-largest parties, both lost vote share; media coverage characterised the result as a return to [[Two-party system|two-party politics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/voices/election-results-hung-parliament-two-party-politics-back-return-labour-conservative-tory-jeremy-a7781256.html|title=Two-party politics is back \u2013 sort of|date=2017-06-09|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref> The SNP, which had won 56 of the 59 Scottish seats at the previous general election in 2015, lost 21. The Liberal Democrats made a net gain of four seats. [[UK Independence Party|UKIP]], the third-largest party in 2015 by number of votes, saw its share of the vote reduced from 12.6% to 1.8% and lost its only seat.\n\nIn Wales, [[Plaid Cymru]] gained one seat, giving it a total of four seats. The [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] retained its sole seat, but saw its share of the vote reduced. In Northern Ireland, the [[Democratic Unionist Party]] (DUP) won 10 seats, [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] won seven, and [[Independent Unionist]] [[Sylvia Hermon]] retained her seat. The [[Social Democratic and Labour Party]] (SDLP) and [[Ulster Unionist Party]] (UUP) lost all their seats. The Conservatives were narrowly victorious and remained in power as a minority government, having secured a [[confidence and supply]] [[Conservative-DUP agreement#2017%20Conservative%E2%80%93DUP%20agreement|deal with the DUP]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-40403434|title=Tories and DUP agree UK government deal|date=2017-06-26|access-date=2019-12-19|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n====Issues during premiership====\nMay triggered [[Article 50 of the Treaty on European Union]] to [[Brexit|leave the EU]] in March 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/13b17624-7057-11e6-9ac1-1055824ca907.html|title=Theresa May ignores calls for Brexit delay|date=1 September 2016|newspaper=Financial Times|accessdate=11 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/mar/29/theresa-may-triggers-article-50-with-warning-of-consequences-for-uk May triggers article 50 with warning of consequence for UK] ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref> However, under her leadership, the government was unable to reach an EU withdrawal agreement approved by the Conservative Party as a whole. How to manage the border between [[Northern Ireland]] and the [[Republic of Ireland]] was a major problem; the so-called '[[Brexit and the Irish border|backstop]]'.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/oct/14/david-davis-calls-on-ministers-to-rebel-against-brexit-deal David Davis calls on ministers to rebel against Brexit deal] ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\nOn 4 December 2018, the May government was found in [[contempt of Parliament]]; the first [[Government of the United Kingdom|government]] to be found in contempt in history on a motion passed by MPs by 311 to 293 votes. The vote was triggered by the government failing to lay before Parliament any legal advice on the proposed withdrawal agreement on the terms of the [[Brexit|UK's departure from the European Union]], after a [[humble address]] for a return was unanimously agreed to by the House of Commons on 13 November 2018. The government then agreed to publish the full legal advice for [[Brexit]] that was given to the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] by the [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Attorney General]] during negotiations with the [[European Union]].\n\n===Premiership of Boris Johnson===\n{{main|Premiership of Boris Johnson}}\n\n==== Party election ====\n{{Main|2019 Conservative Party leadership election}}\n[[Theresa May]], after failing to pass her [[Brexit withdrawal agreement]] through parliament three times, announced her resignation as Prime Minister of the United Kingdom on 24 May 2019 amidst calls for her to be ousted.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/europe/live-news/theresa-may-resignation-announcement-0524-gbr-intl|title=Theresa May to resign as UK Prime Minister|last=Picheta|first=Rob|date=25 May 2019|work=CNN|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-48379730|title=Theresa May resigns over Brexit: What happened?|date=24 May 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> [[Boris Johnson]] had already confirmed at a business event in Manchester days earlier that he would run for [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] leader if May were to resign.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-48299424|title=Boris Johnson confirms bid for Tory leadership|date=16 May 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nJohnson won all five rounds of voting by MPs,<ref name=\"stewart-23-July\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/23/boris-johnson-elected-new-tory-leader-prime-minister|title=Boris Johnson elected new Tory leader|last=Stewart|first=Heather|date=23 July 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=23 July 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and entered the final vote by Conservative Party members as the clear favourite to be elected PM.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/23/boris-johnson-on-course-to-win-tory-leadership-contest|title=Johnson on course to win Tory leadership contest|last=Mason|first=Rowena|date=23 July 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> On 23 July, he emerged victorious over his rival [[Jeremy Hunt]] with 92,153 votes, 66.4% of the total ballot, while Hunt received 46,656 votes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49084605|title=Boris Johnson wins race to be Tory leader and PM|date=23 July 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> These results were announced an event in the [[Queen Elizabeth II Centre]] in [[Westminster]]. In his first speech as Prime Minister Johnson pledged that Britain would leave the [[European Union]] (EU) by 31 October 2019, \"no ifs or buts\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/nov/01/johnson-first-100-days-broken-promises-unlawful-prorogation|title=Johnson's first 100 days: broken promises and an unlawful prorogation|date=1 November 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=2 November 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n====Annulled prorogation attempt ====\n{{Main|2019 British prorogation controversy}}\nOn 28 August 2019, [[Boris Johnson]] announced that he had asked The Queen to prorogue parliament from a date between 9\u201312 September until the [[State Opening of Parliament|opening of a new session]] on 14 October.<ref name=\"wash post\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2019/08/28/read-boris-johnsons-letter-british-lawmakers-about-his-plans-shut-down-parliament/|title=Read Boris Johnson\u2019s letter to British lawmakers about his plans to shut down Parliament|author=Jennifer Hassan|newspaper=[[Washington Post]]|language=en|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref> Parliament was in any case due to have a three-week recess for the [[party conference season]],<ref name=\"Guardian28aug\">[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/aug/28/what-is-prorogation-prorogue-parliament-boris-johnson-brexit \"What is prorogation and why is Boris Johnson using it?\"]. ''[[The Guardian]]'', 28 August 2019.</ref> and Johnson's prorogation would add around four days to the parliamentary break. The 2017\u201319 parliamentary session was the longest since the [[English Civil War]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/parliament-and-elections/parliament/is-this-the-longest-parliamentary-session-ever/|title=Is this the longest parliamentary session ever?|date=2019-05-10|publisher=[[House of Commons Library]]|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper|title=Brexit struggles lead to longest parliamentary session since the Civil War|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/brexit-parliament-session-longest-civil-war/|newspaper=[[i (newspaper)|i News]]|first1=Karl |last1=McDonald|date=13 May 2019|access-date=28 August 2019}}</ref> while the prorogation in 2019 at Johnson's request would have been the longest prorogation since 1930.<ref>{{cite newspaper|title=Westminster shutdown:is Britain facing a coup? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/sep/01/britain-coup-parliament-suspend-prorogue-brexit|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=1 September 2019|author=Meg Russell}}</ref>\n\nThe government said that the prorogation was to allow for the government to set out a new legislative agenda.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/aug/13/bercow-will-fight-to-stop-johnson-closing-parliament-for-no-deal|title=Bercow will 'fight with every breath' to stop Johnson closing parliament for no deal|last=Elgot|first=Jessica|date=13 August 2019|work=The Guardian}}</ref> Others questioned this justification, and said that the prorogation was an improper attempt to evade parliamentary scrutiny of Johnson's [[Brexit]] plans in advance of the UK's planned departure from the [[European Union]] on 31 October 2019; opponents of prorogation included opposition MPs,<ref name=\"Guardian28aug\"/> UK constitutional law scholars,<ref>{{cite newspaper|title=Letters: The 'improper' nature of this prorogation|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/comment/times-letters-the-improper-nature-of-this-prorogation-2r6zq0xfr|newspaper=Times of London|date=3 September 2019}}</ref> and Sir [[John Major]], the former Conservative Prime Minister.<ref>{{cite newspaper|author=Owen Bowcott|title=John Major's lawyer attacks No 10 prorogation claims as 'misleading'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/sep/19/john-majors-lawyer-attacks-no-10-prorogation-claims-as-misleading|newspaper=The Guardian|date=19 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper|title=Boris Johnson should apologise to Parliament for prorogation, says Sir John Major|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/09/24/boris-johnson-should-apologise-parliament-prorogation-says-sir/|newspaper=The Telegraph|author=Tony Diver|date=24 September 2019}}</ref> The [[Speaker of the House of Commons (United Kingdom)|Speaker of the House of Commons]], [[John Bercow]], called the decision a \"constitutional outrage\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channel4.com/news/factcheck/factcheck-parliament-prorogation-explained|title=Parliament \u2018prorogation\u2019 explained|last=Lee|first=Georgina|date=28 August 2019|website=Channel 4|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=28 August 2019}}</ref> \n\nThree separate cases were lodged before the courts alleging its illegality. The [[High Court of Justice]] in London found the issue to be [[non-justiciable]], but the highest civil court in Scotland, the [[Court of Session]] sitting in Edinburgh, ruled prorogation was [[Violation of law|unlawful]] as it had the \"improper purpose of [[wikt:stymie|stymie]]ing Parliament\".<ref>See A. Young, \u2018[https://ukconstitutionallaw.org/2019/09/13/alison-young-prorogation-politics-and-the-principle-of-legality/ Prorogation, Politics and the Principle of Legality]\u2019, U.K. Const. L. Blog (13 Sept. 2019) and E. McGaughey, \u2018[https://ukconstitutionallaw.org/2019/09/14/ewan-mcgaughey-is-there-a-legal-measure-to-judge-parliaments-prorogration/ Is There a \"Legal Measure\" to Judge Parliament\u2019s Prorogration?]\u2019, U.K. Const. L. Blog (14 Sept. 2019)</ref> The issue was brought before the [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]] on 17 September 2019 in the cases [[R (Miller) v The Prime Minister and Cherry v Advocate General for Scotland|''R (Miller) v The Prime Minister'' and ''Cherry v Advocate General for Scotland'']].<ref>{{cite news|title=Scottish judges rule Parliament suspension is unlawful|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-49661855|publisher=BBC News|date=11 September 2019}}</ref> On 24 September, the Supreme Court ruled unanimously that the prorogation was both justiciable and unlawful, and therefore null and of no effect.<ref>{{cite news |last= Bowcott |first=Owen |date=24 September 2019 |title=Boris Johnson's suspension of parliament unlawful, supreme court rules |url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2019/sep/24/boris-johnsons-suspension-of-parliament-unlawful-supreme-court-rules-prorogue |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |publication-place=London |access-date=24 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Supreme Court: Suspending Parliament was unlawful, judges rule |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-49810261 |newspaper=[[BBC News]] |publication-place=London |date=24 September 2019 |access-date=24 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite court |litigants=R (Miller) (Appellant) v The Prime Minister (Respondent) and Cherry & Ors (Respondents) v Advocate General for Scotland (Appellant) (Scotland) |reporter=&#91;2019&#93; UKSC 41 |date=24 September 2019 |url=https://www.supremecourt.uk/cases/docs/uksc-2019-0192-judgment.pdf |access-date=24 September 2018}}</ref> Parliament resumed sitting the following day, resuming the parliamentary session.<ref>{{cite new|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-49820038|title=Parliament: MPs and peers return after court rules suspension unlawful|work=[[BBC News]]|date=25 September 2019}}</ref><ref>https://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2019/september/end-of-the-2017-19-parliament-/</ref> Bercow said he would ensure that the attempted prorogation would be expunged from the House of Commons Journal, the corrected formal record of parliamentary business, and replaced with a statement that Parliament was adjourned for the period of the absence.<ref>Bianca Britton, [https://edition.cnn.com/2019/09/25/uk/mps-return-to-parliament-gbr-intl/index.html Lawmakers return to Parliament after court rules against Boris Johnson's prorogation], CNN (25 September 2019).</ref><ref>Chris Smyth & Steven Swinford, [https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/supreme-court-ruling-this-parliament-is-dead-says-law-chief-geoffrey-cox-p8hnkd5dw Supreme Court ruling: This parliament is dead, says law chief Geoffrey Cox], ''The Times'' (26 September 2019).</ref>\n\n====Calls for early election====\nOn 3 September 2019, [[Boris Johnson]] threatened to call a [[general election]] after opposition and rebel Conservative MPs successfully voted against the government to take control of the order of business with a view to preventing a no-deal exit.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/09/03/brexit-latest-news-boris-johnson-no-deal-vote-general-election/|title=Brexit vote result: Boris Johnson demands general election after rebel MPs seize control of Commons agenda|last1=Rayner|first1=Gordon|last2=Sheridan|first2=Danielle|date=3 September 2019|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> \n \nDespite government opposition, the [[Benn Act|bill to block a no-deal exit]] passed the Commons on 4 September 2019, causing Johnson to call for a general election on 15 October.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49580185|title=MPs back bill aimed at blocking no-deal Brexit|date=4 September 2019|access-date=4 September 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> However, this motion was unsuccessful as it failed to command the support of two-thirds of the House as required by the [[Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011|Fixed-term Parliaments Act]] (FTPA).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49584907|title=Johnson's call for general election rejected by MPs|date=4 September 2019|access-date=4 September 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> A second attempt at a motion for an early general election failed on 9 September.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/sep/09/mps-order-johnson-to-hand-over-aides-messages-about-prorogation|title=Boris Johnson loses sixth vote in six days as election bid fails|last=Mason |first=Rowena |date=10 September 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\n====Brexit negotiations====\n{{main|Brexit negotiations in 2019}}\n\nOn 2 October the Government published a fresh Brexit plan, which included proposals to replace the [[Irish backstop]]. It would create an \"all-island regulatory zone\", meaning that Northern Ireland would essentially stay in the [[European Single Market]] for agricultural and industrial goods, meaning that [[Sanitary and phytosanitary measures and agreements|sanitary and phytosanitary controls]] would be needed between Northern Ireland and Great Britain.<ref name=\"BBC21019\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-49909309 |title=Government publishes Brexit proposals |work=BBC News |date=2 October 2019 |accessdate=2 October 2019}}</ref> The proposal also declared that Northern Ireland, along with the rest of the UK, would leave the Customs Union, meaning that customs controls would be needed for cross-border goods trade.<ref name=\"BBC21019\" /> The proposal did not appear to address cross-border services.{{fact|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn 4 October the Government assured the highest civil court in Scotland that Johnson would send a letter to the EU seeking an extension to Article 50 as required by the European Union (Withdrawal) (No. 2) Act 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-49936352 |title=Brexit: Boris Johnson will send extension letter \u2013 court document |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=4 October 2019 |accessdate=4 October 2019}}</ref> The court was originally due to release their ruling on 9 October, but decided to delay doing so until 21 October, in order to allow the court to \"assess how circumstances have changed\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-49975066 |title=Brexit: Scottish court delays decision on extension letter |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=9 October 2019 |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref> On 17 October 2019, a revised withdrawal agreement, with a changed backstop, was agreed by the EU leaders and Boris Johnson.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/sites/beta-political/files/revised_withdrawal_agreement_including_protocol_on_ireland_and_nothern_ireland.pdf|title=Revised Withdrawal Agreement|last=|first=|date=17 October 2019|website=|publisher=European Commission|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50079385|title=New Brexit deal agreed, says Boris Johnson|last=|first=|date=17 October 2019|work=BBC|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 October, a special Saturday sitting of Parliament was held to debate the revised agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49984367|title=Brexit: Special sitting for MPs to decide UK's future|date=9 October 2019|website=BBC News|accessdate=9 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/09/parliament-set-for-brexit-showdown-on-19-october|title=Parliament set for Brexit showdown on 19 October|last=Murphy|first=Simon|date=9 October 2019|work=The Guardian|accessdate=9 October 2019}}</ref> MPs passed [[Parliamentary votes on Brexit#Second Letwin amendment (19 October 2019)|an amendment]] by 322 votes to 306 that withheld Parliament's approval until legislation implementing the deal had been passed, and forced the Government to request a delay to Brexit until 31 January 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/19/mps-put-brakes-on-boris-johnsons-brexit-deal-with-rebel-letwin-amendment|title=MPs put brakes on Boris Johnson's Brexit deal with rebel amendment|last=Stewart|first=Heather|date=19 October 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=19 October 2019|last2=Proctor|first2=Kate|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Later that evening, 10 Downing Street confirmed that Boris Johnson would send a letter to the EU requesting an extension, but would not sign it.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-50112924 |title=Brexit: PM sends letter to Brussels seeking further delay |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=19 October 2019 |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref> EU Council President [[Donald Tusk]] subsequently confirmed receipt of the letter, which Johnson had described as \"Parliament's letter, not my letter\". In addition, Johnson sent a second letter expressing the view that any further delay to Brexit would be a mistake.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-50112924 |title=Brexit: PM sends letter to Brussels seeking further delay |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=20 October 2019 |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 October, the UK government brought the recently revised EU Withdrawal Bill to the House of Commons for debate.<ref name=\"BBC22Oct\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-50146182|title=MPs reject Brexit bill timetable|work=BBC News|date=22 October 2019|access-date=22 October 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> MPs voted on the Bill itself, which was passed by 329 votes to 299, and on the timetable for debating the Bill, which was defeated by 322 votes to 308. Prior to the votes, Johnson had stated that if his timetable failed to generate the support needed to pass in parliament he would abandon attempts to get the deal approved and would seek a general election. Following the vote, however, Johnson announced that the legislation would be paused while he consulted with other EU leaders.<ref name=\"BBC22Oct\"/><ref name=\"Reuters22Oct\">{{cite web|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-eu/british-parliament-backs-pm-johnsons-brexit-deal-at-important-stage-idUKKBN1X10K0|title=Brexit in chaos after parliament defeats Johnson's ratification timetable|last1=James|first1=William|last2=MacLellan|first2=Kylie|last3=Piper|first3=Elizabeth|website=[[Reuters.com]]|date=22 October 2019|access-date=22 October 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 28 October 2019, it was confirmed that Brexit had been delayed until 31 January 2020.<ref name=BBC281019>[https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50205603 Brexit: Johnson agrees to Brexit extension \u2013 but urges election] ''[[BBC News]]'' 28 October 2019</ref> The following day, MPs backed a [[2019 United Kingdom general election|general election]] on 12 December 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-50229318 |title=MPs back 12 December election |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref> On 30 October 2019, the day named as \"exit day\" in UK legislation was changed to 31 January 2020 at 11.00 p.m.<ref>The European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018 (Exit Day) (Amendment) (No. 3) Regulations 2019 SI 2019 No. 1423, 30 October 2019.[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2019/1423/regulation/2/made]</ref>\n\n==== 2019 general election ====\n{{Main|2019 United Kingdom general election}}\nAt the election, the Conservatives made a net gain of 48 seats, in what was regarded as a [[landslide victory]], winning 43.6% of the vote (the highest share for any party since [[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979]]) and 365 seats (the highest number for the party since [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]]), whereas Labour made a net loss of 60 seats, losing several of its constituencies in northern England, across the Midlands and Wales to the Conservatives (often for the first time in many decades).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election/2019/results|title=Results|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.statista.com/statistics/717004/general-elections-vote-share-by-party-uk/|title=Share of votes in general elections in the United Kingdom from 1918 to 2017, by political party|website=Statista|accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref> Labour's losses in the general election led its leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] to announce his intention to resign as the party's leader.<ref name=\"Corbyn Defeat\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2019-50766114|title=Jeremy Corbyn: 'I will not lead Labour at next election'|publisher=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/socialist-jeremy-corbyn-steps-down-leader-labour-party-after-crushing-n1101166|title=Socialist Jeremy Corbyn to step down as leader of Labour Party after projected defeat in U.K. election|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref> The [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] increased their vote share to 11.6% of the votes, though leader [[Jo Swinson]] was obliged under her party's rules to announce her resignation after losing her seat in [[East Dunbartonshire (UK Parliament constituency)|East Dunbartonshire]], leaving her party with 11 seats.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2019-50771123|title=Lib Dem leader Jo Swinson to step down|date=13 December 2019|accessdate=13 December 2019|publisher=BBC News|language=en-GB}}</ref> The [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] held its one seat and saw its vote share increase.\n\nThe [[Scottish National Party]] (SNP) made a net gain of 13 seats across [[2019 United Kingdom general election in Scotland|Scotland]], winning 45% of the Scottish vote and 48 of the 59 Scottish seats,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2019-50766014|title=SNP wins election landslide in Scotland|date=2019-12-13|access-date=2019-12-15|language=en-GB}}</ref> while in [[2019 United Kingdom general election in Wales|Wales]], [[Plaid Cymru]] retained its four seats with no significant change in vote share. In [[2019 United Kingdom general election in Northern Ireland|Northern Ireland]], for the first time more [[Irish nationalism|Irish Nationalist]] MPs were elected than [[Unionism in Ireland|British Unionists]], although unionist parties still won more votes; [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] retained the same number of seats, and the [[Democratic Unionist Party|DUP]] lost two seats, while the [[Social Democratic and Labour Party]] (SDLP) regained two seats, and the [[Alliance Party of Northern Ireland|Alliance Party]] regained a seat, giving the latter two parties a restored presence in the House of Commons.\n\n==== Post-election aftermath  ====\nThe election results had a variety of different effects and set the dynamics of UK politics going into the [[2020s in United Kingdom political history|new decade]]. For the first time since the 2016 referendum it became almost certain that Brexit would take place with the process of passing the withdrawal agreement through parliament beginning before Christmas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2019/december/withdrawal-agreement-bill/|title=MPs pass Second Reading of the Withdrawal Agreement Bill - News from Parliament|website=UK Parliament|language=English|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref> For the Conservative Party, the election meant a shift from a fairly weak administration in the hung parliament of 2017 to 2019 to governing with a majority on a scale they had not known since the early 1990s, potentially, setting them up to remain in power for many years to come.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2017-40237833|title=10 ways the PM blew her majority|last=Wheeler|first=Alex Hunt and Brian|date=2017-06-14|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-01-22|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2019-50776671|title=Johnson: I will repay the trust of voters|date=2019-12-13|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-01-22|language=en-GB}}</ref> For the Labour Party, the defeat meant an end to the [[Labour Party leadership of Jeremy Corbyn|leadership of Jeremy Corbyn]] with preparations beginning for a [[2020 Labour Party leadership election|new leadership]]  and [[2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election|deputy leadership]] contest in early 2020 whilst rekindling debates within the party and beyond about its tactical and ideological future.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2019-50766114|title=Corbyn: I will not lead Labour at next election|date=2019-12-13|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-01-22|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/dec/31/only-way-labour-win-ditch-labourism-corbyn|title=The only way Labour can win is by ditching \u2018Labourism\u2019 {{!}} Jeremy Gilbert|last=Gilbert|first=Jeremy|date=2019-12-31|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-22|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/21/crushed-by-brexit-how-labour-lost-the-election|title='Crushed by Brexit': how Labour lost the election|last=Stewart|first=Heather|date=2020-01-21|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-22|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/jan/21/keir-starmer-soft-left-approach-unifying-labour|title=Keir Starmer\u2019s soft-left approach is the unifying force that Labour needs {{!}} Zoe Williams|last=Williams|first=Zoe|date=2020-01-21|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-22|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/jan/08/labour-membership-doesnt-want-return-to-1997|title=Labour members want something new \u2013 not a return to 1997 {{!}} Owen Jones|last=Jones|first=Owen|date=2020-01-08|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-22|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> For the Liberal Democrats, Jo Swinson's unseating at the election also meant a fresh [[2020 Liberal Democrats leadership election|leadership election]] in the new year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-51164894|title=New Liberal Democrat leader in place by mid-July|date=2020-01-18|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-01-22|language=en-GB}}</ref> Whilst, for the SNP, dominance in Scotland renewed hopes for a [[Proposed second Scottish independence referendum|second Scottish independence referendum]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/dec/13/nicola-sturgeon-to-publish-independence-referendum-blueprint|title=Scottish independence vote a 'democratic right', says Sturgeon|last=Carrell|first=Severin|date=2019-12-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-22|last2=Brooks|first2=Libby|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>[[Labour Party leadership of Jeremy Corbyn|<br />]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Brexit]]\n* [[2010s political history]]\n*[[2020s in United Kingdom political history]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{United Kingdom topics}}\n\n[[Category:2010s in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Political history]]\n[[Category:Years of the 21st century in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Politics overviews by decade]]\n[[Category:2010 in politics]]\n[[Category:2010 in British politics]]\n[[Category:2011 in British politics]]\n[[Category:2012 in British politics]]\n[[Category:2013 in British politics]]\n[[Category:2014 in British politics]]\n[[Category:2015 in British politics]]\n[[Category:2016 in British politics]]\n[[Category:2017 in British politics]]\n[[Category:2018 in British politics]]\n[[Category:2019 in British politics]]\n[[Category:2010 United Kingdom general election]]\n[[Category:2015 United Kingdom general election]]\n[[Category:2017 United Kingdom general election]]\n[[Category:2019 United Kingdom general election]]\n[[Category:Brexit]]\n[[Category:2010s in politics]]\n", "text_old": "{{see also|2020s in United Kingdom political history|2010s in political history}}\n\n{{see also|2010s#Politics and conflicts|21st century|2019 in politics and government}}\n{{Decadebox|201}}\n{{Year nav topic5|2019|the United Kingdom|politics and government|science|United Kingdom politics and government}}\n\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n\n'''2010s political history''' refers to significant political and societal historical events in the [[United Kingdom]] in the 2010s, presented as a historical overview in narrative format. \n\nThere were four Prime Ministers ([[Gordon Brown|Brown]], [[David Cameron|Cameron]], [[Theresa May|May]], [[Boris Johnson|Johnson]]), four general elections ([[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]], [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]], [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]], [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]), the same number of referendums ([[2011 Welsh devolution referendum|Further Welsh devolution]], [[2011 United Kingdom Alternative Vote referendum|voting reform]], [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|Scottish independence]], [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|Brexit]]) and three parties ([[Labour party (UK)|Labour]], [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]], [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] as a junior coalition partner) had been in government during this time. The decade began with the last months of an unpopular [[Brown ministry|Labour government]] that had been in power for 13 years and was grappling a [[Financial crisis of 2007-08|global financial crisis]], and a [[2010 United Kingdom general election|general election]] that resulted in the first [[hung parliament]] in 36 years, and ended with a [[Brexit]] deadlock that was resolved with a [[2019 United Kingdom general election|general election]] that produced the biggest Conservative majority since [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]].\n\n==History by Premiership ==\n\n===Premiership of Gordon Brown ===\n{{main|Premiership of Gordon Brown}}\n\n==== 2010 general election ====\n{{Main|2010 United Kingdom general election}}\nAt the beginning of the decade the [[United Kingdom|UK]] was governed by the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], which had been in power since its landslide victory in the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 UK general election]] before winning comfortable majorities in the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]] and [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]] general elections. The prime minister was [[Gordon Brown]], who had been in office since 2007. On 6 April 2010, Brown visited [[Buckingham Palace]] to seek [[Elizabeth II|the Queen]]'s permission to dissolve Parliament on 12 April, initiating a general election on 6 May.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/election_2010/8603591.stm|title=Brown triggers May election race|date=2010-04-06|access-date=2019-12-09|language=en-GB}}</ref> Notable events in that campaign included the UK's first televised debates between the leaders of the main parties. In these debates the prime minister was widely considered to have been outperformed by his opponents [[David Cameron]] of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] and [[Nick Clegg]] of the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/election_2010/8621119.stm|title=Leaders clash in historic debate|date=2010-04-15|access-date=2019-12-09|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/election-2010/7696467/General-Election-2010-the-great-debate-election.html|title=General Election 2010: the great debate election|date=2010-05-08|access-date=2019-12-09|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nAt the election, Labour lost 91 seats in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]], but the Conservatives failed to achieve an overall majority, resulting in the first [[hung parliament]] since [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|1974]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/election_2010/8667071.stm|title=First hung parliament for decades|date=2010-05-07|access-date=2019-12-09|language=en-GB}}</ref> Brown remained temporarily as Prime Minister, while the Liberal Democrats and Conservatives entered into talks aimed at forming a [[coalition government]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/may/07/hung-parliament-david-cameron-momentum|title=Hung parliament: David Cameron has momentum, but Brown still has power|last=Travis|first=Alan|date=2010-05-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-09|last2=editor|first2=home affairs|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/election_2010/8669508.stm|title=Lib Dems back Clegg on Tory talks|date=2010-05-08|access-date=2019-12-09|language=en-GB}}</ref> There were also talks between the Liberal Democrats and Labour.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/may/10/labour-liberal-democrats-conservative-coalition|title=Labour prepares to pounce if Liberal Democrat-Conservative coalition talks fail|last=Wintour|first=Patrick|date=2010-05-10|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-09|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> On 10 May, Brown announced his intention to resign as leader of the Labour Party and instructed the party to initiate the election of a new leader. Brown's continued presence as Prime Minister was seen an obstacle to the negotiation of a Labour-Liberal Democrat deal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/election_2010/8672859.stm|title=Brown to quit as Labour leader|date=2010-05-10|access-date=2019-12-09|language=en-GB}}</ref> In a telephone conversation with his predecessor [[Tony Blair]], Blair suggested to Brown that the election had shown that British voters had lost faith in both him and the Labour Party and that the United Kingdom would not accept him continuing as Prime Minister. He concluded that he would not be able to form a government, and announced his resignation as Prime Minister.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/election_2010/8675913.stm|title=Brown resigns as prime minister|date=2010-05-11|access-date=2019-12-09|language=en-GB}}</ref> He also resigned as leader of the Labour Party with immediate effect. Brown was succeeded as Prime Minister by David Cameron, whose party had formed a coalition with the Liberal Democrats, while [[Harriet Harman]] became acting leader of the Labour Party.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/election_2010/8675265.stm|title=Cameron is new UK prime minister|date=2010-05-12|access-date=2019-12-09|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/election_2010/8676333.stm|title=Harman made acting Labour leader|date=2010-05-11|access-date=2019-12-09|language=en-GB}}</ref> The latter until [[Ed Miliband]]'s victory in the [[2010 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|2010 labour leadership contest]] a few months later.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-11412031|title=Ed Miliband is new Labour leader|date=2010-09-25|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-17|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n\n\n=== Premiership of David Cameron ===\n{{main|Premiership of David Cameron}}\n\n==== Appointment ====\nThe [[premiership of David Cameron]] began on 11 May 2010 when [[David Cameron|Cameron]] accepted [[Elizabeth II|the Queen]]'s invitation to form a government, after the resignation of Cameron's predecessor as [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]], [[Gordon Brown]]. While serving as Prime Minister, Cameron also served as [[First Lord of the Treasury]], [[Minister for the Civil Service]] and [[Leader of the Conservative Party (UK)|Leader of the Conservative Party]]. He headed a [[#First term (2010\u201315)|coalition government]] between the Conservatives and the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]. He immediately appointed [[Nick Clegg]], the leader of the Liberal Democrats, as [[Deputy Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Deputy Prime Minister]]. Between them, the Conservatives and Liberal Democrats controlled 363 seats in the House of Commons, with a majority of 76 seats.<ref>{{cite news |author=Lyall, Sarah |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/13/world/europe/13britain.html|title= Britain's Improbable New Leaders Promise Big Changes |newspaper=The New York Times |date=25 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n==== Policies ====\nThroughout his time in office, Cameron's government attempted to reduce the large deficit in government finances through [[austerity]] measures. Internationally, his government [[Operation Ellamy|intervened militarily]] in the [[Libyan Civil War (2011)|Libyan Civil War]] and later authorised the bombing of the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]]; domestically, his government oversaw the [[2011 United Kingdom Alternative Vote referendum|referendum on voting reform]] and the [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|Scottish independence referendum]], both of which confirmed Cameron's favoured outcome (a \"No\" in each case).\n\n==== 2015 general election ====\n{{Main|2015 United Kingdom general election}}\nThe [[2015 United Kingdom general election]] was held on Thursday, 7 May 2015 to elect [[List of MPs elected in the 2015 United Kingdom general election|650 members]] to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]]. After the 2015 general election, Cameron was re-elected as Prime Minister, but this time at the head of a [[#Second term (2015\u201316)|Conservative majority government]] with a parliamentary majority of 12 seats.<ref>{{cite web|title=Election 2015&nbsp;\u2013 Results|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election/2015/results|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref> Forming the first [[Second Cameron Ministry|Conservative majority government]] since 1992, [[David Cameron]] became the first Prime Minister since [[1900 United Kingdom general election|1900]] to continue in office immediately after a term of at least four years with a larger popular vote share, and the only Prime Minister other than [[Margaret Thatcher]] to continue in office immediately after a term of at least four years with a greater number of seats. The [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], led by [[Ed Miliband]], saw a small increase in its share of the vote to 30.4%, but incurred a net loss of seats to return 232 MPs. This was its lowest seat tally since the [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987 general election]]. Senior Labour [[Official Opposition Shadow Cabinet (United Kingdom)|Shadow Cabinet]] members, notably [[Ed Balls]], [[Douglas Alexander]], and [[Scottish Labour Party|Scottish Labour]] leader [[Jim Murphy]], were defeated.\n\nThe [[Scottish National Party]], enjoying a surge in support since the [[2014 Scottish independence referendum]], recorded a number of huge swings of over 30% (including a record-breaking swing of 39.3% achieved in [[Glasgow North East (UK Parliament constituency)|Glasgow North East]]) from Labour, as it won 56 of the 59 Scottish seats to become the third-largest party in the Commons. The Liberal Democrats, led by outgoing Deputy Prime Minister [[Nick Clegg]], had their worst result since their formation in 1988, holding just eight out of their previous 57 seats, with Cabinet ministers [[Vince Cable]], [[Ed Davey]] and [[Danny Alexander]] losing their seats. [[UK Independence Party|UKIP]] came third in terms of votes with 12.6%, but only won [[Clacton (UK Parliament constituency)|one seat]], with party leader [[Nigel Farage]] failing to win the seat of [[South Thanet (UK Parliament constituency)|South Thanet]]. The [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] won its highest-ever share of the vote with 3.8%, and retained the [[Brighton Pavilion (UK Parliament constituency)|Brighton Pavilion]] seat with an increased majority, though did not win any additional seats.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/generalelection/a-victorious-caroline-lucas-has-perfectly-summed-up-how-negative-our-politics-is-10235534.html|title=A victorious Caroline Lucas perfectly has just summed up how negative our politics is|date=2015-05-08|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref> Labour's Miliband (as national leader) and Murphy (as Scottish leader) both resigned, as did Clegg. Farage said that his resignation was rejected by his party, and he remained in post.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2015/05/exclusive-nigel-farage-never-resigned-from-ukip-in-stitch-up/|title=Exclusive: Nigel Farage \u2018never resigned\u2019 from Ukip in \u2018stitch up\u2019|date=2015-05-15|website=Coffee House|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n\n==== EU referendum and end of premiership ====\n{{Main|2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum}}\nImmediately after the vote by the British electorate to leave the [[European Union]] on [[#Referendum on the European Union|23 June 2016]], Cameron announced in a televised speech outside [[10 Downing Street]] that he intended to step down as Prime Minister following the Conservative Party conference in the autumn of that year. Cameron, who had campaigned in favour of the UK remaining in a reformed EU, said that he had informed the Queen of his decision before going to the public. He remarked that \"fresh leadership\" needed to come in to deliver Brexit.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36615028|title=Brexit: David Cameron to quit after UK votes to leave EU|publisher=BBC News|date=24 June 2016|accessdate=24 June 2016}}</ref> He officially resigned as Prime Minister on 13 July 2016, following the unopposed victory of [[Theresa May]] in the [[2016 Conservative Party leadership election|Conservative Party leadership election]] on 11 July.\n\n===Premiership of Theresa May===\n{{main|Premiership of Theresa May}}\n\n==== Party election ====\n{{Main|2016 Conservative Party leadership election}}\nIn [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|a referendum held on 23 June 2016]], the UK voted to [[United Kingdom withdrawal from the European Union|withdraw from the European Union]], with a result of 52% for withdrawal and 48% for remaining within the union. [[David Cameron]], who as Prime Minister had campaigned to remain within the European Union, announced on 24 June 2016, immediately following the announcement of the referendum results, that he would resign from his post.<ref name=\"BBC11JUL\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36768148 | title=Theresa May to succeed Cameron as UK PM on Wednesday | publisher=BBC News | date=11 July 2016 | accessdate=11 July 2016}}</ref> Following the first stages of a [[2016 Conservative Party leadership election|Conservative Party leadership election]], Home Secretary [[Theresa May]]'s only remaining competitor, [[Andrea Leadsom]], withdrew from the race on 11 July 2016. Following this announcement, Cameron said that he would step down from his post on 13 July.<ref name=\"BBC11JUL\" /> Cameron formally tendered his resignation to [[Queen Elizabeth II]] on that day, who subsequently appointed Theresa May as his successor.<ref name=\"BBC16J\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36778350 | title=David Cameron says being PM 'the greatest honour' in final Downing Street speech | publisher=BBC News | date=13 July 2016 | accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"GD13JUL\">{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/13/theresa-may-becomes-britains-prime-minister | title=Theresa May becomes Britain's prime minister | work=The Guardian | date=13 July 2016 | accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== 2017 general election ====\n{{Main|2017 United Kingdom general election}}\nUnder the [[Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011]] an election had not been due until May 2020, but a call by Prime Minister [[Theresa May]] for a [[snap election]] was ratified by the necessary two-thirds vote in a 522\u201313 vote in the House of Commons on 19 April 2017. May said that she hoped to secure a larger majority to \"strengthen [her] hand\" in the forthcoming [[Brexit]] negotiations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2017/may/02/europe-landslide-victory-theresa-may-brexit|title=Strengthen our hand in Europe? No, a landslide for May would weaken it {{!}} Ian Birrell|last=Birrell|first=Ian|date=2017-05-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-19|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n[[Opinion polling for the 2017 United Kingdom general election|Opinion polls]] had consistently shown strong leads for the Conservatives over Labour. From a 21-point lead, the Conservatives' lead began to diminish in the final weeks of the campaign. In a surprising result, the Conservative Party made a net loss of 13 seats despite winning 42.4% of the vote (its highest share of the vote since [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]), whereas Labour made a net gain of 30 seats with 40.0% (its highest vote share since [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]] and the first time the party had gained seats since [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]). This was the closest result between the two major parties since [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|February 1974]] and their highest combined vote share since [[1970 United Kingdom general election|1970]]. The [[Scottish National Party]] (SNP) and the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]], the third- and fourth-largest parties, both lost vote share; media coverage characterised the result as a return to [[Two-party system|two-party politics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/voices/election-results-hung-parliament-two-party-politics-back-return-labour-conservative-tory-jeremy-a7781256.html|title=Two-party politics is back \u2013 sort of|date=2017-06-09|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref> The SNP, which had won 56 of the 59 Scottish seats at the previous general election in 2015, lost 21. The Liberal Democrats made a net gain of four seats. [[UK Independence Party|UKIP]], the third-largest party in 2015 by number of votes, saw its share of the vote reduced from 12.6% to 1.8% and lost its only seat.\n\nIn Wales, [[Plaid Cymru]] gained one seat, giving it a total of four seats. The [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] retained its sole seat, but saw its share of the vote reduced. In Northern Ireland, the [[Democratic Unionist Party]] (DUP) won 10 seats, [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] won seven, and [[Independent Unionist]] [[Sylvia Hermon]] retained her seat. The [[Social Democratic and Labour Party]] (SDLP) and [[Ulster Unionist Party]] (UUP) lost all their seats. The Conservatives were narrowly victorious and remained in power as a minority government, having secured a [[confidence and supply]] [[Conservative-DUP agreement#2017%20Conservative%E2%80%93DUP%20agreement|deal with the DUP]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-40403434|title=Tories and DUP agree UK government deal|date=2017-06-26|access-date=2019-12-19|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n====Issues during premiership====\nMay triggered [[Article 50 of the Treaty on European Union]] to [[Brexit|leave the EU]] in March 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/13b17624-7057-11e6-9ac1-1055824ca907.html|title=Theresa May ignores calls for Brexit delay|date=1 September 2016|newspaper=Financial Times|accessdate=11 December 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/mar/29/theresa-may-triggers-article-50-with-warning-of-consequences-for-uk May triggers article 50 with warning of consequence for UK] ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref> However, under her leadership, the government was unable to reach an EU withdrawal agreement approved by the Conservative Party as a whole. How to manage the border between [[Northern Ireland]] and the [[Republic of Ireland]] was a major problem; the so-called '[[Brexit and the Irish border|backstop]]'.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/oct/14/david-davis-calls-on-ministers-to-rebel-against-brexit-deal David Davis calls on ministers to rebel against Brexit deal] ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\nOn 4 December 2018, the May government was found in [[contempt of Parliament]]; the first [[Government of the United Kingdom|government]] to be found in contempt in history on a motion passed by MPs by 311 to 293 votes. The vote was triggered by the government failing to lay before Parliament any legal advice on the proposed withdrawal agreement on the terms of the [[Brexit|UK's departure from the European Union]], after a [[humble address]] for a return was unanimously agreed to by the House of Commons on 13 November 2018. The government then agreed to publish the full legal advice for [[Brexit]] that was given to the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] by the [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Attorney General]] during negotiations with the [[European Union]].\n\n===Premiership of Boris Johnson===\n{{main|Premiership of Boris Johnson}}\n\n==== Party election ====\n{{Main|2019 Conservative Party leadership election}}\n[[Theresa May]], after failing to pass her [[Brexit withdrawal agreement]] through parliament three times, announced her resignation as Prime Minister of the United Kingdom on 24 May 2019 amidst calls for her to be ousted.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/europe/live-news/theresa-may-resignation-announcement-0524-gbr-intl|title=Theresa May to resign as UK Prime Minister|last=Picheta|first=Rob|date=25 May 2019|work=CNN|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-48379730|title=Theresa May resigns over Brexit: What happened?|date=24 May 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> [[Boris Johnson]] had already confirmed at a business event in Manchester days earlier that he would run for [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] leader if May were to resign.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-48299424|title=Boris Johnson confirms bid for Tory leadership|date=16 May 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nJohnson won all five rounds of voting by MPs,<ref name=\"stewart-23-July\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/23/boris-johnson-elected-new-tory-leader-prime-minister|title=Boris Johnson elected new Tory leader|last=Stewart|first=Heather|date=23 July 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=23 July 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and entered the final vote by Conservative Party members as the clear favourite to be elected PM.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/23/boris-johnson-on-course-to-win-tory-leadership-contest|title=Johnson on course to win Tory leadership contest|last=Mason|first=Rowena|date=23 July 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> On 23 July, he emerged victorious over his rival [[Jeremy Hunt]] with 92,153 votes, 66.4% of the total ballot, while Hunt received 46,656 votes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49084605|title=Boris Johnson wins race to be Tory leader and PM|date=23 July 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=26 July 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> These results were announced an event in the [[Queen Elizabeth II Centre]] in [[Westminster]]. In his first speech as Prime Minister Johnson pledged that Britain would leave the [[European Union]] (EU) by 31 October 2019, \"no ifs or buts\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/nov/01/johnson-first-100-days-broken-promises-unlawful-prorogation|title=Johnson's first 100 days: broken promises and an unlawful prorogation|date=1 November 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=2 November 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n====Annulled prorogation attempt ====\n{{Main|2019 British prorogation controversy}}\nOn 28 August 2019, [[Boris Johnson]] announced that he had asked The Queen to prorogue parliament from a date between 9\u201312 September until the [[State Opening of Parliament|opening of a new session]] on 14 October.<ref name=\"wash post\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2019/08/28/read-boris-johnsons-letter-british-lawmakers-about-his-plans-shut-down-parliament/|title=Read Boris Johnson\u2019s letter to British lawmakers about his plans to shut down Parliament|author=Jennifer Hassan|newspaper=[[Washington Post]]|language=en|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref> Parliament was in any case due to have a three-week recess for the [[party conference season]],<ref name=\"Guardian28aug\">[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/aug/28/what-is-prorogation-prorogue-parliament-boris-johnson-brexit \"What is prorogation and why is Boris Johnson using it?\"]. ''[[The Guardian]]'', 28 August 2019.</ref> and Johnson's prorogation would add around four days to the parliamentary break. The 2017\u201319 parliamentary session was the longest since the [[English Civil War]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/parliament-and-elections/parliament/is-this-the-longest-parliamentary-session-ever/|title=Is this the longest parliamentary session ever?|date=2019-05-10|publisher=[[House of Commons Library]]|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper|title=Brexit struggles lead to longest parliamentary session since the Civil War|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/brexit-parliament-session-longest-civil-war/|newspaper=[[i (newspaper)|i News]]|first1=Karl |last1=McDonald|date=13 May 2019|access-date=28 August 2019}}</ref> while the prorogation in 2019 at Johnson's request would have been the longest prorogation since 1930.<ref>{{cite newspaper|title=Westminster shutdown:is Britain facing a coup? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/sep/01/britain-coup-parliament-suspend-prorogue-brexit|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=1 September 2019|author=Meg Russell}}</ref>\n\nThe government said that the prorogation was to allow for the government to set out a new legislative agenda.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/aug/13/bercow-will-fight-to-stop-johnson-closing-parliament-for-no-deal|title=Bercow will 'fight with every breath' to stop Johnson closing parliament for no deal|last=Elgot|first=Jessica|date=13 August 2019|work=The Guardian}}</ref> Others questioned this justification, and said that the prorogation was an improper attempt to evade parliamentary scrutiny of Johnson's [[Brexit]] plans in advance of the UK's planned departure from the [[European Union]] on 31 October 2019; opponents of prorogation included opposition MPs,<ref name=\"Guardian28aug\"/> UK constitutional law scholars,<ref>{{cite newspaper|title=Letters: The 'improper' nature of this prorogation|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/comment/times-letters-the-improper-nature-of-this-prorogation-2r6zq0xfr|newspaper=Times of London|date=3 September 2019}}</ref> and Sir [[John Major]], the former Conservative Prime Minister.<ref>{{cite newspaper|author=Owen Bowcott|title=John Major's lawyer attacks No 10 prorogation claims as 'misleading'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/sep/19/john-majors-lawyer-attacks-no-10-prorogation-claims-as-misleading|newspaper=The Guardian|date=19 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper|title=Boris Johnson should apologise to Parliament for prorogation, says Sir John Major|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/09/24/boris-johnson-should-apologise-parliament-prorogation-says-sir/|newspaper=The Telegraph|author=Tony Diver|date=24 September 2019}}</ref> The [[Speaker of the House of Commons (United Kingdom)|Speaker of the House of Commons]], [[John Bercow]], called the decision a \"constitutional outrage\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channel4.com/news/factcheck/factcheck-parliament-prorogation-explained|title=Parliament \u2018prorogation\u2019 explained|last=Lee|first=Georgina|date=28 August 2019|website=Channel 4|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=28 August 2019}}</ref> \n\nThree separate cases were lodged before the courts alleging its illegality. The [[High Court of Justice]] in London found the issue to be [[non-justiciable]], but the highest civil court in Scotland, the [[Court of Session]] sitting in Edinburgh, ruled prorogation was [[Violation of law|unlawful]] as it had the \"improper purpose of [[wikt:stymie|stymie]]ing Parliament\".<ref>See A. Young, \u2018[https://ukconstitutionallaw.org/2019/09/13/alison-young-prorogation-politics-and-the-principle-of-legality/ Prorogation, Politics and the Principle of Legality]\u2019, U.K. Const. L. Blog (13 Sept. 2019) and E. McGaughey, \u2018[https://ukconstitutionallaw.org/2019/09/14/ewan-mcgaughey-is-there-a-legal-measure-to-judge-parliaments-prorogration/ Is There a \"Legal Measure\" to Judge Parliament\u2019s Prorogration?]\u2019, U.K. Const. L. Blog (14 Sept. 2019)</ref> The issue was brought before the [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]] on 17 September 2019 in the cases [[R (Miller) v The Prime Minister and Cherry v Advocate General for Scotland|''R (Miller) v The Prime Minister'' and ''Cherry v Advocate General for Scotland'']].<ref>{{cite news|title=Scottish judges rule Parliament suspension is unlawful|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-49661855|publisher=BBC News|date=11 September 2019}}</ref> On 24 September, the Supreme Court ruled unanimously that the prorogation was both justiciable and unlawful, and therefore null and of no effect.<ref>{{cite news |last= Bowcott |first=Owen |date=24 September 2019 |title=Boris Johnson's suspension of parliament unlawful, supreme court rules |url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2019/sep/24/boris-johnsons-suspension-of-parliament-unlawful-supreme-court-rules-prorogue |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |publication-place=London |access-date=24 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Supreme Court: Suspending Parliament was unlawful, judges rule |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-49810261 |newspaper=[[BBC News]] |publication-place=London |date=24 September 2019 |access-date=24 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite court |litigants=R (Miller) (Appellant) v The Prime Minister (Respondent) and Cherry & Ors (Respondents) v Advocate General for Scotland (Appellant) (Scotland) |reporter=&#91;2019&#93; UKSC 41 |date=24 September 2019 |url=https://www.supremecourt.uk/cases/docs/uksc-2019-0192-judgment.pdf |access-date=24 September 2018}}</ref> Parliament resumed sitting the following day, resuming the parliamentary session.<ref>{{cite new|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-49820038|title=Parliament: MPs and peers return after court rules suspension unlawful|work=[[BBC News]]|date=25 September 2019}}</ref><ref>https://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2019/september/end-of-the-2017-19-parliament-/</ref> Bercow said he would ensure that the attempted prorogation would be expunged from the House of Commons Journal, the corrected formal record of parliamentary business, and replaced with a statement that Parliament was adjourned for the period of the absence.<ref>Bianca Britton, [https://edition.cnn.com/2019/09/25/uk/mps-return-to-parliament-gbr-intl/index.html Lawmakers return to Parliament after court rules against Boris Johnson's prorogation], CNN (25 September 2019).</ref><ref>Chris Smyth & Steven Swinford, [https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/supreme-court-ruling-this-parliament-is-dead-says-law-chief-geoffrey-cox-p8hnkd5dw Supreme Court ruling: This parliament is dead, says law chief Geoffrey Cox], ''The Times'' (26 September 2019).</ref>\n\n====Calls for early election====\nOn 3 September 2019, [[Boris Johnson]] threatened to call a [[general election]] after opposition and rebel Conservative MPs successfully voted against the government to take control of the order of business with a view to preventing a no-deal exit.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/09/03/brexit-latest-news-boris-johnson-no-deal-vote-general-election/|title=Brexit vote result: Boris Johnson demands general election after rebel MPs seize control of Commons agenda|last1=Rayner|first1=Gordon|last2=Sheridan|first2=Danielle|date=3 September 2019|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> \n \nDespite government opposition, the [[Benn Act|bill to block a no-deal exit]] passed the Commons on 4 September 2019, causing Johnson to call for a general election on 15 October.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49580185|title=MPs back bill aimed at blocking no-deal Brexit|date=4 September 2019|access-date=4 September 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> However, this motion was unsuccessful as it failed to command the support of two-thirds of the House as required by the [[Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011|Fixed-term Parliaments Act]] (FTPA).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49584907|title=Johnson's call for general election rejected by MPs|date=4 September 2019|access-date=4 September 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> A second attempt at a motion for an early general election failed on 9 September.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/sep/09/mps-order-johnson-to-hand-over-aides-messages-about-prorogation|title=Boris Johnson loses sixth vote in six days as election bid fails|last=Mason |first=Rowena |date=10 September 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\n====Brexit negotiations====\n{{main|Brexit negotiations in 2019}}\n\nOn 2 October the Government published a fresh Brexit plan, which included proposals to replace the [[Irish backstop]]. It would create an \"all-island regulatory zone\", meaning that Northern Ireland would essentially stay in the [[European Single Market]] for agricultural and industrial goods, meaning that [[Sanitary and phytosanitary measures and agreements|sanitary and phytosanitary controls]] would be needed between Northern Ireland and Great Britain.<ref name=\"BBC21019\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-49909309 |title=Government publishes Brexit proposals |work=BBC News |date=2 October 2019 |accessdate=2 October 2019}}</ref> The proposal also declared that Northern Ireland, along with the rest of the UK, would leave the Customs Union, meaning that customs controls would be needed for cross-border goods trade.<ref name=\"BBC21019\" /> The proposal did not appear to address cross-border services.{{fact|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn 4 October the Government assured the highest civil court in Scotland that Johnson would send a letter to the EU seeking an extension to Article 50 as required by the European Union (Withdrawal) (No. 2) Act 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-49936352 |title=Brexit: Boris Johnson will send extension letter \u2013 court document |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=4 October 2019 |accessdate=4 October 2019}}</ref> The court was originally due to release their ruling on 9 October, but decided to delay doing so until 21 October, in order to allow the court to \"assess how circumstances have changed\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-49975066 |title=Brexit: Scottish court delays decision on extension letter |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=9 October 2019 |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref> On 17 October 2019, a revised withdrawal agreement, with a changed backstop, was agreed by the EU leaders and Boris Johnson.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/sites/beta-political/files/revised_withdrawal_agreement_including_protocol_on_ireland_and_nothern_ireland.pdf|title=Revised Withdrawal Agreement|last=|first=|date=17 October 2019|website=|publisher=European Commission|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50079385|title=New Brexit deal agreed, says Boris Johnson|last=|first=|date=17 October 2019|work=BBC|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 October, a special Saturday sitting of Parliament was held to debate the revised agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49984367|title=Brexit: Special sitting for MPs to decide UK's future|date=9 October 2019|website=BBC News|accessdate=9 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/09/parliament-set-for-brexit-showdown-on-19-october|title=Parliament set for Brexit showdown on 19 October|last=Murphy|first=Simon|date=9 October 2019|work=The Guardian|accessdate=9 October 2019}}</ref> MPs passed [[Parliamentary votes on Brexit#Second Letwin amendment (19 October 2019)|an amendment]] by 322 votes to 306 that withheld Parliament's approval until legislation implementing the deal had been passed, and forced the Government to request a delay to Brexit until 31 January 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/19/mps-put-brakes-on-boris-johnsons-brexit-deal-with-rebel-letwin-amendment|title=MPs put brakes on Boris Johnson's Brexit deal with rebel amendment|last=Stewart|first=Heather|date=19 October 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=19 October 2019|last2=Proctor|first2=Kate|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Later that evening, 10 Downing Street confirmed that Boris Johnson would send a letter to the EU requesting an extension, but would not sign it.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-50112924 |title=Brexit: PM sends letter to Brussels seeking further delay |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=19 October 2019 |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref> EU Council President [[Donald Tusk]] subsequently confirmed receipt of the letter, which Johnson had described as \"Parliament's letter, not my letter\". In addition, Johnson sent a second letter expressing the view that any further delay to Brexit would be a mistake.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-50112924 |title=Brexit: PM sends letter to Brussels seeking further delay |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=20 October 2019 |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 October, the UK government brought the recently revised EU Withdrawal Bill to the House of Commons for debate.<ref name=\"BBC22Oct\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-50146182|title=MPs reject Brexit bill timetable|work=BBC News|date=22 October 2019|access-date=22 October 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> MPs voted on the Bill itself, which was passed by 329 votes to 299, and on the timetable for debating the Bill, which was defeated by 322 votes to 308. Prior to the votes, Johnson had stated that if his timetable failed to generate the support needed to pass in parliament he would abandon attempts to get the deal approved and would seek a general election. Following the vote, however, Johnson announced that the legislation would be paused while he consulted with other EU leaders.<ref name=\"BBC22Oct\"/><ref name=\"Reuters22Oct\">{{cite web|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-eu/british-parliament-backs-pm-johnsons-brexit-deal-at-important-stage-idUKKBN1X10K0|title=Brexit in chaos after parliament defeats Johnson's ratification timetable|last1=James|first1=William|last2=MacLellan|first2=Kylie|last3=Piper|first3=Elizabeth|website=[[Reuters.com]]|date=22 October 2019|access-date=22 October 2019|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 28 October 2019, it was confirmed that Brexit had been delayed until 31 January 2020.<ref name=BBC281019>[https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50205603 Brexit: Johnson agrees to Brexit extension \u2013 but urges election] ''[[BBC News]]'' 28 October 2019</ref> The following day, MPs backed a [[2019 United Kingdom general election|general election]] on 12 December 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-50229318 |title=MPs back 12 December election |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref> On 30 October 2019, the day named as \"exit day\" in UK legislation was changed to 31 January 2020 at 11.00 p.m.<ref>The European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018 (Exit Day) (Amendment) (No. 3) Regulations 2019 SI 2019 No. 1423, 30 October 2019.[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2019/1423/regulation/2/made]</ref>\n\n==== 2019 general election ====\n{{Main|2019 United Kingdom general election}}\nAt the election, the Conservatives made a net gain of 48 seats, in what was regarded as a [[landslide victory]], winning 43.6% of the vote (the highest share for any party since [[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979]]) and 365 seats (the highest number for the party since [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]]), whereas Labour made a net loss of 60 seats, losing several of its constituencies in northern England, across the Midlands and Wales to the Conservatives (often for the first time in many decades).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election/2019/results|title=Results|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.statista.com/statistics/717004/general-elections-vote-share-by-party-uk/|title=Share of votes in general elections in the United Kingdom from 1918 to 2017, by political party|website=Statista|accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref> Labour's losses in the general election led its leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] to announce his intention to resign as the party's leader.<ref name=\"Corbyn Defeat\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2019-50766114|title=Jeremy Corbyn: 'I will not lead Labour at next election'|publisher=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/socialist-jeremy-corbyn-steps-down-leader-labour-party-after-crushing-n1101166|title=Socialist Jeremy Corbyn to step down as leader of Labour Party after projected defeat in U.K. election|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref> The [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] increased their vote share to 11.6% of the votes, though leader [[Jo Swinson]] was obliged under her party's rules to announce her resignation after losing her seat in [[East Dunbartonshire (UK Parliament constituency)|East Dunbartonshire]], leaving her party with 11 seats.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2019-50771123|title=Lib Dem leader Jo Swinson to step down|date=13 December 2019|accessdate=13 December 2019|publisher=BBC News|language=en-GB}}</ref> The [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] held its one seat and saw its vote share increase.\n\nThe [[Scottish National Party]] (SNP) made a net gain of 13 seats across [[2019 United Kingdom general election in Scotland|Scotland]], winning 45% of the Scottish vote and 48 of the 59 Scottish seats,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2019-50766014|title=SNP wins election landslide in Scotland|date=2019-12-13|access-date=2019-12-15|language=en-GB}}</ref> while in [[2019 United Kingdom general election in Wales|Wales]], [[Plaid Cymru]] retained its four seats with no significant change in vote share. In [[2019 United Kingdom general election in Northern Ireland|Northern Ireland]], for the first time more [[Irish nationalism|Irish Nationalist]] MPs were elected than [[Unionism in Ireland|British Unionists]], although unionist parties still won more votes; [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] retained the same number of seats, and the [[Democratic Unionist Party|DUP]] lost two seats, while the [[Social Democratic and Labour Party]] (SDLP) regained two seats, and the [[Alliance Party of Northern Ireland|Alliance Party]] regained a seat, giving the latter two parties a restored presence in the House of Commons.\n\n==== Post-election aftermath  ====\nThe election results had a variety of different effects and set the dynamics of UK politics going into the [[2020s in United Kingdom political history|new decade]]. For the first time since the 2016 referendum it became almost certain that Brexit would take place with the process of passing the withdrawal agreement through parliament beginning before Christmas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2019/december/withdrawal-agreement-bill/|title=MPs pass Second Reading of the Withdrawal Agreement Bill - News from Parliament|website=UK Parliament|language=English|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref> For the Conservative Party, the election meant a shift from a fairly weak administration in the hung parliament of 2017 to 2019 to governing with a majority on a scale they had not known since the early 1990s, potentially, setting them up to remain in power for many years to come.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2017-40237833|title=10 ways the PM blew her majority|last=Wheeler|first=Alex Hunt and Brian|date=2017-06-14|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-01-22|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2019-50776671|title=Johnson: I will repay the trust of voters|date=2019-12-13|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-01-22|language=en-GB}}</ref> For the Labour Party, the defeat meant an end to the [[Labour Party leadership of Jeremy Corbyn|leadership of Jeremy Corbyn]] with preparations beginning for a [[2020 Labour Party leadership election|new leadership]]  and [[2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election|deputy leadership]] contest in early 2020 whilst rekindling debates within the party and beyond about its tactical and ideological future.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2019-50766114|title=Corbyn: I will not lead Labour at next election|date=2019-12-13|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-01-22|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/dec/31/only-way-labour-win-ditch-labourism-corbyn|title=The only way Labour can win is by ditching \u2018Labourism\u2019 {{!}} Jeremy Gilbert|last=Gilbert|first=Jeremy|date=2019-12-31|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-22|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/jan/21/crushed-by-brexit-how-labour-lost-the-election|title='Crushed by Brexit': how Labour lost the election|last=Stewart|first=Heather|date=2020-01-21|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-22|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/jan/21/keir-starmer-soft-left-approach-unifying-labour|title=Keir Starmer\u2019s soft-left approach is the unifying force that Labour needs {{!}} Zoe Williams|last=Williams|first=Zoe|date=2020-01-21|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-22|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/jan/08/labour-membership-doesnt-want-return-to-1997|title=Labour members want something new \u2013 not a return to 1997 {{!}} Owen Jones|last=Jones|first=Owen|date=2020-01-08|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-22|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> For the Liberal Democrats, Jo Swinson's unseating at the election also meant a fresh [[2020 Liberal Democrats leadership election|leadership election]] in the new year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-51164894|title=New Liberal Democrat leader in place by mid-July|date=2020-01-18|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-01-22|language=en-GB}}</ref> Whilst, for the SNP, dominance in Scotland renewed hopes for a [[Proposed second Scottish independence referendum|second Scottish independence referendum]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/dec/13/nicola-sturgeon-to-publish-independence-referendum-blueprint|title=Scottish independence vote a 'democratic right', says Sturgeon|last=Carrell|first=Severin|date=2019-12-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-22|last2=Brooks|first2=Libby|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>[[Labour Party leadership of Jeremy Corbyn|<br />]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Brexit]]\n* [[2010s political history]]\n*[[2020s in United Kingdom political history]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{United Kingdom topics}}\n\n[[Category:2010s in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Political history]]\n[[Category:Years of the 21st century in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Politics overviews by decade]]\n[[Category:2010 in British politics]]\n[[Category:2011 in British politics]]\n[[Category:2012 in British politics]]\n[[Category:2013 in British politics]]\n[[Category:2014 in British politics]]\n[[Category:2015 in British politics]]\n[[Category:2016 in British politics]]\n[[Category:2017 in British politics]]\n[[Category:2018 in British politics]]\n[[Category:2019 in British politics]]\n[[Category:2010 United Kingdom general election]]\n[[Category:2015 United Kingdom general election]]\n[[Category:2017 United Kingdom general election]]\n[[Category:2019 United Kingdom general election]]\n[[Category:Brexit]]\n[[Category:2010s in politics]]\n", "name_user": "Fayenatic london", "label": "safe", "comment": "Copying fromCategory:Politics overviews by decadetoCategory:2010 in politicsusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2010s_in_United_Kingdom_political_history"}
{"title_page": "2010s in United States political history", "text_new": "{{See also|2020s in United States political history}}\n'''2010s in United States political history''' is a narrative summary of major political events and issues in the United States from January 1, 2010, through December 31, 2019. The first part is divided chronologically by Congressional sessions and the second part highlights major issues that span several years or even the entire decade. There are links for further information.\n\n==History by era==\n\n{{expand section|date=March 2020}}\n\n===2009-2011, 111th Congress===\n{{see also|Obama Presidency|111th United States Congress}}\nDemocrats swept into 2009 with control over the White House and both Houses of Congress. [[Nancy Peolosi]] (D-CA) was [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House of Representatives]] and [[Harry Reid]] (D-NV) was [[Party leaders of the United States Senate|Senate Majority Leader]]. The Democratic supermajority in the Senate was guaranteed with the election of [[Al Franken]] (D-MN) in January and when Republican [[Arlen Specter]] (D-PA) switched to the Democratic Party. Major legislative victories included the [[Lilly Ledbetter Fair Pay Act of 2009]] (providing equal pay for women), [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009]] (designed to preserve existing jobs and to create new ones), [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] (extending health-care coverage to millions; popularly called \"Obamacare\"), [[Dodd\u2013Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act]] (the first major financial reform since the 1930s), [[Small Business Jobs Act of 2010]] (providing financing for small businesses), [[Tax Relief, Unemployment Insurance Reauthorization, and Job Creation Act of 2010|2010 Tax Relief Act]] (temporary tax relief for the middle class), [[Don't Ask, Don't Tell Repeal Act of 2010]] (allowing gay, lesbian, and transgender people to serve openly in the military), and the [[James Zadroga 9/11 Health and Compensation Act]] (provides support for first responders who survived the [[September 11 attacks|September 11, 2001, terrorist attacks]]).<ref>[https://www.politico.com/story/2010/10/the-legacy-of-the-111th-congress-042983 The legacy of the 111th Congress] By RICHARD E. COHEN, Politico, 1 Oct 2010, retrieved 10 March 2020</ref>\n\nThe Senate confirmed the appointments of two women to the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]]: [[Sonia Sotomayor]] (the first Latino to hold the post)<ref>[https://www.usnews.com/news/national/articles/2009/08/06/sotomayor-confirmed-as-first-hispanic-supreme-court-justice-in-victory-for-obama Sotomayor Confirmed as First Hispanic Supreme Court Justice in Victory for Obama] By Queenie Wong, [[U.S. News & World Report]], 6 Aug 2009, retrieved 22 March 2020</ref> and [[Elena Kagan]].<ref>[https://www.denverpost.com/2010/08/05/senate-confirms-kagans-nomination-to-supreme-court/ Senate confirms Kagan\u2019s nomination to Supreme Court] [[The Denver Post]], 5 Aug 2010, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nPresident [[Barack Obama|Barack Obama's]] September 9, 2009, Congressional address promoting health care reform was interrupted by Congressman [[Joe Wilson (American politician)|Joe Wilson]] (R-SC) who shouted: \"You lie!\" when Obama said his health care plan would not cover undocumented immigrants.<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/09/09/joe.wilson/index.html Rep. Wilson shouts, 'You lie' to Obama during speech] CNN Politics, retrieved 10 March 2020</ref> The Democrats' supermajority in the Senate ended on February 4, 2010, with the election of [[Scott Brown (politician)|Scott Brown]] (R-MA).<ref>[https://www.cbsnews.com/news/brown-mass-win-about-anger-not-obama/ Brown: Mass. Win about Anger, not Obama] CBS News, 20 Jan 2010, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nPresident Obama unsuccessfully tried to close [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]] for suspected terrorists.<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/01/22/guantanamo.order/index.html Obama signs order to close Guantanamo Bay facility] CNN, retrieved 10 March 2020</ref> Conservative opponents of Obama formed the [[Tea Party movement]] in February 2009. Obama was granted the [[2009 Nobel Peace Prize]], despite presiding over the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|war in Afghanistan]] and the [[Iraq War]].<ref>[https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/peace/2009/press-release/ The Nobel Peace Prize for 2009] The Nobel Prize.org, retrieved 22 March 2020</ref> The ''[[Deepwater Horizon oil spill]]'' was a major ecological disaster from April through September 2010.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|encyclopedia=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]|title=Deepwater Horizon oil spill|date=Mar 13, 2020|accessdate=22 Mar 2020|first=Richard |last=Pallardy |url=https://www.britannica.com/event/Deepwater-Horizon-oil-spill}}</ref> A reneotiated [[United States\u2013Korea Free Trade Agreement|free trade agreement with South Korea]] went into effect on December 3, 2010.<ref>[http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2010/12/05/2003490144 US, South Korea sign sweeping free-trade agreement] [[Taipei Times]], 5 Dec 2010, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nThe [[2010 United States elections]] resulted in major victories for the Republican Party.<ref>[https://www.usnews.com/opinion/blogs/peter-roff/2010/11/05/measuring-the-size-of-election-2010s-republican-sweep Measuring the Size of Election 2010's Republican Sweep] By Peter Roff, U.S. News & World Report, 5 Nov 2020, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n===2011-2013, 112th Congress===\n{{see also|Obama Presidency|112th United States Congress}}\nFollowing the 2010 elections, Republicans gained control of the House of Representatives while the Democratic majority in the Senate was narrowed. [[John Boehner]] (R-OH) was Speaker of the House and [[Harry Reid]] (D-NV) was Senate Majority Leader. The Congress was unproductive, passing only 219 bills that were signed into law, compared to 383 in the 111th Congress. Congress failed to pass legislation to keep the [[United States Postal Service|Postal Service]] solvent, and they allowed the [[Violence Against Women Act]] to lapse for the first time since it was passed in 1994.<ref>[http://www.msnbc.com/the-daily-rundown/112th-congress-set-become-least-productiv 112th Congress set to become least productive in decades] By Sarah Blackwill, MSNBC, 13 September 2013, retrieved 11 March 2020</ref>\n\nThe United States entered trade agreements with [[United States\u2013Colombia Free Trade Agreement|Colombia]]<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-18069469 Colombia-US free trade agreement comes into force] BBC News, 12 May 2012, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> and [[Panama\u2013United States Trade Promotion Agreement|Panama]].<ref>[https://www.everycrsreport.com/reports/RL32540.html The U.S.-Panama Free Trade Agreement] Every CRSReport, 8 Nov 2012, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> [[Middle Class Tax Relief and Job Creation Act of 2012|Payroll Taxes]] were cut and the low [[American Taxpayer Relief Act of 2012|income tax rates]] established by the George W. Bush administration were kept in place. The [[National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2012]] not only provided funding for the DoD and authorization for state governors to request military help in the case of natural disasters but also controversially contained anti-terrorist provisions that allow the indefinite detention of American citizens on American soil. The [[Budget Control Act of 2011]] called for a reduction in spending in order to lower the [[United States debt-ceiling crisis of 2011|federal debt]].\n\nCongresswoman [[Gabby Giffords]] (D-AZ) and nineteen other people were shot in [[2011 Tucson shooting|Tucson]] on January 8, 2011.<ref>[https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/local/arizona/2018/04/05/fbi-releases-new-photos-video-2011-gabby-giffords-shooting/489367002/ FBI releases new photos, video of 2011 Giffords shooting] by Josh Susong, AZ Central (USA Today), 5 April 2018, retrieved 11 March 2020</ref> Twenty children and six adults were killed in a shooting at [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting|Sandy Hook Elementary School]] in Newtown, Connecticut, sparking a debate about gun laws.<ref>[https://www.britannica.com/event/Newtown-shootings-of-2012 Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting] Encyclopaedia, retrieved 11 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nThe United States joined NATO in [[2011 military intervention in Libya|military intervention in Libya]],<ref>[https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/2011/03/28/remarks-president-address-nation-libya Remarks by the President in Address to the Nation on Libya] The White House, 28 Mar 2011, retrieved 11 Mar 2020</ref> which led to the [[death of Muammar Gaddafi]].<ref>[https://www.aljazeera.com/programmes/the-big-picture/2018/11/death-gaddafi-181103124656506.html The Death of Gaddafi] Al Jazeera, 5 Nov 2018, retrieved 11 Mar 2020</ref> In May 2011 Navy SEALS killed [[Death of Osama bin Laden|Al-Qaeda leader Osama bin Laden]].<ref>[https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Draft:2010s_in_United_States_political_history&action=edit&section=3 Death of Osama bin Laden Fast Facts] CNN Library, 18 Apr 2019, retrieved 11 Mar 2020</ref> On September 11, 2012, members of Ansar al-Sharia attacked the American diplomatic compound in [[2012 Benghazi attack|Benghazi]], resulting in the deaths of U.S. Ambassador to Libya [[J. Christopher Stevens]] and three other Americans.<ref>[https://www.upi.com/Top_News/US/2012/11/02/US-officials-CIA-ran-Benghazi-consulate/44771351839600/?ur3=1 U.S. officials: CIA ran Benghazi consulate] UPI, 2 Nov 2012, retrieved 11 Mar 2020</ref> The United States stepped up [[drone attacks in Pakistan]], [[Somali Civil War (2009\u2013present)|Somalia]], and [[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Yemen]], targeting Yemeni-American Muslim cleric [[Anwar al-Awlaki]] on September 30, 2011.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-15121879 Islamist cleric Anwar al-Awlaki killed in Yemen] BBC News, 30 Sep 2011, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> His 16-year-old son, American-born [[Abdulrahman al-Awlaki]], was killed two weeks later.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-airstrike-that-killed-american-teen-in-yemen-raises-legal-ethical-questions/2011/10/20/gIQAdvUY7L_story.html U.S. airstrike that killed American teen in Yemen raises legal, ethical questions] By Craig Whitlock, [[The Washington Post]], 22 Oct 2011, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nThe popular movement against income inequality known as [[Occupy Wall Street]] began with a march on [[Wall Street]], New York City in February 2011.<ref>[http://occupywallst.org/about/ About] OccupyWallStreet.org, retrieved 11 March 2020</ref>\n\n[[Trayvon Martin]], an unarmed black 17-year-old, was fatally shot by [[George Zimmerman]] in [[Sanford, Florida]]. The killing received widespread attention focusing on aspects including the possible role of Martin's race and the initial lack of prosecution against Zimmerman, and it raised questions about Florida's [[Stand-your-ground law|\"Hold your ground\"]] gun law.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-17441277 |title=Trayvon Martin: Probe into killing of Florida teenager |date=March 20, 2012 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2012, Wisconsin Governor [[Scott Walker (politician)|Scott Walker]] won a recall election against Milwaukee Mayor [[Tom Barrett (Wisconsin politician)|Tom Barrett]].<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2012/06/05/politics/wisconsin-recall-vote/index.html Walker's Wisconsin win big blow to unions, smaller one to Obama] By John Helton and Tom Cohen, CNN, 6 June 2012, retrieved 11 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nPresident Obama was [[2012 United States presidential election|reelected in 2012]], defeating Republican [[Mitt Romney 2012 presidential campaign|Mitt Romney]].<ref>[https://www.latimes.com/world/la-xpm-2013-jan-04-la-pn-obama-biden-officially-win-second-term-20130104-story.html It\u2019s official: Obama, Biden win second term] By  MICHAEL A. MEMOLI, LA Times, 4 Jan 2013, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> Democrats gained two [[2012 United States Senate elections|Senate seats]].<ref>[https://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Politics/The-Vote/2012/1106/Election-2012-results-Liveblog-In-Senate-Democrats-ward-off-challenges Election 2012 results Liveblog: In Senate, Democrats ward off challenges] [[The Christian Science Monitor]], 6 Nov 2012, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> Democrats won the popular vote and eight [[2012 United States House of Representatives elections|House seats]], but it was not enough to regain control of the [https://transition.fec.gov/pubrec/fe2012/federalelections2012.pdf the lower chamber].<ref>[https://ballotpedia.org/United_States_Congressional_elections_results,_2012 United States Congressional elections results, 2012] Ballotpedia, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n===2013-2015, 113th Congress===\n{{see also|Obama Presidency|113th United States Congress}}\nThe Senate had a Democratic majority, but the House had a Republican majority. Harry Reid (D-NV) was Senate Majority Leader and John Boehner (R-OH) was Speaker of the House.<ref>[https://gai.georgetown.edu/resources-publications/the-113th-congress/113th-congress-by-the-numbers/ 113TH CONGRESS BY THE NUMBERS] Government Affairs Institute at Georgetown University, retrieved 11 Mar 2020</ref> The 113th was one of the least productive in history, notable for brinkmanship (shutting down the government for 16 days in 2013 and almost shutting it down again in 2014). According to [[Gallup (company)]], only 15% of Americans approved of the Congress' work, only 1% more than the all-time low of the 112th Congress. The Senate passed immigration reform but House Republicans killed it; the House passed gun reform, but it did not pass the Senate. House Republicans offered legislation on the economy and health care (voting 50 times to repeal Obamacare), but these did not pass the Senate. Senator [[Rand Paul]] (R-KY) filibustered the nomination of [[John Brennan (CIA officer)|John Brennan]] as CIA director for thirteen hours.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2013/03/07/173693133/nearly-13-hours-later-sen-paul-ends-his-filibuster-heres-the-video Nearly 13 Hours Later, Sen. Paul Ends His Filibuster; Here's The Video] NPR, 7 Mar 2013, retrieved 11 Mar 2020</ref> [[Ted Cruz]] (R-TX) wasted a record 21 hours of the Senate's time by reading ''Green Eggs and Ham'' by [[Dr. Seuss]] as a complaint (but not a fillibuster) against health care.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2016/01/04/rick-santorum-mocks-ted-cruz-green-eggs-and-ham/78253012/ Rick Santorum mocks Ted Cruz for 'Green Eggs and Ham'] by Mary Troyan, USA Today, 4 Jan 2016, retrieved 11 Mar 2020</ref> Senator [[John McCain]] (R-AZ) called the Senate's lack of work \"disgraceful.\"<ref name=unproductive>[https://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/senate/227365-historically-unproductive-congress-ends Historically unproductive Congress ends] BY CRISTINA MARCOS AND RAMSEY COX, The Hill, 16 Dec 2014, retrieved 11 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nAmong the few bills passed were a [[Agricultural Act of 2014|five-year farm bill]] and reform of [[Veterans' Access to Care through Choice, Accountability, and Transparency Act of 2014|VA benefits]].<ref name=unproductive/> They reauthorized the Violence Against Women Act<ref>[https://www.hrw.org/news/2013/02/28/us-violence-against-women-act-renewed US: Violence Against Women Act Renewed] Human Rights Watch, 28 Feb 2013, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> and the [[Pandemic and All-Hazards Preparedness Reauthorization Act of 2013|Pandemic and All-Hazards Preparedness Act]].<ref>[https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/hr307 H.R. 307 (113th): Pandemic and All-Hazards Preparedness Reauthorization Act of 2013] GovTrack.us, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> They supported the government of [[Support for the Sovereignty, Integrity, Democracy, and Economic Stability of Ukraine Act of 2014|Ukraine]]<ref>[https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/hr4152 H.R. 4152 (113th): Support for the Sovereignty, Integrity, Democracy, and Economic Stability of Ukraine Act of 2014] GovTrack.us, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> and the [https://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/Programs/Documents/venezuela_publ_113_278.pdf opposition] in [[Venezuela Defense of Human Rights and Civil Society Act of 2014|Venezuela]].<ref>[https://sanctionsnews.bakermckenzie.com/us-congress-passes-venezuela-defense-of-human-rights-and-civil-society-act/ US Congress Passes Venezuela Defense of Human Rights and Civil Society Act] by EUNKYUNG KIM SHIN AND PAUL AMBERG, Baker McKenzie Blog Sanctions News, 17 December 2014</ref>\n\nInformation about [[Global surveillance disclosures (2013\u2013present)|global surevillance]] was released in June 2013.<ref>[https://www.nationaljournal.com/s/64142/everything-we-learned-from-edward-snowden-2013 Everything We Learned From Edward Snowden in 2013] National Journal, retrieved 11 March 2020 (paysite)</ref> The Supreme Court overturned key provisions of the [[Shelby County v. Holder|Voting Rights Act of 1965]] and the [[United States v. Windsor|Defense of Marriage Act]].\n\nRepublicans swept the [[2014 United States elections|November 2014 elections]].<ref name=unproductive/>\n\n===2015-2017, 114th Congress===\n{{see also|Obama Presidency|114th United States Congress}}\nRepublicans controlled the House of Representatives with John Boehner (R-OH) as Speaker until October 29, 2015, when [[Paul Ryan|Paul D. Ryan]] (R\u2013WI) was chosen to replace him.<ref>[https://history.house.gov/Congressional-Overview/Profiles/114th/ Congress Profiles] United States House of Representatives; History, Art, and Archives; retrieved 11 March 2020</ref> [[Mitch McConnell]] (R-KY) was Senate Majority leader.<ref name=Senate_leader>[https://www.senate.gov/artandhistory/history/common/briefing/Majority_Minority_Leaders.htm#2 Majority and Minority Leaders] Senate.gov., retrieved 22 March 2020</ref>\n\nThe [[USA Freedom Act]] was an updated version of the [[Patriot Act]] with certain restrictions on spying on American civilians. President Obama threatened to veto the [[Iran Nuclear Agreement Review Act of 2015]], but the bill passed the Senate 98-1 and Obama withdrew his threat. The [[Every Student Succeeds Act]] replaced the [[No Child Left Behind Act]]. The [[Justice Against Sponsors of Terrorism Act]], which allows survivors of the [[September 11 attacks|September 11, 2001, terrorist attacks]] to sue [[Saudi Arabia]], which passed over Obama's veto. Obama also vetoed a bill authorizing the [[Keystone Pipeline]].<ref>[https://ballotpedia.org/Barack_Obama:_Vetoed_legislation Barack Obama: Vetoed legislation] Ballotpedia, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> The [[Fixing America's Surface Transportation Act]] provided $305 billion for highway improvement without increasing the gas tax.<ref>[https://usa.streetsblog.org/2015/12/02/5-year-300-billion-fast-act-will-extend-transpo-policy-status-quo-to-2020/ 5-Year, $300 Billion \"FAST Act\" Will Extend Transpo Policy Status Quo to 2020] By Angie Schmitt, USA.Streetsblog.org, 2 Dec 2015, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> The [[Internet Tax Freedom Act]] made the prohibition on taxing Internet services permanent.<ref>{{cite web|website=The Wall Street Journal (Opinion)|title=Obama's Best Day in Office?|date=Feb 24, 2016|accessdate=Mar 22, 2020 |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/obamas-best-day-in-office-1456316788}}</ref> The [[Sexual Assault Survivors' Rights Act]] provides increased rights for victims of sexual assault.<ref>[https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/emaoconnor/historic-bill-of-rights-for-survivors-of-sexual-assault-is-h Historic Bill Of Rights For Survivors Of Sexual Assault Is Heading To Obama's Desk] by Emma O'Connor, BuzzFeed, 7 Sep 2016, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> The [[21st Century Cures Act]] was a victory for [[Pharmaceutical industry|Big Pharma]], allowing new drugs to get on the market more easily.<ref>[https://www.healthnewsreview.org/2016/12/with-media-watchdogs-sidelined-pharma-funded-advocacy-groups-pushed-cures-act-to-the-finish-line/ With media watchdogs on the sidelines, pharma-funded advocacy groups pushed Cures Act to the finish line] by Trudy Lieberman, Health News Review, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nThe Prime Minister of Israel [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] was invited by Speaker Boehner to address a joint session of Congress regarding sanctions against Iran without consulting President Obama in March 2015.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bradner |first1=Eric |title=Criticism over Netanyahu visit intensifies |url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/01/25/politics/mcdonough-obama-netanyahu |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=January 25, 2015}}</ref> Other world leaders to address Congress were Afghanistan President [[Ashraf Ghani]] (March 2015),<ref>[http://www.nwaonline.com/news/2015/mar/26/in-u-s-ghani-vows-afghan-self-reliance-/ \"In U.S., Ghani Vows Afghan Self-Reliance\"]. by Deb Riechmann, ''Northwest Arkansas Democrat-Gazette,'' 26 March 2015, Retrieved 22 March 2020</ref> Japanese Prime Minister [[Shinz\u014d Abe]] (April 2015),<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-japan-speech/japan-pm-abe-to-address-joint-session-of-congress-idUSKBN0MM2DY20150327 Japan PM Abe to address joint session of Congress] by Patricia Zengerle, Reuters, 26 Mar 2020, retrieved 22 March 2020</ref> [[Pope Francis]] (September 2015),<ref>[https://www.politico.com/story/2015/02/pope-address-us-congress-114939 Pope will address Congress in September] By JAKE SHERMAN, Politico, 5 Feb 2015, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> and Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]]<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2016/06/08/politics/modi-speech-u-s-congress-visit/index.html Modi addresses Congress as U.S.-India ties bloom] By Nicole Gaouette and Elise Labott, CNN, 9 June 2016, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> addressed joint sessions of Congress. President Obama [[Cuban thaw|thawed relations with Cuba]], removing the country from the [[State Sponsors of Terrorism (U.S. list)|list of state sponsors of terrorism]],<ref>[https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/u-s-officially-removes-cuba-state-sponsor-terrorism-list-n366621 U.S. Officially Removes Cuba From State Sponsors of Terrorism List] By Andrea Mitchell, NBC News, 29 May 20215, retrieved 22 March 2020</ref> [[Cuba\u2013United States relations|reestablishing diplomatic relations]],<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2015/07/20/politics/cuba-u-s-embassies-opening/index.html U.S., Cuba re-establish diplomatic relations, reopen embassies, By Patrick Oppmann, CNN Politics, 20 July 2015, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> and ending the [[Wet feet, dry feet policy|wet foot, dry foot policy]] that gave preferential treatment to Cuban immigrants.<ref>[https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/world/americas/cuba/article126202999.html Obama ends controversial policy that allowed Cubans to enter U.S. without visas] By Mimi Whitefield, Miami Herald, 12 Jan 2016, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> The United States joined the [[Paris Agreement]] to lower carbon emissions in an effort to keep the global average rise in temperatures below 2&nbsp;\u00b0C on September 3, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |website=BBC World News|title=Paris climate deal: US and China formally join pact|accessdate=March 22, 2020|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-37265541}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, a [[Domestic terrorism in the United States|domestic terrorist]] killed 49 people and wounded 53 others in the [[Orlando nightclub shooting]]. When Speaker Ryan refused to allow debate on gun legislation, 60 Democratic House Members staged a [[2016 United States House of Representatives sit-in]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bade|first1=Rachael|title=Democrats stage sit-in on House floor to force gun vote |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/06/democrats-stage-sit-in-on-house-floor-to-force-gun-vote-224656 |work=Politico|accessdate=March 22, 2016}}</ref> but failed to force a vote.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stein|first1=Sam|title=House Democrats End Their Sit-In Protest Over Gun Reform|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/house-democrats-end-their-sit-in-protest-over-gun-reform_us_576c1760e4b0aa4dc3d4b28f?section=|website=The Huffington Post|accessdate=March 22, 2016}}</ref> In the Senate, [[Chris Murphy]] (D-CT), successfully launched a 15-hour [[filibuster]] that led to two votes on gun control, barring guns from suspected terrorists and expanding background checks on gun purchasers.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Walsh|first1=Dierdra|title=Democratic senator launches filibuster over guns|accessdate=March 22, 2020|publisher=CNN|date=June 15, 2016|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/06/15/politics/gun-filibuster-senate-democrat/}}</ref> Senate Minority Leader Harry Reid (D-NV) blamed \"Republicans who take their marching orders from the [[National Rifle Association]]\" for the defeat of both bills.<ref>{{cite web|website=HuffPost Politics|title=Orlando Massacre Wasn't Enough To Spur Senate To Pass Gun Control Bills|date=Jun 20, 2016|accessdate=22 Mar 2020|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/senate-gun-control-bills-orlando_n_57681a1be4b015db1bca03fa|first1=Michael|last1=McAuliff|first2=Jennifer|last2=Bendery}}</ref> In March 2016 Obama nominated [[Merrick Garland Supreme Court nomination|Judge Merrick Garland]], 63, to fill the Supreme Court seat vacated by the death of [[Antonin Scalia]], but Majority Leader Mitch McConnell refused to hold hearings or bring the nomination up for a vote. Short-handed, the court deadlocked on a number of issues and declined to hear others.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/2018/06/29/624467256/what-happened-with-merrick-garland-in-2016-and-why-it-matters-now What Happened With Merrick Garland In 2016 And Why It Matters Now] By Ron Elving, NPR, 29 June 2018, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nIn an upset victory, [[Donald Trump]] (R) defeated [[Hillary Clinton]] (D) in the [[2016 United States presidential election]]. Clinton won the popular vote (62,523,126 to 61,201,031) but Trump won the [[United States Electoral College|Electoral College]] (306 to 232) and the election.<ref>[https://www.politico.com/2016-election/results/map/president/ 2016 Presidential Election Results] Politico, 13 Dec 2016, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> There were seven [[Faithless electors in the 2016 United States presidential election]].<ref>[https://www.cbsnews.com/news/which-candidates-did-the-seven-faithless-electors-support-election-2016/ Which candidates did the seven \"faithless\" electors support?] BY JULIA BOCCAGNO, CBS News, 21 Dec 2020, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> Democrats gained two Senate seats but Republicans retained control.<ref>[https://www.politico.com/2016-election/results/map/senate/ 2016 Senate Election Results] Politico, 13 Dec 2016, retrieved 22 Mar 2020 [https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/there-were-no-purple-states-on-tuesday/ There Were No Purple* States On Tuesday] By Harry Enten, Five Thirty Eight, 10 Nov 2016, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> Democrats had a net gain of six House seats but Republicans retained their majority.<ref>[https://www.politico.com/2016-election/results/map/house/ 2016 House Election Results] Politico, 13 Dec 2016, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> Each party won six of the tweleve gubnatorial elections.<ref>[https://www.politico.com/2016-election/results/map/governor/ 2016 Governor Election Results] Politico, 13 Dec 2016, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> Six states approved ballot measures liberalizing marijuana use, five passed gun or hunting legislation, and four increased the minimum wage.<ref>[https://www.politico.com/2016-election/results/map/ballot-measures/ Key Ballot Measures Election Results by State] Politico, 13 Dec 2016, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n===2017-2019, 115th Congress===\n{{see also|Trump Presidency|115th United States Congress}}\nThe [[inauguration of Donald Trump]] (R) as 45th President was on January 20, 2017.<ref>[https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2017/1/24/14354036/crowds-presidential-inaugurations-trump-average A crowd scientist says Trump\u2019s inauguration attendance was pretty average] By Sarah Frostenson, Vox, 24 Jan 2017, retrieved 22 March 2020</ref> The [[2017 Women's March]] on January 21, 2017, involved between 3.3. million and 4.6 million marchers and was the largest demonstration in American history.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/womens-march-anti-donald-trump-womens-rights-largest-protest-demonstration-us-history-political-a7541081.html Women's March against Donald Trump is the largest day of protests in US history, say political scientists] by Matt Broomfield, Independent, 23 Jan 2017</ref>\n\nRepublicans controlled the House of Representatives with Paul D. Ryan (R\u2013WI) as Speaker.<ref>[https://history.house.gov/Congressional-Overview/Profiles/115th/ Congress Profiles] United States House of Representatives; History, Art, and Archives; retrieved 11 March 2020</ref> Mitch McConnell (R-KY) continued as Senate Majority leader.<ref name=Senate_leader />\n\nThe 115th Congress reformed the federal criminal justice system, responded to the [[SUPPORT for Patients and Communities Act|opioid crisis]], imposed sanctions on Russia, North Korea, and Iran, and legalized industrial hemp via the [[2018 United States farm bill|2018 farm bill]]. They passed [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017|tax reform]] legislation, which is expected to increase the deficit by $1.4 trillion. Despite multiple attempts, they failed to repeal and replace the [[American Health Care Act of 2017|Affordable Care Act]], pass comprehensive immigration reform, or restrict SNAP benefits. The government was shut down three times:<ref>[https://govtrackinsider.com/the-115th-congress-in-review-76efbaadf03d The 115th Congress in Review] Gov.Track.us, 28 Dec 2018, retrieved 11 Mar 2020</ref> in [[January 2018 United States federal government shutdown|January 2018]] over a dispute about [[Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals|Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals DACA)]] and the [[Mexico\u2013United States barrier|Mexican border wall]],<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/jan/20/us-government-faces-shutdown-after-senate-rejects-funding-bill US government goes into shutdown after Senate rejects funding bill] by Sabrina Siddiqui & Ben Jacobs, ''[[The Guardian]],'' 20 Jan 2018, retrieved 22 March 2020</ref> Senator [[Ron Paul|Ron Paul's]] (R-KY) tantrum on February 9,<ref>[https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2018/1/19/16905584/government-shutdown-history-clinton-obama-explained All 20 previous government shutdowns, explained] By Dylan Matthews, Vox, 12 Jan 2019, retrieved 22 March 2020</ref> and the [[2018\u201319 United States federal government shutdown|December 22, 2018, to January 25, 2019 shutdown]] over the border wall. The last resulted in Trump's declaration of a [[National Emergency Concerning the Southern Border of the United States|State of Emergency]] on February 15.<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2019/01/25/senate-votes-to-reopen-government-and-end-shutdown-without-border-wall.html Trump signs bill to temporarily reopen government after longest shutdown in history] by Jacob Pramuk, CNBC, 25 Jan 2019, retrieved 22 March 2020</ref> [[Day Without Immigrants 2017]] protests were held throughout the United States in February 2017 to demonstrate the importance of immigration.<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2017/02/15/politics/washington-dc-day-without-immigrants/ DC preps for 'Day Without Immigrants,' but Hill takes little notice] By Tal Kopan, CNN, 16 Feb 2017, retrieved 11 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nOn June 14, 2017, Congressman [[Steve Scalise]] (R-LA) and two aides were [[2017 Congressional baseball shooting|hit by gunfire]] during a practice session for the annual Congressional baseball game.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-40275055 Gunman dead after attacking congressmen at Virginia baseball field] BBC News, 15 June 2017, retrieved 12 March 2020</ref>\n\nPresident Trump nominated and the Senate approved two Supreme Court justices: [[Neil Gorsuch]] and [[Brett Kavanaugh]]. Kavanaugh's [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|Judiciary Committee]] was concerned primarily with allegations of sexual misconduct.<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2018/10/06/politics/kavanaugh-final-confirmation-vote/index.html Brett Kavanaugh sworn in as Supreme Court justice] By Clare Foran and Stephen Collinson, CNN, 7 Oct 2018, retrieved 11 Mar 2020</ref> The [[Music Modernization Act]] modernizes music copyright laws and [[America's Water Infrastructure Act of 2018]] relaxes water pollution restrictions.\n\nTrump signed a number of [[executive order]]s to overturn [[Executive Order 13672|actions undertaken]] by President Obama, prioritizing [[Executive Order 13766|economic expediency]] over environmental concerns. He withdrew from the [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]] and restricted [[Executive Order 13769|immigration by refugees]]. He began construction of the [[Executive Order 13767|border wall]] and instituted a [[Executive Order 13769|ban on Muslim immigration]].\n\nAllegations about [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]] and during the November 2016-January 2017 transition period surface, resulting in the resignation of [[National Security Advisor (United States)|National Security Advisor]] [[Michael Flynn]]. FBI Director [[James Comey]] is fired because of the way he handled the investigation. The first call for the impeachment of President Trump is issued on May 7, 2017.<ref>[https://thehill.com/homenews/house/333807-dem-calls-for-trump-impeachment-on-house-floor Dem calls for Trump impeachment on House floor] BY PAULINA FIROZI, The Hill, 17 May 2020, retrieved 12 Mar 2020</ref> [[Robert Mueller]] began his investigation on May 17.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-39957358 Trump Russia inquiry: Former FBI boss to lead probe] BBC News, 18 May 2017</ref>\n\n===2019, 116th Congress===\n{{see also|Trump  Presidency|116th United States Congress}}\nDemocrats controlled the House of Representatives<ref>[https://www.politico.com/interactives/2018/interactive_116th-congress-freshman-younger-bluer-diverse/ Congress's incoming class is younger, bluer, and more diverse than ever] By BEATRICE JIN, Politico, 23 Nov 2018, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> with [[Nancy Pelosi]] (D-CA) as Speaker.<ref>[https://www.businessinsider.com/nancy-pelosi-elected-speaker-of-the-house-new-democratic-majority-2019-1?r=MX&IR=T Nancy Pelosi elected speaker of the House, ushering in new Democratic majority] by Joe Perticone, Business Insider, 3 Jan 2019</ref> [[Jeff Van Drew]] (R-NJ) changed from Democrat to Republican on December 19, 2019.<ref>[https://www.huffpost.com/entry/jeff-van-drew-switches-parties-trump_n_5dfbd87ae4b0eb2264d6a68a Rep. Jeff Van Drew Officially Switches Parties, Pledges \u2018Undying Support\u2019 For Trump] Huff Post, 19 December 2019, retrieved 2 March 2020</ref> Mitch McConnell (R-KY) continued as Senate Majority leader.<ref name=Senate_leader />\n\n==History by issue==\n===Environment and climate change===\n{{Main|Environmental issues in the United States|Climate change in the United States|Climate change policy of the United States}}\n{{See also|Paris Agreement|United States withdrawal from the Paris Agreement|Renewable energy in the United States|Climate change and agriculture in the United States}}\n\n===Foreign and military policy===\n{{Main|Foreign policy of the Barack Obama administration|Foreign policy of the Donald Trump administration}}\n{{See also|Climate security}}\n\n====Afghanistan====\n{{Main|War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)}}\n\n====Africa====\n{{Main|Boko Haram insurgency|Lord's Resistance Army Disarmament and Northern Uganda Recovery Act}}\n\n====India====\n{{Main|India\u2013United States relations}}\n\n====Iran====\n{{Main|Iran\u2013United States relations|Iran\u2013U.S. RQ-170 incident|Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action|2019\u201320 Persian Gulf crisis}}\n\n====Iraq====\n{{Main|Iraqi insurgency (2003\u20132011)|American-led intervention in Iraq (2014\u2013present)}}\n{{See also|Protests against the Iraq War}}\n\n====Latin America====\n{{Main|Latin America\u2013United States relations}}\n\n====Libya====\n{{Main|Libyan Civil War (2014\u2013present)|2012 Benghazi attack}}\n{{See also|Investigation into the 2012 Benghazi attack|United States House Select Committee on Benghazi}}\n\n====Syria====\n{{Main|Syrian civil war|ISIL territorial claims}}\n\n====Venezuela====\n{{Main|Venezuelan protests (2014\u2013present)|Venezuelan presidential crisis}}\n\n====Yemen====\n{{Main|Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen}}\n\n===Guns===\n{{Main|Gun law in the United States|Gun laws in the United States by state|Gun politics in the United States|Gun violence in the United States}}\n{{See also|Mass shootings in the United States|School shootings in the United States}}\n\n===Immigration===\n{{Main|Illegal immigration to the United States|2014 American immigration crisis|Immigration policy of Donald Trump|U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement}}\n{{See also|Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals|Trump administration migrant detentions|Trump administration family separation policy|Trump travel ban|Mexico\u2013United States barrier}}\n\n===Recession of 2008===\n{{Main|Great Recession in the United States}}\nThe [[Great Recession in the United States|Great Recession]] was a severe financial crisis from December 2007 to June 2009 that began when the U.S. housing market crashed, and large amounts of [[Mortgage-backed security|mortgage-backed securities]] and derivatives lost significant value. The United States lost 8.7 million jobs and U.S. households lost $19 trillion of net worth.<ref name=\"investo\">{{cite web |website=Investopedia|title=The Great Recession|url=https://www.investopedia.com/terms/g/great-recession.asp|first=Jim|last=Chappelow|date=March 10, 2010|accessdate=March 19, 2020|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Obama administration spent much of its time and effort into improving the economy and addressing the issues that led to the recession. Obama signed the [[Dodd\u2013Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act|Dodd-Frank Act]] on July 21, 2010, to give the government expanded regulatory power over the financial sector. [[Real gross domestic product|Real GDP]] regained its pre-recession peak in the second quarter of 2011, and in March 2013, the [[Dow Jones Industrial Average]] broke its 2007 high. Workers and households did less well. The [[Unemployment in the United States|unemployment rate]] was at 5% at the end of 2007, reached 10% in October 2009, and did not recover to 5% until 2015. [[Household income in the United States]] did not surpass its pre-recession level until 2016.<ref name=\"investo\"/>\n\n===Rights and freedoms===\n\n====LGBTQ rights====\n{{Main|LGBT rights in the United States}}\n{{See also|Same-sex marriage in the United States|Sexual orientation and gender identity in the United States military}}\n\n====Voting rights====\n{{Main|Voting rights in the United States|Shelby County v. Holder|Voter suppression in the United States}}\n{{See also|2016 Washington, D.C. statehood referendum|2017 Puerto Rican status referendum}}\n\n====Women's rights====\n{{See also|Sexual harassment in the workplace in the United States|Gender pay gap in the United States|Me Too movement}}\n\n===Trade and tarrifs===\n{{Main|United States free-trade agreements|Trump tariffs}}\n{{See also|Trans-Pacific Partnership|United States\u2013Mexico\u2013Canada Agreement|China\u2013United States trade war|Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col}}\n* Other decade overviews: \n**[[2020s in political history]]\n**[[2020s in United States political history]]\n* UK decade overviews:\n**[[2010s in United Kingdom political history]]\n**[[2020s in United Kingdom political history]]\n{{End div col}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n===Congress===\n* [https://www.congress.gov/ Official website, US Congress] \n**[http://clerk.house.gov Clerk of the House of Representatives]\n** [http://cao.house.gov Chief Administrative Office of the House]\n** [http://majorityleader.gov Office of the majority leader]\n** [http://speaker.gov Office of the speaker of the House]\n** [http://www.house.gov/representatives Official list of current members]\n** [https://web.archive.org/web/20110601184453/http://www.rules.house.gov/singlepages.aspx?NewsID=160&rsbd=165 Rules of the House]\n* [https://www.congress.gov// Legislative information and archives for US House and Senate], via [[Congress.gov]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100423082228/http://bioguide.congress.gov/biosearch/biosearch.asp ''Biographical Directory of the United States Congress, 1774 to Present'']\n* [http://dca.tufts.edu/features/aas A New Nation Votes: American Election Returns 1787\u20131825]\n* [http://www.aggdata.com/political/us-representatives Complete Downloadable List of U.S. Representative Contact Information], via AggData LLC]\n* [http://www.usbills.info Information about U.S. Congressional Bills and Resolutions]\n\n{{United States Congress}}\n{{United States legislatures}}\n{{United States topics}}\n\n[[Category:2010s in the United States]]\n[[Category:2010 in American politics]]\n[[Category:Contemporary history of the United States]]\n[[Category:Politics overviews by decade]]\n[[Category:2010 in politics]]\n[[Category:2010s in politics]]\n", "text_old": "{{See also|2020s in United States political history}}\n'''2010s in United States political history''' is a narrative summary of major political events and issues in the United States from January 1, 2010, through December 31, 2019. The first part is divided chronologically by Congressional sessions and the second part highlights major issues that span several years or even the entire decade. There are links for further information.\n\n==History by era==\n\n{{expand section|date=March 2020}}\n\n===2009-2011, 111th Congress===\n{{see also|Obama Presidency|111th United States Congress}}\nDemocrats swept into 2009 with control over the White House and both Houses of Congress. [[Nancy Peolosi]] (D-CA) was [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House of Representatives]] and [[Harry Reid]] (D-NV) was [[Party leaders of the United States Senate|Senate Majority Leader]]. The Democratic supermajority in the Senate was guaranteed with the election of [[Al Franken]] (D-MN) in January and when Republican [[Arlen Specter]] (D-PA) switched to the Democratic Party. Major legislative victories included the [[Lilly Ledbetter Fair Pay Act of 2009]] (providing equal pay for women), [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009]] (designed to preserve existing jobs and to create new ones), [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] (extending health-care coverage to millions; popularly called \"Obamacare\"), [[Dodd\u2013Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act]] (the first major financial reform since the 1930s), [[Small Business Jobs Act of 2010]] (providing financing for small businesses), [[Tax Relief, Unemployment Insurance Reauthorization, and Job Creation Act of 2010|2010 Tax Relief Act]] (temporary tax relief for the middle class), [[Don't Ask, Don't Tell Repeal Act of 2010]] (allowing gay, lesbian, and transgender people to serve openly in the military), and the [[James Zadroga 9/11 Health and Compensation Act]] (provides support for first responders who survived the [[September 11 attacks|September 11, 2001, terrorist attacks]]).<ref>[https://www.politico.com/story/2010/10/the-legacy-of-the-111th-congress-042983 The legacy of the 111th Congress] By RICHARD E. COHEN, Politico, 1 Oct 2010, retrieved 10 March 2020</ref>\n\nThe Senate confirmed the appointments of two women to the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]]: [[Sonia Sotomayor]] (the first Latino to hold the post)<ref>[https://www.usnews.com/news/national/articles/2009/08/06/sotomayor-confirmed-as-first-hispanic-supreme-court-justice-in-victory-for-obama Sotomayor Confirmed as First Hispanic Supreme Court Justice in Victory for Obama] By Queenie Wong, [[U.S. News & World Report]], 6 Aug 2009, retrieved 22 March 2020</ref> and [[Elena Kagan]].<ref>[https://www.denverpost.com/2010/08/05/senate-confirms-kagans-nomination-to-supreme-court/ Senate confirms Kagan\u2019s nomination to Supreme Court] [[The Denver Post]], 5 Aug 2010, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nPresident [[Barack Obama|Barack Obama's]] September 9, 2009, Congressional address promoting health care reform was interrupted by Congressman [[Joe Wilson (American politician)|Joe Wilson]] (R-SC) who shouted: \"You lie!\" when Obama said his health care plan would not cover undocumented immigrants.<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/09/09/joe.wilson/index.html Rep. Wilson shouts, 'You lie' to Obama during speech] CNN Politics, retrieved 10 March 2020</ref> The Democrats' supermajority in the Senate ended on February 4, 2010, with the election of [[Scott Brown (politician)|Scott Brown]] (R-MA).<ref>[https://www.cbsnews.com/news/brown-mass-win-about-anger-not-obama/ Brown: Mass. Win about Anger, not Obama] CBS News, 20 Jan 2010, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nPresident Obama unsuccessfully tried to close [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]] for suspected terrorists.<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/01/22/guantanamo.order/index.html Obama signs order to close Guantanamo Bay facility] CNN, retrieved 10 March 2020</ref> Conservative opponents of Obama formed the [[Tea Party movement]] in February 2009. Obama was granted the [[2009 Nobel Peace Prize]], despite presiding over the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|war in Afghanistan]] and the [[Iraq War]].<ref>[https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/peace/2009/press-release/ The Nobel Peace Prize for 2009] The Nobel Prize.org, retrieved 22 March 2020</ref> The ''[[Deepwater Horizon oil spill]]'' was a major ecological disaster from April through September 2010.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|encyclopedia=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]|title=Deepwater Horizon oil spill|date=Mar 13, 2020|accessdate=22 Mar 2020|first=Richard |last=Pallardy |url=https://www.britannica.com/event/Deepwater-Horizon-oil-spill}}</ref> A reneotiated [[United States\u2013Korea Free Trade Agreement|free trade agreement with South Korea]] went into effect on December 3, 2010.<ref>[http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2010/12/05/2003490144 US, South Korea sign sweeping free-trade agreement] [[Taipei Times]], 5 Dec 2010, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nThe [[2010 United States elections]] resulted in major victories for the Republican Party.<ref>[https://www.usnews.com/opinion/blogs/peter-roff/2010/11/05/measuring-the-size-of-election-2010s-republican-sweep Measuring the Size of Election 2010's Republican Sweep] By Peter Roff, U.S. News & World Report, 5 Nov 2020, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n===2011-2013, 112th Congress===\n{{see also|Obama Presidency|112th United States Congress}}\nFollowing the 2010 elections, Republicans gained control of the House of Representatives while the Democratic majority in the Senate was narrowed. [[John Boehner]] (R-OH) was Speaker of the House and [[Harry Reid]] (D-NV) was Senate Majority Leader. The Congress was unproductive, passing only 219 bills that were signed into law, compared to 383 in the 111th Congress. Congress failed to pass legislation to keep the [[United States Postal Service|Postal Service]] solvent, and they allowed the [[Violence Against Women Act]] to lapse for the first time since it was passed in 1994.<ref>[http://www.msnbc.com/the-daily-rundown/112th-congress-set-become-least-productiv 112th Congress set to become least productive in decades] By Sarah Blackwill, MSNBC, 13 September 2013, retrieved 11 March 2020</ref>\n\nThe United States entered trade agreements with [[United States\u2013Colombia Free Trade Agreement|Colombia]]<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-18069469 Colombia-US free trade agreement comes into force] BBC News, 12 May 2012, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> and [[Panama\u2013United States Trade Promotion Agreement|Panama]].<ref>[https://www.everycrsreport.com/reports/RL32540.html The U.S.-Panama Free Trade Agreement] Every CRSReport, 8 Nov 2012, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> [[Middle Class Tax Relief and Job Creation Act of 2012|Payroll Taxes]] were cut and the low [[American Taxpayer Relief Act of 2012|income tax rates]] established by the George W. Bush administration were kept in place. The [[National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2012]] not only provided funding for the DoD and authorization for state governors to request military help in the case of natural disasters but also controversially contained anti-terrorist provisions that allow the indefinite detention of American citizens on American soil. The [[Budget Control Act of 2011]] called for a reduction in spending in order to lower the [[United States debt-ceiling crisis of 2011|federal debt]].\n\nCongresswoman [[Gabby Giffords]] (D-AZ) and nineteen other people were shot in [[2011 Tucson shooting|Tucson]] on January 8, 2011.<ref>[https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/local/arizona/2018/04/05/fbi-releases-new-photos-video-2011-gabby-giffords-shooting/489367002/ FBI releases new photos, video of 2011 Giffords shooting] by Josh Susong, AZ Central (USA Today), 5 April 2018, retrieved 11 March 2020</ref> Twenty children and six adults were killed in a shooting at [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting|Sandy Hook Elementary School]] in Newtown, Connecticut, sparking a debate about gun laws.<ref>[https://www.britannica.com/event/Newtown-shootings-of-2012 Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting] Encyclopaedia, retrieved 11 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nThe United States joined NATO in [[2011 military intervention in Libya|military intervention in Libya]],<ref>[https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/2011/03/28/remarks-president-address-nation-libya Remarks by the President in Address to the Nation on Libya] The White House, 28 Mar 2011, retrieved 11 Mar 2020</ref> which led to the [[death of Muammar Gaddafi]].<ref>[https://www.aljazeera.com/programmes/the-big-picture/2018/11/death-gaddafi-181103124656506.html The Death of Gaddafi] Al Jazeera, 5 Nov 2018, retrieved 11 Mar 2020</ref> In May 2011 Navy SEALS killed [[Death of Osama bin Laden|Al-Qaeda leader Osama bin Laden]].<ref>[https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Draft:2010s_in_United_States_political_history&action=edit&section=3 Death of Osama bin Laden Fast Facts] CNN Library, 18 Apr 2019, retrieved 11 Mar 2020</ref> On September 11, 2012, members of Ansar al-Sharia attacked the American diplomatic compound in [[2012 Benghazi attack|Benghazi]], resulting in the deaths of U.S. Ambassador to Libya [[J. Christopher Stevens]] and three other Americans.<ref>[https://www.upi.com/Top_News/US/2012/11/02/US-officials-CIA-ran-Benghazi-consulate/44771351839600/?ur3=1 U.S. officials: CIA ran Benghazi consulate] UPI, 2 Nov 2012, retrieved 11 Mar 2020</ref> The United States stepped up [[drone attacks in Pakistan]], [[Somali Civil War (2009\u2013present)|Somalia]], and [[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Yemen]], targeting Yemeni-American Muslim cleric [[Anwar al-Awlaki]] on September 30, 2011.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-15121879 Islamist cleric Anwar al-Awlaki killed in Yemen] BBC News, 30 Sep 2011, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> His 16-year-old son, American-born [[Abdulrahman al-Awlaki]], was killed two weeks later.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-airstrike-that-killed-american-teen-in-yemen-raises-legal-ethical-questions/2011/10/20/gIQAdvUY7L_story.html U.S. airstrike that killed American teen in Yemen raises legal, ethical questions] By Craig Whitlock, [[The Washington Post]], 22 Oct 2011, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nThe popular movement against income inequality known as [[Occupy Wall Street]] began with a march on [[Wall Street]], New York City in February 2011.<ref>[http://occupywallst.org/about/ About] OccupyWallStreet.org, retrieved 11 March 2020</ref>\n\n[[Trayvon Martin]], an unarmed black 17-year-old, was fatally shot by [[George Zimmerman]] in [[Sanford, Florida]]. The killing received widespread attention focusing on aspects including the possible role of Martin's race and the initial lack of prosecution against Zimmerman, and it raised questions about Florida's [[Stand-your-ground law|\"Hold your ground\"]] gun law.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-17441277 |title=Trayvon Martin: Probe into killing of Florida teenager |date=March 20, 2012 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2012, Wisconsin Governor [[Scott Walker (politician)|Scott Walker]] won a recall election against Milwaukee Mayor [[Tom Barrett (Wisconsin politician)|Tom Barrett]].<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2012/06/05/politics/wisconsin-recall-vote/index.html Walker's Wisconsin win big blow to unions, smaller one to Obama] By John Helton and Tom Cohen, CNN, 6 June 2012, retrieved 11 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nPresident Obama was [[2012 United States presidential election|reelected in 2012]], defeating Republican [[Mitt Romney 2012 presidential campaign|Mitt Romney]].<ref>[https://www.latimes.com/world/la-xpm-2013-jan-04-la-pn-obama-biden-officially-win-second-term-20130104-story.html It\u2019s official: Obama, Biden win second term] By  MICHAEL A. MEMOLI, LA Times, 4 Jan 2013, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> Democrats gained two [[2012 United States Senate elections|Senate seats]].<ref>[https://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Politics/The-Vote/2012/1106/Election-2012-results-Liveblog-In-Senate-Democrats-ward-off-challenges Election 2012 results Liveblog: In Senate, Democrats ward off challenges] [[The Christian Science Monitor]], 6 Nov 2012, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> Democrats won the popular vote and eight [[2012 United States House of Representatives elections|House seats]], but it was not enough to regain control of the [https://transition.fec.gov/pubrec/fe2012/federalelections2012.pdf the lower chamber].<ref>[https://ballotpedia.org/United_States_Congressional_elections_results,_2012 United States Congressional elections results, 2012] Ballotpedia, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n===2013-2015, 113th Congress===\n{{see also|Obama Presidency|113th United States Congress}}\nThe Senate had a Democratic majority, but the House had a Republican majority. Harry Reid (D-NV) was Senate Majority Leader and John Boehner (R-OH) was Speaker of the House.<ref>[https://gai.georgetown.edu/resources-publications/the-113th-congress/113th-congress-by-the-numbers/ 113TH CONGRESS BY THE NUMBERS] Government Affairs Institute at Georgetown University, retrieved 11 Mar 2020</ref> The 113th was one of the least productive in history, notable for brinkmanship (shutting down the government for 16 days in 2013 and almost shutting it down again in 2014). According to [[Gallup (company)]], only 15% of Americans approved of the Congress' work, only 1% more than the all-time low of the 112th Congress. The Senate passed immigration reform but House Republicans killed it; the House passed gun reform, but it did not pass the Senate. House Republicans offered legislation on the economy and health care (voting 50 times to repeal Obamacare), but these did not pass the Senate. Senator [[Rand Paul]] (R-KY) filibustered the nomination of [[John Brennan (CIA officer)|John Brennan]] as CIA director for thirteen hours.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2013/03/07/173693133/nearly-13-hours-later-sen-paul-ends-his-filibuster-heres-the-video Nearly 13 Hours Later, Sen. Paul Ends His Filibuster; Here's The Video] NPR, 7 Mar 2013, retrieved 11 Mar 2020</ref> [[Ted Cruz]] (R-TX) wasted a record 21 hours of the Senate's time by reading ''Green Eggs and Ham'' by [[Dr. Seuss]] as a complaint (but not a fillibuster) against health care.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2016/01/04/rick-santorum-mocks-ted-cruz-green-eggs-and-ham/78253012/ Rick Santorum mocks Ted Cruz for 'Green Eggs and Ham'] by Mary Troyan, USA Today, 4 Jan 2016, retrieved 11 Mar 2020</ref> Senator [[John McCain]] (R-AZ) called the Senate's lack of work \"disgraceful.\"<ref name=unproductive>[https://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/senate/227365-historically-unproductive-congress-ends Historically unproductive Congress ends] BY CRISTINA MARCOS AND RAMSEY COX, The Hill, 16 Dec 2014, retrieved 11 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nAmong the few bills passed were a [[Agricultural Act of 2014|five-year farm bill]] and reform of [[Veterans' Access to Care through Choice, Accountability, and Transparency Act of 2014|VA benefits]].<ref name=unproductive/> They reauthorized the Violence Against Women Act<ref>[https://www.hrw.org/news/2013/02/28/us-violence-against-women-act-renewed US: Violence Against Women Act Renewed] Human Rights Watch, 28 Feb 2013, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> and the [[Pandemic and All-Hazards Preparedness Reauthorization Act of 2013|Pandemic and All-Hazards Preparedness Act]].<ref>[https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/hr307 H.R. 307 (113th): Pandemic and All-Hazards Preparedness Reauthorization Act of 2013] GovTrack.us, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> They supported the government of [[Support for the Sovereignty, Integrity, Democracy, and Economic Stability of Ukraine Act of 2014|Ukraine]]<ref>[https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/hr4152 H.R. 4152 (113th): Support for the Sovereignty, Integrity, Democracy, and Economic Stability of Ukraine Act of 2014] GovTrack.us, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> and the [https://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/Programs/Documents/venezuela_publ_113_278.pdf opposition] in [[Venezuela Defense of Human Rights and Civil Society Act of 2014|Venezuela]].<ref>[https://sanctionsnews.bakermckenzie.com/us-congress-passes-venezuela-defense-of-human-rights-and-civil-society-act/ US Congress Passes Venezuela Defense of Human Rights and Civil Society Act] by EUNKYUNG KIM SHIN AND PAUL AMBERG, Baker McKenzie Blog Sanctions News, 17 December 2014</ref>\n\nInformation about [[Global surveillance disclosures (2013\u2013present)|global surevillance]] was released in June 2013.<ref>[https://www.nationaljournal.com/s/64142/everything-we-learned-from-edward-snowden-2013 Everything We Learned From Edward Snowden in 2013] National Journal, retrieved 11 March 2020 (paysite)</ref> The Supreme Court overturned key provisions of the [[Shelby County v. Holder|Voting Rights Act of 1965]] and the [[United States v. Windsor|Defense of Marriage Act]].\n\nRepublicans swept the [[2014 United States elections|November 2014 elections]].<ref name=unproductive/>\n\n===2015-2017, 114th Congress===\n{{see also|Obama Presidency|114th United States Congress}}\nRepublicans controlled the House of Representatives with John Boehner (R-OH) as Speaker until October 29, 2015, when [[Paul Ryan|Paul D. Ryan]] (R\u2013WI) was chosen to replace him.<ref>[https://history.house.gov/Congressional-Overview/Profiles/114th/ Congress Profiles] United States House of Representatives; History, Art, and Archives; retrieved 11 March 2020</ref> [[Mitch McConnell]] (R-KY) was Senate Majority leader.<ref name=Senate_leader>[https://www.senate.gov/artandhistory/history/common/briefing/Majority_Minority_Leaders.htm#2 Majority and Minority Leaders] Senate.gov., retrieved 22 March 2020</ref>\n\nThe [[USA Freedom Act]] was an updated version of the [[Patriot Act]] with certain restrictions on spying on American civilians. President Obama threatened to veto the [[Iran Nuclear Agreement Review Act of 2015]], but the bill passed the Senate 98-1 and Obama withdrew his threat. The [[Every Student Succeeds Act]] replaced the [[No Child Left Behind Act]]. The [[Justice Against Sponsors of Terrorism Act]], which allows survivors of the [[September 11 attacks|September 11, 2001, terrorist attacks]] to sue [[Saudi Arabia]], which passed over Obama's veto. Obama also vetoed a bill authorizing the [[Keystone Pipeline]].<ref>[https://ballotpedia.org/Barack_Obama:_Vetoed_legislation Barack Obama: Vetoed legislation] Ballotpedia, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> The [[Fixing America's Surface Transportation Act]] provided $305 billion for highway improvement without increasing the gas tax.<ref>[https://usa.streetsblog.org/2015/12/02/5-year-300-billion-fast-act-will-extend-transpo-policy-status-quo-to-2020/ 5-Year, $300 Billion \"FAST Act\" Will Extend Transpo Policy Status Quo to 2020] By Angie Schmitt, USA.Streetsblog.org, 2 Dec 2015, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> The [[Internet Tax Freedom Act]] made the prohibition on taxing Internet services permanent.<ref>{{cite web|website=The Wall Street Journal (Opinion)|title=Obama's Best Day in Office?|date=Feb 24, 2016|accessdate=Mar 22, 2020 |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/obamas-best-day-in-office-1456316788}}</ref> The [[Sexual Assault Survivors' Rights Act]] provides increased rights for victims of sexual assault.<ref>[https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/emaoconnor/historic-bill-of-rights-for-survivors-of-sexual-assault-is-h Historic Bill Of Rights For Survivors Of Sexual Assault Is Heading To Obama's Desk] by Emma O'Connor, BuzzFeed, 7 Sep 2016, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> The [[21st Century Cures Act]] was a victory for [[Pharmaceutical industry|Big Pharma]], allowing new drugs to get on the market more easily.<ref>[https://www.healthnewsreview.org/2016/12/with-media-watchdogs-sidelined-pharma-funded-advocacy-groups-pushed-cures-act-to-the-finish-line/ With media watchdogs on the sidelines, pharma-funded advocacy groups pushed Cures Act to the finish line] by Trudy Lieberman, Health News Review, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nThe Prime Minister of Israel [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] was invited by Speaker Boehner to address a joint session of Congress regarding sanctions against Iran without consulting President Obama in March 2015.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bradner |first1=Eric |title=Criticism over Netanyahu visit intensifies |url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/01/25/politics/mcdonough-obama-netanyahu |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=January 25, 2015}}</ref> Other world leaders to address Congress were Afghanistan President [[Ashraf Ghani]] (March 2015),<ref>[http://www.nwaonline.com/news/2015/mar/26/in-u-s-ghani-vows-afghan-self-reliance-/ \"In U.S., Ghani Vows Afghan Self-Reliance\"]. by Deb Riechmann, ''Northwest Arkansas Democrat-Gazette,'' 26 March 2015, Retrieved 22 March 2020</ref> Japanese Prime Minister [[Shinz\u014d Abe]] (April 2015),<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-japan-speech/japan-pm-abe-to-address-joint-session-of-congress-idUSKBN0MM2DY20150327 Japan PM Abe to address joint session of Congress] by Patricia Zengerle, Reuters, 26 Mar 2020, retrieved 22 March 2020</ref> [[Pope Francis]] (September 2015),<ref>[https://www.politico.com/story/2015/02/pope-address-us-congress-114939 Pope will address Congress in September] By JAKE SHERMAN, Politico, 5 Feb 2015, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> and Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]]<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2016/06/08/politics/modi-speech-u-s-congress-visit/index.html Modi addresses Congress as U.S.-India ties bloom] By Nicole Gaouette and Elise Labott, CNN, 9 June 2016, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> addressed joint sessions of Congress. President Obama [[Cuban thaw|thawed relations with Cuba]], removing the country from the [[State Sponsors of Terrorism (U.S. list)|list of state sponsors of terrorism]],<ref>[https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/u-s-officially-removes-cuba-state-sponsor-terrorism-list-n366621 U.S. Officially Removes Cuba From State Sponsors of Terrorism List] By Andrea Mitchell, NBC News, 29 May 20215, retrieved 22 March 2020</ref> [[Cuba\u2013United States relations|reestablishing diplomatic relations]],<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2015/07/20/politics/cuba-u-s-embassies-opening/index.html U.S., Cuba re-establish diplomatic relations, reopen embassies, By Patrick Oppmann, CNN Politics, 20 July 2015, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> and ending the [[Wet feet, dry feet policy|wet foot, dry foot policy]] that gave preferential treatment to Cuban immigrants.<ref>[https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/world/americas/cuba/article126202999.html Obama ends controversial policy that allowed Cubans to enter U.S. without visas] By Mimi Whitefield, Miami Herald, 12 Jan 2016, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> The United States joined the [[Paris Agreement]] to lower carbon emissions in an effort to keep the global average rise in temperatures below 2&nbsp;\u00b0C on September 3, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |website=BBC World News|title=Paris climate deal: US and China formally join pact|accessdate=March 22, 2020|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-37265541}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, a [[Domestic terrorism in the United States|domestic terrorist]] killed 49 people and wounded 53 others in the [[Orlando nightclub shooting]]. When Speaker Ryan refused to allow debate on gun legislation, 60 Democratic House Members staged a [[2016 United States House of Representatives sit-in]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bade|first1=Rachael|title=Democrats stage sit-in on House floor to force gun vote |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/06/democrats-stage-sit-in-on-house-floor-to-force-gun-vote-224656 |work=Politico|accessdate=March 22, 2016}}</ref> but failed to force a vote.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stein|first1=Sam|title=House Democrats End Their Sit-In Protest Over Gun Reform|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/house-democrats-end-their-sit-in-protest-over-gun-reform_us_576c1760e4b0aa4dc3d4b28f?section=|website=The Huffington Post|accessdate=March 22, 2016}}</ref> In the Senate, [[Chris Murphy]] (D-CT), successfully launched a 15-hour [[filibuster]] that led to two votes on gun control, barring guns from suspected terrorists and expanding background checks on gun purchasers.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Walsh|first1=Dierdra|title=Democratic senator launches filibuster over guns|accessdate=March 22, 2020|publisher=CNN|date=June 15, 2016|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/06/15/politics/gun-filibuster-senate-democrat/}}</ref> Senate Minority Leader Harry Reid (D-NV) blamed \"Republicans who take their marching orders from the [[National Rifle Association]]\" for the defeat of both bills.<ref>{{cite web|website=HuffPost Politics|title=Orlando Massacre Wasn't Enough To Spur Senate To Pass Gun Control Bills|date=Jun 20, 2016|accessdate=22 Mar 2020|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/senate-gun-control-bills-orlando_n_57681a1be4b015db1bca03fa|first1=Michael|last1=McAuliff|first2=Jennifer|last2=Bendery}}</ref> In March 2016 Obama nominated [[Merrick Garland Supreme Court nomination|Judge Merrick Garland]], 63, to fill the Supreme Court seat vacated by the death of [[Antonin Scalia]], but Majority Leader Mitch McConnell refused to hold hearings or bring the nomination up for a vote. Short-handed, the court deadlocked on a number of issues and declined to hear others.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/2018/06/29/624467256/what-happened-with-merrick-garland-in-2016-and-why-it-matters-now What Happened With Merrick Garland In 2016 And Why It Matters Now] By Ron Elving, NPR, 29 June 2018, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nIn an upset victory, [[Donald Trump]] (R) defeated [[Hillary Clinton]] (D) in the [[2016 United States presidential election]]. Clinton won the popular vote (62,523,126 to 61,201,031) but Trump won the [[United States Electoral College|Electoral College]] (306 to 232) and the election.<ref>[https://www.politico.com/2016-election/results/map/president/ 2016 Presidential Election Results] Politico, 13 Dec 2016, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> There were seven [[Faithless electors in the 2016 United States presidential election]].<ref>[https://www.cbsnews.com/news/which-candidates-did-the-seven-faithless-electors-support-election-2016/ Which candidates did the seven \"faithless\" electors support?] BY JULIA BOCCAGNO, CBS News, 21 Dec 2020, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> Democrats gained two Senate seats but Republicans retained control.<ref>[https://www.politico.com/2016-election/results/map/senate/ 2016 Senate Election Results] Politico, 13 Dec 2016, retrieved 22 Mar 2020 [https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/there-were-no-purple-states-on-tuesday/ There Were No Purple* States On Tuesday] By Harry Enten, Five Thirty Eight, 10 Nov 2016, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> Democrats had a net gain of six House seats but Republicans retained their majority.<ref>[https://www.politico.com/2016-election/results/map/house/ 2016 House Election Results] Politico, 13 Dec 2016, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> Each party won six of the tweleve gubnatorial elections.<ref>[https://www.politico.com/2016-election/results/map/governor/ 2016 Governor Election Results] Politico, 13 Dec 2016, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> Six states approved ballot measures liberalizing marijuana use, five passed gun or hunting legislation, and four increased the minimum wage.<ref>[https://www.politico.com/2016-election/results/map/ballot-measures/ Key Ballot Measures Election Results by State] Politico, 13 Dec 2016, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n===2017-2019, 115th Congress===\n{{see also|Trump Presidency|115th United States Congress}}\nThe [[inauguration of Donald Trump]] (R) as 45th President was on January 20, 2017.<ref>[https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2017/1/24/14354036/crowds-presidential-inaugurations-trump-average A crowd scientist says Trump\u2019s inauguration attendance was pretty average] By Sarah Frostenson, Vox, 24 Jan 2017, retrieved 22 March 2020</ref> The [[2017 Women's March]] on January 21, 2017, involved between 3.3. million and 4.6 million marchers and was the largest demonstration in American history.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/womens-march-anti-donald-trump-womens-rights-largest-protest-demonstration-us-history-political-a7541081.html Women's March against Donald Trump is the largest day of protests in US history, say political scientists] by Matt Broomfield, Independent, 23 Jan 2017</ref>\n\nRepublicans controlled the House of Representatives with Paul D. Ryan (R\u2013WI) as Speaker.<ref>[https://history.house.gov/Congressional-Overview/Profiles/115th/ Congress Profiles] United States House of Representatives; History, Art, and Archives; retrieved 11 March 2020</ref> Mitch McConnell (R-KY) continued as Senate Majority leader.<ref name=Senate_leader />\n\nThe 115th Congress reformed the federal criminal justice system, responded to the [[SUPPORT for Patients and Communities Act|opioid crisis]], imposed sanctions on Russia, North Korea, and Iran, and legalized industrial hemp via the [[2018 United States farm bill|2018 farm bill]]. They passed [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017|tax reform]] legislation, which is expected to increase the deficit by $1.4 trillion. Despite multiple attempts, they failed to repeal and replace the [[American Health Care Act of 2017|Affordable Care Act]], pass comprehensive immigration reform, or restrict SNAP benefits. The government was shut down three times:<ref>[https://govtrackinsider.com/the-115th-congress-in-review-76efbaadf03d The 115th Congress in Review] Gov.Track.us, 28 Dec 2018, retrieved 11 Mar 2020</ref> in [[January 2018 United States federal government shutdown|January 2018]] over a dispute about [[Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals|Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals DACA)]] and the [[Mexico\u2013United States barrier|Mexican border wall]],<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/jan/20/us-government-faces-shutdown-after-senate-rejects-funding-bill US government goes into shutdown after Senate rejects funding bill] by Sabrina Siddiqui & Ben Jacobs, ''[[The Guardian]],'' 20 Jan 2018, retrieved 22 March 2020</ref> Senator [[Ron Paul|Ron Paul's]] (R-KY) tantrum on February 9,<ref>[https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2018/1/19/16905584/government-shutdown-history-clinton-obama-explained All 20 previous government shutdowns, explained] By Dylan Matthews, Vox, 12 Jan 2019, retrieved 22 March 2020</ref> and the [[2018\u201319 United States federal government shutdown|December 22, 2018, to January 25, 2019 shutdown]] over the border wall. The last resulted in Trump's declaration of a [[National Emergency Concerning the Southern Border of the United States|State of Emergency]] on February 15.<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2019/01/25/senate-votes-to-reopen-government-and-end-shutdown-without-border-wall.html Trump signs bill to temporarily reopen government after longest shutdown in history] by Jacob Pramuk, CNBC, 25 Jan 2019, retrieved 22 March 2020</ref> [[Day Without Immigrants 2017]] protests were held throughout the United States in February 2017 to demonstrate the importance of immigration.<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2017/02/15/politics/washington-dc-day-without-immigrants/ DC preps for 'Day Without Immigrants,' but Hill takes little notice] By Tal Kopan, CNN, 16 Feb 2017, retrieved 11 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nOn June 14, 2017, Congressman [[Steve Scalise]] (R-LA) and two aides were [[2017 Congressional baseball shooting|hit by gunfire]] during a practice session for the annual Congressional baseball game.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-40275055 Gunman dead after attacking congressmen at Virginia baseball field] BBC News, 15 June 2017, retrieved 12 March 2020</ref>\n\nPresident Trump nominated and the Senate approved two Supreme Court justices: [[Neil Gorsuch]] and [[Brett Kavanaugh]]. Kavanaugh's [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|Judiciary Committee]] was concerned primarily with allegations of sexual misconduct.<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2018/10/06/politics/kavanaugh-final-confirmation-vote/index.html Brett Kavanaugh sworn in as Supreme Court justice] By Clare Foran and Stephen Collinson, CNN, 7 Oct 2018, retrieved 11 Mar 2020</ref> The [[Music Modernization Act]] modernizes music copyright laws and [[America's Water Infrastructure Act of 2018]] relaxes water pollution restrictions.\n\nTrump signed a number of [[executive order]]s to overturn [[Executive Order 13672|actions undertaken]] by President Obama, prioritizing [[Executive Order 13766|economic expediency]] over environmental concerns. He withdrew from the [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]] and restricted [[Executive Order 13769|immigration by refugees]]. He began construction of the [[Executive Order 13767|border wall]] and instituted a [[Executive Order 13769|ban on Muslim immigration]].\n\nAllegations about [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]] and during the November 2016-January 2017 transition period surface, resulting in the resignation of [[National Security Advisor (United States)|National Security Advisor]] [[Michael Flynn]]. FBI Director [[James Comey]] is fired because of the way he handled the investigation. The first call for the impeachment of President Trump is issued on May 7, 2017.<ref>[https://thehill.com/homenews/house/333807-dem-calls-for-trump-impeachment-on-house-floor Dem calls for Trump impeachment on House floor] BY PAULINA FIROZI, The Hill, 17 May 2020, retrieved 12 Mar 2020</ref> [[Robert Mueller]] began his investigation on May 17.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-39957358 Trump Russia inquiry: Former FBI boss to lead probe] BBC News, 18 May 2017</ref>\n\n===2019, 116th Congress===\n{{see also|Trump  Presidency|116th United States Congress}}\nDemocrats controlled the House of Representatives<ref>[https://www.politico.com/interactives/2018/interactive_116th-congress-freshman-younger-bluer-diverse/ Congress's incoming class is younger, bluer, and more diverse than ever] By BEATRICE JIN, Politico, 23 Nov 2018, retrieved 22 Mar 2020</ref> with [[Nancy Pelosi]] (D-CA) as Speaker.<ref>[https://www.businessinsider.com/nancy-pelosi-elected-speaker-of-the-house-new-democratic-majority-2019-1?r=MX&IR=T Nancy Pelosi elected speaker of the House, ushering in new Democratic majority] by Joe Perticone, Business Insider, 3 Jan 2019</ref> [[Jeff Van Drew]] (R-NJ) changed from Democrat to Republican on December 19, 2019.<ref>[https://www.huffpost.com/entry/jeff-van-drew-switches-parties-trump_n_5dfbd87ae4b0eb2264d6a68a Rep. Jeff Van Drew Officially Switches Parties, Pledges \u2018Undying Support\u2019 For Trump] Huff Post, 19 December 2019, retrieved 2 March 2020</ref> Mitch McConnell (R-KY) continued as Senate Majority leader.<ref name=Senate_leader />\n\n==History by issue==\n===Environment and climate change===\n{{Main|Environmental issues in the United States|Climate change in the United States|Climate change policy of the United States}}\n{{See also|Paris Agreement|United States withdrawal from the Paris Agreement|Renewable energy in the United States|Climate change and agriculture in the United States}}\n\n===Foreign and military policy===\n{{Main|Foreign policy of the Barack Obama administration|Foreign policy of the Donald Trump administration}}\n{{See also|Climate security}}\n\n====Afghanistan====\n{{Main|War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)}}\n\n====Africa====\n{{Main|Boko Haram insurgency|Lord's Resistance Army Disarmament and Northern Uganda Recovery Act}}\n\n====India====\n{{Main|India\u2013United States relations}}\n\n====Iran====\n{{Main|Iran\u2013United States relations|Iran\u2013U.S. RQ-170 incident|Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action|2019\u201320 Persian Gulf crisis}}\n\n====Iraq====\n{{Main|Iraqi insurgency (2003\u20132011)|American-led intervention in Iraq (2014\u2013present)}}\n{{See also|Protests against the Iraq War}}\n\n====Latin America====\n{{Main|Latin America\u2013United States relations}}\n\n====Libya====\n{{Main|Libyan Civil War (2014\u2013present)|2012 Benghazi attack}}\n{{See also|Investigation into the 2012 Benghazi attack|United States House Select Committee on Benghazi}}\n\n====Syria====\n{{Main|Syrian civil war|ISIL territorial claims}}\n\n====Venezuela====\n{{Main|Venezuelan protests (2014\u2013present)|Venezuelan presidential crisis}}\n\n====Yemen====\n{{Main|Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen}}\n\n===Guns===\n{{Main|Gun law in the United States|Gun laws in the United States by state|Gun politics in the United States|Gun violence in the United States}}\n{{See also|Mass shootings in the United States|School shootings in the United States}}\n\n===Immigration===\n{{Main|Illegal immigration to the United States|2014 American immigration crisis|Immigration policy of Donald Trump|U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement}}\n{{See also|Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals|Trump administration migrant detentions|Trump administration family separation policy|Trump travel ban|Mexico\u2013United States barrier}}\n\n===Recession of 2008===\n{{Main|Great Recession in the United States}}\nThe [[Great Recession in the United States|Great Recession]] was a severe financial crisis from December 2007 to June 2009 that began when the U.S. housing market crashed, and large amounts of [[Mortgage-backed security|mortgage-backed securities]] and derivatives lost significant value. The United States lost 8.7 million jobs and U.S. households lost $19 trillion of net worth.<ref name=\"investo\">{{cite web |website=Investopedia|title=The Great Recession|url=https://www.investopedia.com/terms/g/great-recession.asp|first=Jim|last=Chappelow|date=March 10, 2010|accessdate=March 19, 2020|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Obama administration spent much of its time and effort into improving the economy and addressing the issues that led to the recession. Obama signed the [[Dodd\u2013Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act|Dodd-Frank Act]] on July 21, 2010, to give the government expanded regulatory power over the financial sector. [[Real gross domestic product|Real GDP]] regained its pre-recession peak in the second quarter of 2011, and in March 2013, the [[Dow Jones Industrial Average]] broke its 2007 high. Workers and households did less well. The [[Unemployment in the United States|unemployment rate]] was at 5% at the end of 2007, reached 10% in October 2009, and did not recover to 5% until 2015. [[Household income in the United States]] did not surpass its pre-recession level until 2016.<ref name=\"investo\"/>\n\n===Rights and freedoms===\n\n====LGBTQ rights====\n{{Main|LGBT rights in the United States}}\n{{See also|Same-sex marriage in the United States|Sexual orientation and gender identity in the United States military}}\n\n====Voting rights====\n{{Main|Voting rights in the United States|Shelby County v. Holder|Voter suppression in the United States}}\n{{See also|2016 Washington, D.C. statehood referendum|2017 Puerto Rican status referendum}}\n\n====Women's rights====\n{{See also|Sexual harassment in the workplace in the United States|Gender pay gap in the United States|Me Too movement}}\n\n===Trade and tarrifs===\n{{Main|United States free-trade agreements|Trump tariffs}}\n{{See also|Trans-Pacific Partnership|United States\u2013Mexico\u2013Canada Agreement|China\u2013United States trade war|Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col}}\n* Other decade overviews: \n**[[2020s in political history]]\n**[[2020s in United States political history]]\n* UK decade overviews:\n**[[2010s in United Kingdom political history]]\n**[[2020s in United Kingdom political history]]\n{{End div col}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n===Congress===\n* [https://www.congress.gov/ Official website, US Congress] \n**[http://clerk.house.gov Clerk of the House of Representatives]\n** [http://cao.house.gov Chief Administrative Office of the House]\n** [http://majorityleader.gov Office of the majority leader]\n** [http://speaker.gov Office of the speaker of the House]\n** [http://www.house.gov/representatives Official 